<HTML>
<TITLE>Figure 5: Efficiency Functions</TITLE>

<A HREF="echelle.html">Return to Echelle Manual</A>

<P><HR><P>

<A NAME="fgint">Figure 5: Efficieny Functions</A> <P>

 <P><A NAME="fgin_pan1">(<EM> Panel 1</EM>)</A>
The quantum efficiency curves of the CCD-Mil and the CCD-Tek.  

<IMG SRC="fig_int_b.gif" WIDTH=553 HEIGHT=543 > <P>

<P><HR><P>

 <P><A NAME="fgin_pan2">(<EM> Panel 2</EM>)</A>
The CCD QE curves combined with the blaze function of cross disperser
A. 

 <IMG SRC="fig_int_d.gif" WIDTH=564 HEIGHT=515 > <P>

<P><HR><P>

 <P><A NAME="fgin_pan3">(<EM> Panel 3</EM>)</A>Normalized black body
spectra for temperatures T = 3200&#176;K (roughly the temperature of a
tungsten bulb, like the current flat lamp) and T = 5800&#176;K (close
to the effective temperature of the sun).

<IMG SRC="fig_int_c.gif" WIDTH=572 HEIGHT=529 > <P>

<P><HR><P>

 <P><A NAME="fgin_pan4">(<EM> Panel 4</EM>)</A> The
product of the two black body curves with combined CCD QE and cross
disperser blaze function.  For T = 3200&#176;K is shown in the top
half, and for T = 5800&#176;K is shown in the lower half.

<IMG SRC="fig_int_e.gif" WIDTH=562 HEIGHT=525 > <P>

<P><HR><P>

