<HTML>
<TITLE>Evolution of Elliptical Galaxies</TITLE>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

Ref: Aguilar, L., ASP Conf. Ser., vol., 86, p. <BR>
Presented at: Fresh Views on Elliptical Galaxies<BR>
Held at:      INAOE, Puebla, Mex. <BR>
Dates:        14--17 March, 1995 <BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>
Evolution of Elliptical Galaxies in Rich Clusters:<BR>
The N-Body Approach<BR>
</H2>
<BR>
<EM>Luis A. Aguilar</EM><BR>
Instituto de Astronom&iacute;a, U.N.A.M., Ensenada, M&eacute;xico<BR>
</CENTER>

<H3>Abstract</H3>

 <P>Rich clusters of galaxies provide us with laboratories to study
environmental effects on the evolution of individual galaxies. Among
these effects we have interactions of galaxies with the overall
potential well of the cluster, with the other galaxies, and with the
intracluster medium. An extensive statistical investigation of the
average changes produced by these effects is needed as a first step
toward a simulation of the dynamical evolution of rich clusters of
galaxies. Most N-body simulations to date, however, have concentrated
in modeling particular objects in the sky.

<H4>Keywords:</H4> Clusters of Galaxies, Elliptical Galaxies, Tidal
Interactions

<H3>Introduction</H3>

 <P>First of all a word about the title; the one in bold type is the
one that appeared in the conference program, and that is the one I
should be talking about. The title with the additions that appear in
italics is what I am really going to talk about today. Clusters of
galaxies are comprised of disk and irregular galaxies, in addition to
elliptical galaxies, and rich clusters, although quite conspicuous,
contain only a minority of the visible galaxies. Because Disk galaxies
are notoriously more difficult to simulate than elliptical galaxies,
I'll take advantage of the fact that the interest of this conference
is elliptical galaxies, and restrict my talk accordingly.  The dense
environment of rich clusters, takes the environmental effects to their
extremes and so is a good starting point.

 <P>We can artificially divide the dynamical evolution of a cluster of
galaxies into two stages: virialization and quasi-equilibrium
evolution. During the first stage the future cluster detaches from the
Hubble flow and collapses in on itself, undergoing violent
relaxation. During the second stage the rough global properties of the
cluster have been set, although the galaxies within continue to evolve
and the cluster may keep accreting material. The work reviewed in the
present talk relates to the interaction of already fully formed
elliptical galaxies. Although one may doubt the validity of this
assumption when modeling the early stages of cluster evolution, recent
observations of distant clusters of galaxies made with the Hubble
Space telescope (<A HREF="#fig1">figure 1</A>), lend credence
to our hypothesis. These observations show that, at least during a
significant part of the life of a cluster, fully formed elliptical
galaxies are among its basic interacting units. It may well be that
not only during the quasi-steady evolution, but even during cluster
virialization, our use of elliptical galaxies is not far from the
truth.

<P><HR><P>
<A NAME="fig1"></A>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="fig1.gif" width=180 height=161>
</CENTER>

 <P>Figure 1: Detail of a deep HST image of a cluster near 3C324 at a
redshift of z=1.2; the luminous object has the luminosity profile,
shape, and color of a normal elliptical (Dickinson 1995, NASA/STScI).

<P><HR><P>

 <P>Before proceeding to model the dynamics of the entire cluster,
however, we must model the basic interaction of one galaxy with
another, or with the cluster potential. As we will see, most
simulations of the basic two-galaxy interaction have concentrated in
modeling actual systems in the sky, aiming to reproduce most of the
photometric and kinematic data available. Although the matches
achieved in these fits are impressive, these simulations do not help
much the cluster modeler, who needs a large ensemble of simulations
spanning the relevant parameter space from which to predict, at least
statistically, the likely outcome of a generic encounter. Most of the
physics involved is known, the main difficulty resides in the vast
amounts of computer time required to explore a significant portion of
the parameter space.

 <P>The purpose of my talk is to give a quick, and by no means
exhaustive, view of the status of the field of numerical simulation of
the dynamical evolution of rich clusters of galaxies. First, studies
of galaxy-galaxy interactions are discussed, both hyperbolic and
merging encounters, then investigations of galaxy-cluster
interactions are reviewed, before moving onto simulations of the
overall cluster dynamics.  Interactions with a gaseous component,
although important, are not covered here.  A last section ponders the
puzzling homogeneity of density profiles and shapes of elliptical
galaxies, both simulated and real, and summarizes some interesting
arguments that have been advanced for the universality of the
r^{1/4} surface density profile.

<H3>Galaxy-Galaxy Interaction</H3>

 <P>Encounters between galaxies can result in tidal stripping and
merging.  These phenomena have opposite effects on the luminosity
function of the cluster: while the first erodes galaxies moving them
to the faint end of the luminosity distribution, the latter populates
the bright end.  Galactic encounters promote luminosity segregation
and erode halos too, yielding material to the cluster potential
well. For these reasons, a good model for galactic encounters is an
essential ingredient of a cluster simulation. The border that
separates merging from hyperbolic encounters, defines the delicate
balance between runaway merging and severe halo truncation of
otherwise non-interacting luminous components.


<H4>Mergers</H4>

 <P>Merging has come a long way from the Toomre &amp; Toomre (1972) work
where they first launched the now respectable ``merging hypothesis''.
In that now classic reference, the Toomres used a three-body
approximation to follow the orbits of test particles around two
interacting mass centers. The literature on this subject is quite
extensive and the reader is referred to the excellent reviews of the
field (e.g. Barnes &amp; Hernquist 1992b). In this talk I will
concentrate on three recent works.

 <P>The first is the work of K. Borne and collaborators (Borne 1988a,
1988b; Borne &amp; Hoessel 1988; Borne, Balcells &amp; Hoessel 1988).  They
have developed what they call the Multiple Three-Body Algorithm
(MTBA), which, being relatively fast and interactive, has allowed them
to explore a large number of experiments, thus achieving good fits to
photometric and kinematic observations of the interacting pairs
NGC 2672/73, NGC 4782/83, NGC 7236/37. The main disadvantage of this
approach is that this is not a truly self-gravitating scheme, and
questions remain as to the validity of the fine details of their
matching. Even so, this is a valuable tool because of the exploration
of parameter space that it permits.

<P><HR><P>
<A NAME="fig2"></A>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="fig2.gif" width=611 height=460>
</CENTER>

 <P>Figure 2:Comparison of Arp 86 photometry and the best Salo &amp;
Laurikainen (1993) model. Notice that the model successfully
reproduces the spiral pattern.

<P><HR><P>

 <P>A more recent work along this line has been published by Salo
&amp; Laurikainen (1993), who have used a 3-dimensional, spherical
polar grid method, to simulate the merging of two self-gravitating
galaxies containing stars and gas, embedded in rigid spherical
halos. They have used this code to match the photometric and
kinematical information of Arp 86. The correct projected separation,
radial velocity difference, morphology, velocity field, main tidal
features and spiral pattern of the primary galaxy are matched 
(<A HREF="#fig2">figure 2</A>). This simulation, however, is a tour de
force that has been finely tuned to mimic a specific system.


 <P>To finish this section, it is necessary to mention the very
sophisticated merging simulations of J. Barnes and L. Hernquist
(Barnes &amp; Hernquist 1991, 1992a; Hernquist &amp; Barnes 1991). The most
significant elements added by their numerical experiments are the use
of a hierarchical tree code that is self-gravitating and does not
require any kind of overall symmetry, and the use of multi-component,
completely self-gravitating, N-body galaxies that incorporate a
bulge, a disk and a dark halo. The reader is referred to Barnes (1994)
for a summary of this work. Among the main results obtained are:
self-gravity does not destroy fine tidal features like tails and
bridges; orbital angular momentum of the luminous components is
efficiently dissipated by the dark halos; the halos can also absorb a
significative fraction of the orbital energy and thus produce merging
of luminous components that are widely separated; merger remnants have
projected r^{1/4} profiles; the degree of flattening and shape of
isophotes, which range from ``disky'', to elliptical, to ``boxy'',
depends on the relative orientation of the interacting galaxies. The
result that dark halos can absorb large fractions of orbital energy
and angular momentum, removes a previous criticism of the merging
hypothesis, namely that only close to head-on collisions can produce
slowly rotating, realistic, luminous ellipticals.

 <P>Despite the great improvements introduced by the work of these
authors, a limited number of simulations have been performed, and many
of them have been made to fit specific objects in the sky. A
significant exploration of parameter space remains to be done and, in
particular, a good merger criterion is still lacking. One difficulty
lies in the large number of parameters needed to uniquely specify the
encounter between two spinning, disk galaxies. A reduced set of
parameters may be possible if, instead of matching the photometry and
kinematics, only the changes in global quantities are required.


<H4>Hyperbolic Encounters</H4>

 <P>This is a problem that has also been extensively investigated.
The work of Richstone (1975, 1976) and Dekel et al. (1980) in
particular, greatly influenced simulations of cluster evolution during
the early 1980's. These authors posited that the fractional change in
internal energy and mass of a galaxy that is tidally stripped, scales
as either a linear or quadratic power-law of the relevant encounter
parameters, the exponent being set by the internal orbital
constitution of the galaxy.

 <P>Aguilar &amp; White (1985) showed that the changes follow a smooth,
intermediate behaviour between linear and quadratic scaling, and that
this unique behaviour is not affected by the orbital make up of the
galaxy.  They also found that the final relaxed configuration has an
r^{1/4} surface density profile and that strong encounters produce
larger, dimmer galaxies while weak collisions produce compact,
brighter galaxies, thus explaining the apparent contradictory
observations of Kormendy (1982) and Stromm &amp; Stromm (1978). This
work, however, assumed a rigid perturbing galaxy, equal masses for the
interacting galaxies and did not consider dark matter.

<P><HR><P>
<A NAME="fig3"></A>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="fig3.gif" width=609 height=361>
</CENTER>

 <P>Figure 3:Fractional change in luminous mass (left panel) and M/L
ratio (right panel) as a function of initial M/L or an r^{1/4}
galaxy that suffers an encounter with a galaxy of equal mass (lower
curves) or 1.5 times more massive (upper curves), with impact
parameter 5.6 and relative velocity 1.8 times the galaxy's r_e and
v_{rms}. Notice how changes in luminous mass decrease as the initial
M/L increases, the dark halo, however, is eroded, and the final
M/L decreases.

<P><HR><P>

 <P>Aguilar &amp; Aceves (1992) extended this work to consider
galaxies with dark halos. They found that dark halos act as shields
that protect the central luminous components at the expense of being
heavily eroded (<A HREF="#fig3">figure 3</A>). More recently, Levine
&amp; Aguilar (1995) have undertaken a large number of simulations
spanning different mass ratios, impact parameters, relative velocities
and dark halos. These simulations have been done with a tree code and
a large number of particles, thus removing most of the shortcomings of
previous investigations. <A HREF="#fig4">Figure 4</A> shows the
evolution of the projected surface density profiles of two interacting
galaxies. Notice that as time passes, a radial wave of unrelaxed
particles move outwards leaving in its wake the final, r^{1/4}
profile. The position of this wave, signaled by an ``overluminous
bump'', is given by the local dynamical timescale and thus can be used
as a dynamical clock to date past encounters.

<P><HR><P>
<A NAME="fig4"></A>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="fig4.gif" width=792 height=612>
</CENTER>

 <P>Figure 4:Temporal evolution of the surface brightness profile of
two colliding galaxies. The straight lines are the r^{1/4} profiles
fitted to each galaxy in the last frame excluding the outermost,
unrelaxed regions. The radial position where the local dynamical time
is equal to the time since the moment of closest approach, is
indicated by vertical bars for each galaxy in the last three
frames. The frames are on a geometrical temporal sequence before and
after the moment of closest approach (Time=0) The encounter
parameters are M_1/M_2 = 4, v_{col}/v_{rms}=2, p/r_e=1, where
v_{rms} and r_e refer to the more massive galaxy.

<P><HR><P>

<H3>Galaxy-Cluster Interaction</H3>

 <P>Although it is common to think of tidal stripping and halo
truncation as due to galaxy-galaxy interactions, the role of the
overall cluster potential well is important too. Merritt &amp; White
(1987) and Merritt (1988) have studied this phenomenon using a
monopolar N-body code to follow 2000 particle galaxies within a rigid
cluster potential. They conclude that tidal damage is strongly
dependent on the ratio of orbital pericenter to cluster core radius
and weakly dependent on orbital eccentricity. Galaxies that cross the
cluster core are severely truncated down to 4 to 8&#215;10^{11}
M_{\odot}. More recently, Valluri (1993, 1994) has studied the effect
of the cluster tidal field in disk galaxies.  Test particles are
evolved in the combined potential of a modified Hubble profile for the
cluster and a Miyamoto disk within a halo and spheroid for the
galaxy. A decline in rotation curves is found outside ~20 kpc. This is
a subject that clearly needs more work.



<H3>Simulation of the Overall Cluster Evolution</H3>

 <P>All the interactions we have reviewed come together when modeling
the dynamics of a rich cluster of galaxies. This is a topic that has
been extensively studied; the <A HREF="#tbl1">table</A> on next page
gives a summary of the physical mechanisms included and methods used
in a selected list of studies. It is apparent that the number of
studies and of physical phenomena considered in them quickly reached a
maximum in in the mid 1980's. Since then, most simulations have not
attempted to be as comprehensive in their inclusion of environmental
effects, although it is clear that the subject of dark matter has
received a lot of attention.

 <P>This trend is explained, at least in part, by the belief that the
changes in global quantities were very dependent on the internal
orbital structure of interacting galaxies (see section 2.2). Miller
(1983) considered models with the two ``collisional rules'' then in
vogue and came up with widely variant results. The fraction of
galactic mass stripped by collisions, for instance, could vary from as
little as ~8% to as much as 70%. Most recent studies have
centered on specific issues like mass and luminosity segregation
(Evrard 1987, West &amp; Richstone 1988), or the role of dynamical
friction (Carlberg &amp; Dubinski 1991). What has been lacking is a more
comprehensive simulation that puts all the interactions together;
particularily in lieu of the fact that the old collision rule
uncertainty has been resolved.

<P><HR><P>
<A NAME="tbl1"></A>

<CENTER>
 <P>Table 1 <P>
 <IMG SRC="tbl1.gif" width=489 height=280>
</CENTER>

<P><HR><P>

<H3>Why do Ellipticals have a Universal Density Profile?</H3>

 <P>Most luminous elliptical galaxies have fairly elliptical isophotes
and surface brightness profiles which are well approximated by
r^{1/4} profiles. Even very disturbed recent mergers like NGC 7252
can be fitted with this profile (Schweizer 1982). In the numerical
arena, both mergers and hyperbolic encounters produce end products
with this profile. What is producing such uniformity?

 <P>An interesting hypothesis has been put forward recently by Hjorth
&amp; Madsen (1991). These authors argue that the key to this mystery
lies in violent relaxation, which promotes a Boltzmann-like phase
space distribution funtion at the center. At large radius, where
violent relaxation is incomplete, Aguilar &amp; White (1986) and Jaffe
(1987) have argued that any phenomenon that promotes a continuous,
non-zero distribution of particles across the E=0 energy surface in
phase space, will produce a distribution that behaves as f(E) \propto
|E|^{5/2}. Putting together these two asymptotic forms for f(E) at
small and large radii, Hjorth &amp; Madsen show that the simplest
continuous functional form that satisfies these conditions results in
a model which closely resembles an r^{1/4} profile and which fits,
even better than this profile, the photometry of NGC 3379 
(<A HREF="#fig5">figure 5</A>).

<P><HR><P>
<A NAME="fig5"></A>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="fig5.gif" width=576 height=395>
</CENTER>

 <P>Figure 5:Differences between the major axis surface brightness
profile of NGC 3379 and the best fitted R^{1/4} law (dashed line),
and the same R^{1/4} law and a model proposed by Hjorth and Masden
(1991).

<P><HR><P>

<H3>Conclusions</H3>

 <P>Although a large degree of sophistication has been achieved in
N-body simulations of the basic galaxy-galaxy interaction, most of
the work has concentrated on modeling specific systems.  To advance
the state of the art in the problem of simulating the dynamics of a
rich cluster of galaxies, a more comprehensive systematic exploration
of the relevant parameter space is required. For the case of
interacting elliptical galaxies, at least, it is now possible to
conduct such study. For the case of interacting disk galaxies it
remains to be determined whether a manageable reduced set of
parameters is sufficient to model statistically the global changes
that are required for a cluster simulation; in particular a good
merger criterion is of utmost importance. The case of galaxy-cluster
interaction remains poorly studied. This is even more so for the still
nascent study of the modeling of the gaseous component of both
galaxies and intracluster medium.

 <P>Despite these shortcomings, a more realistic simulation of the
dynamics of a rich cluster that incorporates most of the interactions
discussed here, should be possible in the near future. The wealth of
information potentially obtained, together with the large amounts of
observational information on cluster of galaxies, particularily now
that it is possible to study clusters at large redshifts, make this a
very desirable goal.


<H3>Acknowledgments</H3>

 <P>I want to thank S. Levine for allowing me to show some of our
results and for figuring out how to coerce the PASP LaTeX macro
package to write the somewhat unorthodox title of this
contribution. This work was supported by CONACYT grant 3739-E.


 <P><EM>M. D'Onofrio:</EM> Actually, Elliptical galaxies do not follow
an r^{1/4}-law, but a generalized r^{1/n}-law, with n a free
index that can vary from 1 to 10, and is correlated with the
luminosity of the galaxy.  How much do your conclusions change if the
r^{1/4} behavior is not universal?

 <P><EM>L. Aguilar:</EM> A variation of n from 1 to 10 is not,
actually, a large variation in terms of the resulting potential
function, on the other hand, the arguments of Hjorth &amp; Marsden are
only approximate. In my view it is already quite striking that a
simple argument can lead to something that roughly resembles real
galaxies. Variation as the ones that you mention are beyond the
arguments presented here.

 <P><EM>M. Carollo:</EM> Despite the overall similarities, ``small''
ellipticals look in many respects different from ``large''
galaxies. Can the approach you propose follow ``ellipticals'' over the
whole range?

 <P><EM>L. Aguilar:</EM> Dwarf ellipticals behave in a different
manner and the arguments that I have mentioned here apply to luminous
ellipticals alone.  For one thing, one of the results of our
simulations is that when there is a large disparity between the masses
of the interacting systems, the smaller galaxy ends up with a
truncated profile, different from the r^{1/4} profile of the more
massive galaxy.

 <P><EM>G. Djorgovski:</EM> (In response to D'Onofrio and
Carollo). Both you and your questioners are ``right''. There is a real
variety in the observed surface brightness profiles of ellipticals,
which roughly correlates with luminosity. However, they do basically
look the same, roughly following Hubble-R^{1/4} profiles.  The
question you posed at the end of your talk, namely, why do ellipticals
occupy only a small range of dynamical structures which are in
principle open to them, is, in my mind, the central question in our
understanding of elliptical galaxies.

 <P><EM>R. Davies:</EM> What ultimately limits the merging process in
rich clusters?

 <P><EM>L. Aguilar:</EM> Merging cross sections depend on the
geometrical cross sections and are thus set by the size of the
halos. Environmental processes that limit the size of halos will
ultimately limit the merging process.  There are two ways in which you
can limit the size of galactic halos: tidal truncation due to the mean
cluster field and tidal truncation due to hyperbolic
encounters. D. Merritt modeled the first phenomenon and found it to be
an extremely efficient mechanism, capable of trimming down halos to a
size where tidal stripping was no longer important.  The way in which
he estimated the amplitude of the tidal field, however, may have
resulted in an overestimate. G. Miller, among other authors, modeled
the second mechanism, but his results were inconclusive because of the
uncertainty introduced in the ``collision rules'' that he used.  Now
that we have better collision rules we intend to model both
mechanisms. In any case and by whatever particular mechanism, it seems
that the current merging rate in rich clusters is just a shadow of
what happened in the past.

 <P><EM>D. Merritt:</EM> Cosmological simulations suggest that the
core radius of the dark matter in galaxy clusters might be very
small. Could galaxies in clusters survive tidal interactions with a
central, dark matter cusp?

 <P><EM>L. Aguilar:</EM> This is a question that maybe you should
answer, since most of the little numerical work that has been done on
mean field truncation is yours. You and Simon (White) found that
strong tidal truncation occurs around the cluster core radius, where
the tidal force is maximal. If keeping the total mass constant you
decrease the core radius of the cluster mass profile, the maximum
tidal force increases, but the volume where this occurs decreases,
thus affecting less galaxies, but more strongly.

