<HTML>
<TITLE>Interactions Between Elliptical Galaxies</TITLE>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

Ref: Levine, S. &amp; Aguilar, L., 1995, ASP Conf. Ser., vol. 86, p. 77<BR>
Presented at: Fresh Views on Elliptical Galaxies<BR>
Held at:      INAOE, Puebla, Mex. <BR>
Dates:        14--17 March, 1995 <BR>

<CENTER>
<H2>
Interactions between Elliptical Galaxies<BR>
</H2>
<BR>
<EM>Stephen Levine</EM><BR>
and<BR>
<EM>Luis Aguilar</EM><BR>
Instituto de Astronom&iacute;a, U.N.A.M., Ensenada, M&eacute;xico<BR>
</CENTER>

<H3>Abstract</H3>

 <P>When an elliptical galaxy undergoes a transformation which
satisfies two simple physical assumptions, the resulting observable
properties of the galaxy lie on a plane in the three dimensional space
defined by effective radius, effective surface brightness, and central
velocity dispersion.  The angle between this plane and the observed
Fundamental Plane of Galaxies is less than 15&#176;, implying that
most of any predicted change is projected along the fundamental plane,
regardless of the specific details of the interaction responsible for
the change.

<H4>Keywords</H4> Elliptical Galaxies, Fundamental Plane, Virial Theorem

<H3>Motivation</H3>

 <P>Elliptical galaxies have been observed to cluster near a two
dimensional plane in the three dimensional space of effective radius
(r_e), effective surface brightness (mu_e = -2.5 log Sigma_e)
and central velocity dispersion (sigma_0) (Djorgovski &amp; Davis
1987, Dressler et al. 1987, Bender, Burstein &amp; Faber 1992, 1993,
Guzm&aacute;n, Lucey &amp; Bower 1993).  This observed restriction
holds for galaxies spanning a large range in sizes and a wide range of
environments (see <A HREF="#fig1">fig. 1</A>).

<H3>The Change Plane</H3>

 <P>When an elliptical galaxy undergoes a transformation that
satisfies two simple properties, we can relate the changes in the mass
M and the binding energy E of the galaxy to changes in its
observational properties (r_e, mu_e, and sigma_0).  We assume that
before and after the interaction that (1) <EM>the galaxy is in virial
equilibrium</EM> and, (2) <EM>the functional form of the radial
surface brightness profile is the same type of 2-parameter form</EM>.
This says nothing about the particulars of the interaction.

<P><HR><P>
<A NAME="fig1"></A>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="fig1.gif" width=792 height=612>
</CENTER>

 <P>Figure 1:Observed elliptical systems (Bender, Burstein &amp; Faber
1993, Table 1).  The range of the scales on the axes is the same as in
<A HREF="#fig2">figure 2</A>.

<P><HR><P>

 <P>Under these assumptions, the Mass and Binding Energy of the galaxy
can be written in terms of observable quantities as

<PRE>
M = alpha Sigma_e   r_e^2 ,
M = beta            r_e sigma_0^2 ,
E = gamma Sigma_e^2 r_e^3.
</PRE>

<P> alpha, beta, and gamma are constants, that do <STRONG>not</STRONG>
change under the transformation (e.g. the mass to light ratio
alpha is unchanged).  The first relation comes from the geometry,
and the latter two from virial equilibrium.  For a variable x,
Delta x = x_{final} / x_{initial}.  The ratios of the
final to initial mass and binding energy can be written as

<PRE>
log(Delta M) =   log(Delta Sigma_e) + 2 log(Delta r_e) +
             =                          log(Delta r_e) + 2 log(Delta sigma_0)
log(Delta E) = 2 log(Delta Sigma_e) + 3 log(Delta r_e).
</PRE>

In the space of log(r_e), log(sigma_0), and log(Sigma_e),
these reduce to the plane

<PRE>
log(Delta r_e) - 2 log(Delta sigma_0) + log(Delta Sigma_e) = 0
</PRE>

 <P>It is intriguing to note that the angle between the observed
Fundamental Plane and this ``Change Plane'' is less than 15&#176;,
implying that most of the predicted change is projected along the
Fundamental Plane.  The changes in the observable properties given in
terms of the changes in M and E are

<PRE>
log(Delta r_e)      =  2  log (Delta M) -   log(Delta E) 
log(Delta sigma_0)  =0.5[-log (Delta M) +   log(Delta E)] 
log (Delta Sigma_e) =  -3 log (Delta M) + 2 log(Delta E) .
</PRE>

<H3>Collisions to Changes</H3>

 <P>In order to assess the effect of galaxy--galaxy interactions, we
need to relate the parameters describing an interaction to those
describing the change in the galaxy caused by the interaction.
Aguilar &amp; White (1985) followed a series of n-body interactions
between equal mass galaxies to derive cross-sections, relating the
impact velocity v_{infty} and impact parameter p_{infty} of a
collision to the changes in mass and binding energy of the galaxies
involved.

 <P>In order to estimate the importance of tidal interactions in the
observed spread of galaxy properties, we have carried out a few simple
Monte-Carlo simulations of the evolution of a number of elliptical
galaxies in the core of a very rich cluster.  What we have done is to
follow the changes in a single galaxy over a Hubble time as it moves
through an array of galaxies with a uniform spatial distribution
(where l is the mean intergalactic distance), and a Maxwell-Boltzmann
velocity distribution (characterized by the cluster velocity
dispersion v_{cl}).  All the galaxies are presumed to have the same
mass, and each encounter was specified by a randomly chosen p_{infty},
and v_{infty} and lasted for a time t_{coll}=(2p_{infty}/v_{infty}).
After each encounter, the time was incremented, the target galaxy's
parameters were updated and new impact parameters were drawn.  This
continued until the sum of the interaction times reached a Hubble
time.  The experiment was then repeated with many galaxies.  One of
the problems with this simple experiment is that since the
cross-sections were computed for equal mass galaxies, by implication,
the whole cluster is always composed of galaxies with mass equal to
the target galaxy we are following.

In the simulation shown, l = 21&#215;r_e where r_e~3 kpc (giving a
spatial density of ~950 Mpc^{-3}), and v_{cl} = 5&#215;sigma_0,
sigma_0~200 km s^{-1}.  <A HREF="#fig2">Figure 2</A> shows the
resulting dispersion of the change in observable properties of
evolving 10,000 identical galaxies.  The change in intensity Sigma_e
has been converted to a change in surface brightness mu_e to simplify
comparison with the data shown in <A HREF="#fig1">figure 1</A>.

<P><HR><P>
<A NAME="fig2"></A>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="fig2.gif" width=792 height=612>
</CENTER>

 <P>Figure 2: The final observable properties of each test galaxy are
plotted in terms of the initial properties.  To help show the
restrictive nature of the change produced by tidal interactions, we
have included the box bounded by a reduction by a factor of 10 in M
and E. The ranges of the axes is the same as the range in 
<A HREF="#fig1">figure 1</A>, for ease of comparison.

<P><HR><P>

<H3>Conclusions</H3>

 <P>From the above arguments, and the simple experiment, two things
become clear.  First, that to properly assess the importance of tidal
interactions between galaxies in a range of environments, we need a
set of interaction cross-sections that cover a range of galaxy mass
ratios, as well as impact velocities and parameters.  These can then
be used to model the changes that take place in galaxies during the
relatively short time of interaction (short relative to their expected
lifetimes) in simulations of evolution of galaxies in cluster
environments.  We are currently running a set of self-consistent
simulations using galaxies of varying masses with r^{1/4} profiles to
derive interaction cross-sections.  The second point is that the
simple physical arguments presented at the beginning of this paper are
not limited to tidal interactions in clusters, but rather apply to any
interactions between elliptical galaxies that satisfy the two
criteria.

 <P><EM>M. Dickinson:</EM> The processes you describe involve multiple
galaxy-galaxy encounters within a rich cluster environment, yet the
fundamental plane also seems to apply to galaxies in the field, where
the number of encounters may be small over a Hubble time.  Are there
somehow different mechanisms at work populating/defining the plane in
clusters vs. the field?

 <P><EM>L. Aguilar:</EM> A brief comment on M. Dickinson's question:
you shouldn't be left with the impression that you need a dense
environment for Steve's argument to work.  All that you need is for
the system to satisfy two simple hypotheses: (1) There's virial
equilibrium and (2) Elliptical galaxies are described by a 2-parameter
functional form for the density profile.  If you satisfy these two
simple hypotheses by whatever phenomenon that shapes Elliptical
galaxies (in rich or sparse environments) then you get something that
is suspiciously close to the Fundamental Plane.

 <P><EM>E. Recillas:</EM> Would a change in angular momentum in your
simulations make any difference in your results?

 <P><EM>S. Levine:</EM> Technically yes, though since we are only
looking to characterize to first order the results of the
interactions, it should not really make a noticeable difference.
Also, we are already attempting to sample a 3-dimensional parameter
space, and can only do that in a very crude manner, adding angular
momentum would only compound that problem.

<H3>References</H3>

<P> Aguilar, L. A. &amp; White, S. D. M. 1985, ApJ, 295, 374

<P> Aguilar, L. A. &amp; White, S. D. M. 1986, ApJ, 307, 97

<P> Bender, R., Burstein, D. &amp; Faber, S. 1992, ApJ, 399, 462

<P> Bender, R., Burstein, D. &amp; Faber, S. 1993, ApJ, 411, 153

<P> Djorgovski, S., &amp;  Davis, M. 1987, ApJ, 313, 59

<P> Dressler, A., Lynden-Bell, D., Burstein, D., Davies, R.,
Faber, S., Terlevich, R., &amp; Wegner, G. 1987, ApJ, 313, 42

<P> Guzm&aacute;n, R., Lucey, J. &amp; Bower, R. 1993, in <EM>Structure,
 Dynamics and Chemical Evolution of Elliptical Galaxies</EM>, I. J.
 Danziger,  W. W. Zeilinger &amp; K. Kj&auml;r, ESO: Garching, 19
 <P> <HR><HR> <P>

