Astronom&iacute;a, UNAM</EM>, No. 123.

 <P>Alvarez, M. and Maisterrena, J. 1977,
<EM>Rev. Mex. Astron. Astrof.</EM>, 2, 43.  

 <P>Bely, P.Y. 1987, <EM>PASP</EM>, 99, 560.

 <P>Crawford, D.L. 1987, <EM>Kitt Peak National Observatory Facilities
Book</EM>, NOAO.

 <P>Garstang, R.H. 1989, <EM>PASP</EM>, 101, 306.

 <P>Mendoza, E.E. 1971, <EM>Bol. Obs. Tonantzintla Tacubaya</EM>,
<STRONG>6</STRONG>, 95.

 <P>Mendoza, E.E. 1973, <EM>Mercury</EM>, <STRONG>2</STRONG>, 9.

 <P>Mendoza, E.E., Luna, J. &amp; G&oacute;mez, T. 1972,
<EM>Bol. Obs. Tonantzintla Tacubaya</EM>, <STRONG>6</STRONG>, 215.

 <P>Merrill, K.M. and Forbes, F.F. 1987, <EM>Comparison Study of
Astronomical Site Quality of Mount Graham and Mauna Kea</EM>, NNTT
Technology Developement Program Report No. 10, NOAO.

 <P>Osmer, P.S. and Wood, H.J. 1984, in <EM>Site Testing for Future
Large Telescopes</EM>, eds. A. Ardeberg and L. Woltjer, ESO, p95.

 <P>Sarazin, M. 1990, <EM> VLT Site Selection Working Group Final
Report</EM>, ESO-VLT Report No. 62.

 <P>Walker, M.F. 1971, <EM>PASP</EM>, 83, 401.

 <P>Walker, M.F. 1983, in <EM>Site Testing for Future Large
Telescopes</EM>, ESO, p3.

 <P>Westphal 1974, <EM>Infrared Sky Noise Survey</EM>, Final Report
NASA-NGR-05-002-185, California Institute of Tecnology.

<H3>FIGURE CAPTIONS</H3>

 <P><STRONG><A NAME="fig1">Figure 1.</A></STRONG> Monthly fraction of
nights scheduled for observation on the 2.1m telescope at San Pedro
M&aacute;rtir. Holiday periods, maintenance and engineering runs and
scattered periods of undersubscription of telescope use are
excluded. The total amount of scheduled nights in the studied period
was 2533. 43% of these were scheduled for photometric programs.

 <P><STRONG><A NAME="fig2">Figure 2.</A></STRONG> Monthly ranges of
night temperatures recorded inside the open dome of the 2.1m telescope
during the period July 1982 to June 1992. The bars mark the extreme
temperatures registered during that month and the stars correspond to
the monthly average maximum and minimum temperatures.

 <P><STRONG><A NAME="fig3">Figure 3.</A></STRONG> Monthly mean
relative humidity near the ground and its standard deviation in San
Pedro M&aacute;rtir.

 <P><STRONG><A NAME="fig4">Figure 4.</A></STRONG> Monthly fraction of
nights of low (continuous line), medium (broken line) and high (dotted
line) relative humidity, according to the definitions given in Section
2.

 <P><STRONG><A NAME="fig5">Figure 5.</A></STRONG> Monthly fraction of
nights of photometric (broken line) and of spectroscopic quality
(continuous line) in San Pedro M&aacute;rtir during the period January
1984 to December 1991.

 <P><STRONG><A NAME="fig6">Figure 6.</A></STRONG> Yearly fraction of
nights of photometric (broken line) and of spectroscopic quality
(continuous line) in San Pedro M&aacute;rtir during the period January
1984 to December 1991. The dotted line marks the actual use of the
2.1m telescope (excluding the time lost due to telescope/instrument
failure) in the period July 1982 to June 1992.

 <P><STRONG><A NAME="fig7">Figure 7.</A></STRONG> Monthly fraction of
nights of photometric (lower lines) and of spectroscopic quality
(upper lines) in several sites (continuous lines) compared to those of
San Pedro M&aacute;rtir (broken lines). The dotted lines in pannels b
and d are the actual KPNO 4m and 2.1m telescope use fractions (b) and
of the University of Hawaii 2.2m telescope on Mauna Kea (d). The
absisa for Cerro Tololo and La Silla (a) runs from July to June, while
for the Northern Hemisphere sites the absisae run from January to
December.

 <P> <HR><HR> <P>
 
