<title> Historia de Mexico </title>

<img src="http://bufadora.astrosen.unam.mx/~aceves/blueline.gif">
<p>
<h1> Historia de M&eacute;xico</h1>
<p>
<img src="http://bufadora.astrosen.unam.mx/~aceves/blueline.gif">
<p>
<p>
<p>

<ul>

<li> La Historia de la Conquista de M&eacute;xico por William <a href= "gopher://gopher.vt.edu:10010/02/135/1">Prescott</a>. El archivo
es bastante grande como podr&aacute;n imaginar por el tama&ntilde;o del propio libro.

<p>

<li> El art&iacute;culo <i><a href="http://bufadora.astrosen.unam.mx/~aceves/Mexico/Opaz.ps">Exorcismo 
y Liberaci&oacute;n</i></a> de Octavio Paz referente a Hern&aacute;n
Cort&eacute;s.

<p>

<li> Algunos Datos Hist&oacute;ricos sobre M&eacute;xico <i><a href= "http://mexico.udg.mx/Historia/datos.html">Datos-M&eacute;xico</i></a>.

<p>

<li> Algunos documentos hist&oacute;ricos referentes a M&eacute;xico ir&aacute;n apareciendo poco a poco. Por lo pronto vean estos
"entremeses":
	<ul>
	<li><b>Fco. Villa y El&iacute;as Calles:</b> <i> "In the frequent
meetings between Zapatistas and Socialists of Yucatan, where I
have been most of the time, I have learned that Soto y Gama and other
comrades have trying to get permission to send a committee headed
by Engineer Argal Barrios to approach Villa and dissuade him from his
rebellous attitude but they say that so far General Obreg&oacute;n 
does not acquiesce. The arrival of General El&iacute;as Calles has
made the sending of such a commission more difficult for he told
them that he had already given orders to Enr&iacute;quez to 
settle the matter, pursuing Villa until killing him; that this
latter is nothing more than a bandid and should be anihilated,
otherwise there will be the danger of his committing depredations
that will prejudice the Revolution and the new Government above
all in the eyes of the Americans. At these statements those 
agitating the "ontente" with "comrade Villa", as they call him,
became shocked and grieved. They are waiting for De la Huerta to
see if he consents to the idea".</i> <tt> American Embassy/Office of The Military Attach&eacute;. City of Mexico. May 30, 1920. Report No. 1658. </tt>	

	<li><b>C&aacute;rdenas y el Petr&oacute;leo:</b> (1) <i>"The Ambassador</i> (Daniels) <i>had a conference on March 23 with President
C&aacute;rdenas. The President stated that he regretted very much
the necessity of expropiating the oil companies' properties but 
felt that their withdrawal of funds from the country last fall
precipitated the financial conditions now existing in the country/
..The President assured the Ambassador that he did not want to sell
oil to Japan, Germany, Italy or any other totalitarian nation. He 
is desirous of selling it to the United States and other democracies.
He also stated that the payement would be made to the oil companies
in oil. He felt that the value of the share of oil which the
companies would receive would probably approximate their 
present returns and they would be relieved of all responsibility
of production and the labor troubles which they were never able
to adjust".</i> <tt>[March 25, 1938]</tt>
(2)<i>"..the Country is rife with rumors. Until the drastic action of
the United States in suspending the silver purchases and its reported
strong representations to the Mexican Government relative to 
expropiated properties, the feeling of foreign interests and of
prominent men in opposition to the Government was that the 
United States would support the present Mexican Goverment 
against any revolutionary move. Now, however, the feeling is
that a revolutionary leader may receive at least moral support
from foreign interests. This is based on the knowledge that
every successful revolution in Mexico has had the backing of 
American interests in this country and encountered no 
opposition from the United States Government".</i><tt>[April 1, 1938]
</tt> 
(3)<i>"Laguna Oil Co. is japanese owned./ ..Ing Modesto C. 
Rolland ..Assistant Secretary of Deparment of Economics, which
issues all the permits for oil drillings.. is President of 
the Veracruzana Oil Company".</i> <tt>[Report No. 9194. October 4, 1939]</tt>
(4)<i> "The reason for the seeming inconsistensy of President
C&aacute;rdenas` attitude toward this Japanese controlled 
company is probably due to his thinking that no one knew, outside
of those actually involved, what had been going on in the
Compa&ntilde;&iacute;a Veracruzana. It must not be forgotten that 
the drilling permits given to the company have never been 
referred to either in the daily papers or the official bulletins 
which publish just such news. He may consider that no one has
proof of Japanese influence, or, that there can exist no proof of
his cognizance of such influence therefore, to any possible 
questioning as to the legality of granting drilling permits to any
company which was not wholly Mexican, he can say that, upon
investigation, he had no reason to believe that it was other than
it seemed./ ..In conclusion: it seems reasonable to assume that
President C&aacute;rdenas believes that the facts of Japanese
influence in the Compa&ntilde;&iacute;a Veracruzana are not known
to others than those concerned, and that even if these facts 
become known he cannot be accused of acting in other than a
legal manner. Further, that he is anxious for foreign capital to
exploit the resources of his country and probably believes
that the greated the distance between Mexico and such investing countries, the better for the eventual well-being of Mexico."</i>
<tt>[Report No. 9216. October 27, 1939]</tt>
American Embassy, Office of the Military 
Attach&eacute; - Mexico City. Intelligence Reports.



	</ul>





<p>
 
</ul>
</DOC>
