<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	<A NAME="1">10TH ANNUAL RENEGADES / Edited By Michael Warshaw</A></FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="144"></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="406"> <FONT 
SIZE="+7">Create &amp; Destroy</FONT><BR><BR>

</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
<P>
	<A HREF="#A">RICHARD HECKHMAN</A>
</P>
<P>
	<A HREF="#B">MARTHA STEWART</A>
</P>
<P>
	<A HREF="#C">JOHN LEDECKY</A>
</P>
<P>
	<A HREF="#D">BOB BORCHARDT</A>
</P>
<P>
	<A HREF="#E">BILL HANLEY</A>	
</P>
<P>
	<A HREF="#F">JAMES DAVID POWER</A>
</P>
<P>
	<A HREF="#G">RICK SCOTT</A>	
</P>
<P>
	<A HREF="#H">CHRISS WITTLE</A>
</P>
	
	<A HREF="#K">RENEGADES UPDATES</A>
	<BR>
	</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<FONT SIZE="+1">That is the essential mission of the entrepreneur, as defined by Joseph Schumpeter: Destroy the past to create the future. Renegades see opportunity where others see restrictions. Because they decide that the rules don't apply, renegades achieve the impossible -- time and time again. Always there are the naysayers. Martha Stewart was told she was trying to glorify mere housewifery, and nobody would buy it. Richard Heckmann kept hearing that there couldn't be a global water company. The Big Three automakers told J. D. Power he had nothing to teach them about their customers. But renegades don't run with the pack. They write their own rules. Stewart built a homemaking empire. Heckmann created the first multinational water colossus. And J. D. Power dragged the auto industry, kicking and screaming, into a new age of customer satisfaction. The rules simply don't apply. See that, see how these renegades do it, and you see that anything -- even your wildest dream -- is possible.</FONT></TD>
	</TR>
	<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<IMG SRC="heckmann.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="144" HEIGHT="144" BORDER="0"><FONT SIZE="-2"><P>Photograph By VERN EVANS</P></FONT>
<P>
	<FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR=#CC000C><A NAME="A">GLOBAL GIANT</A></FONT></TD>
</P>
	

<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
<P>
Richard Heckmann stared in disbelief at the business 
plan that had come across his desk. It sought financing for a water-filtration company, and it painted an amazing picture. There were tens of thousands of water companies in the United States, mostly run by engineers. They had sliced up the market into little pieces. There was no consolidation, no industry giant. Nobody believed it was possible to build a national water company.<P>It was simply the greatest entrepreneurial opportunity he had ever seen.<P>Heckmann had founded his first company --  Tower Scientific Corp. of Seattle, Wash. -- in 1971. He cashed out in 1977 and was appointed to the top financial position in the Small  Business Administration by President Carter. In 1982, he joined Prudential-Bache Securities as a first-year retail stockbroker; by 1986, he was one of the firm's top producers. He invested in several entrepreneurial ventures, becoming one of the founders of Cal-laway Golf and, with his brother-in-law, an owner of ski-goggle maker Smith Sport Optics Corp. <P>In 1988, Heckmann and a couple of friends invested in American Toxic Control (ATC), the California company with the startling plan to consolidate the water industry. ''It was so simple. You could put a hundred entrepreneurs in a room and tell them this story, and every one will get it,'' he says. ''It was as simple as, Where's the big water company? How can it be that with a product necessary for life itself, and with no synthetic substitute, there's no IBM or General Motors in it? How can you have a big cereal maker and not have a big water maker?''<P>There was one problem. Heckmann had no confidence in the top management. He lasted only three board meetings before he quit.<P>''But I kept this business plan on the corner of my desk and watched as the business got screwed up,'' he says. ''I couldn't get this idea out of my mind.''<P>In the spring of 1990, when ATC had about $17 million in revenues, Heckmann started hearing about real trouble in the company. ''Some of the managers called me, because we had stayed in touch,'' he says. ''I was asking how it was going, and they were saying, 'Terrible. This business is going to go bankrupt, and it's a shame.' ''<P>Heckmann was still at Prudential, earning a ''low-seven-figure income.'' He was married with five children. ''I took a 90 percent cut in pay,'' he says. ''We had a family meeting. I sat my wife down at the dinner table, and I asked for her credit cards. I said, 'This is either going to be very big or it's going to be a bust.' ''<P>Heckmann was 46. He had spent the last few years helping clients get rich. He wanted to build something of his own. ''I was at the peak of where my brain would be,'' he says. ''I was convinced of the concept and convinced I had what it took to do it. I knew I could raise the money it would take. <P>''I also knew there wasn't a lot of time left for me to take a risk like this. This was a very serious gamble. It had to work. It had my undivided attention.''<P>ATC was a penny stock in the pink sheets. Heckmann went to the top guys and made his move. ''I told them I was going to buy up a majority interest in the company and fire them all and throw their board out; and if they didn't allow that, I'd sue 'em, because I was already a shareholder,'' he says. ''I put up some money in an escrow account, and they blinked, essentially.'' <P>In July 1990, Heckmann took over. His first job was to fix the company. He raised $1.6 million, putting up 20 percent himself and going to his clients to raise the rest. ''I told them this was a hell of an idea,'' he says. ''The only reason they didn't all tell me I was crazy was that I had already had a hell of a career and was involved in several successful companies.''<P>Heckmann has long been a student of the great entrepreneurial success stories. He's read everything he could get his hands on about such achievers as Bill Gates and Sam Walton. He was convinced he had a company with the potential of Wal-Mart on his hands. <P>''Look at Ely Callaway,'' he says. ''He saw the golf business differently from the way the people in the industry saw it. They fell in love with their technology and forgot about what the market wanted. The same was true in the water business. All the guys who could have built the business we did were engineers, convinced that what the customer cared about was technology. But what the customer really wants is clean water. It's not the technology that sells the product; it's the product that sells the product. Look for industries that get wrapped up in their technology, and you can kill them.''<P>Heckmann changed the Palm Desert, Calif., company's name to United States Filter Corp. It took him only a year to complete an IPO. <P>''I had about 40 percent of a company that went public at eight bucks a share,'' he says. ''I can grow it at 10 or 15 percent a year and have a nice life. Or I can do what I know is the right thing and go balls to the wall and build a huge company.''<P>Heckmann went on an acquisitions spree, buying up small water companies. He knew well the story of how Wayne Huizenga had built two huge companies in separate industries -- Waste Management Inc. and Blockbuster Video -- through acquisition and consolidation. That was his model. ''The book on Waste Management was required reading for all managers,'' he says. ''We bought it by the case.''<P>In six years, Heckmann built the leading global provider of water and wastewater products and services. He became an expert in his industry. Name any product, from chocolate to tennis balls, and he can tell you how much water is necessary for its production. In 1990, his revenues were $23 million. U.S. Filter just completed a $225 million quarter. He now owns only 3 percent of the company, but that stake is worth about $50 million.<P>Heckmann hopes U.S. Filter will be a $10 billion company in five years. ''And I believe if we make the right moves now, this could be a $50 billion to $60 billion company. It took Waste Management 10 years to get to $1 billion. We're growing at twice that rate, faster than Microsoft did. Fifty years from now, we'll be in the category of the U.S. Steels of the world.''</P>
	</TD></TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="B">A</A></FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR=#CC000C>Martha's Way</FONT>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>Martha Stewart had a hell of a time getting her first book published. Her vision was for a lavish coffee-table book about entertaining at home, filled with full-color photographs. Her publishers balked at the expense, wanting to cut half the content and print half the photos in black and white. Stewart pushed to print at least 50,000 copies; the publishers planned to print 25,000. <P>Why should they risk more? This was back in the early 1980s, when fast-track mommies fought to stake their claim in corporate America. Here was Stewart, piecing together recipes and scenes of decadent leisure, glorifying mere housewifery.<P>The cynics were wrong. Since Entertaining hit the stores in 1982, it has sold more than 500,000 copies. ''It was an instant success because it filled a void,'' Stewart said at a press luncheon last November. ''It was a big-format book, but people started to take that book into the kitchen.''<P>Where others saw no opportunity at all, Stewart saw that void -- and filled it with her formidable presence. She has created an entire industry that includes home improvement, interior design, gardening, cooking, entertaining, and more. She thrives despite the skeptics.     <P>''Martha Stewart Living isn't really living at all,'' sniffed The New Republic last May. But Stewart is a classic study in entrepreneurship, with the roots of her well-tended empire extending back to her childhood. At age 10, fed up with the 50-cents-an-hour going rate for baby-sitters, she started organizing birthday parties for the kids in her middle-class New Jersey neighborhood. Later she worked as a teen model, went to college, got married, and had a daughter, Alexis. <P>In 1967, Stewart joined a young Wall Street brokerage firm and began pulling in a six-figure income. By the early 1970s, though, she was already tiring of the rat race. She still liked selling -- but now she wanted to sell something of her own.<P>At the time, Stewart and her husband were renovating an old house they had bought in Westport, Conn. She toyed with a couple of businesses -- a takeout food shop, a catering partnership that lasted less than a year -- before forming Martha Stewart Inc. in 1980. Her husband (the two are now divorced), a publishing executive, introduced her to the head of Crown Publishing Group, and Entertaining was born.<P>Today, Stewart has 18 books, an Emmy-award-winning TV show, a syndicated newspaper column, a mail-order business, her own line of paints, and, of course, the phenomenal magazine Martha Stewart Living. <P>In 1990, she produced a test issue of a completely different version of the home and women's magazines that already existed. The magazine industry was in terrible shape: The recession was causing a tremendous drop in spending on advertising, and many titles closed. Stewart finally found a sponsor with Time Inc., and Martha Stewart Living now sells more than 2 million copies a month.<P>''Stewart is one of the best self-marketers in this business,'' says Steve Cohn, editor of the Media Industry Newsletter. ''She's amazing -- she appeals to ordinary women as well as upscale types.'' <P>Stewart continues to push relentlessly to grow her brand through all facets of the media. Her TV show is moving from weekly to six days a week. Plans for an Internet site with an ''Ask Martha'' format (similar to her newspaper column) are under way. Her corporation -- Martha Stewart Living Enterprises of New York, which is a division of Time Warner Inc. -- brought in an estimated $200 million last year.<P>By linking her name and image with her products, Stewart has established herself as an icon of good taste. More important, she bucked the odds and created a brand that is inextricably tied to her -- she never has to worry about losing control of her company.	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="C">A</A></FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<IMG SRC="ledecky.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><FONT SIZE="-2"><P>Photograph By MICHAEL J. BOWLES</P></FONT>
<P>
	<FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR=#CC000C><P>The Hidden Giant</P></FONT>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>Jon Ledecky had a bold plan. If he could bring together a bunch of little office distributors, he could create the first giant office-supplies retailer. His secret: Let each small business maintain its name and local identity, instead of being folded into a faceless formula.<P>One by one, he went to 100 independent suppliers with a proposition: Join forces and create an industry-dominating giant. It was a bold idea -- and they thought it was nuts. ''Ninety-five of them showed me the door,'' Ledecky says. ''They said, 'That will never work.' '' <P>It was the same with the banks. Ledecky went to 40 investment banks; each turned him down. At the 41st, now-defunct Mabon Securities, he got bold. ''Sit down and strap yourselves in,'' he told the assembled bankers. ''I don't want you to fly out the window.'' He gave them his pitch, brazenly predicting $1 billion in sales within one year, and held his breath. <P>They bought it, agreeing to help him take this nonexistent business public. Ledecky acquired the five companies that had signed on and formed U.S. Office Products Inc. in Washington, D.C., in early 1995. ''I wanted to create something that is the antithesis of Wal-Mart in its approach,'' says Ledecky, 39. ''If you can keep these local companies vibrant and part of the community, then they're going to do just as good a job as any of the big national chains.'' <P>Under the U.S. Office Products arrangement, 50 percent of the owner's buyout is paid in company stock. Each owner and his key management personnel are guaranteed -- in writing -- employment for at least two years. ''I want to inspire loyalty,'' explains Ledecky. ''And I don't want them ever looking over their shoulder, afraid that the heavy hand of corporate is going to go back on its promises.'' <P>Once he got his company off  the ground, suitors came calling -- even the previous skeptics. Of the original 100 businesses Ledecky met with, 67 are now on board. He easily met his billion-
dollar goal in the first year. ''Our backlog of acquisitions is typically half a billion dollars,'' he says. For 1996, the total hit 130 acquisitions with combined revenues of about $3 billion. <P>Ledecky can't believe other industries aren't already leaping on his winning for-mula. ''This concept is applicable to so many different methods of distribution,'' he says. ''Local consumer-electronics stores, for example, should get together on a market-
by-market basis. They could be as big as Circuit City.''<P>The next target is the $300 billion international market. But within his company, Ledecky strives to keep a low profile. ''We're there to support the independent entre-preneurs,'' he says. ''Call any receptionist at any of our businesses and ask them who Jon Ledecky is. They won't know. That's the way it should be.'' 
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="D">A</A></FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR=#CC000C>Think Small, Grow Big</FONT>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>Bob Borchardt used to get all kinds of abuse from  buyers when he made sales calls to electronics stores.  ''They were courteous because they thought Bob was a good guy,'' says Alan Segal, an independent sales rep for Borchardt's company, Recoton Corp. ''But they'd always say things like, 'Why are you selling these wires and connectors and crap? You should be selling big-ticket items like stereos and televisions.' They thought Bob could make a lot of money if he had more exciting merchandise.''    <P>Those buyers figured Borchardt's product line  -- hookup cables and other accessories for home electronics -- was a penny-ante racket. But it was the only business Borchardt knew.<P>In 1936, his father, Herbert, started Recoton as a tiny manufacturer of steel phonograph needles. By the time Bob joined the business in 1961, the company also sold brushes, cloths, and a few other record-care products. Still, the business was doing only $500,000 in sales and struggling to survive.<P>''We had a good distribution system. We just needed more products to sell,'' says Borchardt, 58, now president of Recoton. In 1969, he went to Japan to line up suppliers, putting together a comprehensive line of accessory products: audio cables, headphones, cleaning products, and small speakers. Back home in the U.S., he started to plug for shelf space in stores. The buyers said he was crazy. They didn't want to push aside stereos and TV sets for wires.<P>''In the early days, we were really fighting for real estate,'' says Borchardt. ''We were asking for three to six feet to display our products. A piece of a wall. Anything. Because we knew our stuff would sell if they would push it a little. The consumers wanted it.''<P>Meanwhile, the electronics industry took off, with a boom in VCRs and other home-entertainment technology. As the corner electronics store disappeared and discount ''superstores'' began to dominate the market, profit margins on big-ticket items slid, and retailers were forced to find other sources of revenue. Borchardt's accessories, with their high profit margin, became much more attractive. <P>But Borchardt knew retailers didn't want to deal with dozens of vendors selling hundreds of different accessories. To transform his foothold into an industry-dominating presence, he had to create a one-stop resource for retailers.  <P>He began an aggressive campaign to raise capital, then started buying small manufacturers of accessories and bringing them under the Recoton umbrella.  In 10 years -- from 1983 to 1993 -- he acquired close to a dozen companies.<P>Today, from bases in New York City and Lake Mary, Fla., Recoton offers a comprehensive line of consumer-electronics accessories, ranging  from wireless speakers to antennas to video-game joysticks. The company sells under 18 different brand names, including Acoustic Research, Ampersand, Discwasher, STD, NHT, SoleControl, and Jensen, the speaker manufacturer, which Recoton acquired last year for $85 million. With the addition of Jensen, Recoton's sales surpassed $300 million in 1996.<P>John Bradley, accessories buyer for the West Coast electronics chain The Good Guys, watched Borchardt revolutionize the electronics industry. ''It used to be that retailers sold a big-ticket item in a box and never thought outside the box,'' he explains. ''Instead of trying to get the customer to say yes just once, Borchardt taught them that a salesperson should get the customer to say yes three or four times, get him to 'enhance' the product he purchased with a few other high-quality items.  He got them thinking in a whole new way.''
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="E">A</A></FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<IMG SRC="hanley.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><FONT SIZE="-2"><P>Photograph By CHRIS WADE</P></FONT>
<P>
	<FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR=#CC000C>Control Your Destiny</FONT>
</P>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>Bill Hanley did the impossible. He brought together his competitors and got them to join forces so all would thrive. <P>Hanley's company, Galileo Corp. of Sturbridge, Mass., is one of a half-dozen leading fiber-optics makers based in a small section of central Massachusetts. When he took over Galileo in 1984, its business revolved around $10 million worth of defense contracts. If the government stopped buying, the company would disappear.<P>He could have tried to cut back on government contracts. Instead, Hanley built up Galileo's defense work while the military was still buying, to $27 million in 1987, then used the proceeds to develop products for commercial users, including office products, medical equipment, and scientific tools. When the cutbacks came, in the early 1990s, Galileo survived only because it had started to build that base. <P>But the company and its local competitors were fighting for the same scraps of the remaining fiber-optics business, against a growing wave of foreign competitors in an increasingly global marketplace. <P>One day, Hanley found himself chatting with a writer from the local business paper about the fierce competition he faced. "Nobody can win in those circumstances," he said. "Everybody  is eating from each other's plate all year long. It's pretty unhealthy."<P>The writer posed an interesting question: If their rivalry was killing Hanley and his competitors, why not join forces? Work together to give each company its own niche and make sure everybody eats?<P>Everybody Hanley brought the idea to said it was impossible. But he refused to let it go. *<P>With the help of local chamber of commerce officials, Hanley put together a meeting with his five top competitors, all local CEOs. "They had the attitude of, Why are we here?" Hanley says. "I said there ought to be a way to work together and create an organization to represent the best interests of all our companies."<P>Hanley envisioned a future in which the companies marketed themselves as the region where fiber optics was born and where customers could tap a deep pool of expert labor. Separately, they would keep scrabbling for crumbs. Together, they would become a global giant. "We could secure our economic future," he told them. "We wouldn't be victims to economic cycles and military buying cycles."<P>The other CEOs didn't buy it. How could they cooperate after years of competing against one another?<P>Hanley went back and produced a white paper, laying out his vision in detail. He proposed that they found an organization called the Center for Advanced Fiber Optic Applications (CAFA), which would coordinate R&amp;D; develop new products and technologies to win business for all the companies; and promote the member companies to the outside world. <P>All the competitors jumped aboard, providing the initial financing to get CAFA up and running. More funding came from NASA, which kicked in with a $1.34 million grant, and the state, which floated a 
$2 million bond issue.<P>Now CAFA is targeting customers all over the world, marketing the central Massachusetts fiber-optics community as a hotbed of technology. Already, 18 percent of Galileo's business is overseas. The firm has less than $1 million in defense contracts, out of total revenues of $42.6 million.<P>"There's still a healthy competition between us, but we try to stay out of each other's niches," Hanley says. "We're now tightly focused on competition from outside, on what the Japanese are doing and the Chinese are doing."<P>Hanley believes the model can be translated into other industries. "People get tired of being victims. There's a lot of pain involved. If you can come up with a way to control your own destiny, people will join you."
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="F">A</A></FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<IMG SRC="power.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><FONT SIZE="-2"><P>Photograph By VERN EVANS</P></FONT>
<P>
	<FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR=#CC000C>Know Your Customer</FONT>
</P>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>James David Power stood before an array of the top power brokers from Italy's automobile industry and told them how his consumer surveys could help them learn more about their customers -- and sell a lot more cars. The reception they gave him was not warm, to say the least.<P>''During the question-and-answer period they blatantly told me I didn't understand their market,'' says Power, the 65-year-old chairman of J. D. Power and Associates. ''Their argument was, you can't come over from the United States and tell us how to market our cars -- we've been selling cars for a hundred years here in Europe.''  <P>It was d&eacute;j&agrave; vu all over again for the man who has changed the way American companies make and sell cars. Twenty-five years ago, when he first approached the Big Three automakers -- Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler -- they also gave Power the cold shoulder. Just a few years later, they got slammed.<P>''Back then, the Big Three were looking for research that confirmed what they felt was right for the consumer,'' says Power, who previously worked for Ford and GM. ''When we were trying to do research for them, we used to have a saying: Torture the data until it confessed. They really weren't interested in finding out what the customer was thinking.''<P>Power left Detroit and, in 1968, launched J. D. Power and Associates of Agoura Hills, Calif. His goal: to perform independently funded studies that would be free from bias. Because he paid for the studies himself, he owned the data and could sell it. <P>The question, of course, was whether anybody was interested in buying. The Big Three weren't -- not at first. When Power tried to sell their research departments his customer-satisfaction and vehicle-quality studies, he ran into a brick wall. Their attitude: What can some independent researcher tell us that we don't already know?<P>But Japanese automakers who were looking for a leg up on their American competitors bought Power's data and studied it carefully. It was a critical strategic tool in their campaign to break the American market -- and it worked.<P>By the mid-1980s, the Big Three were forced to listen to Power. ''Our goal has always been to help improve the quality of cars,'' says Power. ''People like Ralph Nader wanted to protect consumers, too, but I always thought he was anti-Detroit. We wanted to work with Detroit.''<P>Some say Power's surveys have been instrumental in the Big Three's comeback. Today, carmakers that rank high in Power surveys pay a licensing fee of as much as $250,000 to advertise the result. But that's a small price to pay when you consider that a J. D. Power and Associates No.1 ranking can potentially double the sales of a particular model.<P>Based on the success of his automotive surveys, Power has branched into the computer industry. Last year, revenues hit $46 million. His next -- and perhaps most daunting -- goal is to take his research overseas.<P>''We're facing the same resistance in Europe and the Far East that we once faced in Detroit,'' he says. ''They don't want us to upset the status quo. What we're telling them is that we just want to educate the automobile industry to better understand what's going on, not be blindsided like the Big Three were here in the United States.''<P> 
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="G">A</A></FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR=#CC000C>Health-Care Juggernaut</FONT>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	Rick Scott was a 34-year-old mergers-and-acquisitions lawyer when he bought his first hospital. In 1987, he and wealthy Texan Richard Rainwater paid $125,000 each for two struggling hospitals in El Paso. Practically everybody said they were throwing their money away. With 40 percent of the nation's hospital beds unoccupied, costs skyrocketing, and a record of terrible inefficiency, health care seemed like the wrong industry to bet on. But Scott had a plan.<P>He treated his hospitals as he would any unprofitable business. He cut costs by trimming the staff, consolidating operations, and negotiating better deals for supplies. He implemented quality controls.  Then he and Rainwater bought a nearby hospital that was competing for patients and shut it down. Soon, their first two were turning a profit.<P>In retrospect, Scott's idea seems simple: create a health-care company based on cost, quality, and customer satisfaction. But 10 years ago, few hospitals were practicing that credo. The industry was dominated by nonprofit hospitals that lacked the incentive to become more efficient. Scott argued that this was because no one running them had their own money at risk.<P>After El Paso, he began to duplicate, then refine, his experiment in other cities. He encouraged doctors to invest in his hospitals, believing that if the doctors who worked there had money at stake, they'd think of ways to become more efficient and more profitable. He also spent thousands, sometimes millions, of dollars to upgrade facilities after he bought them.     <P>Scott -- whose only previous business experience had been running a pair of doughnut shops -- has repeated this scenario hundreds of times over the past nine years, with remarkable success. His Nashville-based company, Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. -- he's the chairman and CEO -- has been gobbling up hospitals across the United States at lightning speed, fueled by a high-priced stock that serves as currency to buy more properties. Today, Columbia/HCA is the largest for-profit hospital chain in the country. It includes 347 hospitals, has combined revenues of $18 billion, and recently became America's ninth-largest private employer.<P>Scott's move to make hospitals leaner and more efficient is now being copied all over the country. Other hospitals have begun their own merger moves in an attempt to share costs and services.
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"><A NAME="H">A</A></FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT SIZE="+3" COLOR=#CC000C>Revolution In Progress</FONT>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>In his darkest days, in 1994, sleepless nights were the norm for media entrepreneur Chris Whittle. He had overextended his company, Whittle Communications LP, into too many divisions. For more than three years, he had been selling off his print-and-video empire to cut his losses. At the same time, he was trying to launch the first Edison Project schools: high-quality, privately run institutions funded by public tax dollars.<P>But his financial woes were widely known, and the conventional wisdom was that public schools were just that: public. They were run by individual school districts and certainly were not appropriate ground for entrepreneurs looking for profitable enterprises. ''The Jeffersonian dream was that every child would be provided with an education,'' Whittle says. ''It wasn't that a school district would have to do it.''<P>He had to prove his idea was possible. He would have to put up much of his own money to persuade investors to join him in his commitment to the project. ''I was betting the farm -- my homes, investments, everything. It was one of the few times in my business career that I really did feel the wind at my back. I've never felt like Edison wouldn't make it.'' <P>His vision: Boards of school districts would turn over tax money designated for each student's education to Edison, which would be contracted to educate those students. The kicker: Students at Edison schools would get a level of high-quality, more global and technology-oriented instruction enjoyed nearly exclusively by students attending elite private schools. The profit for Edison would come through cost efficiencies that would result in using less tax money. <P>In 1989, with 19 years under his belt in the media industry, Whittle had been asking himself what to do with the second half of his entrepreneurial life. He was invited to make a speech by a business round-
table. The subject: What he would do to change education in the United States.<P>He came up with two ideas. ''One, I thought that as a country we needed to invest more in the design of our education programs,'' he says. ''Second, I thought, Why not have the American free-enterprise system going into schools? Boeing doesn't build all its engines. Just because a public school system funds schools doesn't mean it has to do the educating.''<P>Then-Senator (later Secretary of Education) Lamarr Alexander was in the audience and, sparked by Whittle's ideas, asked for his notes. ''He tried in certain ways to institute some of the ideas in his state, and I saw how difficult it was for a politician to do. That's when I thought maybe I should do it.''<P>Whittle raised $75 million in start-up financing, much of it his own money. He brought together about 40 talented people from different sectors -- education, technology, media -- to form a think tank. Their ideas, gathered over a period of two years, would help design the educational program for what Whittle calls ''the first national network of great schools.''<P>In 1995, Whittle's vision became reality. Four Edison elementary schools opened in Texas, Kansas, Michigan, and Massachusetts, and four junior high schools opened in 1996. Four new elementary schools opened this past fall in Colorado, Massachusetts, Michigan, and Florida. Edison schools, housed within existing public schools, are generating revenues of about $37 million.<P>Whittle originally hoped to create 200 privatized schools by 1996, but revolutions take time. ''Do I think there will be 200 Edison schools someday? No. I think there'll be thousands.''
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<HR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"></FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><A NAME="K">Renegade Update 1993</A></FONT>
	<FONT SIZE="+3">Stanley Hubbard</FONT>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>In 1992, Stanley Hubbard, founder of U.S. Satellite Broadcasting Co., held up an 18-inch satellite dish before a meeting of cable-television moguls. With this invention,he told them, he would eat their industry alive.<P>The meal has begun. In the fall of 1993, he and his partners launched the first direct-broadcast satellite (DBS). Today, the service delivers as many as 200 channels of crystal-clear television to more than 4 million subscribers.<P>''For so many years we heard it was impossible, that nobody would buy a dish,'' Hubbard says. ''Now it's the fastest-growing home-electronics product in history.''<BR><HR>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"></FONT>
	</TD></TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Renegade Update 1991</FONT>
	<FONT SIZE="+3">Ted Turner</FONT></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>They all said Ted Turner was crazy for trying to create a national network on cable. All news? From Atlanta? Who would watch?<P>Then the Gulf War hit. The world tuned in to CNN. Its live-coverage reporting revolutionized the entire medium.<P>Today, the ones who laughed at ''Chicken Noodle News'' are copying his formula. NBC and Fox have launched their own 24-hour news channels.  <P>And the man who started it all just engineered one of the biggest mergers in history -- with Time Warner Inc. -- and reigns over an empire with revenues topping $7.5 billion.<BR><HR></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"></FONT>
	</TD></TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Renegade Update 1990</FONT>
	<FONT SIZE="+3">Steve Mariotti</FONT></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>When Steve Mariotti decided to teach poor, urban teenagers to become entrepreneurs and take control of their destinies, people said he was wasting his time. Those kids didn't have the discipline.  <P>Mariotti nearly went bankrupt creating the National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship. But his mission caught on with donors and sponsors, who gave him the funding he needed. His students grabbed the opportunity to turn their lives around, founding hundreds of businesses in 10 years.<P>Now other nonprofits -- such as the W. K. Kellogg Foundation and the Ford Foundation -- are instituting programs to encourage students to choose entrepreneurship over life in the streets.<BR><HR></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"></FONT>
	</TD></TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Renegade Update 1996</FONT>
	<FONT SIZE="+3">Jim McCann</FONT></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>Jim McCann built a telemarketing colossus with a product nobody believed could be sold over the phone: flowers. Now he is creating the model for building a fortune from sales over the Internet. <P>When he bought 1-800-Flowers, it was nearly bankrupt. McCann turned it into a $250 million success with revolutionary telemarketing strategies and a ubiquitous ad campaign that made him a household name. The company runs infomercials and has established a huge presence on AOL, CompuServe, MSN, and the Web, bringing in an estimated 20 percent of the company's revenues.<BR><HR></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"></FONT>
	</TD></TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Renegade Update 1993</FONT>
	<FONT SIZE="+3">Michael Bloomberg</FONT></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>After butting heads with his boss, Michael Bloomberg left his high-powered Wall Street job and created ''the Bloomberg'': a computer-and-software package that brought modern graphics and up-to-the-second market information to stock and bond traders. He created a new industry standard. More than 90 percent of his company's estimated $710 million in revenues is from that product.<P>But in a brilliant move, Bloomberg, having decided he was really in the information business, spun his financial expertise into an all-media empire, creating a new wire service, a radio station, a television-news provider, and newsletters. Now he's bringing the Bloomberg brand to Europe and Asia.<BR><HR></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<FONT SIZE="-1"><FONT SIZE="-1"><A HREF="#1">BACK TO THE TOP</A></FONT> <FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFFFFF"></FONT>
	</TD></TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Renegade Update 1992</FONT>
	<FONT SIZE="+3">Ely Callaway</FONT></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">
	<P>The old golf companies dreaded innovation. Then came Ely Callaway and the Big Bertha, a revolutionary new club that improved the performance of long-distance drivers. Next Callaway bypassed the golf specialty shops, marketing his club directly to consumers. It was unheard-of.<P>In 1991, revenues were $50 million. Last year, sales approached $700 million.  At age 77, Callaway just stepped down as CEO of Callaway Golf Co., remaining as chairman.  His newest venture: a subsidiary to manufacture technologically advanced golf balls.<BR><HR></TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>


<TABLE WIDTH="550">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">
	<H5><BR><BR><A HREF="1TOC.html">JANUARY/FEBRUARY 1997</A> / <A HREF="../../info.html">INFORMATION</A> / <A HREF="../../index.html">HOME PAGE</A> / <A HREF="../../subinfo.html">SUBSCRIPTIONS</A></H5>
	</TD>
</TR>
