Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<P>
<P>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>1EdNote.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	EDITOR'S NOTE / By Scott DeGarmo</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="../toc%20art/scott.jpeg" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="180" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><!--art credti here--></FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>A RENEGADE IDEA</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">John Goode Says There's a Time to Stop Being Disadvantaged</FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">A Renegade has guts, vision, and integrity. </FONT>

</P>
<P>John Goode, a black restaurateur from Austin, Tex., recently showed the world he had an abundance of those three qualities.<P>
Rather than allow himself to be certified as a minority, Goode lost a lucrative government contract. <P>
When you're struggling, a move like that takes guts.<P>
Why did Goode do it? Because he believed he was no longer ''disadvantaged.'' <P>
That kind of honesty is the essence of integrity.<P>
Now, Goode feels it is time others do the same. <P>
His ability to see the larger meaning in his actions, as well as his commitment to spread the credo of hard work and self-reliance, marks John Goode as a man of vision. <P>
A lot of protests are symbolic. In Goode's case, standing up for his beliefs meant the cancellation of his contract to sell barbecue from his restaurants at Austin's city convention center. <P>
''It has cost me dearly,'' he says -- adding that he has had no second thoughts about his decision, despite a significant loss of revenue that endangers his newly launched restaurant. In fact, the action seems to have reinforced his conviction.<P>
Goode originally signed on as a subcontractor to the primary concession operator for the city in 1989. He did so under a provision aimed at assisting new and struggling minority-owned businesses. Now his business has grown, and he no longer wants the ''disadvantaged'' label. Had he simply gone along with the system, he'd probably still be selling his barbecue at public events. <P>
''But I want to be judged on the quality of my food and the service that my staff and I provide,'' says the 51-year-old entrepreneur. ''Why should I be forced to participate in set-asides or affirmative-action programs?'' he asks. ''In the free enterprise system, you need to be able to stand on your own and compete.'' <P>
Unfortunately, the prime contractor did not see it that way and chose another minority business. <P>
Goode's stand on principle has inspired dozens of people to call or write to him. Some have traveled miles to visit him in his two restaurants -- both called Mr. Bones -- in the Austin area. One family drove from Lubbock just to shake his hand.<P>
Goode wants his action to set an example. <P>
''I think minority businesses need to understand that a lot of times affirmative-action and set-aside programs do more to hurt than to help. Everyone looks at us as being incapable of doing the job,'' says Goode. As a result, he adds, people ''never pay attention to minority-owned companies'' that are succeeding on their own merits, because they are good businesses.<P>
''Not everything can be blamed on racism,'' says Goode, who is concerned that affirmative action encourages minority youth to assume ''I don't have to work real hard because I am going to get a piece of it anyway.'' Goode also questions whether middle-class black college graduates can rightfully consider themselves disadvantaged.<P>
Goode started his culinary career as a pot washer in a Chinese restaurant, then moved up to dishwasher, fry cook, busboy, waiter, salad chef, and on to restaurant manager. By the age of 24, he owned a French restaurant in San Francisco. Other restaurants followed. <P>
Along the way, he's taken a slew of college classes, including bookkeeping, writing, and English. ''I've also read a lot, and most people I deal with figure I have a college degree. In fact, I can stand equal to most people with an MBA,'' he says with entrepreneurial self-confidence. ''Being a minority has given me strength. I was raised by my grandmother and uncle, who taught me two things: No one gives you anything, and never take no for an answer.''  <P>
Like other business owners, Goode often works long hours seven days a week at his two restaurants, attending to every detail. His original barbecue restaurant is filled with bric-a-brac and antiques that he's collected, such as old saddles, lanterns, and hand-crank ice cream machines. His new restaurant, in nearby Cedar Creek, serves a mix of barbecue, steaks, and seafood. Eye-catching Western-style murals cover the building, drawing customers from Highway 71 East, 30 miles outside Austin. Goode envisions hosting corporate events and picnics on the five-acre, parklike grounds. <P>
Now, if I were a CEO in the Austin area, I'd stop by a Mr. Bones for some fresh catfish or barbecue -- and I'd check out the premises for my next sales meeting or company outing. Then I'd sit and soak up the entrepreneurial inspiration! aSUCCESS in 1898. <P>

</P>
</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


