<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12Eye.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="6" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	THE ENTREPRENEURIAL EYE / Edited By Kristin Dunlap Godsey</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><!--art credti here--></FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>WASHINGTON WATCH</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Easier Retirement Planning</B></FONT><BR><BR><P>
There was bad news and good news in the Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996. The bad news for entrepreneurial companies: the minimum-wage hike. The good news: Starting this year, most companies with 100 or fewer employees can establish a new Savings Incentive Match Plan for Employees (SIMPLE). 
</P>

<P>
''This kind of retirement plan is similar to a 401(k), but it's easier and cheaper to administer,'' explains Jack LaBombard, assistant vice president of New England Retirement Services in Boston. It also marks the first time that very small companies -- fewer than 25 employees -- can provide a cost-effective salary-deferral plan.
</P>

<P>
Under the SIMPLE plan, employees can contribute as much as $6,000 per year of pretax income. Employers must generally match these contributions dollar for dollar, for up to 3 percent of pay, or contribute a flat 2 percent each year.
</P>

<P>
''This new legislation makes it more attractive for employers to provide everyone with tax-sheltered retirement plans,'' says LaBombard. The act also repeals the family aggregation rule, which lumped together the salaries of a husband and wife who co-owned a business; anything over $150,000 per year could not be counted toward a retirement plan. Now each owner can claim up to $150,000.
</P>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><P>
INTERNET</FONT><BR>
<B>Market Yourself In Cyberspace
</B></P>

You don't need ''professional'' Web hosting services or space in an online mall to get noticed on the Internet. Jon Bard, author of the audiotape series Internet Marketing for Beginners, offers do-it-yourself advice in a new, free booklet. For example:
</P>

<P>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Web-page design. Fancy, feature-filled sites are fine for some businesses but not necessary for everyone. Most Internet users are still using 14.4bps modems, Bard says, so it's a hassle for them to download complex graphics anyway. Instead, keep it simple. Software is available to help you design your own site, and you don't have to be a computer programmer to learn HTML.
</UL>
</P>

<P>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Promoting your site. Don't pay anyone to add links to your page. Search the Web for sites that are compatible in subject matter,e-mail them, and ask if they'd like to trade links with you. Provide your URL address so they can check out your home page. To get listed in search engines at no charge, just go to the ''Submit It'' Web site at <A HREF="http://www.submit-it.com">http://www.submit-it.com</A> and fill out the forms. 
</UL>
</P>

<P>
The booklet, ''Online Marketing: Do It Yourself &amp; Save Thousands,'' also recommends low-cost solutions for creating auto-responders and making your site interactive. For a copy, send a self-addressed, stamped, legal-size envelope to Two Mile High Press, Online Booklet Offer, 
P.O. Box 1030, Fairplay, Colo. 80440-1030. 
</P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+3">IPO UPDATE</FONT><BR>
<B>A Meaty Proposal
</B></P>

<P>
<DIR>
	<LI><B>Spotlight:</B> Famous Dave's of America Inc. 
of Minneapolis.
	<LI><B>Description:</B> Barbecue-restaurant chain.

	<LI><B>1996 Revenues (First Three Quarters):</B> $2.7 million.

	<LI><B>Amount Raised:</B> $2.7 million.
</DIR>
</P>


<P>
Famous Dave's has been around for less than two years and has only three restaurants. But CEO Dave Anderson was able to take it public on the strength of its short-term track record and his own business experience.
</P>

<P>
Local Twin Cities investors were sold instantly. ''Once they came to our restaurants and couldn't get in, they realized how hot this concept was,''Anderson says. Outside of town, he emphasized his role in taking the well-known restau-rants Rainforest Cafe and Grand Casinos public. 
</P>

<P>
''I'm looking to make this a national company with 500 stores in the next five years,'' he says. Funds from the IPO will be used in part to build a solid infrastructure through the creation of a management team and a training program.
</P></TD>
</TR>


