http://www.successmagazine.com:80/archives.html/jan97.html/1Global.html 199.92.136.187 19970114134410 text/html 5951
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Tuesday, 14-Jan-97 13:41:20 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 09-Jan-97 22:31:40 GMT
Content-length: 5760
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>1Global.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	GLOBAL ENTREPRENEUR / By Niklas von Daehne</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>THE BIG CATCH</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">Making Waves With an Off-the-Cuff Concept </FONT>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">


<P><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Christmas 1989 was around the corner, and Annoushka Ducas's mother, who sold fresh fish to 60 of London's top restaurants, once again wondered what to give her customers as a token of appreciation.</FONT>


</P>



<P>
''Why don't we design some fish cuff links?'' suggested Ducas, then a 23-year-old real estate agent with a passion for designing silver jewelry.
</P>

<P>
The chefs were delighted. Encouraged, Ducas called Harvey Nichols and Harrods, two of London's most exclusive retailers, asking whether she could drop by during her lunch hour to show them her cuff links. Both stores instantly caught on to the fish motif and asked Ducas to make a handful of other designs.
</P>

<P>
Sensing that her cuff links could help solve a common problem -- that of finding an original present for men -- Ducas quit her job and launched Links of London Ltd. with her boyfriend, John Ayton, who is a lawyer.
</P>

<P>
With only &#163;2,000 (about $3,100) in savings, Ducas and Ayton had little room for error. ''We made a firm decision that we would start slowly,'' says Ducas, who was born to a Russian mother and an English father. ''It was a business that we didn't know very much about.''
</P>

<P>
Shortly thereafter, her mother died, and Ducas took over the reins at her business, Rockport Fish Ltd. ''I did fish from five in the morning until noon,'' recalls Ducas, ''drove home, took a bath, and then did silver the rest of the day.''
</P>

<P>
Ducas picked up a few tricks as a fishmonger that she also applied to the silver trade -- such as working closely with just a few suppliers and never committing to vast quantities.
</P>

<P>
''I was never in a position where I got far too much stock,'' says Ducas. ''That's something I learned from the fish business. You do not buy too much fish.''
</P>

<P>
In 1992, Links of London opened its first retail shop in London's financial district, the City, offering cuff links for every taste: golf and tennis designs for athletic men; stars and moons for dreamers; and a pair with ''Buy'' on one link and ''Sell'' on the other for financiers.
</P>

<P>
<B>The Importance of Packaging
</B><br>
Selling what they call ''affordable luxury'' -- most of their cuff links cost between &#163;45 and &#163;65 -- to a male clientele, Ducas and Ayton created a retail environment that had the elegance and sophistication of a jewelry store but didn't make customers feel they had to spend thousands of pounds.
</P>

<P>
"We operate in a very stuffy industry,'' says Ayton, who is now married to Ducas. ''We have come up with something that is really fresh, new, 
and young. This is a very unusual way of selling 
precious metal.''
</P>

<P>
Slick product brochures reinforce Links of London's image, and the company also makes the most of packaging, believing that half the joy of a gift is presentation. In fact, Links of London, much like Tiffany's, has such stylish packaging it has become part of the gift itself. ''It's very rare that somebody buys something from us and throws the box away,'' says Ducas.
</P>

<P>
In 1994, as Links of London boomed, Ducas decided to sell Rockport Fish and devote all her time to the silver business. She gradually expanded the product line, adding such accessories as money clips and key rings, watches, tableware, and women's jewelry. Ayton, meanwhile, quit his job in 1995 to work full-time on a strategy to expand distribution further.
</P>

<P>
Links of London now operates five retail stores in London and has just opened outlets in Hong Kong and Melbourne. The company's merchandise is also sold in such select U.S. department stores as Saks and Bloomingdale's, as well as in Japan and France. Total sales for 1996 were expected to exceed $8 million.
</P>

<P>
Although Ducas and Ayton aim to establish a worldwide chain of independent Links of London stores, they stress that they won't compromise their carefully crafted concept to speed up growth.
</P>

<P>
''Our look is very clean and streamlined, so it can't take too much confusion,'' says Ducas. ''People come into one of our shops, and they know that whatever they'll buy, it's going to be silver or silver-plated.'' She adds, ''We will always be very, very focused. I think that's hugely important.'' After all, it takes patience to catch the big fish. a
</P>

<P>
Justin Leighton/Network/SabaAnnoushka Ducas's passion for fish and designing silver jewelry helped her build an $8 million business.<p>

SUCCESS contributor Niklas von Daehne covers the London financial markets for Bloomberg L.P.
</P>


</P>


<!--text goes here-->
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


