<DOCHDR>
http://www.successmagazine.com:80/archives.html/jan97.html/1CreativeFinancing.html 199.92.136.187 19970114134534 text/html 5927
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Tuesday, 14-Jan-97 13:41:55 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 09-Jan-97 22:30:37 GMT
Content-length: 5736
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>creative financing</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	CREATIVE FINANCING / By Ginna Jacobson</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="creative.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by TODD FRANCE</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR><BR>Capitalizing On an Idea</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">How to Fund Your Start-up Without a Product</FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">

<FONT SIZE="+1"><P>No product in hand, just an idea in mind. That's what Robert Vito had when he set out to change the home-electronics industry. His company would sell a revolutionary wireless technology that would transmit data from various sources over existing electrical wires. Every outlet in a home could be a phone jack; a CD player on one floor could send music to speakers on another; a computer in a bedroom would drive a printer in the basement; a cableless TV in the den could receive cable programs without rewiring if you have a cable TV elsewhere.</FONT><P>All he needed was $200,000 for a feasibility study. He looked to family and friends. Without a product, ''I had to sell them on the strength of the vision,'' says Vito, then a technology manager at Price Waterhouse who had worked on the idea with an inventor. The vision sold, and Vito brought in a veteran design engineer with an impressive consumer-electronics background.
<P>This first round of funding would spearhead a successful three-year quest. Beginning in 1993, Vito would amass more than $18 million in five rounds from 300 private investors. With each round, he would seek more capital to take his Malvern, Pa.-based Elcom Technologies Corp. to its next stage. Using a give-more-to-get-more strategy, he opted to decrease his equity from 40 percent in 1993, when he founded Elcom, to his current 11 percent stake. ''I'm more satisfied owning a small share of a successful venture than a larger piece of a less promising company,'' he says.<P>Use Experts to Back Up Your Vision<P>A team of engineers further refined the technology, and after six months Vito knew his idea could be executed. Next challenge: getting $1 million to build a plug-in prototype. He decided to put experts and prospective shareholders together.<P>For a week in early 1994 Vito held an open house at Elcom's small headquarters, seeking to raise the money from, he says, ''professional people we knew and people they knew.'' Still without a product, he showed potential investors his staff instead. Cofounder Myrddin Jones, with marketing experience from Commodore, Philips, GTE, and Sperry Electronics, helped explain the sales potential. Engineer Rudy Harford helped translate the technology.<P>Vito told his audience that he had taken a significant drop in income when he left Price Waterhouse to start Elcom. ''For shareholders to have confidence, you have to be personally at risk,'' he says. He offered shares of the company for $1 apiece. ''Everybody has to understand the stock's structure. Too often, entrepreneurs get involved with financial experts, and the numbers get confused.''<P>By December 1994, Vito had a prototype: ezTV. To get $3 million to continue research and begin production, he held another open house to give product demonstrations. ''There was no solicitation this time -- investors were coming to us,'' he says.<P>Financial stakes increased in August 1995, when he sought $4 million to contract out manufacturing of Elcom's first products. But now he had several prototypes, including ezPHONE, which puts phone, fax, and modem capabilities in any room that isn't wired for a telephone. ''Shareholders and potential investors could take the products home and test them there,'' Vito says.<P>Decide How Much Control to Sacrifice<P>By May 1996, Vito was ready to produce and distribute various products. Seeking a hefty $11 million, he worked with Pennsylvania Merchant Group, a Philadelphia investment-banking firm. Today Vito, also a professor of entrepreneurship at Penn State University, says he wishes he had approached the bank sooner. ''I could have ramped up the company a lot quicker. They have an excess of cash, a shortage of ideas, and they look for [start-up technology] companies like Elcom.''<P>Another wrong he'd right: create more stock at the outset. ''Management could have retained more equity, and more control, in the company,'' he says.<P>Whatever his regrets, Vito's vision, know-how, and reliance on experts have led outside analysts to estimate Elcom's sales to be $15 million this year -- with eight "ez" products sold on QVC, in catalogs, and in consumer-electronics retail stores. And his quest continues. He plans to raise an additional $20 million -- to expand product research and fund international sales efforts -- by going public. <P>Gianna Jacobson is a St. Louis-based contributing writer who specializes in finance and entrepreneurship.
	
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


