<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12DirectSell.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="6" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	DIRECT SELLING / By Duncan Maxwell Anderson</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="300" >
	<IMG SRC="direct.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><FONT SIZE="-2"><P>Photograph by RIED HORN</P></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+4">POSITIVE REVOLUTION</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>PN's Founders Aim to Create a<BR>New Culture</B></FONT><BR>
<P>
<P>Try this one on: Everyone in network marketing is interested in personal development. People improve their incomes using goals, self-discipline, public-speaking courses, and so on. Why not start an MLM company where the main product is -- personal development? That was Jeff Olson's inspiration. It's been a wild ride since he and his partner, Eric Worre, started their company, The Peoples Network (TPN) Inc., in Dallas two years ago. TPN sells satellite dishes and exclusive programming by such motivational superstars as Jim Rohn and Brian Tracy. It finally has hit its stride and begun to grow explosively. Paul Meyer, founder of the personal-development giant Success Motivation Institute, is now a partner. SUCCESS talked with Olson, the CEO and president.<P>How did you get into network marketing?<P>I come from corporate America. I was in management at Texas Instruments by age 26 and then started two companies. I was on an airplane when a flight attendant handed me an NSA tape. <P>Was that the first you'd heard of the industry?<P>No. I'd been to an Amway meeting 11 years before. At that time, I said to myself, ''Network marketing isn't for me. I'm a corporate guy.'' But now it occurred to me that if I'd joined Amway 11 years earlier, I wouldn't be starting over again -- I'd have a big business. I joined NSA and became one of the top distributors after a year and a half. When I went to Quorum a few years later, I became the top distributor and then CEO.<P>Where did you get the idea for TPN?<P>My partner, Eric Worre, and I realized that for people to keep improving, tapes and seminars weren't enough. They needed a nurturing environment. So we created a company where people buy satellite dishes to receive regular personal-development programming. The network is supported by people selling and consuming other products from our Global Mall catalog. Our goal is to create a culture of self-improvement that helps people overcome the negative environment around them.<P>How did you start?<P>For the first two years, we got the faculty together. It wasn't like starting another type of company, where you're formulating a vitamin or something. It was like herding cats. They're busy, they have other commitments -- and we're asking them to commit to a new network marketing company in their own arena. Then we had to produce 600 shows.<P>What did the program cost to join?<P>It was too expensive: $800. You got a satellite dish, teaching aids, books, videos, audios, and training programs. There was too much in the package. It was a Ferrari, and not everyone could get in. But it kept starts to where we could handle them.<P>What was cash flow like?<P>We were stretching our bills out to 90 days, longer with some people. Of course, it was the Peter-Paul-Mary payment schedule: ''Borrow from Peter to pay Paul and keep Mary waiting.''<P>Our software system blew up in September 1995. We had to start all over again, and it wasn't pretty. We were shipping to the wrong people, paying the wrong people. Honestly, I don't think we would have been successful through that if we hadn't had people who believed in our cause to change America, one family at a time.<P>What do you want to change?<P>We want to get people away from the 150 channels of garbage that are on the airwaves today and bring them into a positive culture. I think a society is defined by its heroes. Do Roseanne and Madonna and Dennis Rodman portray the values society should hold? If a show doesn't have sex, drugs, or death, you won't find it on TV. From birth to age 18, kids see 200,000 acts of violence. And we can't figure out why 13-year-olds walk up and shoot <BR>
people in cold blood. They've seen it on TV. They say that to have a cause, you need an enemy. I have <BR>
an enemy. <P>What got you onto this crusade?<P>Having a child. I want to know my daughter is learning that she can accomplish anything she sets her mind to. It's great to see so many kids of other TPN families growing up more positive and optimistic and alive.<P>What's your business goal?<P>To be in 10 million homes in North America. We're going to be big in videos, books, tapes, and seminars. We'll have a hosted home page on the Internet. I've had media companies come by, hoping to merge or buy us out. We have an interesting subscriber base. Anything we do will be on our terms, based on what's best for our people.<P>How big is TPN now?<P>In 1996, we had 50,000 subscribers and $40 million in revenues. In October, I reduced the price of signing up to $199.  Starts in October were two and a half times September's. November was 50 percent more than October. In 1997, we'll grow four- or five-fold, to 150,000 subscribers or more. I spent two years keeping the lid on this thing. Now I've taken it off. <P>Reid HornJeff Olson (above) and his partner, Eric Worre, created an MLM company that sells moti-vational and personal-development programming distributed by satellite television. Olson hopes The Peoples Network (TPN), now at $40 million, can overpower the negative influence of mainstream TV and change people's lives.<P>Senior editor Duncan Maxwell Anderson specializes in direct selling and entrepreneurial management.
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
<P>

<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

<P>
<H4><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>UPDATES</FONT></H4>

<FONT SIZE="+3">MLM Capitalism</FONT>
</P>


<P>* Herbalife International, based in Los Angeles, is on track to close  1996 with $500 million in wholesale sales. A recent meeting in St. Petersburg, Russia, drew 10,000.<P>* The Wave 3 Way to Building Your Downline -- by former SUCCESS senior editor Richard Poe -- has sold more than 60,000 copies, ranking fifth on The New York Times list of best-selling business paperbacks.<P>* A friend of SUCCESS's, giving a seminar in Sydney, Australia, asked how many in his audience had a personal or business relationship with someone in a foreign country. About 80 percent raised their hands. Even small MLM distributors have foreign downlines. Wired with fiber-optic cable and crisscrossed with cell-phone networks, Australia and New Zealand are direct-selling giants about to be born.
<BR><HR SIZE="1"><BR>
<P>
<H4><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>BOOK BONUS</FONT></H4>
<FONT SIZE="+3">The Right Goals</FONT>
</P>
<P>''People are not lazy,'' says personal-development author Tony Robbins. ''They simply have impotent goals -- that is, goals that do not inspire them.''<P>For years, Bill King of Salt Lake City frustrated his sponsors at Oxyfresh. He and his wife, Susan, used Oxyfresh products, but Bill wouldn't take the time out from running his dental lab to build his downline. He was a perfectionist and spent long hours in the lab custom-grinding dental crowns and bridges for a perfect fit. <P>Then fate seemed to play some cruel tricks on Bill: He lost four major clients and, with them, 40 percent of his business. He had to step up his already crushing work pace to replace it. At 39, he developed a chronic soreness in one shoulder and a numbness in his hands.<P>''You've got carpal tunnel syndrome,'' Bill's doctor told him. If he kept working, it could only get worse.<P>Bill's upline, Roland Fox, persuaded him and Susan to come to a leadership-training seminar at company headquarters in Spokane, Wash. Bill was asked to introduce himself and tell the other attendees what he would most like to do in life. He'd never answered that question before. ''Just once in my life,'' said Bill, ''I'd like to take my wife and go fly-fishing down in New Zealand.'' He was embarrassed by the modesty of his dream, yet he knew he'd spoken from the heart. The dream he had uttered would resonate in his life.<P>At this juncture, Bill's daughter sent him an article about the Internet. It occurred to him that the computer might help him get more results from his prospecting time each week. Bill underwent a transformation. The shy man who had tiptoed uncertainly through his Oxyfresh business for four years vanished. Another Bill King took his place, one who had seldom shown his face in public but had ruled his dental lab with an iron fist for more than 20 years.<P>What fueled Bill's transformation was his obsession with service. Bill alone foresaw a grand new direction for Oxyfresh that could benefit every distributor and customer. <P>He won over both Roland and Oxyfresh's skeptical CEO, Richard Brooke, and set about designing a massive corporate Web site.<P>Bill started a co-op. For a $1,000 fee, he would help any distributor create his own home page linked to the corporate Web site. Visitors could learn about the company, sign up by e-mail, find a list of co-op members who could serve as sponsors -- and even read the members' personal stories. Applications for co-op membership poured in.<P>Today, Bill still operates a dental lab in his house and leases another in Salt Lake City. In the first half of 1996, his Web site (http://oxyfresh.com) got more than 160,000 hits, generating 10,000 leads for co-op members. He has profited from some of these leads himself and has finally begun to develop his organization.<P>Bill recently got an unexpected -- but cosmically appropriate -- bonus as well. With Oxyfresh earnings, he bought a condominium in Park City, Utah. Because the condo was still under construction, the developer offered buyers a free round-trip ticket for two to anywhere in the world, plus accommodations. Last April, Bill and Susan set off on their dream trip to New Zealand and Australia. You can bet that Bill packed his fly-fishing tackle. a<P>-- Adapted from The Wave 3 Way to Building Your Downline, by Richard Poe.

</P></TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>


