<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>12books&Tapes.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="4" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	BOOKS AND TAPES / By Duncan Maxwell Anderson</FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT SIZE="+4">
	<BR>LIFETIME PROFITS</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">Building Sales Through One-to-One Marketing</FONT><BR><BR><BR>
	</TD>
	<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="100">
	<B><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>BOOKS</FONT></B>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="400">
	<P>
<B>Enterprise One to One, <BR>
by Don Peppers and Martha Rogers.</B>
</P>


<P>
The best way to build sales is no longer to sell one product to an ever larger number of people. Today, high-powered computers and interactive communications media let you do something much more profitable: sell a wide variety of products and services to one customer at a time, for a lifetime. In Enterprise One to One, Don Peppers and Martha Rogers, authors of the best-selling The One to One Future, show some of the strategies and products you can create.<P>You gain a growing share of a customer's spending by catering ever more precisely to his needs. For instance, in the near future, virtually all appliances will contain chips that let them learn and remember their users' habits and preferences. Your car will recognize you by your weight as you sit down -- and immediately set the air conditioner, seat, shock absorbers, mirrors, and music the way you like them. When you get your next car, these preferences can be uploaded to it.<P>Toy companies like the makers of Lego could advertise their Web site on their packaging. The site would help the company collect information about how children use a specific toy -- not for statistical market research but to find out what related products those individual children would like.<P>The Custom Foot, based in Westport, Conn., delivers made-to-order shoes from Italy in three weeks for the price of off-the-shelf shoes. A scanner that looks like a mirror takes all the dimensions of a customer's foot in 7 to 10 minutes. Coming soon: Show or sketch a picture of a style you want, and Custom Foot will have the shoe made for you. The owner of the Custom Foot has a valuable asset for a mass-market shoemaker like Ferragamo: the names, measurements, and style preferences of individual customers. He could even sell Ferragamo shoes -- custom-made, of course -- for a licensing fee.<BR><BR><BR>
<P>
<B>The Witch Doctors, <BR>
by John Micklethwait and Adrian Wooldridge.</B>
</P>
In The Witch Doctors, two editors from The Economist, John Micklethwait and Adrian Wooldridge, skewer the pretensions of the modern management-consulting business, which generated $11.4 billion in fees for 1994 and probably will bring in $21 billion in 1999. The book is brimming with ideas for the global marketplace.<P>Britain's super-consultant Charles Handy says companies will soon consist of a ''core company'' -- a small squad of entrepreneurs and bureaucrats -- aided by unskilled workers he calls ''somebodies,'' as in ''somebody can do that,'' and knowledge workers with portfolios of creative or analytical skills they market to a variety of companies.<P>At Wipro Infotech, a software firm in Bangalore, India, engineers are redesigning General Electric's internal software system for one fifth of what it would cost in the West. The finished product is transmitted to GE in America by satellite dish. Elsewhere in India, companies are acting as security guards by watching video screens of warehouses and offices in America.<P>McDonald's didn't succeed in Tokyo until it let a local entrepreneur create little snack bars in the city center, ignoring the suburban marketing plan favored by headquarters. The company let him use fattier meat to please the Japanese palate and change Ronald McDonald's name to Donald McDonald, since the Japanese have trouble with r's.<P>But perhaps technical products are universal. The authors recount a Peter Drucker story about a neighbor of his in California who sells medical beepers to hospitals all over the world. ''What about the language and culture?'' Drucker asked when his neighbor returned from installing a system in Osaka. ''I don't need to understand Japan,'' the man said. ''I understand hospitals.''<P><BR>
<P>
<B>Hope Is Not a Method, <BR>
by Gordon R. Sullivan and Michael V. Harper</B>.
</P>
Hope Is Not a Method is a book by two of the men involved with converting the U.S. Army from a ponderous, armed multitude into a mobile, high-tech force, a change completed after the Gulf War. The Army picked up technologies and management ideas from business. Entrepreneurs can learn much from the Army about leadership.<P>When planning for tomorrow's world, ''don't ask yourself what the 'next' organization will look like,'' say the authors, ''but rather, what the organization 'after next' will look like.'' Your idea of the next one will be constrained by today's realities. A man who works at an electronics firm told the authors that by the turn of the century, more than half the value added in his company's products and services will come from software. By staring that fact in the eye, the company is discovering that it has implications for everything from investment to personnel policies.<P>An American lieutenant-colonel in Vietnam beat back an ambush by a vastly larger Communist force over the course of four days by taking mental breathing spaces at regular intervals to ask himself three questions: What is happening? What is not happening? How can I  influence the action? 
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="100">
	<B><BR><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>TAPES</FONT></B>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="400">
	<BR>
<B>Advanced Tactics for Power Negotiating, <BR>
by Roger Dawson.</B>



<P>Power, says negotiation expert Roger Dawson in his new video, Advanced Tactics for Power Negotiating, belongs to the party who projects that he's more willing to walk away. If you find your dream house or the perfect commercial space for your business, before you sit down to negotiate, find two other locations you'd be almost as happy with. You'll project the fact that you have options, and have a better chance of getting what you want most.<P>Many things convey walk-away power, such as projecting that you have a consistent set of values. It suggests that you'll hang on when the going gets tough -- or walk away if something smells fishy.<P>Beware of this in yourself: ''I can't walk away from this. I've invested all this time negotiating.'' The time you've invested is gone. The question is, What's the best decision from this point?<P>Extra knowledge about the other side gives you an enormous edge. An information-gathering tip: People are always more likely to share information with professional peers than with those outside their profession. If you're going to buy another company, send your controller to have lunch with theirs, and your maintenance chief to have lunch with theirs. Warn your people not to reveal too much about you. They'll come back with all kinds of good stuff.<P>As Dawson always says, negotiation is the highest and best use of your time. What else pays you $1,000 or more per hour? Or $1,000 per second?
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE WIDTH="500">
<TR>
