<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>FRANCHISING: Multi-unit Masters</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	FRANCHISING: Multi-unit Masters</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="fran.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by<BR> GARY SPECTOR</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4"><BR>MARKET LIKE MAD</FONT><BR><FONT 
SIZE="+1">How One Man Built a<BR> McDonald's-Franchise Empire</FONT><BR><BR><BR>
<BR><BR><BR>
<P><B><FONT COLOR=#CC000C></FONT></B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"></FONT></P>

</TD>
</P>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><P>
<P>If you can sing all the ingredients of a Big Mac, thank (or blame) Max Cooper. In 1957, as a principal in the public relations firm Cooper,Burns &amp; Golin in Chicago, Cooper landed the account for a young hamburger chain called McDonald's. Since then, he's never stopped watching out for hot new ideas to keep McDonald's in the public eye. Today, as a multi-unit franchisee, he runs a whopping 47 restaurants in the Birmingham, Ala., area (the average McDonald's franchisee owns three). And he still puts his personal stamp on each store.</FONT> <P>Take, for instance, last winter. Cooper read in the paper about record snowfalls in Michigan, where the city manager of Sault Ste. Marie was scratching his head over what to do with it all. Cooper offered a solution. He spent $4,000 to have two truckloads of snow hauled the nearly 1,000 miles from Sault Ste. Marie to one of his restaurants and dumped into the children's Playland. Birmingham families lined up at 6:00 a.m. to experience a white Christmas. ''It rarely snows down here,'' Cooper says, a chuckle in his soft voice. ''The kids had a ball.''<P>As owner of one of the largest franchises in McDonald's 20,000-restaurant arsenal, Cooper knows a thing or two about growing a successful business. He's also picked up a few publicity tricks after four decades. He has a knack for knowing which gimmicks will become trends and which will be flashes in the pan (he's shown that both types have their place in shrewd marketing). He also believes originality is overrated. ''Publicity is the business of opportunity,'' he says. ''I've always felt that I don't have to be an originator -- just a good duplicator. You can take a small idea and expand it, or just ride along on a big idea.''<P>From Humble Origins . . .<P>McDonald's started franchising in 1956 and spent its early years building up stores in pockets of the country, such as Los Angeles, Cleveland, and Washington, D.C. The total number of franchises was still small when Cooper's firm was hired, as was his advertising budget. In pursuit of nationwide exposure, he and his partners would hound news columnists with story ideas.<P>''It was tough,'' says Cooper. ''If something wasn't happening in New York, they figured it must not be a trend.'' What was more exasperating, when something that happened at one of the stores did get a mention in the paper, writers would omit the company name -- referring only to ''a local restaurant.'' <P>As McDonald's grew, Cooper could afford to be more ambitious in his publicity efforts. His firm arranged for hamburgers to be served on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange. It sponsored a traveling all-American high-school band. <P>In 1964, Cooper took a two-year leave of absence from his firm to become the McDonald's national advertising man-ager, overseeing a staff of one. ''The advertising budget was $3 million,'' he recalls. ''The first thing I did was buy a one-quarter sponsorship of the Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade.'' The sponsorship entitled McDonald's to three and a half minutes of commercials, not to mention free advertising via the band in the parade whose members wore the company's logo over their uniforms. ''We had a big bass drum with our logo on it, too,'' he says. ''This was before the days when you saw ad slogans everywhere. So that surprised a lot of people!'' <P>Cooper became the franchisee of three poor-performing McDonald's restaurants soon after. ''The appeal of having the market to myself was very attractive,'' he says of the Alabama franchise. ''We didn't have a reputation here yet, and these stores had very low volume.'' The day he took over the units, a local competitor moved in next door to one of them. Just like that, the restaurant's volume dropped even further, by half. <P>''We had no money for promotion,'' Cooper says. ''It was a real struggle for about five years.'' He and his partner, Ed Levins, spent most of their time getting the operations side of things running smoothly. To put together a direct-mail campaign, they asked customers where they lived in order to target areas for more business.<P>Cooper quit his other business obligations to become a full-time franchisee in the early '70s, after McDonald's had hooked up with a national advertising firm. But he never lost his eye for hot promotional ideas, sometimes plugging innovations that turned out to be before their time. His restaurants have been serving combination meals at a discount -- the precursor to today's ubiquitous value meals -- consistently since 1975. The meals have always sold well, Cooper says, but ''nobody in the industry recognized it. It wasn't even copied by our competitors.''<P>About that same time, McDonald's ran a national TV ad for its Big Mac featuring the ''Two all-beef patties'' jingle. Cooper felt the idea had the potential to create a huge buzz, even though McDonald's wasn't making a fuss over it. ''I thought, What if we tried to get people to say the whole thing in four seconds?'' he says.<P>He took the audio off the 60-second spot and converted it into a local radio ad, which he ran relentlessly to get people familiar with it. When the time was right, the campaign hit the streets. ''We'd interview people at random and ask them to sing the jingle in four seconds,'' he explains. ''If they could, we'd give them a $5 gift certificate. Soon everybody in Birmingham was singing it. Once, at a restaurant, I overheard a guy practicing at the next table.''<P>Sales at the Bir-mingham stores shot up 25 percent, and the McDonald's head office took note. The campaign was relaunched nationwide, and the jingle is now considered one of the chain's most successful campaigns ever.<P>Speak Softly, Carry Big Ideas<P>Sitting in his office in Birmingham, beside a large bookshelf housing (among other company treasures) a bronze statue of Ronald McDonald, Cooper sips tea from a delicate, floral-patterned cup and saucer. He is not what you'd expect in a publicity machine. It is surprising to realize that, as the franchisee of 47 restaurants (the average worth of a McDonald's unit is $1.5 million), he is a rich man with considerable power. ''On the outside, I know I don't seem particularly creative or optimistic,'' he admits. He is well past retirement age, slightly disheveled, and he speaks barely above a whisper in an even, painstaking tone.<P>We breakfast on biscuits fresh from the McDonald's up the road. ''We've worked with them to improve the biscuit,'' Cooper says. ''As big as McDonald's is today, much of what is developed is one-size-fits-all. You can work on variations, though, as long as you get permission from headquarters.'' <P>At the store by 5:00 a.m. day after day, Cooper and one of his kitchen staffs tinkered with the biscuit recipe ever so slightly, going for a made-from-scratch taste. The result is fairly impressive. In fact, he still works closely with all his restaurants, likening himself to the high-ranking officers at the Pentagon. ''You have to know what it's like to take that hill,'' he explains. ''I'm always looking for ways to improve.''<P>As evidenced by last year's snow adventure, he remains a publicity man at heart. Even though McDonald's is now a long way from its humble beginnings -- you can't open your eyes these days without its logo dancing in front of you -- Cooper values the local touch. ''You buy into a franchise because it's successful. The basics have been developed, and you're buying the reputation,'' he says. ''But individual, local marketing is just as important, because of the additional exposure you get. You have to take personal pride in your business.''<P>For Cooper, that pride is nurtured by the challenge to stay creative. He attracts customers to one of his restaurants with a movie theme that features The Wizard of Oz. The floor is embedded with its own yellow brick road. The seating area is divided by a wall encasing dolls patterned after the characters. An old-fashioned white-lighted movie marquis spans the order counter. ''As with any company, to be a success in franchising, you have to have that burning desire,'' he says. ''If you don't have it, don't do it. It isn't easy.<P>''Besides,'' he adds, ''why would you want to run a business that's not perfect?'' *<P>SUCCESS associate editor Kristin Dunlap Godsey covers entrepreneurial trends and marketing techniques.

	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


