<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>monitor</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	OPPORTUNITY MONITOR / By Carol Steinberg</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="144">
	<BR><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR=#CC000C><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P>
<B>Spotlight:<BR> </B>BIG Entertainment Franchise Corp.
</P>
	
<P>
<B>Founders:<BR></B>Mitchell Rubenstein, Laurie Silvers.
</P>

<P>
<B>Concept:<BR> </B>High-tech kiosksand traditional stores that sell sci-fi/fantasy comic books and entertainment merchandise.
</P>

<P>
<B>Year Founded:<BR> </B>1993.
</P>

<P>
<B>Headquarters:<BR></B>Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>

<P>
<B>Total Initial Investment:<BR></B>$208,500 to $219,000.</FONT>
</P>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="406">

<FONT SIZE="+3">THAT'S <BR>ENTERTAINMENT!</FONT><BR>

<P>LOGO ?Opening a franchise in New York State is like flashing your name in lights. As the nation's third most populated state and fourth most touristed, New York offers companies enor-<BR>
mous exposure, which can drive franchise sales. <P>New York City units, in particular, ''make a franchise more high-profile,'' says David J. Kaufmann, senior partner at Kaufmann, Feiner, Yamin, Gildin &amp; Robbins LLP, a New York law firm representing franchisors. <P>Big Apple stores tend to be larger, costlier, and splashier. The city's aggressive media and investment communities ''compel franchisors to place high-visibility units in New York so that the important folks will learn the brand,'' Kaufmann says.<P>As a result, of the 12 states in which companies must register to sell franchises, New York usually is one of the first targets. It typically attracts about 200 new applications each year. During October alone, the New York State Department of Law okayed initial registration applications for 15 companies. Six of the approved companies are food-related, trying to break into such established segments as pizza, subs, and Mexican eateries. More unique concepts include a program for physicians to diagnose and treat male impotence, and early-childhood music education classes that begin when Baby is still in the womb. <P>The three entertainment-oriented companies in the group are United States Basketball League Inc. of Milford, Conn., which sets up teams of professional athletes that compete against other league teams; Color Me Mine Inc., a paint-it-yourself ceramics shop being franchised by Koo Koo Roo Inc., a Los Angeles-based chicken chain; and BIG Entertainment Franchise Corp.'s retail stores for sci-fi/fantasy comic books and entertainment paraphernalia. <P>BIG Entertainment is so en-thralled with New York that it plans to open its flagship store around Manhattan's 42nd Street.<P>Revolutionizing The Retail Environment<P>The founders of BIG Entertainment thrive on venturing into un-charted territory. Mitchell Rubenstein, 43, and his wife, Laurie <BR>
Silvers, 45, both attorneys, created the Sci-Fi Channel on cable television. After selling the channel in 1992 for an eight-figure sum, the duo launched BIG Entertainment Inc. a year later.<P>Their original mission was to develop an exclusive line of science-fiction and fantasy properties, using such celebrities and big-name authors as Leonard Nimoy, Mickey Spillane, and Tom Clancy. BIG publishes a line of comic books that includes Nimoy's Primortals and Spillane's Mike Danger. The company also licenses its 20 properties for films, video games, CD-ROMs, posters, and other mediums.<P>But Harry Hoffman, a board member of BIG Entertainment, realized the firm was sitting on a retailing gold mine. Hoffman, the former CEO of Walden Books, saw BIG's exhibit at a comic book convention and thought that by showcasing entertainment products in malls, BIG could create a new income stream. <P>In October 1994, the company opened a 560-square-foot retail store in the Mall of America, in Bloomington, Minn. It rolled out its first kiosk and within weeks quickly had seven in operation. ''I liked the portability factor,'' says Rubenstein, BIG's chairman and chief executive officer.<P>The kiosks attract customers by combining merchandise and entertainment -- a technique popularized by Disney and Warner Bros. ''You have to make yourself distinct from the rest of the crowd by enhancing the shopping experience,'' says Kurt Barnard, a retail forecaster and president of Barnard's Retail Marketing Report, headquartered in Scotch Plains, N.J.<P>The high-tech super-kiosks, positioned outside food courts, measure 166 square feet -- more than two to three times the size of an average kiosk. A bank of 16 TV monitors showcases movie trailers and merchandise promos. Racks display 700 different items, from the top 100 comic books, averaging $2.50 each, to such collectibles as a Star Trek 30th-anniversary pocket watch ($95) and Superman Doomsday bookends ($215).<P>''It's really the next generation of kiosk,'' says Rubenstein. ''We're like a light bulb in the mall.'' <P>Unlike Warner Bros. and Disney, which sell proprietary products, BIG, says Rubenstein, sells the ''best of the best from a genre'' by any company. The potential for top-notch salespeople to boost the average $14 transaction is enormous, he suggests. <P>In September of last year, for example, Superman-garbed employees hawked products that capitalized on the superhero's marriage to Lois Lane. ''We ride the coattails of what's hot,'' Rubenstein says. ''I call it Entertainment du Jour.'' <P>Sales at the units are soaring, at $1,700 per square foot, according to Shopping Centers Today. ''That's enormous,'' says Kurt Barnard. BIG Entertainment's retail operations contributed about half the public company's $8 million in revenues last year. It expects to turn a profit in 1997.<P>BIG's stimulating retail environment has attracted the attention of major financiers. A group headed by the cochairman of the nation's largest mall developer, Indianapolis-based Simon/DeBartolo Group Inc., recently invested in the company. <P>Now, with 29 kiosks and one tra-ditional store, BIG Entertainment plans to use franchising to open at least 200 units within four years. Area developers will buy the rights to develop whole markets. Rubenstein anticipates a hub-and-spoke approach: Traditional stores in malls will support surrounding kiosks.<P>The company has hired some franchise veterans -- including five former Blockbuster executives -- to execute its expansion plan. BIG has already developed a point-of-sale computer system, a buying group, and a distribution center.<P>The company-owned Manhattan store should have its premiere within 12 to 18 months. Rubenstein wants it to be out of this world. There will be wall-to-wall movie screens and circus-type performances by jugglers, sword swallowers, and comic book characters. ''Since everyone goes through New York at some point or another,'' says the founder, ''it will really give people an opportunity to see us.'' <P>SUCCESS contributing editor Carol Steinberg has been covering franchise businesses for national publications for a dozen years.</P></TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>


