<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>wilson harrel</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	WILSON HARRELL</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<BR><FONT SIZE="-2"></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR><BR>A LEADER LIKE YOU</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">The Test That Reveals Who Should Be ''First Banana''</FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">

<FONT SIZE="+1"><P>I recently got a call from Mike, an entrepreneur who is also an inventor -- a genius. Over the years, Mike has invented and patented several medical-care products, selling the patents to large companies that marketed the products and paid Mike a royalty. He's made a lot of money. But with his last invention, a high-tech apparatus for hospitals, he decided to develop and market the product himself.
</FONT><P>He organized a company, formed a board of directors, recruited a president, raised about $5 million from friends and relatives, developed a prototype, and conducted successful market tests. The product is now ready to be launched. The potential is enormous. Mike is chairman and CEO and still owns 55 percent of the stock. But he had a question: <P>''Should I remain CEO, or is it time for me to bow out and appoint someone else?'' <P>It's a question every entrepreneur faces one day. I asked, ''What do you want to do with your life?''<P>Mike's answer: ''I hate all the details involved with running the company. I dread going to the office. I was happy as long as we were developing the product and getting it ready for the market. But now I'd much rather be back in my laboratory working on something new.''<P>''Who will be the new CEO?''<P>''I'm not sure. Naturally, I've thought about making our president -- Bob -- the CEO. But somehow, I'm concerned. He's done a great job handling all the details I detest, but he doesn't have a fire in his belly. When we're together in a meeting and it comes time to motivate, I find myself doing all the talking while he sits quietly nodding his head. Maybe I should stay as chairman and CEO and let Bob continue as chief operating officer for a while.''<P>''Mike, is Bob a 'First Banana' or a 'Second Banana'?'' I asked. Mike looked at me as if I were nuts, so I explained: A few years ago, when I was wrestling with the problem of replacing myself in a company, my friend and counselor, Art Linkletter, asked me that same question. Way back in the days of vaudeville, the star of the show was always called the First Banana. Everybody else in the cast was a Second Banana. In the corporate world, you can always spot a First Banana. When he walks into a room, you somehow feel his presence. When he speaks, people listen. Wherever he stands is always center stage. Wherever he sits becomes the head of the table. I repeated my question to Mike: ''Is Bob a First Banana?'' <P>Without a moment's hesitation, Mike said, ''No, he's not.'' End of discussion. An entrepreneurial company can't survive without a leader who takes command and draws people's assent by the sheer power of his personality. Bob will not become CEO. The next question: ''Who will?'' Entrepreneurs spend their entire business lives picking the right people to work for them. And even if they pick the wrong ones, they can motivate them to go beyond their capabilities. Yet when it comes time for entrepreneurs to replace themselves, they make horrible mistakes. <P>Part of the problem is that, being leaders, we surround ourselves with Second Bananas who are content to fulfill our vision. Unfortunately, when we want to leave, no one within the company is qualified for the CEO's job, so it goes to an outsider. And that's after executive search agencies, consultants, and boards of directors have reached a consensus. And we all know what great decisions committees make! Is it any wonder that most entrepreneurial companies fail after the departure of the founder? If the company is large enough and if the product or service is strong enough and if there are sufficient financial resources, the company will probably survive. If not, the anointed leader won't have the guts and imagination for the task, and disaster follows.<P>Find a Star<P>Mike's company is preparing a national rollout with enormous growth potential. The CEO must be someone who can recruit and motivate a team of racehorses -- a true First Banana. But they're hard to find, because most of them are off doing their own thing or living out in tinsel land with Art Linkletter and the other stars. My recommendation to Mike: Go find a company run by a First Banana who is in a similar or related business, and merge your company with it. If you don't like that idea, grit your teeth and run the company until it's rich enough to bring in management. Then go public or sell out. <P>When that day comes when you're ready to pass on your leader's mantle, don't let friendship, loyalty, years of service, or personal relationships ever persuade you to install a Second Banana. After all, you've got to find a worthy replacement for a world-class First Banana. Right? Right! a<P>To obtain For Entrepreneurs Only or Harrell's video, The Entrepreneurial Revolution, see page 79.<P>Gary MossWilson Harrell is a consultant and speaker to the entrepreneurial market and the author of the book For Entrepreneurs Only. To reach Harrell, fax him at 770-889-4030.
	
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


