<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>the entrepreneur</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	INSIDE TRACK / The Entrepreneur / Edited by Kristin Dunlap Godsey</FONT><BR><BR><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	
	<IMG SRC="water.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="144" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by ANDY GOODWIN</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>A JOLT OF INSPIRATION</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><!--deck goes here--></FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">
<P>Like most college students, David Marcheschi used to pull all-nighters cramming for tests. But while others had no trouble gulping coffee and soda to stay awake, Marcheschi hated the taste of both. Why couldn't someone caffeinate plain water? he wondered.</FONT><P>A few years later, Marcheschi was still hunting for a drink with the kick of caffeine but without the flavor. Over lunch with a friend, he mentioned his idea. The friend's father, it turned out, owned a beverage company with a staff chemist. The chemist agreed to look into it.<P>Within weeks, he had perfected the formula for Water Joe, a half-liter bottle of spring water laced with as much caffeine as an eight-ounce cup of coffee. Marcheschi took the formula, created a label, and prepared to launch his product. Unfortunately, nobody was willing to bottle his brew. ''To bottle Water Joe, a company would have had to purchase special equipment,'' Marcheschi says. ''That led to a lot of noes.''<P>Late in 1995, after two years of meeting with bottlers all over the country, Marcheschi found an artesian well-water company in his own backyard. Nicolet Forest Bottling of South Barrington, Ill., already had a water distribution system in place. Even better, the company wanted to form a partnership with Marcheschi. He jumped at the offer. He could now launch Water Concepts LLC without the high start-up costs he had anticipated. <P>In its first months, Water Joe seemed a natural for the 24-hour convenience stores and truck stops that cater to bleary-eyed customers. But Marcheschi was confident of a broader market.<P>''Our product fulfills the niche of coffee and then some,'' he says. He rattles off a list of hooked customers: athletes looking for a boost, bands that perform late into the night, and dental patients whose teeth are turning brown from coffee. ''People are making lemonade or orange juice with it,'' he adds. <P>And the real diehards are using it to brew coffee.&#009;<P>By the end of 1996, after about a year of full-scale production, Water Joe was shipping 400,000 bottles each week to every state in the country. Annual sales for the Chicago-based company are about $12 million, says an industry analyst.<P>By emphasizing the caffeine in the product, Marcheschi is positioning Water Joe as a soft-drink alternative to Coke and Mountain Dew and is situating it next to them on store shelves. ''The bottling companies that said no at first are asking to bottle for me,'' he says. "Now there are knock-offs of Water Joe -- so I know we're legitimate.'' </P>-- Gianna Jacobson<P 
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


<TABLE WIDTH="500">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">
