<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>hot opps</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	INSIDE TRACK / Hot Opportunities in Nostalgia</FONT><BR><BR><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="175">
	
	<IMG SRC="hotopps.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by ANDY GOODWIN</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4"><BR>SOLID GOLD '70s</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><!--deck goes here--></FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3" WIDTH="325">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Selling to Generation X, with its 60 million consumers, can be lucrative -- if you can get their attention. Some entrepreneurs attract twentysomethings in droves by taking them back to their childhood.</font>
<P><B>Razor &amp; Tie</B></P>You can't talk about '70s revivalism without mentioning Cliff Chenfeld and Craig Balsam, cofounders of Razor &amp; Tie in New York City. These two arguably started it all.<P>''It was late 1989,'' says Chenfeld. ''The country was in a recession, and we thought younger people might be getting nostalgic for the sillier parts of the '70s.''  They quit their jobs as corporate lawyers, put together a compilation album called ''Those Fabulous '70s,''  and sold it on TV. As a selling point, buyers were offered free membership in The '70s Preservation Society, of which Chenfeld and Balsam were chairmen. Customers ate it up.<P>''That record grossed $2.25 million,''  Chenfeld says. More compilations followed. The '70s Preservation Society kept the buzz going through merchandising and national events like the Lava Lamp Awards (which awarded Danny Bonaduce, TV's Danny Partridge, the mantle of ''Sexiest Man of the '70s''). Member surveys -- Did David Carradine really know kung fu? -- and special reunions of '70s bands and sitcom casts kept the mood light and sales brisk.<P>Razor &amp; Tie moved into '80s compilations and generated nostalgia for the present with its ''Living in the '90s.''  The company now has a record label of its own and is signing new artists, such as Cledus T. Judd, country music's answer to Weird Al Yankovic. Its total revenues exceed $20 million.<P><B>Hometown TV Inc.</B><P>Who wouldn't want a license plate holder that reads: ''I'd rather be sailing with Gilligan and the Skipper''? Greg Akers and Mendy Abrahamson, founders of Hometown TV in Cincinnati, have a whole line of goodies featuring goofy sitcoms of the past. It all started with The Andy Griffith Show.<P>''We both loved that show as we were growing up,''  says Akers, 33. ''When we were in college, we'd try to buy each other Mayberry stuff. But it was hard to find.'' <P>In 1991 they secured the license to the show, got a loan from the bank in their old hometown, and started developing products. The newly formed Hometown TV mailed its catalog to the show's 3,000 fan club members in October 1992. Soon after, The Cincinnati Enquirer ran a flattering article that included the company's 800 number. The piece was picked up by 93 newspapers across the country.<P>"That Christmas, we were getting calls from all over the place," says Akers. Things kept getting better: The restaurant chain Cracker Barrel started selling the products, and Andy Griffith himself requested some jackets. "I thought, 'Pinch me!' " Akers laughs. "The cast members wore them on a reunion special on TV, and after that, our phones rang off the hook."<P>Gilligan's Island seemed a natural next step. That catalog was launched with a three-hour tour down the Ohio River: The actors who played Gilligan, the Professor, and Mary Ann were the guests of honor.<P>Today, with sales of about $1 million, Akers and Abrahamson don't have to chase after other old sitcoms. Favorites like I Love Lucy are coming to them. Best of all, thanks to reruns on cable, the market for merchandise has expanded. ''Little kids are watching,''  says Akers. ''There's a whole new group of fans.''  <P><B>Figures Inc.</B><P>In 1989, at the age of 18, Anthony Balasco looked at his massive collection of action figures -- characters from Star Wars, The Six Million Dollar Man, even the rock group KISS -- and saw opportunity. He bought up a bunch more and placed ads in collector magazines to sell them. Seven years later, little has changed in Balasco's business strategy. Today, however, his Figures Inc. of Cranston, R.I., is a $1 million company.<P>''This market has definitely grown,''  says Balasco. ''People who loved this stuff as kids are grown up and have money.'' <P>So if you're looking for a Luke Duke to round out your Dukes of Hazzard collection, Balasco's your man. Ditto if you've always wanted your very own Andy Gibb doll. Figures Inc. does all its business through mail-order and carries hundreds of items. ''It's getting harder and harder to get stuff from the '70s,'' he says. <P>Balasco relies on specialty-magazine ads, trade and toy shows, and word of mouth to sell his wares. He hopes to broaden his reach in the near future: ''This industry is pretty big overseas.''
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


<TABLE WIDTH="500">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">
