<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12ITmarketing</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	INSIDE TRACK / MARKETING</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<BR><FONT SIZE="-1"></FONT><BR><BR><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4">LICENSE TO SELL</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><!--DECK GOES HERE--></FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<FONT SIZE="+1">Rubin rides on big-name coattails to success.About fifteen years ago, Helen of Troy Corp. hit the wall. Although the little-known company from El Paso, Tex., sold $10 million worth of beauty appliances to salon suppliers in 1981 and held 25 percent of its market, sales were flat and there was no growth in sight. CEO Gerald Rubin knew he had to take some products to retail to create momentum.</FONT><P>The key to going retail, thought Rubin, was name recognition. Helen of Troy didn't have the money to launch a major advertising campaign, so Rubin searched for a cheaper way. <P>Acting on a tip from his father, a beauty industry wholesaler, Rubin went to Vidal Sassoon with a sweetheart deal: He'd give the company $100,000 up front and an above-market 10 percent royalty in exchange for its glitzy name.<P>It worked. Helen of Troy may still toil in virtual anonymity, but its products are everywhere -- in disguise. The company rides on the coattails of big retail players by setting up licensing agreements.<P>''If we had not gotten the name, we would still be a $10 million company,'' says Rubin, 52. As soon as the deal was signed, he pumped out a line of consumer hair-care appliances labeled with the Vidal Sassoon moniker. The products sold like an old stalwart. Helen of Troy's sales grew twelve-fold over the next 10 years. In 1992, Rubin orchestrated a similar deal with Revlon, and soon products carrying the two well-known tags accounted for 80 percent of his business.<P>Vidal Sassoon (which was acquired by Procter &amp; Gamble in 1985) and Revlon spend a combined total of about $300 million on advertising each year, so Rubin reaps those benefits without spending a dime. He also sidesteps large commitments of capital by contracting manufacturing to factories principally in China. <P>Last October, Helen of Troy acquired the rights to the Dr. Scholl's name for footbaths and massagers. Sales for 1996 exceeded $200 million. The company still sells its original line of appliances to salon professionals as well.<P>Having been around curlers, bobby pins, and shampoo all his life, Rubin has confidence in his products and has not been afraid to take risks. ''We know we can uphold and maintain the integrity of the brand names,'' he says. <P>He hopes to capture more than half of the personal care market and make Helen of Troy a $1 billion business in 10 years. The plan is to stay the current course. ''We're constantly looking for brand names to license,'' says Rubin. <P ALIGN="RIGHT">-- Justin Brown<P ALIGN="CENTER">
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


