<HEAD>

  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">

  <TITLE>  1 ITScope.html</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">





<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" WIDTH="500">

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">

	 <FONT COLOR=#CC000C>Inside Track /SUCCESS SCOPE</FONT></TD>

</TR>

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500"><BR>

	<FONT SIZE="+4">Cutting-edge concepts from business

journals and newsletters</FONT><BR><BR>

	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="111">

	<IMG SRC="../jan97.html/Feedback.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="92" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Illustrations by <BR>SCOTT MATTHEWS</FONT>

	</TD>

	

	<TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="300">

<B>	Collect Customer Feedback

</B>

<P>For new-product development and market expansion, customer feedback is the key, says Sales &amp; Marketing Management. If you can afford it, custom market research firms will conduct surveys and focus groups based on any parameters yougive them. Less expensive resources include market research firms and syndicated-service research firms, which gather broader data and sell it. <P>Once you get the information you need, you can use it to target specific groups of customers more accurately. Ferret out poorly served customer niches, and hit them for more sales. Identify the best growth opportunities, both nationally and internationally, and set long-term marketing strategies accordingly. ''Any company can profit from customer feedback,'' the publication states.  <P>

	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="111"></TD>

	

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="300">

	<B><!--head here--></B>





<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>

<!--copy here-->

	</TD><Td></TD>

</TR>

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="411">

	<B>Managing Generation X</B>

<P>Twentysomethings have different ideas about the role work plays in their lives, according to Nation's Business magazine. What motivates them to perform may surprise their baby-boomer bosses. These employees value a sense of fun, recognition for good work, cross-training, and flexible scheduling in the workplace. ''Generation Xers want to make a meaningful contribution,'' says the publication.</P>

To manage them effectively:

<UL TYPE=DISC>

	<LI>Focus on results, not processes.

	<LI>Set clear deadlines for tangible results.

	<LI>Give them freedom to manage their own time and work.

	<LI>Provide opportunities to interact with others (Generation Xers work well in teams).

	<LI>Give constant, specific feedback.

</UL>

	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">

	<IMG SRC="../jan97.html/Genx.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="125" BORDER="0">

	</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>

