<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>1 Tech Clinic</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE / Cyber Forum</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="clinic.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="144" HEIGHT="144" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by SCOTT SCHULMAN</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4"><BR>BEING THERE</FONT><BR><FONT 
SIZE="+1">LapLink Puts you Behind Your Desktop When You're on the road</FONT>
<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<B><A NAME="9">Bulletin Board</A></B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">Power Photos</FONT><BR>

<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
MGI Software Corp. has released Version 8.0 of PhotoSuite, the popular photo software product. PhotoSuite allows you to capture, edit, catalog, and transform photos easily so you can insert them into your multimedia presentations, promotional materials, and even your Web page.<P>As in previous versions, PhotoSuite includes its share of special effects and play tools.  For instance, you can make your own custom sports cards from pictures of your employees or friends instead of from pictures of real players.  But what's new in Version 8.0 is greater compatibility with the Internet.<P>Use PhotoSuite as the default image viewer in either Netscape or Microsoft Explorer, and you can capture images from your favorite Web sites.  Also, clicking on the "Convert Album to HTML" feature allows you to turn a photo album you created in PhotoSuite into a Web document.  Each photo is reduced to a postage stamp-size image (JPEG) that's linked to a full-size photo and description.  With this feature, you can place your entire catalog of products on the Web with only a few clicks of your mouse.<P>PhotoSuite retails for $79.95 and is available for Windows and Mac users.<P></FONT>  

<FONT SIZE="+2">Telephone Manager</FONT><BR><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>If you wish you had a secretary to screen your calls but can't afford one, the YoYo, from Big Island Communications Inc., may be the next-best option.  It's a hardware device that connects your telephone to your computer and turns it into a powerful telephone manager.<P>YoYo, which costs around $150, logs your calls, dials numbers for you, even pages you if you're away from your computer.  But the real fun starts when you get Caller ID, which is available in almost all states (contact your local phone company).  With each incoming call, YoYo displays the name and number of the caller on your computer screen.  If that number's on your "block" list, the call goes straight to your answering machine.<P>Another nice feature:  The YoYo can also automatically access records in your YoYo phone book or contact manager so you'll know exactly who's calling before you pick up the phone.   <P>YoYo was originally designed for Mac, but it's now available for the PC, too.</P></FONT>

<FONT SIZE="+2">Just for Photos</FONT><BR><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
Polaroid has come out with an affordable scanner for people who want to digitize their photos.  Priced at $299, PhotoPad, which is about the same size as a Polaroid camera, allows you to scan any photo (up to 4-by-6 inches) quickly and easily  into your computer.<P>The PhotoPad software offers you a choice of scanning resolutions that range from 100 dpi to 400 dpi, automatic color correction, and exposure controls.  Capturing an image requires just one step after you place the photo on the scanner.  Click on the on-screen capture button, and the image appears on your screen in less than a minute.<P>You can then manipulate and save the image in a variety of formats by using additional software that Polaroid has packaged with the PhotoPad.
<BR><BR><BR>
<P><B><FONT COLOR=#CC000C></FONT></B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"></FONT></P>

</TD>
</P>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">It's 11:00 p.m. and Kirby Knight is in a hotel room in Los Angeles, preparing a bid to sell his low-fat, all-natural sausages to a national restaurant chain. But he needs to see updated sales figures that are stored in his desktop computer at his office 250 miles away.</FONT> <P>No problem. Knight, the 47-year-old CEO of San Luis Sausage Co. of Los Osos, Calif., has LapLink for Windows 95 on his Canon Innovabook laptop. He dials up his office computer via modem, launches LapLink, and after a few clicks of the mouse, he's looking at what's on his desktop's screen. <P>If you spend a lot of time on the road, as Knight does, remote-access software is something you should look into. From his laptop in his hotel room, Knight can control all the functions of his desktop PC as if he were at its keyboard. He can work on any file and save it on both computers. He can cut, copy, and paste data back and forth between computers. And though they're in different cities, Knight and his wife, Grace, who creates all the company's sausage recipes, can edit a document, such as a contract, simultaneously.<P>''It's great for collaborations,'' Knight says. ''With e-mail, you can't work on a document with another person at the same time.''<P>Knight uses LapLink, from Traveling Software of Bothel, Wash., to transfer price lists, spreadsheets, presentations, and other information among his laptop, his office PC, and his home PC. Since LapLink features multiple simultaneous connections, he could even work on all three computers at the same time -- the program can connect him to as many as 11 computers.<P>Remote control sounds great, but transferring data by modem cross-country or around the world can run up quite a phone bill. LapLink, however, has several features that help you save money.<P>* It's fast. LapLink uses compression <BR>
technology to make file transfers as quick as possible. Maximum speed can be achieved by reducing the full color spectrum to black and white. With a 28,800 modem, it takes only  a few seconds to transfer a page anywhere in the world.<P>* If you have Microsoft System Agent as well, you can schedule unattended file transfers when long-distance phone rates are lowest. For example, you can instruct LapLink to update your sales reports on all your computers in the middle of the night.<P>* If you lose your modem connection during a transfer, LapLink remembers where it was and sends only the missing portion of the file when you reconnect.<P>* You can log on the Internet with a local call and connect with any other LapLink user who is online. So two people in different cities can agree to log on at the same time and conduct business for the cost of a local call.<P>When asked if LapLink helps him save money, Knight shakes his head. ''No,'' he says. ''It helps me make money.''<P>San Luis Sausage, which supplies the Ritz-Carlton, Peninsula, and other hotels, resorts, and restaurants in 10 states, plans to go national soon. Sales have doubled every year since the company was founded in 1989. And Knight is negotiating with Disney to offer a ''signature sausage'' for its theme parks.<P>Says Knight: ''As entrepreneurs, one thing we have going for us over a large company is that we can make decisions and change gears quickly. <P>"Thanks to LapLink, I can prepare a document at 6:00 in the morning and have it on somebody's desk before they get to work. If I can show that company I'm more interested in its business than somebody else is, things will go my way.
<HR>
<P>
<B>What You Need</B>
<BR>
S P E C S H E E T
</P>

<P>
LAPLINK. Price: $149. Requirements: Windows 95 or 3.1, Intel or compatible 386 DX 33MHz, 8MB RAM, VGA monitor, 7MB hard disk space. A trial version of LapLink is available for download via Traveling Software's home page at <A HREF="http://www.travsoft.com.">http://www.travsoft.com.</A>
</P>
<P>
SUCCESS contributing editor Dan Gutman can be reached at <A HREF="mailto:DanGut1@aol.com.">DanGut1@aol.com.</A>
</P> 
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


