<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>1 TechatWork</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="1" CELLSPACING="5" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>TheTechnology Edge Edited by David Carnoy<BR>TECHNOLOGY AT WORK BY FRANK HERTZ</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
	
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+5">Wireless Wonders </FONT> 

<H3>Make Yourself Reachable Anywhere
</FONT></H3>
	</TD>
</TR>
 

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<BR><BR>
<P><B>WyndMail</B><P>Christopher David had a problem. David, the director of client resources for the Association of American Medical Colleges in Washington, D.C., was expected to respond quickly to queries of the association's most nervous and demanding clients -- medical school applicants -- even while on the road, far from his desktop computer or a phone line. <P>''If someone is having a problem submitting their application or with one of the association's software products, that has to be taken care of quickly,'' David says. ''It's crucial for me to be able to check and send my e-mail without having to go to my office.''<P>David decided to get a second e-mail address through WyndMail, a two-way wireless messaging service from Wynd Communications Corp. of San Luis Obispo, Calif. Now he can receive and send e-mail through his wireless modem wherever he is, even in the back of a taxi, rushing across town. Better yet, he can use his keyboard to send voice messages to any phone number. ''This is Christopher David,'' a computer-generated voice might say. ''I am stuck in traffic. I will be 15 minutes late. Sorry about the delay.''<P>When David receives e-mail, WyndMail sends a wireless signal to his notebook, first with a ''snapshot'' of an incoming message, then a download of the full text. The snapshot includes such information as the sender, the message's subject, and the time it was sent. After he looks at the snapshot, David can then decide to receive the message, store it on WyndMail's Internet server, or delete it. <P>''It lets me decide how best to handle my work,'' he says. ''It saves my clients time, and it saves me time.''<P>* WyndMail. Price: $29.95 per month (includes 200 150-character messages) plus 5 cents for each additional message. PC requirements: DOS or Windows 3.1 or better, either a Type III IBM Wireless PC Card, a Type II MegaHertz All Points Wireless PC Card, or the Ericsson Mobidem. Mac requirements: Type II or Ericsson System 7 or better and a wireless modem listed above. 
<P><B>Personal Messenger 100C</B> <P>When Motorola designed the Personal Messenger 100C Wireless Modem Card, it made sure the cellular modem was as wireless as possible. Just slide the Personal Messenger into any PCMCIA slot -- Type II or III -- and it's good to go, no cords or cellular phones to attach.<P>Motorola, based in Schaumburg, Ill., also made it secure. The PM100C's CDPD (Cellular Digital Packet Data) network technology automatically encrypts and authenticates messages that are transmitted over the network. It also supports TCP/IP, which means you can tap into your network at the office and use any application you'd normally use. <P>A common problem with any wireless product is battery drain. The Personal Messenger automatically enters into sleep mode when not sending or receiving data, which gives you up to eight hours of operation with a rechargeable NiCad battery. Run out of power, and you can slide in a set of regular alkaline batteries.<P>What's pleasantly surprising about the Personal Messenger is the cost. Although the unit runs for around $600, the user fees are charged for only the amount of data you send and receive -- not for the time you're connected to the CDPD network.<P>* Personal Messenger 100C. Price: $500 to $700, depending upon airtime options. Requirements: DOS 5.0, Windows 3.1 or better. *<P>AirNote<P>Welcome to e-mail heaven. Wireless Services Corp. of Bellevue, Wash., has come up with an ingenious way to get your most important e-mail immediately.
<P><B>AirNote</B></P> Wireless E-mail allows anyone with an Internet e-mail account to receive wireless messages on an alphanumeric pager or PCS telephone. AirNote is a subscription service; there's no software or hardware involved, except for the alphanumeric pager, which you must buy separately.<P>Here's how it works. An AirNote subscriber is assigned an e-mail address. When a message is sent to that address, it's converted and forwarded to the subscriber's pager. <P>At the Wireless Services Web site (http:// www.airnote.net), users can scan and retrieve sent messages and establish delivery schedules. If you don't want to be paged with every e-mail, you can activate filters to screen which e-mail messages get forwarded and which stay behind for later viewing. As an added bonus, all e-mail sent to the customized address also gets sent to your desktop e-mail address.<P>* AirNote. Price: $14.95/month. Requirements: Access to an Internet e-mail account and an alphanumeric pager. 
<P><B>Companion</B><P>Dave Pandrea, the technical support manager of Varian Chromatography Systems in Walnut Creek, Calif., used to get flak from customers who were tired of being shunted into the voice-mail system when they had an emergency. ''Both our service agents and our customers were frustrated,'' says Pandrea. His clients, including the Environmental Protection Agency and the Food and Drug Administration, use Varian products to analyze food, water, air, and soil. ''People simply needed to speak live to one of our experts.''<P>Two years ago, Pandrea installed the Companion Wireless Communications System from Nortel of Richardson, Tex. Ever since, he hasn't received a complaint about his tech support staff. Companion lets you go wherever you want in your office, warehouse, or store and forwards your calls to a hand-held cordless telephone. It's not a cellular system; Companion technicians can work with your existing telephone system and strategically place cordless-phone base stations around your office or complex.<P>Varian's facility is on an 11-acre site, which means Pandrea's staff can do work far from their desks yet still be available for clients. He says: ''Whether we're inspecting a part, having a brief discussion in the corridor after a meeting, or walking in from the parking lot, we're always accessible. We don't miss a call.''<P>* Companion. Price: Varies by system, averaging $1,250 per user. A fully integrated wireless key system, Companion works with any PBX, Centrex, or key system and operates in the 1910-1920 dedicated MHz spectrum.
<P><B>TrackMan Live!</B><P>Many entrepreneurs and salespeople use computer-based presentations to pitch their ideas and sell their products. But wouldn't they do better -- and appear more natural -- if they circulated freely about a room while they were speaking? <P>That's the idea behind TrackMan Live!, a cordless mouse from Fremont, Calif.-based Logitech that allows you to stray up to 30 feet from your computer and still have control. TrackMan Live! fits in the palm of your hand and functions as a thumb-operated, three-button mouse. When you're presenting, the first button moves you forward, the middle button moves you backward, and you can use the third button to highlight points with draglock. <P>Software, which ships with the unit, lets you assign specific commands to the second and third buttons. You can even edit with such commands as cut-and-paste. You can also adjust the cursor size and sensitivity to make the cursor more visible on the screen. <P>Since TrackMan Live! uses radio-control -- not infrared -- technology, you don't have to worry about objects blocking the signal between your mouse and your computer. It also means that you don't have to point the device at the receiver for the signal to be transmitted. As a result, TrackMan Live! is easy to use, even in a dark room. TrackMan Live! Price: $149. PC requirements: DOS 3.3 or better, Windows 3.0 or better. Mac requirements: Mac SE or better, System 6.0 or better.<P>Frank Hertz is a freelance writer based in Brighton, Mass. He can be reached at 74774. 1160@compuserve.com.<P></P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550"><BR><BR>
