<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>1 cyber forum</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE / Cyber Forum</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="cyber.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="108" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by<BR> TED DAYTON/SHOOTING STAR</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4"><BR>MEETING OF THE MINDS</FONT><BR><FONT 
SIZE="+1">Online Service Offers Advice<BR> to Entrepreneurs</FONT><BR><BR><BR>
<BR><BR><BR>
<P><B><FONT COLOR=#CC000C></FONT></B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"></FONT></P>

</TD>
</P>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><P>
<P>Three years ago, Chip Meyers wanted to hire a marketing manager for his start-up bike-alarm company, Sports Alert. He advertised the position in the Los Angeles Times and asked friends and business associates for referrals, but all he got was a steady stream of people who were wrong for it.</FONT><P>''It was very frustrating,'' says Meyers, 29. ''I ended up wasting a lot of time and money. It just seemed like there had to be a better way for a small business that couldn't afford to hire a recruiting firm to find good candidates to fill a position.''<P>He thought of starting a national publication that would address the problem. He wanted to call it America's Brightest. The title was a reference to both David Halberstam's book The Best and the Brightest, about the Kennedy administration, and the quality of the job seekers who would post their r&eacute;sum&eacute;s in the publication.<P>Eventually, the task of launching a national publication would prove too daunting -- even to Meyers, who'd founded two successful businesses by the time he was 25. But a Web-based employment service made sense. Unfortunately, others had beat him to the punch.<P>''There seemed to be a lot of competition in the employment area, so I felt we had to offer something more,'' he says.<P>What Meyers ended up offering is what he describes as a ''one-stop service center for small-business owners and working professionals.'' Really, it's a bunch of services he wished he had but couldn't afford when he started his first two businesses. In 1989, he started The Campus Phone, a company that sold telephones with built-in phone directories and notepads for student dormitories. Three years later he founded Sports Alert.<P>''When you start a new business, there are all these issues you run up against that you don't anticipate,'' Meyers says. ''I wanted to consult lawyers and accountants, but they wanted to charge me a lot of money. I thought that if we could offer the small-business owner a package of services and access to experts for a low monthly fee, we could be a very useful, cost-effective tool.''<P>In order to use the Santa Monica, Calif.-based America's Brightest services -- http://www.americasbrightest. com -- you have to become a subscriber. There are two plans: individual subscribers pay $9.95 a month, small-business subscribers, $49.95. Among the services offered to both types are legal and tax advice, travel tips, and an employment database that features detailed information about both job seekers and potential employers. You can e-mail one of the service's experts, who will answer your questions via e-mail within five days.<P>Business subscribers have access to such premium services as a national public relations database and a private investigator who will do a background check on a prospective employee for an additional but reduced fee.<P>''There are basically two models for doing a service-oriented Web site,'' Meyers says. ''One is advertising-based, and the other is subscription-based. I chose to go the subscription route because I didn't think there were enough advertising dollars to go around on the Internet. Unless you're a big site, you just can't get the advertising money.''<P>According to Meyers, the biggest challenges a Web-site business owner faces are making people aware of the site, then getting them to come back to it. In an effort to lure subscribers, Meyers invites visitors to America's Brightest to use the service for one month free of charge.<P>He says, ''Only the quality of the product can get people to continue to subscribe. Knowing that, we decided to do things on a grander scale than many other sites.''<P>A quality Web site, he believes, can be designed and set up for as little as $15,000. Meyers spent $35,000 on America's Brightest, with an additional $65,000 going toward equipment, office space, and marketing. He says it costs $17,000 per month to maintain and improve the site. By early 1997, he hopes to be making a profit, though any profit will go directly into marketing so he can make people more aware of the site.<P>If the going gets rough, he at least has good advisers to whom he can turn. ''All the experts I have on the site are people I've used myself,'' he says. Then, after a beat, he adds: ''And will continue to use.''

	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


