<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>hot tips</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="4" WIDTH="500">

<TR><TD ALIGN=center VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">
	<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>TECHNOLOGY EDGE / HOT TIPS</FONT><BR><BR><BR>
	</TD></TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="150">
	<FONT SIZE="+3">Internet VCR</FONT><BR>Surf While You Sleep
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<P>You stare at your computer screen, waiting for that Web site as it gradually -- ever so gradually -- builds itself. The minutes pass. If you could, you would strangle your computer.<P>Don't do it. There's help out there. And it's free.<P>FreeLoader, a Windows application that latches onto your Netscape or Microsoft Explorer browser, allows you to access Web sites while you're away from your computer and save them to your hard drive for later viewing. <P>As with a VCR, you program FreeLoader to access specific sites at specific times, preferably when fewer people are surfing the Web. Once the images are stored on your hard drive, they load in a snap.<P>The service is particularly useful for people who frequently visit the same set of Web sites. With FreeLoader, you can "subscribe" to several Web sites, save their pages to your hard drive each night while you sleep, then view them in the morning. But beware: The more sites you subscribe to -- and the more graphically complicated the site -- the more hard-drive space you'll need. Also, you have to pay for the time the program surfs the Web for you, so it's best to have a flat-fee unlimited access account with your Internet provider.<P>Recently, FreeLoader Inc. launched FreeLoader 2.0. The most significant enhancement in this version is an interactive screen saver that consists of several framed images that float across your screen. If one of the Web sites you subscribe to has finished downloading to your hard drive, it will appear as a framed image with an ''alert'' message telling you it is ready to view. Clicking on other images, such as advertisers MSNBC and Sony Music, delivers news and information from those sites. FreeLoader 2.0 can be downloaded free of charge at the FreeLoader Web site (<A HREF="http://www.freeloader.com">http://www.freeloader.com</A>).
	</TD></TR>
	<TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="150">
	<FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>Hot Web Site</FONT><BR>BUSINESS DIRECTORY
	</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR>If you're a consumer looking for a product or a business looking for a potential client or partner, The Business Expressway's Web site (<A HREF="http://www.bizxp.com">http://www.bizxp.com</A>) might be just the place to start. The Business Expressway is a full-service Internet directory designed specifically for small-business owners who are interested in expanding through the Internet.<P>At the site, you can either search the directory for a particular business or create a listing for your own business. Any business with an existing home page can be listed for free, but you can create a greater presence by adding different degrees of artwork and information to your listing. Prices range from $50 per year for a basic business registration to $250 for a billboard listing. </P></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="150">
	<FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>Trade Show Network</FONT><BR>
	</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><P>Exhibitor magazine has launched The Exhibitor Network on the Internet. For advice on booth staffing, shipping, presentations, and salaries, ambitious trade show and event planners now have a 24-hour resource. By logging onto The Exhibitor Network (<A HREF="http://www.exhibitornet.com">http://www.exhibitornet.com</A>), you can access and download press releases, the latest industry statistics and research studies, Exhibitor magazine articles, online classified ads, and more.<P>In the Hot Exhibiting Tips section, visitors can catch the Tip of the Week and are encouraged to send their own. For example, Mike Paige of Parke-Davis offered this advice one week: "Anticipate where attendees will enter an island exhibit so your salespeople can engage them more quickly. We created an enclosed, tunnel-shaped 'art gallery' -- with only one entrance and one exit. Salespeople were positioned at the gallery's exit." </TD></TR>
</TABLE>
