	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">COVER STORY / WORKING AT HOME</FONT><BR><HR>

	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"WIDTH="225">
<FONT SIZE="+4">MASTERS <BR>OF THE WEB</FONT>
<H3>You Can Build A<BR>Multimillion-Dollar Business<BR>In Cyberspace<BR><BR>By Tom Stein</H3><BR><BR><BR><HR>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">Winning Web Sites</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Here are the Web addresses for the companies profiled
in this feature:


<P>
<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com">http://www.amazon.com</A>
</P>

<P>
<A HREF="http://www.autobytel.com">http://www.autobytel.com</A>
</P>

<P>
<A HREF="http://www.greetst.com">http://www.greetst.com</A>
</P>

<P>
<A HREF="http://www.onsale.com">http://www.onsale.com</A> 
</P>
</FONT></TD>
	
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275
	"><FONT SIZE="+1"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<IMG SRC="web.bez1.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="120" BORDER="0"><P>
<FONT SIZE="-2">Photographs by VERN EVANS</FONT><BR><P>Friends and coworkers were stunned when, one day two years ago, Jeff Bezos, a high-powered investment banker in New York City, kissed his job and huge salary good-bye. ''What made you throw it all away?'' people asked. His reply: ''The Internet.''</FONT>
</P>

<P>
''I heard that Internet usage was growing 2,300 percent annually,'' Bezos,
now 32, explains. ''That was a wake-up call. I knew something important
was going on.'' Bezos saw the future. He would build a business on the World
Wide Web.
</P>

<P>
In 1994, he made a list of 20 products that were uniquely suited to the
online environment. Narrowing the list down, he finally settled on books,
and in July of 1995, he launched Amazon.com Inc. Since then, sales have
risen at an astounding rate of 34 percent each month. ''The largest physical
bookstore in the world has only 175,000 titles,'' says Bezos. ''We offer
1.1 million. No metropolitan area is large enough to support such a store.''
</P>

<P>
Skeptics continue to knock the Web as a place for commerce, complaining
that the medium is overrated and fraught with security problems. Meanwhile,
Bezos and others steadily amass fortunes. This year, retail sales on the
Internet will hit $518 million, according to John C. McCarthy of Cambridge,
Mass.-based Forrester Research Inc. As more people log on, he predicts,
that number will climb to $6.6 billion by the year 2000.
</P>

<P>
So far, the real winners are not big-name retailers but ambitious start-ups
that exist solely on the Internet. ''The Web is a great enabler,'' says
McCarthy. ''It allows the Amazon.coms to battle the Barnes &amp; Nobles.''
</P>

<P>
Hoping to strike it rich, hordes of entrepreneurs are rushing to the
Net. As of late 1995, there were 12,000 businesses on the Web. This year,
48,000 more premiered. But only a few have mastered the medium. For example,
CDnow Inc., which sells CDs, videos, and games over the Internet, expects
to bring in $6 million this year. At Virtual Vineyards, a site that sells
wines, sales have risen 20 percent per month since its inception last year.
The secret of both companies' success: developing better and more innovative
ways to offer goods and services. Read on to learn what it takes to create
a multimillion-dollar company in cyberspace.
</P>

<P>
<B>Become the Biggest
</B></P>

<P>
Like a starry-eyed prospector, Bezos packed up his belongings and headed
West to mine Internet gold. While his wife drove their car cross-country
to Seattle -- ''because it has a high concentration of technical talent
and is a nice place to live,'' he says -- Bezos sat in the passenger seat
and wrote a business plan.
</P>

<P>
In a rented home, Bezos set up his office and began recruiting people
who could help him build a Web site for Amazon.com. He knew the site had
to offer services that a traditional bookstore could not. ''We can't have
sofas or sell cappuccino,'' he says, ''but we can still make it fun and
engaging to come to Amazon.''
</P>

<P>
For starters, visitors are invited to jot down their thoughts on any
book in the Amazon catalog. ''In the physical world, you couldn't give customers
a 3M pad, tell them to write down what they think about the books, and then
post it on the bindings,'' says Bezos. ''But online, that approach works
perfectly.'' Authors and publishers are also encouraged to discuss their
works on the site.
</P>

<P>
A highly popular feature on the Amazon site is its personal notification
service called Eyes &amp; Editors. If a customer loves kayaking, for instance,
he can fill out an electronic form asking to be notified of all new releases
on the sport. Amazon tracks the request and sends the individual an e-mail
whenever a kayaking book comes out. The cost, says Bezos, is measured in
hundredths of a penny.
</P>

<P>
When people enter the Amazon site, they can search the extensive catalog
by author, title, or subject key word. With a single click, customers can
also browse national best-sellers and staff favorites. Orders are placed
directly over the Internet. Most books are shipped within one to three days,
while rarer releases can take from four to six weeks.
</P>

<P>
At first, Bezos worried that consumers weren't ready to buy books online.
''Normally, you hear about a book that interests you and make a mental note
to drop by the bookstore and pick it up,'' he says. ''I didn't know how
long it would take for consumers to change their habits.''
</P>

<P>
As it turns out, time-pressed customers love the convenience of ordering
books through their PCs. Though Bezos won't reveal revenues, Business Week
recently estimated that the company generated $17 million in its first year.
</P>

<P>
Amazon also profits by conducting business with other online companies
through its Associates Program. ''We market this technology that allows
any Web site to build its own bookstore,'' says Bezos. ''Let's say you run
a site about dinosaurs. It's likely you'll also want to offer books on the
subject.'' Amazon provides the shipping and fulfillment while individual
sites receive 8 percent of revenues. So far, thousands of Web-site operators
have signed up for the service.
</P>

<P>
''Companies that are competing on the Web are also cooperating in order
to grow the pie,'' says Vince Gelormine, author of Guerilla Web Strategies.
While everyone's goal is to increase traffic, the big winners tap into the
whole online community to cross-market their sites.
</P>

<P>
<B>Build a National Network
</B></P>

<P>
Web surfers are typically young, well-educated professionals. Right now
they're turning to the Net for such products as software, music CDs, and
financial services, but as the Internet grows, there's room for a broader
range of goods and services. Stephen R. Kelly, creator of the Beulah, Mich.-based
Internet Profit Report, explains: ''If you're an independent dealer who
wants to sell refrigerators over the Net, that model won't work well. But
if you link together 100 fridge centers that agree to give the lowest prices,
then you really have something.''
</P>

<P>
Peter Ellis's Web-based company, Auto-By-Tel Corp., connects customers
with more than 1,400 car dealers across North America. Visitors to the site
are looking for a hassle-free car-buying experience, says Ellis. After perusing
basic information about new cars, they fill out a form listing the model,
color, and options they want and the price they are willing to pay. Within
48 hours, a dealer in their area calls to give them a price. According to
Auto-By-Tel guidelines, the customers should be in and out of the dealership
within an hour.
</P>

<P>
Auto dealers pay an annual fee of $2,500 to be listed on the site, plus
$250 to $1,500 a month for referrals. According to Ellis, about 600 cars
are sold daily through the system. He estimates that his Web site will generate
$3 billion in car sales this year.
</P>

<P>
Back in 1990, Ellis owned seven dealerships of his own. But during the
Gulf War, business dried up, and he was forced to liquidate. Driven into
semiretirement, he spent his time thinking of ways to reinvent the car industry
and make car shopping more customer-friendly. ''Most people in the industry
are high-pressure,'' says Ellis. ''But the way the system is set up, there
is no incentive to change.''
</P>

<P>
In 1994, he bought his first computer and subscribed to America Online
and Prodigy. He began marketing cars in the online classified sections.
The following year, he teamed up with an investor, John Bedrosian, to launch
a service on Prodigy. ''We projected we'd do about 1,500 purchase requests
a month,'' he says. ''On the fourth day alone, we had 1,300 requests.''
The business really took off in July 1995, when Auto-By-Tel went on the
World Wide Web.
</P>

<P>
At first, the biggest hurdle was persuading dealerships to sell cars
at close to wholesale prices. But, says Ellis, the economies of scale created
by the Internet make lower costs possible. ''I used to spend $500 to market
a new car,'' he explains. ''But with our Web-site model, it costs the dealer
about $25.''
</P>

<P>
Part of the savings comes from Auto-By-Tel's strategic ad campaign. ''A
full-page ad in the Saturday Los Angeles Times can cost $15,000,'' says
Ellis. ''For that money, I can advertise electronically and reach far more
people.''
</P>

<P>
Kelly agrees that any successful Web business must know where to promote
itself on the Web. ''If you are selling high-end watches, you don't want
to place your banner on a site that sells computer games, no matter how
popular it is,'' he advises. ''Instead, link it to a fashion site where
people may be looking to accessorize.''
</P>

<P>
Besides advertising on top auto sites, Ellis places banner ads on search
engines Yahoo! and Excite. He has worked out a cost-effective deal to ensure
that his ads reach a target audience. ''We have a special relationship with
these search engines,'' he explains. ''If the key word is car, truck, or
automobile, our banner will pop up at the top of the page.''
</P>

<P>
Ellis predicts his Irvine, Calif.-based company will exceed $6 million
in revenues this year and says that number will increase dramatically once
the company starts providing low-cost auto insurance and financing. It has
received an additional $15 million from GE Capital.
</P>

<P>
<B>Create an Entertaining Environment
</B></P>

<P>
Unlike most high-tech start-ups, Web-based businesses have low capital
requirements. Software packages allow anyone to build his own site easily
and cheaply from scratch. ''You can spend 200 bucks and be successful,''
says Kelly, ''or spend millions and have nothing happen.''
</P>

<P>
Take Jerry Kaplan, for instance. In a previous life, he was the high-flying
founder of Go Corp., a Silicon Valley start-up that was supposed to use
a new pen-based technology to reinvent the computer. The company wasted
$75 million in corporate sales and VC funding before it was sold in 1993.
</P>

<P>
Go's demise proved a powerful learning experience for Kaplan. When he
and his two partners, Alan Fisher and Razi Mohiudden, launched Onsale.com,
an electronic auction house, last year, they did so with only $500,000 and
no outside funding. ''I learned the importance of focus and of not running
up expenses until I was confident about the size and character of the market,''
says the 44-year-old Kaplan.
</P>

<P>
With the Internet gaining mass appeal, Kaplan decided he would be among
the first to create a compelling shopping experience in cyberspace. ''People
go to a mall because it's fun and interesting,'' he says. ''They don't just
send off orders to a database. The problem with selling on the Net was that
it wasn't fun.''
</P>

<P>
Kaplan's Onsale site creates a carnival atmosphere that combines Las
Vegas glitz with QVC-style hucksterism. When customers enter, they are met
with a list of products up for auction. Players place their bids and are
contacted by e-mail if they win. Auctions last two or three days.
</P>

<P>
Debuting in May 1995, the site was an immediate hit with cyber citizens
looking for a new retailing experience. ''Our customers come to us because
they enjoy the thrill of the hunt,'' says Kaplan. ''They get the emotional
satisfaction of having beat out someone else.''
</P>

<P>
Initially, the site carried everything from rare baseball cards to computer
hard drives, but Kaplan and his partners soon realized that technology-related
products sold best. They phased out all other merchandise and focused exclusively
on refurbished, hard-to-find computers and peripherals. Today, Onsale Inc.,
based in Mountain View, Calif., has relationships with more than a dozen
manufacturers and hundreds of computer resellers. The site currently moves
some 4,000 products weekly, tallying revenues of $1 million per week and
receiving a 10 percent to 20 percent commission on every sale.
</P>

<P>
''We learned that you can sell anything if the price is low enough,''
says Kaplan. ''We can unload as many 386s as the supplier can give us.''
</P>

<P>
Onsale has steered clear of what Web expert Bruce Judson calls the Field
of Dreams strategy. ''Just because you build it doesn't mean they will come,''
says Judson, author of NetMarketing: How Your Business Can Profit From the
Online Revolution. ''More than 5,000 new commercial sites go up each month.
Most have no plans for promoting the site or winning consumer attention.''
</P>

<P>
Kaplan draws about 20 percent of Onsale's first-time shoppers through
banner ads on computer-related Internet sites like CNET. He also gives people
plenty of reasons to come back. Customers are encouraged to put witty comments
next to their bids, such as ''Keep the bids low and make these guys lose
money.'' There are contests and product giveaways. These techniques, claims
Kaplan, give the company a human face and leave customers wanting more.
</P>

<P>
''As an online entrepreneur, you need to differentiate yourself from
your nonelectronic counterparts,'' he concludes. ''You need to change the
way consumers think about purchasing products.''
</P>

<P>
<B>Add Lots of Value
</B></P>

<P>
<IMG SRC="web.e.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="132" HEIGHT="96" BORDER="0">In 1993, Tony Levitan (left) and Fred Campbell graduated from Stanford Business
School with big entrepreneurial dreams. They were going to use in-store
kiosks and interactive TV to pioneer electronic retailing. But six months
later, they didn't even have a business plan. ''Our idea wasn't feasible,''
says Levitan. ''It looked like we needed $20 million just to get off the
ground.''
</P>

<P>
But Levitan wasn't ready to give up. When he heard about the World Wide
Web, he knew it would help him achieve his goals.
</P>

<P>
Armed with $100,000, he and his partner conducted market research to
find a product ideally suited to the Internet. ''People get wired to communicate,''
says Levitan, ''so we began looking for a product that would have significant
gross margins and help build community.'' Their search led them to greeting
cards.
</P>

<P>
The greeting card industry was dominated by a handful of major players,
such as Hallmark Cards and American Greetings. The partners knew they could
use the Internet to help alternative cardmakers crack the traditional retail
market.
</P>

<P>
To secure content for their new company, Greet Street Inc. of San Francisco,
the entrepreneurs attended industry trade shows. ''We told these small card
companies they shouldn't get shut out of the cyberworld as they did the
retail world,'' says the 36-year-old Levitan. ''We would provide them with
access to a broad new audience.'' Greet Street now has exclusive agreements
with 40 publishers, whose niche cards target everyone from gays and lesbians
to sports fanatics to environmentalists.
</P>

<P>
In 1995, the service was launched on America Online. A Web site followed
several months later. Visitors can use the fast-search function to pinpoint
any of the 2,500 cards on the site. Cards are divided by category and typically
cost $1.75 each. There are additional charges for personal inscriptions.
Cards can be sent by regular U.S. mail or express delivery. Greet Street's
revenues for 1996 will be about $700,000.
</P>

<P>
Despite concerns over security issues, the vast majority of Greet Street
shoppers don't mind transmitting their credit card numbers over the Web.
''The media has done a lot to fuel consumer fears,'' says Judson, ''but
security on the Net is really a nonissue. The major credit card companies
are now setting new standards in security.''
</P>

<P>
Greet Street's biggest challenge is delivering a true electronic advantage.
Among its many cutting-edge features is something called ''perfect memory.''
An absent-minded husband, for instance, can input important dates like his
anniversary or his wife's birthday in the Greet Street database. A timely
e-mail message from the company reminds him when to order.
</P>

<P>
Another winning feature is what Levitan calls ''site morphing.'' Greet
Street has developed strategic relationships with popular sites on the Internet.
If a user links to Greet Street from a sports site, he will immediately
see a sports-related card on the home page. Someone who connects from NetNoir,
an Afro-centric site, will see cards targeted to a black audience. ''We
want to introduce Greet Street on terms that are consistent with what the
customer wants,'' says Levitan. The founders are also developing a new line
of interactive greeting cards called ''E-greetings.'' With sound and animation
capabilities, these cards will transform lifeless e-mail messages into multimedia
extravaganzas.
</P>

<P>
All these value-added features are helping to distinguish Greet Street
from the herd and to catapult sales. ''We fully expect to be a $100 million
company within five years,'' says Levitan.
</P>

<P>
Like any new business, an online venture has its share of risks and rewards.
But the pioneers profiled here have proven that the Internet is indeed a
viable place to do business. They've blazed a trail for the next wagon load
of online entrepreneurs. In the process, they have radically transformed
the way business will be conducted in the 21st century.
</P>

<P>
''When I am 80 years old, I won't even remember having walked away from
my Wall Street bonus,'' says Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com. ''On the other hand,
I might sincerely regret not having participated in the Internet.''
</P>


<P>
Former SUCCESS senior writer Tom Stein has reported widely on hot new
entrepreneurial businesses.</TD></TR><TR>
</P>

