	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="400">
	<BR>
	
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Everyone agreed Tim Jemison had a great business plan, but no one wanted to give him any money. He'd formed Online Scouting Network  LLC (OSN) to allow colleges to recruit high school athletes over the Internet. He positioned the company as a cutting-edge new media venture, figuring that being in a hot category would put him on the fast track to cash. At the time, Internet-related stocks &#45; led by Netscape &#45; were soaring. <BR> 
But potential investors refused to commit the $1.2 million he needed. ''We sat down with four or five banks, and they all said they didn't want anything to do with a start-up,'' Jemison recalls. ''They said they lend on results, not projections.'' Venture capital firms specializing in new media and Internet enterprises complained his market wasn't big enough.<BR>    
In a last-ditch effort, Jemison decided to send his plan to business and sports moguls who might not know anything about the Internet, but who understood recruiting. One was NBC sportscaster Bob Costas, who forwarded the plan to his financial adviser, Kathy Lintz. Jemison had finally reached someone who grasped his vision. Within 10 weeks, Lintz and her athlete-clients agreed to fund $900,000 of OSN's start-up costs.<BR>
Entrepreneurs can be so focused on finding money that they forget to target the right candidates. And investors, always on the hunt for high returns, must also make compatibility a top priority. <BR> 
The five stories that follow demonstrate that understanding your investor's mindset may be the single most important factor in finding money.</FONT></P>

	<BR>		
<FONT SIZE="-1"><B>Focus on the Future</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">The Entrepreneur</FONT>
<P>For most of her career, Pam Piper was a consultant to government contractors. In 1986, she founded Modern Technology Systems Inc. of Riverdale, Md.
''I wanted to build my own business instead of helping other people build theirs,'' she says. Piper toiled away in a home office, landing enough small contracts to pay her bills and put food on the table.
In 1990, she was in the running for her first big contract, worth $400,000 per year for five years. ''It was the kind of contract you can start to build a business from,'' she says.
Though desperate for the work, Piper didn't have the resources to fulfill the contract immediately if she won it. She didn't have money to hire people or purchase equipment. And without collateral and a track record, she couldn't get a line of credit with a bank. </P>
''How do you start work on the contract, meet your payroll and expenses, when you have to finish some of the work before you get paid?'' she wondered. 
Through her network of contractors, Piper heard about Princeton Capital Finance Co. of Princeton, N.J., an asset-based lender that finances government and commercial contract receivables.
At first, Piper was leery Princeton would take advantage of her vulnerable position by charging exorbitant interest rates. That wasn't the case. Princeton lent her a percentage of the invoice so she could get the work. Her customer then paid Princeton directly, and Princeton deducted its interest fee (about three percentage points above prime) and sent the balance to Piper. Princeton wrote a letter saying it would finance the project if everything went according to plan. That enabled Piper to clinch the deal.
With her new ability to fund projects, Piper began bidding on bigger and more lucrative contracts. Today, she's a veteran of the contracting system, with $15 million in 1995 revenues and 195 employees.
''My relationship with Princeton allowed us to grow at a rate that we hadn't even thought about before,'' she says. ''There are areas where a company like Princeton Capital offers assistance and support that a bank would not.''
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">The Lender<BR>
</FONT>As far as Princeton Capital was concerned, Pam Piper was ''a typical undercapitalized government contractor who needed capital for rapid growth,'' says senior vice president Chuck Smith.
Each month, Smith meets dozens of government contractors. Before backing a contractor, he carefully weighs his expertise, the strength of the customer paying for the work, and the caliber of the contract (measured in dollars and length of time).
At one end of the spectrum are fledgling entrepreneurs with a onetime contract for a onetime service from a small municipality. At the other end are the Pam Pipers. Smith and his partners called her references, including other agencies from which she had contracted work. Her reputation was ''impeccable.'' They were encouraged that the federal government contract was ''multiyear and multimillion dollar.'' 
Smith believed Piper could consistently deliver the work she promised. ''We didn't have to question the federal government's ability to pay, but what its level of satisfaction with Pam's company's performance would be,'' says Smith. ''The capability of her company and her technical skill gave us a great deal of confidence.''
As Modern Technology has expanded, Piper has much more power with lenders. Princeton has courted her business, continually lowering the interest rates she pays for her contract ventures.
''If she says she needs to move away from asset-based lending, we will help introduce her to banks,'' says Smith. ''We may also want to become what she would get at a bank.''
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"><B>Find Your Guardian Angel</B></FONT><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+2">The Entrepreneur</FONT><BR>
When Tim Jemison founded Online Scouting Network last year with two buddies from college, he thought that fund-raising would be the easiest part. But Jemison was stuck on what he called ''middle ground &#45; too small for the venture capitalists, too early for the banks.''
Figuring that only ''angels'' &#45; wealthy private investors &#45; had enough money to take a chance on OSN, ''we entered our wild goose phase of business development and made a list of people with the financial wherewithal to risk money on this,'' says the young entrepreneur. 
Jemison sent his plan to Donald Trump, Warren Buffet, Ted Turner, George Steinbrenner, and a handful of other sports and business moguls, including Bob Costas. Costas's business manager, whose daughter had played volleyball in high school and college, read the plan, understood the idea's potential, and sent the information to Kathy Lintz, Costas's financial manager.
Lintz had so much confidence in OSN's prospects that she put $30,000 of her own money into the deal. Her clients initially invested $900,000. Armed with the equity investment he needed, Jemison persuaded United National Bank of Bridgewater, N.J., to lend him the remaining $300,000.
With the service up and running since April, Jemison has already been offered $2 million for his Somerville, N.J.-based company. But with first-year revenues heading to $750,000 and projections for $2.3 million by the end of the second year, Jemison is nowhere near ready to sell out. In fact, he's getting ready to raise money again &#45; about $1.5 million &#45; in part to expand the service to include music and arts recruiting. This time, he will approach professionals in the field first. 
''Even though we are an Internet company, we found that operating within that category could have been our downfall,'' says Jemison. ''In the end, it was the athletic community that came through because they understood the concept. They may not have realized the potential of Netscape or Yahoo!, but they definitely understand recruiting.''
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">The Angel</FONT><BR>Each year, Kathy Lintz reviews about 50 proposals for new businesses, many of which are sports-related. Her clients at KBL Financial Management are professional and retired athletes, including football superstars Roger Craig and Jerry Rice and baseball players Ryne Sandburg and Joe Carter.
Lintz is most receptive to plans that are clearly written by the entrepreneur. It's easy to tell which ones are written by an attorney or an accountant. Clues that tip her off are ''pages and pages of legalese or columns and columns of accountant-driven numbers.''
The OSN plan was a simple three-page executive summary, with just enough numbers to explain an investor's return. In clear and specific terms, the plan outlined exactly how the service would work and maintain a market. 
As soon as she read OSN's business proposal, the St. Louis investor called Jemison to set up a meeting. ''I've never read a plan and been immediately moved to pick up the phone on the spot,'' she says. ''Jemison had no idea who I was or how his plan had ended up on my desk.''
Lintz wanted more details on the opportunity. ''I was definitely interested but still dubious,'' she says. ''I needed to meet them, see where they were in the development of the project, and meet the people who had been helping them develop the idea. We needed to work through the corporate structure. We still had so far to go.''
Lintz encouraged Jemison to restructure OSN into a limited liability corporation for a more favorable tax structure. She negotiated veto power and spending limits and wangled a position on OSN's four-member management team. Though her goal is ''not to run their company for them,'' she says she would not have committed the funds without some day-to-day involvement. 
''My involvement is not a lack of confidence, but recognition that I am ultimately responsible for the money we've invested and that my clients are people with a high level of personal visibility,'' says Lintz. ''To get involved, we needed some control.''
<BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"><B>Know When to Sell Yourself</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">The Entrepreneur</FONT><BR>
To raise $135,000, Lauren Moseley knew she had to promote herself, not her concept. Her retail business, Health & Fitness Resource of Bedford, Tex., wasn't the sort lenders covet. Not only was she a retail start-up, she was on the cutting edge of the new and unproven wellness movement. 
When talking to investors, Moseley played up her background and management skills. Armed with a Harvard MBA, a career in international finance with Philip Morris, and five years as product director for Johnson & Johnson, Moseley knew how to identify and capture a ripe market. 
For months, she crafted her business plan. Then she approached the Dallas Small Business Development Center and asked about financing alternatives. She was directed to Emerson Hall, a regional vice president at GE Small Business Finance Corp., a division of General Electric Co. that provides SBA financing to business ventures.
''The banks were not even willing to look at my business plan. I couldn't even get a meeting,'' says Moseley. ''Emerson listened to what I was doing and tuned into all the details.''
GE's first requirement was that Moseley commit her own cash to the project. Between her savings and help from family members, she came up with $45,000. Hall and his associates needed to confirm that her business plan was viable.
''They challenged me on my sales projections and asked me to do more market research,'' says Moseley. ''They were not discouraging me, just getting me to the point where I could get the financing.'' Though GE's interest rates were about three points higher than a bank's, the terms were more favorable. GE stretched Moseley's loan out over seven years &#45; a long amortization by any standard.
''I started working with GE last November and got approval for a $90,000 loan by New Year's,'' says Moseley. ''By May of this year, the store was open.''
She plans to open several Health & Fitness Resource outlets in the Dallas/Fort Worth market and franchise the concept down the road.
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">The Lender<BR>
</FONT>Though GE charges rates that can be slightly higher than a bank's, it doesn't subject borrowers to such intense scrutiny or rigorous standards. For example, it processes loans faster than a bank, and its SBA guarantee allows for longer-term financing. GE does not focus as much on collateral. That's why it's an attractive financing tool for start-up entrepreneurs. 
When Emerson Hall read Moseley's business plan and listened to her describe her strategy, ''she communicated very clearly, This is what I'm doing, this is what I need, this is how I'll pay it back,' '' he recalls. Hall was looking for confirmation that she would go the extra mile to repay a loan. 
His concern was allayed when Moseley staked her own equity. ''Even with a small loan, it's important to us &#45; it shows a commitment level.''
Hall scrutinized Moseley's sales predictions. She'd already gone to health food stores and bookstores to make notes on what people purchased and how much they spent. He sent her back to speak directly with store owners.
He liked that she had expenses and cash-flow projections broken down monthly. ''It accounted for cyclical and seasonal fluctuations,'' he says. ''Her management experience helped.''
Hall likes proven concepts best, but he's willing to bet on thoroughbreds just out of the gate. ''By the time Lauren is on her second or third location, depending on the market, her [interest] rates will likely go down,'' he notes. ''We have the financial resources. If we can start with a company when it is small, we can stay with it through its lifetime.''
<BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="-1"><B>The Power of Passion</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">The Entrepreneur</FONT><BR>Larry Carpenter started with a long-term goal and a short-term borrowing strategy to reach it. After working for a billboard advertising and commercial real estate company in Dallas, he saw how profitable the business could be. He founded Carpenter Outdoor Advertising Co. of St. Louis with the intent to own and operate 30 billboards within five years. 
Today, eight years later, Carpenter owns and manages nearly 100 billboards in Missouri and Texas, with assets in excess of $3 million, revenues of about $1 million, and profit margins exceeding 30 percent. 
Carpenter uses his line of credit to pay for construction and supplies; he still funds the acquisition of each sign property one project at a time. 
''I could look for half a million dollars to fund a number of projects, but big deals are tough,'' Carpenter says. ''I borrow only $40,000 to $50,000 at a time, which makes the deals more conceivable.''
Back in 1988, Carpenter needed $40,000 to construct his first billboard site. He went to four banks. Three showed him the door. The last, Mark Twain Bank of St. Louis, showed him the office of then senior lending officer Tim Peterson.
''He understood my entrepreneurial background and my goals, but my job was to think like a bank and provide him with the information he was looking for,'' says Carpenter. 
He provided Peterson with realistic revenue and expense projections and educated him about the market. ''If a bank is not familiar with your industry, it may take a while for it to make a decision. I provided professional brochures on our company and other billboards, with support materials from the Outdoor Advertising Association of America, with a picture of where the industry was headed.''
Peterson was willing to lend Carpenter the $40,000 he needed, but only at a cost two points higher than the prime rate.
At the time, ''the high rate was in proportion to the risk,'' says Carpenter. ''My loans are around the prime rate now.'' Carpenter currently is borrowing about $160,000 to fund a five-sign package. He'll infuse an additional $40,000 of his own money for real-estate acquisitions.
''My vision was focused on individual goals &#45; to borrow bite-size amounts to build a sizable business,'' says Carpenter. ''I could stop now and have accomplished that. But I'd rather reset my goals.''
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">The Banker</FONT><BR>
Tim Peterson liked two elements of Larry Carpenter's proposal: his information and his passionate delivery. 
Carpenter discussed the St. Louis business community and provided details about the outdoor advertising market. He talked about real estate acquisition, sign construction, and steel purchasing. For each project, he presented all of his expense and income projections in the same format that banks use.
''He had information on the billboard market that we didn't have ourselves,'' says Peterson. ''We had not been a major player in that industry, and he did a lot of work helping us understand the business.''
Just as important as the facts, Carpenter's passion gave him an edge. ''A start-up doesn't have equity or a track record or a customer base to support it, so we look for other sources of support of why the business will be successful,'' says Peterson. In those cases, ''we're not looking for big margins or high rates of return, just for confidence in the repayment of a loan.''
''Occasionally,'' Peterson concludes, ''you just feel good enough about a deal to take on some risk. Carpenter, he says, was one of those instances. Not only did Larry have his own money in the deal, he was aggressive and energetic and willing enough to make me feel that we were taking only a small risk.''
<BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"><B>Be Bigger, Faster, Stronger</B></FONT><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+2">The Entrepreneur</FONT><BR>As the president of a chain of long-term-care facilities, Jon Sherwin saw dozens of independent nursing homes struggling to keep up with regulatory and legislative health care changes. He had a solution. In 1994, he founded The Frontier Group Inc. to buy independent nursing homes and operate them as a chain of his own, reducing administrative costs and simplifying regulatory changes.
Sherwin needed $34 million to begin his buying spree. He figured he could raise $11 million in venture capital and borrow the balance from a bank. The health care veteran set up meetings with several venture capitalists ''even before our business plan was developed, to feel around where we were headed,'' he says.
Knowing he would need to tap several sources, Sherwin fine-tuned his plan to include a group of venture capital firms, augmented with debt financing. He began negotiations with Minneapolis-based Norwest Venture Capital and Weston Presidio Capital of Boston. Both firms have experience investing in health care concerns, and together they agreed to fund most of Sherwin's business.
Raising the $11 million, Sherwin said, ''proved more a case of selling ourselves than selling our concept. The concept has to make sense, and the numbers have to work, but they had more questions about us and our plans and why were we credible and who else would be involved.''
Today, The Frontier Group owns and operates 16 nursing homes generating more than $100 million in annual revenues, and Sherwin has raised an additional $90 million to fund his expansion goals.
He interviews all his prospective partners, asking them how involved they want to be, how frequently they would want financial reports, and how detailed they would want their information.
''The more money we raise, the more people we have involved, and you're constantly having to respond to their divergent views,'' says Sherwin. ''I pay as much attention to the quality of our investors as the amount of money they have. I do as much due diligence on them as they did on me.'' 
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">The Venture Capitalist
</FONT><BR>
''Jon Sherwin presented a compelling case for his strategy,'' says Ernie Parizeau, general partner in Norwest's Boston office. Norwest maintains an active equity position in about 100 companies, mostly in communications, software, and health care. 
''We look for three things in an investment, and Frontier fit all of them,'' says Parizeau. The first is the quality of the management team. ''Jon was a mature leader with a track record of success.'' 
Parizeau wants companies with the potential to become valuated at $100 million. If a market niche is too small, the company will never create enough value to warrant the infusion of capital. ''If Jon is right about his goals, the company has a chance to become sizable.'' 
Proprietary advantage is another major concern. Frontier's timing and unique acquisition strategy gave it an edge. Many states have imposed moratoriums on nursing home construction, while changes in federal regulations have created chaos for independent operators. Buying up existing facilities would give them instant market share. 
Parizeau visited nursing homes and pored over government regulations as part of his due diligence. Next, he had to convince at least two of his partners of the merits of the deal. ''They challenged me on the risks, on the contingency plans, the numbers in general,'' he says. A single rule change by Medicaid could throw off all the numbers. 
Parizeau got the go-ahead from his partners and then made his own proposal to Sherwin. ''We basically ignore whatever a company proposes to us,'' Parizeau says. ''The investor should really make the proposal. They tell us what they think they're worth, and we use their projections, but ultimately market demand determines what we want to invest.''
SUCCESS contributing writer Gianna Jacobson of St. Louis specializes in finance and entrepreneurship.
	
