<HEAD>
    <TITLE>10Rino</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT SIZE="+4">MASTER THE FUTURE</FONT>
<H4>How the Rhino Brothers Trained Their Instincts and Turned $3 into $70
Million </H4>
<H4>By Michael Warshaw </H4>
<FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by Sam Jones / CD Cover by Maria Ferri</FONT>
	</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><IMG SRC="rino.gif" ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH="180" HEIGHT="180" BORDER="0"></TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+1">Some people become entrepreneurs because building companies is exhilarating.
Some don't trust the corporate world with their destiny. But Richard Foos,
47, and Harold Bronson, 46, did it because they are punctilious pranksters
who refused to stop until they got what they wanted. </FONT><BR>
<BR>
From a three-dollar pile of used records, they built Rhino Entertainment
Inc. -- a $70 million cash machine with no major debt. It's a relentlessly
profitable company in the riskiest industry of all: popular music. <BR>
<BR>
The traditional record industry is driven by market research, which chronicles
the past. It runs itself in circles trying to replicate hits. Foos and Bronson
created records that didn't yet exist -- collections of novelty tunes and
past hits -- but which they wanted to buy. <BR>
<BR>
At the Harvard Business School, entrepreneurship professor Howard Stevenson
says leadership relies on the ability to make the future predictable. That's
what the Rhino founders do. They've built an army of employees who share
their passion for pop culture as well as the ability to think like customers
and sell what they love. Together, they've created a massive new market
and revolutionized the record business. <BR>
<BR>
''Logically, if you want to start a record label, you divorce yourself from
your personal taste and look at what's selling in the commercial market,''
says Bronson. <BR>
<BR>
Rhino Entertainment prospers by doing the opposite. It produces CDs, videos,
and books (as well as films), most of which are creatively packaged collections
of material from the past. ''We put out albums we would like to buy,'' says
Foos. ''I loved the Turtles. I was frustrated that you couldn't buy a 'Best
of the Turtles' collection.'' So he designed one, and it became one of the
company's earliest best-sellers. <BR>
<BR>
Thinking like your customer is the most high-tech research there is. In
Rhino's early years, Foos and Bronson designed all the products by the seats
of their pants, wrangling for rights and writing liner notes themselves.
Every one of Rhino's 130 employees is encouraged to act like its founders,
developing product ideas based on their own tastes and enthusiasms. The
Washington Post calls Rhino ''the premier archival label'' in America. <BR>
<BR>
Rhino grew because Foos and Bronson learned to clone themselves. They nurture
a deliberate culture of creativity, beginning with the company's Big Ideas
program: bonuses paid to employees who produce innovative ideas. <BR>
<BR>
Follow Your Passion <BR>
<BR>
In the late 1960s, Foos was studying sociology at USC in Los Angeles. Bronson
was across town at UCLA, making $17.50 per week as a student rep for Columbia
Records. <BR>
<BR>
One day, Foos was at a swap meet when he met a dealer selling hundreds of
LPs for a buck apiece. The vendor had bought the entire lot at Aron's Records
on Melrose Avenue, a new-and-used-record shop -- for three dollars. <BR>
<BR>
Foos went to Aron's and spent three bucks of his own for a huge pile of
old jazz and blues records. At first, he threw his inventory into the trunk
of his car and drove it around to flea markets. In 1973, Foos leased a storefront
of his own in Westwood, close to the UCLA campus. He had no business plan,
no financing -- nothing. Foos just opened the doors and blindly charged
ahead. And so he called it Rhino Records. <BR>
<BR>
Bronson eventually started working at the store. ''When Harold joined me,
I was such a revolutionary, I didn't want to pay any of the bills, and I
didn't want to pay taxes,'' says Foos. ''Harold could sort of keep books
and pointed out we should pay the bills.'' <BR>
<BR>
Rhino Records was a pit, overstuffed with tables and chairs Foos brought
from home and fixtures he found in a supermarket dumpster. Foos spent entire
days without seeing a single customer, so he and Bronson began throwing
crazed promotions, anything to attract attention. Polka Day. Redneck Day.
On Hassle the Salesman Day, they wore matching seersucker suits. On Jewish
Day, customers were served corned beef on rye and encouraged to bargain.
The promotions established the shameless, Mad-magazine sensibilities that
mark Rhino to this day -- and they worked. Record collectors started flocking
to the hole-in-the-wall shop. <BR>
<BR>
Carve Out a Niche <BR>
<BR>
In 1975, Bronson and Foos cut a record, a giveaway promotion sung by Wild
Man Fischer, a grungy local street character. It was called Go to Rhino
Records. The oddball single was picked up by local radio stations and earned
Rhino an underground following. <BR>
<BR>
Foos sold the store in 1978 to go into the record business full-time. Rhino's
first album, a collection of tunes from Wild Man Fischer, was produced for
$500. It was the first in a series of wild novelty records, such as an all-kazoo
version of Led Zeppelin's Whole Lotta Love. They got picked up by radio
stations across the country and sold like crazy. ''[Foos and Bronson] were
blindly arrogant in a charming way,'' recalls longtime employee Gary Stewart,
now senior vice president and architect of many Rhino products. ''It's not
like selling shoes. It's something that's very personal and subjective.
When you connect with an audience on that level, there's luck involved.''
<BR>
<BR>
The Rhino label grossed $60,000 in 1978. Bronson and Foos were ecstatic.
But they kept the company strictly low rent, with shabby backroom offices
and warehouses packed with thrift shop furniture. A P.A. system was powered
by someone's old guitar amp. The phones were a joke. And everybody used
to take turns cleaning the bathroom. ''Undeniably, Richard and I are very
smart,'' says Bronson. ''We minimized our material needs so the company
could benefit from the profits. We got into the habit of taking minimal
salaries.'' <BR>
<BR>
But by 1979, radio had had its fill of novelty tunes. Rhino was suddenly
faced with lean times -- until it discovered a completely new market. <BR>
<BR>
A midsize record label called Sire was producing the first serious albums
of collected old rock and rhythm and blues tunes. Influenced by that example,
Rhino entered the reissue business. <BR>
<BR>
Decision makers at most record companies were a generation older than the
fans. They didn't realize the hippie generation was getting older and yearning
for the music of its youth. ''To the record companies, the old stuff was
chump change,'' says former vice president of sales Keith Altomare, adding
that getting licensed to rerelease old hits was a piece of cake. ''They
figured, 'We have somebody willing to pay money for these titles. Why not
give it to them?' '' <BR>
<BR>
It was not unlike those cheap records from Aron's on Melrose. Foos and Bronson
got rights to the songs because nobody else could see the potential, and
they created a new niche: reasonably priced, high-quality compilations of
past records. <BR>
<BR>
At the time, reissues were the bottom of the record industry barrel, slapped
out quickly from old inventory. Rhino put the concept first, researching
imaginative themed compilations of reissue music, complete with heavily
researched liner notes and creative packaging. ''We had the advantage of
making it up as we went along,'' says Foos. ''We weren't limited by the
rules.'' <BR>
<BR>
''More specifically, when we put out our first album, it was financed for
next to nothing,'' adds Bronson. ''With the money we made from that, we
put out two more. We always knew that we had to make a profit.'' <BR>
<BR>
Foos and Bronson would go to any length to make the product they wanted.
Once, Rhino couldn't get rights to the original hit tune ''Louie Louie.''
The Rhino Brothers, as Foos and Bronson are known (even though they're not
related), found composer Richard Berry, dragged him into a studio, and recut
the song -- imitating the original, note for note. According to Forbes,
the resulting collection sold 100,000 copies for a probable $135,000 profit.
<BR>
<BR>
Only 10 percent of the records produced in this country turn a profit. By
contrast, 90 percent of Rhino's products make money. The company has no
major debt and has not lost money in any of the last 18 years. <BR>
<BR>
Maintain Your Edge <BR>
<BR>
In its early years, Rhino's employees resisted growth. They were afraid
of losing the company's special touch. ''We begged Richard not to move out
of our first building,'' remembers Brian Schuman, one of the original employees
and now head of manufacturing operations. ''It was a dungeon, but it was
Rhino.'' <BR>
<BR>
Foos felt the same way. For years, he even refused to buy a copier. Employees
would run next door to a stationery store and make copies for a dime apiece.
It wasn't until 1983, when Rhino was a $2 million company, that somebody
was able to persuade Foos to buy an old wet-process clunker. ''It was very,
very late,'' Stewart says. <BR>
<BR>
''We never knew how big this could get, and we used our own profits to grow,''
says Foos. ''No banks believed in us enough for us to get a lot of debt.
We always expanded a step at a time.'' And they were careful to hire employees
who shared the passion for pop culture that was building their company.
<BR>
<BR>
Every time they realized Rhino had to become more sophisticated, in legal
work or financials or marketing, Bronson and Foos would learn as much about
those skills as they could. By the time the company grew too large for them
to handle these chores themselves, they could afford to hire a pro. ''It
means we're more sophisticated about some things than other record companies,
things like human resources and people having accessibility to the top,''
says Bronson. <BR>
<BR>
They insist on policing the Rhino culture, staying involved in hiring decisions
and meeting with individual employees every six months. ''We have a special
vision of what a Rhino product entails,'' says Bronson. <BR>
<BR>
Employees say Foos is the center of the company, running it day to day.
Bronson's contribution is more creative, closer to the artistic work. They
are soft-spoken and serious in person, not at all the outrageous personalities
you would expect. ''They're not necessarily the best of friends, but they're
good partners,'' Stewart observes. ''They agree on what the company is about.
<BR>
<BR>
''When I started here, I was in my early 20s,'' he adds. ''I stuck it out
because I believed in what we were doing. We cared about who was buying
our product. And we still do. We hire passionate people, passionate about
music and life.'' <BR>
<BR>
Keep Your Focus <BR>
<BR>
The Rhino Brothers learned a critical lesson in 1987, one that almost cost
them the company. They got their first gold single, and it became a disaster.
They released a modest local hit from an L.A. musician named Billy Vera
called ''At This Moment.'' The song was featured on the TV show Family Ties.
''It became a number-one record,'' Stewart says. ''We were selling 50,000
copies a day. Everybody in the company was stuffing envelopes.'' <BR>
<BR>
The success was intoxicating. Foos and Bronson figured they were now in
the hit business. ''We spent a year trying to replicate that success, and
it almost killed us,'' Stewart says. ''We lost a ton of money and caught
ourselves just in time.'' <BR>
<BR>
Rhino returned to its focus on reissues. Now the company uses strategic
partnerships to expand its market. In 1992, it partnered with giant label
Warner/Elektra/Atlantic (WEA) Corp., owner of the Atlantic label catalog
of classic rhythm and blues artists. It supplies the music and the distribution
power. Rhino delivers the hip sensibilities that craft the old tunes into
distinctive new products. Last year, Rhino joined with Turner Entertainment
to release soundtracks from Turner's huge library of MGM films. <BR>
<BR>
As huge as it is, Rhino keeps its sardonic edge. In April, U.S. Secretary
of Labor Robert Reich made a heavily publicized visit to the company's Westwood
headquarters. He conducted a forum with employees and gave Rhino an award
for its corporate citizenship. ''We are highlighting companies that treat
their workers as assets to be developed, rather than as costs to be cut,''
he said. <BR>
<BR>
Meanwhile, Foos was writing a letter to Bob Dole, who has spoken out against
rap music. Foos offered him a copy of White Men Can't Wrap, a Rhino compilation
of pop hits spoken, rather than sung, by '50s and '60s actors. He also offered
to take Dole to lunch should he win the election, since they would then
both have the title ''president'' and could swap ideas. <BR>
<BR>
''When I came to Rhino two years ago, I was impressed by the level of sophistication
they were at already,'' says CFO Colin Reef. ''I don't think we want to
become a $2 billion company, because it would be very difficult to maintain
what we have here, that hands-on, boutique feel to the company.'' <BR>
<BR>
Keep in Touch with the Customer <BR>
<BR>
Trays of sandwiches cover folding tables. Practically the whole company
has gathered, many sitting on the floor, for Open Forum, the anything-goes
monthly meeting. ''A significant portion of every employee's compensation
is tied to the company's performance,'' says Reef. ''That's why we have
Open Forum, so we can share a lot of information.'' <BR>
<BR>
The group begins a heated discussion as Foos and Bronson watch from the
front of the room. The credits printed on each Rhino product list employees
who worked directly on that release. Some of the workers in other areas
of the company feel left out. They want everyone to get listed. ''It would
be nice to see your name in print,'' Stewart tells them. ''I do believe
everybody is part of the products.'' <BR>
<BR>
But some, including executive vice president Bob Emmer and media relations
senior director David Dorn, whose father is a record producer, resist the
idea. Eventually, the group pounds out a consensus solution. The packaging
of future Rhino products will include little stories showcasing different
company departments. <BR>
<BR>
''Richard and Harold run this company in a democratic way,'' says Dorn.
''They'll go along with the majority, as long as it's not a bad business
decision.'' <BR>
<BR>
''You have a company and these employees, and they have to grow,'' Bronson
says after the meeting. He insists it's the only way to survive, especially
now. When Rhino was young, it had the reissues market to itself and was
the secret success of the record industry. ''We did better every year, but
nobody paid us much attention because we had no hits,'' says Bronson. <BR>
<BR>
Today, Rhino is too big to be ignored. ''Everybody wants to be in the reissue
business. Everybody thinks it's a gold mine,'' says Stewart. ''We created
the market, and now it's a feeding frenzy. It makes us have to be smarter.''
<BR>
<BR>
Foos believes Rhino should do nothing to react to the competition. ''The
majors won't get more creative,'' he says. ''Nothing they do will replace
our sensibility.'' <BR>
<BR>
Most of his customers are just like him, Foos believes. Not fanatics, but
interested in having someone like Rhino collect records for them, putting
together the hits they remember. He and Bronson have no exit strategy, not
yet. ''We love what we're doing,'' he says. ''We really expect it to grow.''
<BR>
<BR>
You must think like the customer you serve to run your company by instinct.
And you have to have employees who can do what you do. Foos and Bronson
are like farmers, and creative employees are their cash crop. Rhino anticipates
the tastes of its audience. That's how it expanded from novelty records
to reissues to movie soundtracks. <BR>
<BR>
Customers buy records for the artist and don't care what record company
name is on them -- with one exception. Rhino has built a powerful brand;
few other record companies can sell products based on their names. <BR>
<BR>
Foos and Bronson never stopped honing their instincts and their organization.
They took crumbs from the tables of their giant competitors and built a
money-making colossus renowned as the hippest record company in the world.
 <BR>
<BR>
SUCCESS executive editor Michael Warshaw specializes in entrepreneurial
management. 
	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><HR>
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C"><H2>Steal From the Giants
</H2>
Behind the remarkable growth of Rhino Records are principles to power any
entrepreneurial organization: <BR>
<BR>
* Mine the power of profitable passions. Think like the customer, and you
will always find new markets. What the automobile, the personal computer,
the Sony Walkman, and Rhino Records share is that no consumer knew he wanted
them until they were created. Their inventors were inspired by personal
obsessions. <BR>
<BR>
* Build on strength, not structure. Leading-edge businesses change their
boundaries at will to focus  on adding the most value for the customer.
<BR>
<BR>
* Cultivate people. Delegate process. Rhino employees stay close to its
vision because the founders hire people with pop-culture enthusiasm, stay
involved with hiring decisions, and meet with each employee every six months.</FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>


