<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>12HomeOffice.settel</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">COVER STORY / WORKING AT HOME</FONT><BR><HR>

	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"WIDTH="225">
<FONT SIZE="+4">A BUSINESS MAXIMIZED AT HOME</FONT>
<H3>Independent sales representative Marti Settle designed her entire house,
not just her home office, to support her busness --<BR>and all are thriving.<BR>BY TOM MORAN</H3><IMG SRC="set.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER="0"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR> <FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by RICK PATRICK</FONT></TD>
	
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275
	"><FONT SIZE="+1"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P>Marti Settle was stuck in traffic outside Dallas, just trying to get
home after another day running her small graphic-design company. It was
1989, and she was happy being her own boss. Yet she cleared only about $50,000
annually, sometimes working 14-hour days and commuting more than an hour
between Dallas and her home in suburban Denton, Tex. She knew she'd never
get rich doing what she did, and she felt she was ''just going to get old
and die on that freeway.''</FONT></P>

<P>A year or so later, she would be introduced to health and weight-control
products from Enrich International and the financial-growth potential of
network marketing. By 1992, after building an independent-sales organization
part-time, she took the plunge and made Enrich her only business. Soon one
month's work would bring her $20,000 in income -- what it took six months
to make at her graphic-design firm. Today Marti enjoys a ''comfortable six-figure
income'' working from her home, commuting now only a bad memory.</P>

<P>Here's what it took for this entrepreneur to make a successful switch
from one business to another and reap terrific rewards.</P>

<P><B>Catching the Vision of an Opportunity</B></P>

<P>At the age of 45, Marti Settle -- she kept telling herself -- was moderately
successful. Yet she felt dissatisfied. She knew her long commute was one
reason for the dissatisfaction; limited income and the demands of her business
-- having to deal with employees, government regulations, and taxes -- were
other factors. What she didn't know was that in the near future her work
and her financial situation would change forever.</P>

<P>In 1991, Marti's sister, Carol Crowley, told her about Enrich International,
based in Orem, Utah. Carol was selling Power Trim pills, which she claimed
would increase Marti's metabolism and energy level and help her lose weight.
A few weeks later, and lighter, Marti slapped a bottle of the product on
her husband's desk. ''Roger, try these,'' she said. ''They work.''</P>

<P>A self-proclaimed meat-and-potatoes man, he rolled his eyes. For marital
harmony, however, he tried them and soon found himself eating only half
his steak. Then ''he caught the vision,'' Marti says. For Roger, the financial-growth
potential in network marketing was clear. The idea was not just to sell
the product but to recruit other salespeople and encourage them to sell
and recruit more people. Every sale made by this growing network of salespeople
would result in a commission for the person who recruited them. Yet, deeply
involved in his insurance business, Roger was not ready to make a change.</P>

<P>Marti was. She sold her company and took a job at a Dallas graphics printing
house, enabling her to develop her Enrich business at night and on weekends.
''I called friends and told them to try Enrich products,'' Marti says. ''It
just went from there.''</P>

<P>By December 1991, Marti had really caught the bug. She left the printing
firm and worked her Enrich business full-time from one of Roger's spare
offices. ''I was there 10 to 15 hours a day, seven days a week,'' she says.
Her success was energizing. ''I didn't know I had this knack. But when you
get excited about something, it's fun.'' Soon she was recruiting salespeople
by the dozens, establishing her ''success line.'' It meant long hours on
the phone, talking to friends first, then friends of friends, and so on.</P>

<P>The first Enrich bonus checks started coming, at a few hundred dollars
monthly. Within a year a good month would bring close to $20,000. These
days, after four and a half years in the business, almost all months are
that good. ''I now have 5,000 people in my success line,'' Marti says. ''And
every time someone somewhere in my line orders $100 worth of products from
Enrich, I get about $5.'' That passive income multiplied many times over,
combined with her own retail-sales profits, adds up, says Marti, to a six-figure
annual income.</P>

<P><B>High Tech Is Integral to Her Business</B></P>

<P>''Our home was designed to maximize the work of a home-based business
and the steady stream of social activities and meetings that accompany network
marketing,'' says Marti. Interviews with potential distributors are held
in the downstairs library, a good atmosphere for getting acquainted with
new people. ''We can turn off the phones and have very productive meetings
in much less time while keeping the conversation at a comfortable level
so we can conduct interviews on our terms.''</P>

<P>The Settles moved into their Argyle, Tex., Mediterranean-style home,
or ''big white castle,'' as Marti describes it, in 1994. It boasts five
bedrooms; a master bathroom with sauna, double tub, and television set;
and seven more rooms, all in 6,200 square feet of space -- not including
the exterior porches and balconies. A business associate or guest stepping
into the foyer is treated to gracefully curved twin cherry-wood staircases
framing an overhanging crystal chandelier. Throughout the house, windows
stretch from floor to ceiling, letting in golden streams of light and creating
a warm, open atmosphere.</P>

<P>Marti's upstairs office has an outdoor balcony with wicker seating for
casual business discussions, or meetings can be held indoors, by the office
fireplace. Custom-designed cherry-wood cabinets conceal Enrich products
and office supplies, and a dumbwaiter near the back stairways lets Marti
move products, boxes, and equipment up- and downstairs with ease. Like her
cabinets, her desk and chairs are a rich cherry wood.</P>

<P>High tech plays an integral role in growing Marti's business. She uses
an IBM 350 computer to keep track of sales and other business matters; a
Canon B140 fax easily enables her to stay in touch with her success line;
and a Lexmark Optra R-Plus laser printer produces top-quality correspondence,
faxes, and other documents. Business flyers and brochures for marketing
purposes look professional with photos and art scanned in by her Envisions
8800S scanner. And a Panasonic phone system throughout the house makes paging
possible from room to room. Marti markets her business online as well, with
Internet Global. ''Electronic telecommunications has made working at home
seamless,'' she says.</P>

<P>Other parts of the home are also designed for business. The theater,
with its 100-inch Sony TV, serves as a video-screening room for up to 40
people at weekly training meetings. Or ''members of our success line can
have their children watch movies upstairs while we meet downstairs, eliminating
the need for sitters.'' Potluck business lunches for 75 people, seated in
the foyer or on balconies, feature motivational speakers, whose voices and
images can be beamed to any room in the house courtesy of an advanced audiovisual
system.</P>

<P><B>Entrusting Her Financial Future to Herself</B></P>

<P>Early this year several major insurance firms stopped issuing comprehensive
home-insurance policies in the region as a result of floods, storms, and
tornadoes, giving Roger more time to help out with Marti's Enrich organization.
''Since Roger's business has primarily been built on homeowner insurance,
he effectively has no product to sell,'' notes Marti, ''a classic example
of how traditional businesses, in which so many of us entrusted our financial
futures, can evaporate in the blink of an eye.''</P>

<P>Meanwhile, Marti's days of working 100-hour weeks are long over. She
tries to be in her office by 9. ''But if I don't feel like it,'' she says,
''I don't. If I want to spend the day playing with my grandchildren, I just
walk out the door. The fact is,'' she adds, ''after I sold my agency and
walked away from the graphic-design industry, I found a new industry, a
new company, and a new lease on life all at once -- and I've never looked
back.'' *</P>

<P>Tom Moran is a New Jersey-based journalist who specializes in feature
writing and education. </TD></TR><TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">
	<H5><BR><BR><A HREF="12decTOC.html">DECEMBER 1996</A> / <A HREF="../../info.html">INFORMATION</A> / <A HREF="../../index.html">HOME PAGE</A> / <A HREF="../../subinfo.html">SUBSCRIPTIONS</A></H5>
	</TD>
</TR></TABLE>



