<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE> 12Homeofficewerner.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">COVER STORY / WORKING AT HOME</FONT><BR><HR>

	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"WIDTH="225">
<FONT SIZE="+4">GETTING DOWN TO BUSINESS</FONT>
<H3>The best place for it is at home, says Paul Wenner, creator of the wildly
successful Gardenburger.<BR>BY LISA SILVER</H3><IMG SRC="wen.gif" WIDTH="132" HEIGHT="120"><BR> <FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by CHARLES MARAIA</FONT>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275
	"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">By his own admission, Paul Wenner's head is ''often in the clouds.''
The socially conscious entrepreneur's flights of fancy have taken him from
selling electric cars to building houses from recycled materials to opening
a vegetarian restaurant -- all unsuccessfully. In 1981, however, experimenting
with food in his restaurant's refrigerator, he made a patty of leftover
rice pilaf, added fresh mushrooms and onions, oats, and low-fat cheeses,
then grilled it. Though his eatery would fail, his ''Gardenburger'' would
arguably become America's most popular meatless patty.</FONT>
</P>

<P>
Four years later, Wenner founded Wholesome &amp; Hearty Foods Inc. Within
a year he had more than 100 accounts and a small profit. Over the next decade
his Portland, Ore.-based company would grow an average 80 percent annually.
In 1993 financial publications pronounced his company the fastest-growing
stock in the nation. Sales in 1996 have topped $40 million, and in February
he sold his 100-millionth Gardenburger. Today, Gardenburgers are served
in more than 35,000 food-service outlets throughout the United States and
Canada and sold in more than 12,000 stores. Wenner's story illustrates how
an entrepreneur's unbounded enthusiasm and total belief in his product can
play as critical a role in success as a flawless business plan.
</P>

<P>
''I Had to Do Something I Believed In''
</P>

<P>
Suffering from asthma and tuberculosis as a child, Paul Wenner was restricted
from most activities. So when he tired of playing with his chemistry set
in his room, he'd go to the kitchen of his family's Portland home and fling
open the cupboards. At nine, he cooked his first Thanksgiving dinner.
</P>

<P>
Like many children in the 1950s, he grew up on meat and potatoes. At
age 17, however, he decided to make a change when he read of a man who'd
recovered from respiratory problems after becoming a vegetarian. Wenner
eliminated all animal products from his diet and would eat only fresh vegetables,
fruits, whole grains, and, for spice, onions and garlic -- foods that years
later would end up in his Gardenburger. ''Within a month, I was able to
breathe normally for the first time in my life,'' he says. ''I realized
then that there was a major connection between what you put in your mouth
and how you feel.''
</P>

<P>
After four years in the Air Force, Wenner attended a community college,
going through six majors before graduating in 1973 with degrees in television
production and general studies while also running a shoeshine business.
''After a while I thought, 'How am I going to make a living doing this?'''
</P>

<P>
Thereafter he would work in a health club, run a juice bar, and teach
food and nutrition classes. In 1975 he started selling electric cars, but
''people didn't want to plug in their automobiles nightly or drive 35 miles
per hour.'' The cars went unsold, and several thousand dollars were lost
-- but not Wenner's desire to save the environment. Next he would fix up
old houses using recycled materials and then sell them. He was making money
until the real-estate market crashed and he lost everything. ''It was a
disaster,'' he says.
</P>

<P>
But Wenner did own one building outright. In 1980, with a partner who
put in $10,000, he opened The Gardenhouse, a natural-foods restaurant in
Gresham, Ore. ''I cooked, waited tables, did the books,'' he says. ''I worked
100-hour weeks.'' One morning, he began experimenting to come up with the
day's special. His Gardenburger would become the most popular item on the
menu. Still, the restaurant was losing money, and after 31&#142;2 years
Wenner had to close. ''Here I was, 38 years old and asking, what now? I
couldn't take just any old job -- I had to do something I believed in. I'm
driven to help people make better food choices, which helps their health.
I knew I'd eventually succeed.''
</P>

<P>
''Lower the Valleys, Higher the Mountains''
</P>

<P>
In exchange for a place to live, he cooked and cleaned for a friend.
''I was so broke, I couldn't buy toothpaste, but I kept reminding myself:
The lower the valleys, the higher the mountains.'' That was in 1984, and
with the nation's eating habits changing, he wondered whether other restaurants
would serve his Gardenburgers. So he made patties by night and knocked on
doors by day. Within a couple of months, a restaurant, a hospital service,
and a college cafeteria were serving his creation.
</P>

<P>
In 1985 his sister, Linda, a broker with a venture-capital firm, encouraged
Wenner to contact her boss, a health-conscious multimillionaire. After buying
a book on how to write a business plan, Wenner sent him a Gardenburger and
a prospectus asking for $45,000. ''He said, 'Is that all you need?''' Wenner
recalls. ''I was so ignorant back then that I didn't even know what he meant.
So he said, 'Okay, let's do this: I'll take 55 percent of the business,
and I'll give you $60,000.' He also asked me point-blank: 'When can you
make money?' I thought that after working 100-hour workweeks for a year,
I could make money by the 13th month,'' which is what Wenner told him.
</P>

<P>
Wenner used the capital to found Wholesome &amp; Hearty Foods, buying
a refrigerated van and selling Gardenburgers door-to-door across Oregon.
Within a year he had over 100 accounts. ''I made, I think, $300 the 13th
month, and my partner called me from Europe and said, 'You made money, Paul!
You made $300!' This guy spends $300 on a bottle of wine, but he said, 'I
put a million dollars into projects, and people lose my money. What I really
like is that you did what you said you would do.'''
</P>

<P>
More Efficiency in a Home Office
</P>

<P>
Wenner spends 90 percent of his working time at his Portland home. (He
also has a house in Hawaii.) ''You can get more done at home,'' he says.
''In a corporate office, people interrupt you all the time.'' He purchased
a crumbling, two-story church for $19,000 in 1986 and rebuilt it using recycled
materials; worth $300,000 today, the structure is a gleaming white, four-story
domain with a tower overlooking Portland, a rooftop deck, and a living room
in which an Art Deco scene in fiber optics illuminates an entire wall. He
has a vegetable garden, a swim spa, a croquet court, and light-lined walkways.
</P>

<P>
His second-floor office looks out on a blaze of red and orange flowers
and tropical grasses. Actually three rooms in one, it comprises a test kitchen;
a dining room with a 16-foot-long table used for spreading out his work
as well as for meetings and entertaining; and a desk area partitioned off
by a wall of glass blocks. A typical workday begins at 8:30 a.m., when Wenner,
equipped with a fresh-fruit ''Hawaiian smoothie,'' tackles urgent phone
calls from management. An assistant handles the 60-plus other calls he receives
daily and correspondence; he himself initiates around 25 calls -- about
marketing, public relations, and new-product development (through the years
his GardenProducts have come to include GardenSausages, Gardenburger Veggie
Medley, and more meatless foods). A home-cooked lunch is often combined
with business meetings. The rest of the day is spent on various projects
-- infomercials; writing a book on healthy eating habits; starting up One
Percent for Health, a foundation to encourage food corporations to donate
1 percent of their pretax profits to support education about healthy living.
</P>

<P>
Wenner writes and designs marketing materials on a Macintosh PowerBook
270C Duo Dock computer, which converts to a laptop. A Hewlett-Packard Laser
Writer 8 prints his correspondence, and a Canon Fax/Phone B70 does his plain-paper
faxing. E-mail to business associates is sent through America Online, and
his Internet Web site serves as one way to advertise.
</P>

<P>
Wenner believes the roots of his success were planted the day he took
his health into his own hands and saw results. ''People often ask me what
business classes I've taken,'' he says. ''Well, real life has been my M.B.A.
and my Ph.D. I do what I know best, and I never give up. Never.'' *
</P>

<P>
Lisa Silver is a New York-based journalist whose feature articles appear
regularly in national magazines and online publications. 
</P></TD></TR><TR>


	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">
