  <TITLE>12Homeofficetracy.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">COVER STORY / WORKING AT HOME</FONT><BR><HR>

	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"WIDTH="225">
<FONT SIZE="+4">FLOOD YOUR LIFE WITH IDEAS</FONT>
<H3>That's what motivational expert Brian Tracy recommends to improve every
part of your business -- and your life. <BR>BY LISA SILVER</H3><IMG SRC="tracy.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="143" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2"><!--Photograph by GOES HERE--></FONT><HR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">Seven Keys to Success</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Having scrambled to survive and finally having achieved great success
in his own life, Tracy offers what he believes are the qualities critical
to success:
<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">
<DIR>
<P>
<P>
 	<LI>Clarity. Eighty percent of success comes from being clear on who you are, what you believe in, and what you want.
</P>
</P>
<P>
 	<LI>Competence. You can't climb to the next rung on the ladder until you are excellent at what you do now.
</P>
<P>
 	<LI>Constraints. Eighty percent of all obstacles to success come from within. Find out what is constraining you or your company and deal with it.
</P>
<P>
 	<LI>Concentration. The ability to focus on one thing singlemindedly and see it through until it's done takes more character than anything else.
</P>
<P>
 	<LI>Creativity. Flood your life with ideas from many sources. Creativity needs to be exercised; like a muscle, if you don't use it you'll lose it.
</P>
<P>
 	<LI>Courage. Most in demand and least in supply, courage is the willingness
	to do the things you know are right.
</P>
<P>
 	<LI>Continuous learning. Read at the very least one book a week on business to keep you miles ahead of the competition. And just as you eat and bathe, organize your time so you spend 30 minutes a day exploring e-mail, sending messages, going through the Web sites, because it's like exercise. It's the only way you can keep on top of technology. If you get away from it, you'll lose your edge.
</P>
</DIR>
Remember, adds Tracy, &quot;once you decide what it is you want, you
can learn whatever you need to learn. The key is to get the knowledge and
practice it until it becomes a skill. When I did that, every single part
of my life improved. Not overnight but over time.&quot; </FONT></TD>
	
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275
	"><FONT SIZE="+1"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P>
In his first two years as a motivational speaker, Brian Tracy ended up
paying the equivalent of $100 per head for people to hear him. In real-estate
development by day, he had hired someone to sell his success-strategies
seminars, but that person couldn't sell anything: Only six or seven people
attended his first presentation, one of whom had paid; later seminars turned
out to be free, though Tracy thought his audience had paid. He went to the
edge of the cliff financially.</FONT>
</P>

<P>
Tracy's climb to the top as a motivational expert would begin two years
later, in 1983, after a representative from IBM came to one of his seminars.
A contract with the corporate giant followed, as well as seminars for Exxon,
Chevron, McDonnell Douglas, real-estate firms, banks, and numerous other
companies. Today Tracy makes more than 100 presentations a year, and his
San Diego-based human-resource company, Brian Tracy International, retails
$21 million annually from sales of his audiocassette training programs,
videotapes, and books, the last including Maximum Achievement and
Advanced Selling Strategies. His is a story of how an entrepreneur
who is flexible about the process of achieving his goals and dedicated to
continuous, lifelong learning can attain business success -- despite a rocky,
even disastrous, start.
</P>

<P>
<B>Becoming Proactive, Not Reactive, in Business
</B></P>

<P>
The oldest of four boys, Brian Tracy was the hell-raiser in the family.
''I was a complete failure in school and got more demerits, detentions,
and expulsions than any kid around,'' says Tracy, who was born in Canada
but raised in Pomona, Calif. At 16 he dropped out of school, uninterested
and unmotivated, and would earn money washing dishes and working in factories
and construction. When he was 21, he packed up an old car and drove cross-country.
A few years later, on a ship out of Halifax, Nova Scotia, he ''went off
to see the world'' and didn't return for 10 years. By the time he was 30,
he had lived in 80 countries and spoke four languages. But it was an experience
in Africa that made an incredible impact on his life.
</P>

<P>
In 1965 Tracy set out with friends to travel from Vancouver, British
Columbia, to Cape Town, South Africa. Midway across the 1,000-mile Sahara
Desert, however, the carburetor on his Land Rover broke down, then the steering
rods and clutch. With their water supply low, Tracy says, ''I knew that
if we couldn't fix the car, we would die.'' Drawing upon skills he'd picked
up as a kid, he repaired the car, and the group made it across the desert.
</P>

<P>
''That's when something locked in,'' he says. ''I realized I was responsible
for my own life. From that point on, I stopped blaming my parents, teachers,
other people. I knew nothing in my life would ever change unless I changed;
I knew a person must be a proactive agent in his life rather than a reactive
agent.''
</P>

<P>
Tracy would reach Cape Town just over a year later. This experience,
he says, taught him a critical lesson. ''You must be clear about the goals
you set, flexible about the process of achieving them, and then continually
learn all you can in every way possible'' to have success. He has practiced
what he learned ever since.
</P>

<P>
In 1966 Tracy would find himself in Johannesburg, where he peddled office
supplies and gadgets. ''It was the only work I could find, going door-to-door,
office-to-office, selling stuff, and it didn't go well at first,'' he says.
''So I decided to study selling.'' In fact, Tracy says, in every case, when
he had a new business challenge, he got every book he could find on the
subject ''and stayed up late at night reading them cover to cover. And I
spoke to everybody I could find in the business, so I was able to accelerate
my learning curve dramatically.''
</P>

<P>
As a result, in 1968 he would manage a 95-person sales force for a company
in Canada. A few years later, when his interests turned to mutual funds
and real estate, he learned everything he could about those fields. By 1978
the former high-school dropout was chief operating officer of the Edmonton,
Alberta-based Patrician Land Corporation, then a $265 million development
company, and one year away from earning a college degree in communications.
The year before, he'd met Barbara, who would soon become his wife and, later,
vice chairman of Brian Tracy International.
</P>

<P>
Through all the years and all the travel, Tracy stayed true to his belief
in continuous learning. He read at least two business books a week (among
his favorites, Peter Drucker's Practices of Management and Andrew
Grove's High-Output Management) and attended self-improvement seminars.
''I saw all these eager, sincere people who had paid $500 to improve themselves,
and the seminars were terrible. I thought: 'I can do better than that.'''
And he did.
</P>

<P>
<B>Everything Costs Three Times More Than Expected
</B></P>

<P>
In 1981 Tracy created a seminar on success strategies he used in his
climb to CEO. In the course evaluation, attendees rated his talk 99 out
of 100 -- just what his entrepreneurial spirit needed to seek the next challenge.
He would leave his real-estate career to found BTI in Edmonton, but he made
some costly mistakes. Says Tracy, ''There are three basic rules of thumb
to know when you start a business:
</P>

<P>
''1. Everything costs three times more than you expected.
</P>

<P>
''2. Everything takes twice as long.
</P>

<P>
''3. Every three months you'll face a small-business crisis that could
sink your business if not responded to responsibly.''
</P>

<P>
Tracy candidly admits that he didn't know these rules when he started
BTI. ''I learned,'' he adds, ''but at a terrible rate. It took three to
four years to become a top speaker and trainer. I had to sell my home, my
car, my furniture. I moved into a rented house and lived on credit cards.''
</P>

<P>
Despite the struggle, Barbara, who had just had their first child, encouraged
him. ''She always said our financial problems were just a temporary blip
on the radar screen,'' he says.
</P>

<P>
She was right. In 1983 an IBM representative came to one of Tracy's courses,
and the blip disappeared. Other corporations followed, and in 1986 the CEO
moved BTI's headquarters from Edmonton to San Diego.
</P>

<P>
<B>Technology Cuts the Time It Takes to Get a Result
</B></P>

<P>
More than half of Tracy's work is done at his home, though he has a fully
staffed office at company headquarters, minutes away. ''You can't get any
work done at work,'' he says. ''Seventy-five percent of all time in a corporate
office is spent interacting with other people. If that can be done with
a phone or fax instead, the need to be there drops dramatically.''
</P>

<P>
His California abode, shared with Barbara and their children, Christina,
16, Michael, 14, David, 10, and Catherine, 5, is one of Tracy's greatest
pleasures. Tucked away behind a redwood gate in Solana Beach, the 5,000-square-foot
stucco-and-stone ranch-style house sits on a bluff surrounded by palm trees
and overlooking a golf course and rolling hills. Light streams in through
seven skylights, and the traditionally decorated rooms are furnished in
Chinese cherry wood. The entire second level is the couple's 600-square-foot
master suite; on the first level are five other bedrooms, five bathrooms,
a library, and a wine cellar. There's a swimming pool, a garden of 100 rosebushes,
and a skateboard ramp out front for the kids.
</P>

<P>
Designed to limit distractions and maximize efficiency, his home office,
a business-book-lined retreat carpeted to reduce noise and separated from
the residence by double doors, is ''almost like a business cocoon,'' Tracy
says. The 30-or-so magazines and other publications he subscribes to can
be found here, as well as two television sets to review his videos or watch
educational or informational programs. Tracy thinks of his home office as
a kind of production line, and he works straight through from 7 a.m. until
6:30 p.m., when he stops to enjoy dinner with his family; afterward he resumes
work until 9.
</P>

<P>
When it comes to business tools, Tracy doesn't believe in ''cheaping
out.'' ''A businessperson's most valuable asset is time,'' he says. ''Working
at home is a way of reducing transition time, traveling time, and functioning
time. Technology reduces the time it takes to get a particular result. My
home computer is networked into the computers in my corporate office, so
I can access all the financial data, accounting data, all correspondence
and communications, just by dialing in and punching a button.''
</P>

<P>
For presentations, books, and articles, Tracy writes on a Macintosh PowerBook
280C Duo Dock computer, which converts to a laptop. He uses a Macintosh
Laser Writer Select for printing and a Xerox Home Copier. With his computer's
internal fax/modem, he sends documents to the head office and, through America
Online and CompuServe, e-mail to associates worldwide. One phone line is
designated for fax and online purposes; two other lines, with voice mail
and speakerphone, handle the 20 to 30 calls he receives daily from clients
and staff about upcoming presentations. But he also swears by a good old-fashioned
to-do list -- still ''the best of all time-management techniques.''
</P>

<P>
On the true importance of money, Tracy, as one would expect, is clear:
''The whole point of life is to really live, to expand your horizons. Every
person owes it to himself to develop to the point where he can be financially
free so he can turn his mind to higher and better things. When you reach
a point where you don't have to worry about money, your mind is free to
make a difference in the world.''</TD></TR><TR>
</P>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">
