	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">COVER STORY / WORKING AT HOME</FONT><BR><HR>

	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"WIDTH="225">
<IMG SRC="news.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="60" HEIGHT="90" BORDER="0">
<FONT SIZE="+4">Entrepreneurial News</FONT>
<H3>Fast Facts to Help You Run Your Business Better<BR>By Kathleen Upton Finch
</H3><BR> <FONT SIZE="-2"></FONT>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275
	"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">
<P>
<B>National Association of 
Home Based Businesses</B>
</P>

<P>
Whether your business is still just a bright idea, a start-up, or already up and running, the National Association of Home Based Businesses exists for the serious entrepreneur. ''Basically, our role is to provide development and support services for home-managed businesses,'' says Rudy Lewis, president of the association, founded in 1984. ''We work with about 200 classifications of entrepreneurs, from  interior designers to management consultants.'' Among association services: helping members keep their businesses open 24 hours a day with an Internet site for home enterprises listed at the state, national, and international levels. ''We prepare our members for the global marketplace,'' says Lewis.</FONT>
</P>


<P>
To qualify for membership, applicants must fill out business- and marketing-plan forms, then provide an outline of performance steps they'll take to meet their business goals. Members pay a $125 first-year fee; thereafter the annual fee drops to $48. For more information: National Association of Home Based Businesses, 10451 Mill Run Circle, Suite 400, Owings Mills, MD 21117; 410-363-3698.
</P>


<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">High-Tech Equipment 
At Low Cost</FONT>
</P>


<P>
Now's the time when companies upgrade their office hardware, scheduling new-equipment purchases to take advantage of year-end tax breaks. What does this mean for you? The chance to cash in on high-tech buys for your business as a flood of computers -- as many as 10 million each year -- make their way to the used-products marketplace.
</P>


<P>
It's no wonder, then, that the number of specialty shops like Minneapolis-based Computer Renaissance and Kenilworth, N. J.'s Rumarson Technologies Inc. is growing. These shops refurbish the machines, then sell them at outlets or through the mail for savings between 25 percent and 75 percent.
</P>


<P>
''Our prices are based on prevailing market conditions, as well as the condition of the machine,'' says Michael Flynn, general manager of Computer Renaissance, ''and they all come with some sort of warranty, usually 30 days.'' Stock at Rumarson Technologies, which claims a standard 90-day warranty, has included a Compaq DeskPro 486, which retailed for $2,000 new and sold for $525 used, and an IBM IBX 486, which originally retailed for $2,150 and sold for $875 used. Each machine was about two years old.
</P>


<P>
Even better buys: never-touched computers. This past year, Rumarson Technologies bought close to $15 million worth of unused, discontinued equipment direct from AT&amp;T and sold it at discounted prices. To reach Computer Renaissance, call 1-800-433-2540; Rumarson Technologies, 1-800-929-0029.
</P>


<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Making Fast (Paper) Work of Business-Loan Applications</FONT>
</P>


<P>
While many banks won't consider small-business loan applications, a smaller cash infusion is possible -- and available -- for home-based entrepreneurs through the Small Business Association. In fact, more than 8,000 lenders are participating in the SBA program, including NationsBank, Citibank, Barnett Bank, and The Money Store.
</P>


<P>
''Banks have been reluctant to bother with loans under $100,000 because all the paperwork involved was costly to process,'' says SBA spokesman Mike Stamler. To help solve the problem, the SBA has the LowDoc -- or Low Documentation -- Loan Program. ''We've taken a loan application that used to be measured in inches down to one page,'' says Stamler. LowDoc loans, which average $54,000, now account for about 50 percent of the loans arranged through the SBA.
</P>


<P>
Eligibility requirements vary depending on the type of business, but all applicants must be running or starting a business, and it must be a for-profit venture. ''Lenders traditionally want a major collateral commitment for a business loan,'' says Stamler. ''But with LowDocs, we're more interested in anticipated cash flow.'' For more details about LowDocs, call your local office of the Small Business Administration.
</P>


<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Protect Your Laptop</FONT>
</P>


<P>
Before hitting the road with your laptop computer, take heed. Between 1994 and 1995, laptop thefts increased almost 40 percent over the previous year. To protect your investment, look into insurance coverage.
</P>


<P>
''Laptops disappear from hotel rooms, airports, car trunks, just about anywhere,'' warns David Johnston of Safeware, The Insurance Agency Inc., which specializes in policies for computers and other home-based equipment. ''After it's stolen is when many people find out their computer is not covered under their homeowner policy.'' Indeed, most homeowner policies limit home-office equipment coverage to about $2,500, and some exclude coverage for out-of-home and out-of-country thefts as well as thefts from unoccupied cars.
</P>


<P>
Additional protection can be had from many companies for under $100. Five thousand dollars' worth of coverage for hardware and software, for example, is available for $69 a year from Safeware; $10,000 in coverage costs $200 a year. But before buying any specialized insurance for electronic equipment, phone your homeowner carrier to learn what is and isn't covered.  To reach Safeware, call 1-800-800-1492.
</P>


<P>
Kathleen Upton Finch, a Connecticut-based journalist, specializes in business issues.
</P></TD></TR><TR>


