<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	FRANCHISE GOLD 100 / CEO Q &amp; A  <BR><BR>
	</TD>
	
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+5">The Secrets Of Success From Four Savvy Franchise CEOs.<BR><BR> </FONT> 


<BR><MENU>
 	<LI><A HREF="#1">Alan Schonberg</A> was a founder of Management
	Recruiters International Inc.
	<LI><A HREF="#2">Ed Rensi</A> is CEO and president of franchise industry
	leader McDonald's 
	<LI><A HREF="#3">Gene Obermeyer</A>, president and COO of Norrell Temporary
	Services
	<LI><A HREF="#4">Anthony Vidergauz</A>, president and CEO of California
	Closets 
</MENU>
<BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	

<H1  ALIGN=left><A NAME="1">Grow, Survive, Thrive</A> </H1>
<P><STRONG>In 1965, Alan Schonberg was a founder of Management
Recruiters International Inc. (#7), a modest executive-search firm. From
the beginning, the company grew through franchising. Today, it has 660 offices
worldwide (60 are company owned; the rest are franchised) and annual revenues
of nearly $350 million. </STRONG></P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: Was your business more straightforward
when you started in 1965?</B> </P>

<P>Schonberg: You have to go back to the history of
the search and recruitment business. During the Depression, employment agencies
were almost like union halls. People sat around and were sent out on a day
job. From 1947 until about 1960, the employment placement fees were paid
by the applicant, not the companies. Companies began to nibble at paying
fees in the very late '50s and early '60s. We formed Management Recruiters
in 1965 on the premise that the candidate would never pay the fee -- only
the employer. We were pioneers in that. </P>

<P>The most recent change came around 1992 during
the quality movement. Companies wanted to instill quality improvement in
hiring. Instead of promiscuously doing business with 28 search firms, they
wanted to find only one or two that could satisfy their needs. And that
created something we never really knew we had: the staffing industry. As
a result, we too have become a hybrid in the staffing industry, and it's
given us our greatest growth. We have divisions today that do outplacement,
supply temporary executives, and outsource sales staffs and human resources
functions. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: It seems that with current trends, you've
been able to ride a real wave of growth in your business.</B> </P>

<P>Schonberg: We have. The recession of 1991 hurt
us, but by 1993, we went into an upward mode. There's been growth in the
staffing industry, of which we are a part. I'm not sure whether our recent
success is due to the maturation of franchising or the quality of the business
that this franchise is in. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: Who are the franchisees you have coming
into the system?</B> </P>

<P>Schonberg: We have seen, in the last three to five
years, more serious franchise buyers; higher-caliber and quality franchise
buyers, people who have accomplished more in their previous situations than
we've seen in the past. And we've seen an awful lot of refugees from the
corporate world. Ninety-nine percent have never been in our business before.
</P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: What draws them to your business? </B></P>

<P>Schonberg: They don't like hamburgers, mufflers,
cleaning houses. They like a business-to-business thing, which is what we
are. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: What's the average investment somebody
has to make to open a Management Recruiters franchise? </B></P>

<P>Schonberg: About $125,000. That's for everything.
We spend several days with them doing site selection, getting them set up.
Then they come to a three-week training course here in Cleveland. Then we
connect them to our network; we have the nation's largest videoconferencing
network -- 260 videoconferencing studios throughout the country -- and through
distance learning we train all their new people. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: Do you encourage multiple-unit franchisees?</B>
</P>

<P>Schonberg: No. The personal dynamics in this business
are such that if I had my way, I'd probably have no one in multiple-unit
franchises. They can do so much more with their own personal dynamics within
their own four walls. But some I can't stop. They want to have two or three
or four offices, and they do. Then they have to hire managers, then fire
managers, then their own operations fall down. Frankly, we're not the Golden
Arches where you pull up to the corner of 6th and Main and great, there's
a McDonald's -- and there's also one at 8th and Main. Ours is a personal
business. It involves establishing relationships that have integrity, honesty,
and are confidential. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: How do you keep the competition from coming
in and doing the same things you're doing? </B></P>

<P>Schonberg: Our barrier to competition is the size
and momentum we already have. We've got 660 offices and 3,500 account executives.
We've got all this technology going for us; we've got all this collectiveness
going for us. How can these small independents compete with us? They can't.
* <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.4 -437838. -->

<P ALIGN=LEFT><A NAME="2">CEO Q &amp; A </A></P>

<H1>The View From the Big Chair </H1>

<P><STRONG>Ed Rensi is CEO and president of franchise industry
leader McDonald's (#1):</STRONG> </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: What was learned from the launch of the
Arch Deluxe? </B></P>

<P>Rensi: We used a lot of public relations to introduce
the sandwich. McDonald's has always got to find fun ways to deliver its
news. Besides that, the sandwich tastes really good, and it's really exceeded
our expectations in a lot of ways. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: There was that reported</B> </P>

<P>problem; your ad agency made a media budget error.
</P>

<P>Rensi: First of all, it was an error in projections,
not an actual cash error. And it was frankly a minor thing that got blown
way out of proportion. Our total ad budget is $900 million, and this error
was $18 million. </P>

<P>We went to our franchisee leadership and told them
exactly what happened in great detail, because we believe if you're going
to have great franchisee relationships, you have to have total candor. In
the absence of good communications, the grapevine takes over, and you get
a lot of anecdotal information. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: What trends do you see taking shape in
franchising?</B> </P>

<P>Rensi: I think franchising is the single most important
business tool to preserve the free enterprise system in the United States.
When people have a vested interest in a direct way in the GNP, they perform
differently; and I think franchising is a great way to give people opportunity
while providing a safety net. </P>

<P>One of the major issues today, with the rapid market
expansion, is how do you keep individual stores profitable? We went out
to our franchisees and said, ''Participate with us to work this out.'' We
talked about such things as a low-cost approach to construction and development,
to purchasing and infrastructure for such things as food and paper. We produced
a number of tools. We have market-share panels, populated by franchisees,
and they hear business cases from franchisees who might be affected by new
restaurant sites. They make a judgment as to what kind of assistance the
franchisee might need to deal with the new stores. And the company funds
that. We allocate tens of millions of dollars to that. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: What is your position on the new minimum-wage
laws? </B></P>

<P>Rensi: I don't think it will be harmful to franchisees,
because everybody in America has to raise wages to the new minimum. If this
minimum wage were unfairly targeted to one industry, that would be a problem;
but this is across the board. It's an economic train track we're on, but
we're all headed in the same direction. We all want to make a profit, and
we all want to deliver customer service. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: What's your advice to those looking to
buy or grow a franchise business?</B> </P>

<P>Rensi: It's something you already know: Anybody
looking for a franchise today had better do his homework. He had better
understand the business he's looking into, and he'd better understand whether
he likes it or not. </P>

<P>There are no guarantees in this world. You're always
going to run into pitfalls. </P>

<P>But that's one of the benefits of franchising:
Those kinds of things are minimized, and there's a track record you can
look at. A talented businessperson who has a customer-service focus can
make just about any business work if he has the right location. Too often,
people who fail in franchising want to blame the system, and often it's
themselves that are the problem. They think they'll take the retirement
fund, put it into a franchise, and it will become an annuity. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: Where do you want to take McDonald's in
the next few years?</B> </P>

<P>Rensi: As a major shareholder of the company, I
think McDonald's has a fabulous future. I think the potential outside the
U.S. is huge, and we're just beginning to tap into it. I saw an article
just yesterday about the shortage of seats in schools for all the children.
It just warms my heart to see that all these baby boomers are having grandkids
that McDonald's will be able to serve. </P>

<P>It's been my experience that the executives at
McDonald's don't have big egos. They're accessible, and they value the franchisees.
You have to have a set of beliefs and values; you have to have a system
and make it work. Any franchisor that can't convey that level of confidence
and keep intact that fundamental value system is making a huge mistake.
</P>

<P ALIGN=LEFT><A NAME="3">COO Q &amp; A </A></P>

<H1>Staying on Top of Trends </H1>

<P><STRONG>Gene Obermeyer, president and COO of Norrell Temporary
Services (#52), talks about the changing economy.</STRONG> </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: Norrell's founder, Guy Millner, is running
for the U.S. Senate. What's his platform? </B></P>

<P>Obermeyer: Guy started the company 35 years ago.
Back then, he placed recent college grads in sales jobs. Today, Norrell
is a billion-dollar company that provides very complex customer solutions.
Guy felt it was time to step out of the day-to-day operations. He knows
a lot of people in the business community, and he wanted to devote his time
and energy to making the government more effective. He wants to get tougher
on crime, reduce taxes, downsize the government, and impose term limits.
He feels there are too many career politicians who get in there and lose
touch with the common person. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: As you've grown Norrell, what have been
your biggest challenges or mistakes? </B></P>

<P>Obermeyer: Our biggest challenge has been to remain
close to the customer and not miss the trends as they come along. In the
1980s, staffing was a retail-focused business. Customers just called and
said, ''I need X number of people to do the job.'' In the early '90s, all
of that changed. Companies saw that it was costly to use a large number
of vendors. As they reduced the number of vendors, we saw our margins drop
from 32 percent to 22 percent. We had to transform our operating centers
from acting independently to driving more volume through our branches. </P>

<P>One mistake we may have made was getting into health
care in the early 1980s. With the graying of America, there seemed to be
a big need to supply nurse staffing in hospitals. That's similar to what
we do. But with home care, Medicaid, and new government regulation, the
industry changed so much. By the end of the 1980s, it was almost completely
nonsynergistic to our other business. We decided to get out. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: Where are the opportunities for growth
for Norrell? What about for entrepreneurs interested in a franchise? </B></P>

<P>Obermeyer: We have a strategic plan to double in
size by the year 2000. We're planning on expanding our relationships with
large users -- clients with more than $1 million in annual billings. There's
a tremendous opportunity with outsourcing and for specialized temps in growing
areas like information technology and financial services. </P>

<P>Having company units in main cities and franchising
in secondary markets works best for us. We can attract people already in
the marketplace who can deal with local customers. Most -- about 49 percent
-- of our franchisees are owned by women and minorities. We have opportunities
throughout the Midwest and Northwest. We want to move into new markets.


<H1><A NAME="4">The Sultan Of Storage </A></H1>

<P><STRONG>Anthony Vidergauz, president and CEO of California
Closets (#25), reveals his strategy to make his company synonymous with
closet and home-office design.</STRONG> </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: What initially attracted you to California
Closets?</B> </P>

<P>Vidergauz: I'm from South Africa. In 1986, my wife
and I were in Los Angeles visiting her mother. Two days before we were due
to leave, California Closets did her closets. In 24 hours, they turned a
messy closet into a beautiful place. I was so impressed, I went to see the
president of this fledgling company. I went to ask whether they would sell
franchises in South Africa. Instead, I ended up taking a job in the legal
department. I'm a lawyer by profession. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: How did you move from the legal department
to CEO?</B> </P>

<P>Vidergauz: In 1990, Williams Sonoma bought California
Closets. They thought there was a synergy with their retail company, Hold
Everything. But it didn't work, because their timing was terrible. The Gulf
War had just started, and the bottom fell out of the economy. We were just
a branch of a very big public company. They hired someone to run California
Closets, and things didn't click. I felt that they may be willing to talk
about a sale. One day on the golf course, I asked my mentor, Bill LeVine
of PIP Printing, to help me buy the company. He agreed, and I contacted
the chairman of Williams Sonoma; and within three months, we had a deal.
</P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: How do people make money selling closets?</B>
</P>

<P>Vidergauz: One of the hottest industries around
is the storage industry. Ten years ago, custom-designed systems were done
for people with disposable income. Fortunately, today it's a lot more mainstream.
People are very busy. People want to be organized. </P>

<P>We've sold franchises from Helena, Mont., to New
York City. Volume varies. A mini franchise may be doing $15,000 per month.
New York City is doing $300,000 per month. Our average franchise is doing
$75,000 per month in sales. </P>

<P>The average sales call is 90 minutes. The customer,
usually a woman, invites us into the most embarrassing part of her home
-- her messy closets. That's a hot lead. A good salesperson closes nearly
80 percent of his appointments. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: You're expanding your original concept
to include home-office design. How do you plan to build a name in that market?</B>
</P>

<P>Vidergauz: We're in the house already. As a company,
we have to maximize our opportunity. There are 44 million people working
from home. We thought, ''Why don't we do the same thing in the home office
as we do in the closet?'' We've just rolled out this concept called Room
2 Work. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: Who's your competition, and how are you
different?</B> </P>

<P>Vidergauz: The other big franchise chain is Closet
Factory, which is about one-third our size. We've been different all along
because we pioneered this industry. We're first in innovation and customer
service. Our goal is to simplify your life. That's our motto. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: What do you do to make franchisees successful?</B>
</P>

<P>Vidergauz: We've done a tremendous amount of work
in customer service. Contractors do not enjoy a reputation of being on time
and cleaning up at the end. We call customers after every job. Every customer
fills out a survey, and I read every one of them. </P>

<P>We've improved our communication within the system.
We have a franchisee advisory council, an ongoing newsletter, an owners'
convention. We've significantly increased the quality and quantity of our
training. </P>

<P><B>SUCCESS: Where do you see yourself 10 years from
now?</B> </P>

<P>Vidergauz: We want to build the California Closet
brand name. We set up a national marketing fund, which more than 90 percent
of our franchisees contribute to. Now, you'll see us in Architectural Digest
and Martha Stewart Living. People buy from a name they trust. We are determined
that California Closet will be synonymous with storage. </P>

<P>We don't want to sell as many franchises as we
possibly can. We sell big territories. Most of the country is sold out,
but there are a few areas still open: Salt Lake City, Raleigh, N.C., Albuquerque,
Memphis. We're rolling out high-quality retail stores. We certainly want
to sell California Closets worldwide. 
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

