<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>11Gold100Method</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


 FRANCHISE    GOLD 100

<H1>
Ranking the Best
</H1>
<H2 ALIGN="LEFT">
Survey Criteria and Methodology
</H2>
<P>
More than 2,500 businesses today are exploiting franchising as a growth strategy. And an increasing pool of entrepreneurial franchisees are taking these companies to new heights. How do you identify the best practices and the best opportunities? 

<P>
You won't find a better ranking of franchise businesses than the 1996 SUCCESS/Arthur Andersen Franchise Gold 100. Our complex criteria allow us to evaluate fairly new players side by side with national giants. And because of our partnership with FRANDATA Corp. of Washington, D.C., we were able to draw data directly from each company's Uniform Franchise Offering Circular (UFOC), thus dramatically increasing the pool of companies that were evaluated. UFOCs are disclosure documents required by state regulatory agencies in order to sell franchise units.

<P>
Access to FRANDATA's database of UFOCs and our improved methodology allowed us to analyze the more than 600 leading franchise companies that met our criteria. We limited our survey to U.S. companies with an established track record. Specifically, we reviewed only franchise businesses that met three criteria: 


<DIR>
	<P>
	<LI>a minimum of 15 operational units
	</P>

	<P>
	<LI>a minimum of three years in business as a franchise 
	</P>

	<P>
	<LI>a current plan or intent to sell franchises in the U.S. 
	</P>


	<P>
	<LI>Companies that met these qualifications were analyzed in four areas, with each area given a weighted percentage based on average scores:
	</P>


	<P>
	<LI>franchisor's financial performance (27 percent)
	</P>

	<P>
	<LI>corporate growth, management, and stability (28 percent)
	</P>

	<P>
	<LI>franchisor/franchisee relationship (28 percent)
	</P>

	<P>
	<LI>opportunities for growth (17 percent)
	</P>
</DIR>

<P>
<B>Franchisor's Financial<BR>
Performance
</B>
<P>
Using audited financial statements, KPMG/Peat Marwick LLC's Dallas office calculated each company's financial performance, which is the clearest indicator of stability. Companies earned points for a healthy return on equity. Other important factors we considered were the ratio of current assets/current liabilities, ratio of debt/equity, and total revenue growth for the past two years. 

<P>
This year, we also looked at the franchisor's operating margin percentage (earnings before interest and taxes) in the overall financial scoring. 

<P>
<B>Corporate Growth, Management, and Stability
</B>
<P>
We attempted to eliminate any bias toward larger companies by examining the percentage growth in the number of domestic franchised units instead of the total system size. We also examined the number of domestic franchised units joining and leaving the system during the same period to determine net growth. We evaluated the existing management team's strength to grow the company.

<P>
<B>Franchisor/Franchisee Relationship</B>

<P>
We compared the length of initial training for each system with other companies in that industry instead of comparing it with an overall average. Readers pointed out that the depth of training necessary to learn operations for a hotel franchise differs greatly from that of learning how to run a carpet-cleaning franchise. We assessed the quality of services provided by the franchisor by having 10 random franchisees in each system rate the training, operations manuals, and support services. Franchisors got points if they provided useful proprietary software systems to franchisees -- and more points if they didn't charge for these systems. Attorney Warren Lewis analyzed litigation histories: the number of suits disclosed (adjusted to account for the total number of franchisees in the system); the percentage of concluded actions with significantly adverse holdings; and the number of pending actions with significantly adverse allegations.

<P>
<B>Opportunities for Growth</B>

<P>
Franchisors that offer direct financing or that connect franchisees with financiers won points. We looked favorably at the availability of exclusive territories and opportunities for continuous renewal. Companies that contractually encourage multiunit development, and/or offer reductions in fees for multiunit purchases, or had active regional advertising funds, scored points.

<P ALIGN="LEFT">
<I>OUR PANEL OF EXPERTS</I> <BR>The Franchise Gold 100 research team was headed by attorney Jeffrey E. Kolton, president and founder of FRANDATA Corp. and a member of the International Franchise Association's Board of Directors. Dave Munk, head of Information Systems for FRANDATA, and Gary Wingo and Amy Brockman of KPMG's Washington, D.C., office helped assure the statistical accuracy of the methodology. 

<P>
Regina O. Gardner, president and owner of UNIGLOBE Dynamic Travel Inc. of Houston. Gardner serves on the Franchise Advisory Council of the IFA. 

<P>
William B. Cherkasky, president and CEO of the Education Foundation of the International Franchise Association of Washington, D.C., and former president of the IFA (1981 to 1995).

<P>
Patrick Kaufmann, associate professor of marketing at Georgia State University in Atlanta. Kaufmann has conducted extensive studies of franchise businesses. 

<P>
Nordahl L. Brue, cofounder of Bruegger's Corp. (which was recently merged with Quality Dining Inc.), and co-owner of more than 150 franchised units of Bruegger's.

<P>
Warren Lewis, an attorney with the Washington, D.C., law firm of Lewis &amp; Trattner. Lewis is the founder of the Capital Area Franchise Association and a member of the Council of Franchise Suppliers Advisory Board of the IFA. 

<P>
Michael Seid, leading franchise consultant and managing director of Strategic Advisory Group Inc. of West Hartford, Conn., a franchise advisory firm with a strategic alliance with KPMG. Seid is also a former franchisee and franchisor.

