   <TITLE>11FranDiligence</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0b1">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=1024 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	FRANCHISE GOLD 100<BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">Do Your Due Diligence </FONT>

<H3>How to Invest<BR>in a Winning Franchise<BR> <I>By Katherine Callan</I></H3>
<BR><BR><BR><BR><HR><BR>

<FONT COLOR=#CC000C><H3>Checklist for Investigating A Franchise </H3>


<P>If you're considering investing in a franchise, you want to undertake
the same due diligence as you would for any other major financial deal.
A key process is to talk to other franchisees. There is no better reality
check than visiting sites and talking with the owner and/or manager, customers,
and employees. Observe traffic flow and the flow of business. Note vendor
names for future investigation. Note the quality of service and attitude
of the employees, then visit at least three more sites. </P>

<P>The Federal Trade Commission has stated: &quot;Speaking with current
and former franchisees is probably the most reliable way to verify the franchisor's
claims. Visit or phone as many of the current and former franchisees as
possible. Ask them about their experiences. See for yourself the volume
and type of business being done.&quot; </P>

<P>Be sensitive to franchisees' schedules. Typically, they are operating
and, in some cases, managing their businesses on a day-to-day basis. Contact
franchisees by telephone first to arrange a time to visit their site or
talk in more depth by phone. </P>

<P>Of course, there are other vital steps to follow, which are outlined
below: </P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI><P>Create a customized franchisor profile. Determine the variables that constitute your ideal franchise company based on industry, investment required, geographic preference, etc. </P>
	<LI><P>Contact franchisors and request their marketing materials. Review these materials as well as other information available on franchising. </P>
	<LI><P>Review the offering circular. Note company and management background,	and review start-up/ongoing costs, level of support, and provisions of franchise agreement, etc. </P>
	<LI><P>Talk with franchisees. Determine the level of franchisee satisfaction, and prepare financial projections. </P>
	<LI><P>Visit sites. Evaluate the day-to-day operations, and realistically determine if the business appears to be a good fit for you -- especially
	<LI>compared with your personality, marketing ability, management skills, and level of financial and time commitment. </P>
	<LI><P>Examine the competition. Note how the competition rates overall and, specifically, in your market area. What are the strengths and weaknesses compared with the franchise you are considering? </P>
	<LI><P>Meet with a franchise attorney and accountant. Carefully review the franchise agreement. Prepare financial projections and, if needed, a business plan to secure financing. </P>
	<LI><P>Complete discussions with franchisor. Negotiate the franchise agreement and make a commitment.</FONT></P>
</UL>

<P>From the SUCCESS Guide to Selecting a Franchise.


	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P>This past April, at the age of 81, Estelle Musico opened her fourth McDonald's
restaurant. &quot;My husband and I got interested in McDonald's because
our friends owned one,&quot; says the company's oldest franchisee. &quot;We
went with them to conventions. I learned what McDonald's was all about.&quot;
</P>

<P>Even though she lacked business experience, Musico believed she had what
it took to run a McDonald's. At the age of 59, after a career as a teacher
and a psychologist, she and her husband bought their first unit in Somerset,
Penn. </P>

<P>&quot;During orientation, we were trained in handling people,&quot; she
says. &quot;We learned about communication skills and the psychology of
listening. That was right up my alley. I certainly didn't know about equipment
and operations, but I felt certain I could learn.&quot; Musico found business
ownership was almost as much fun as it was profitable. Inspired, she opened
more locations. ''I find it exhilarating,'' she says. </P>

<P>It's always a gamble to invest in a new franchise opportunity. But through
proper due diligence, the risk can be greatly minimized. Whether, like Musico,
you befriend someone in the system, or you investigate every aspect of the
business yourself, knowing the system intimately will increase your chances
of success. </P>

<P>We asked top franchisees to outline the most important steps to take
before signing on the dotted line. </P>

<P><B>Obtain Massive Amounts of 
Information From Other Franchisees </B></P>

<P>Manuel Morales Jr. recently opened his first HQ Business Center in downtown
San Juan, Puerto Rico. </P>

<P>&quot;I visited 22 HQ centers and talked with seven owners before I bought
one,&quot; he says. Morales owns a 30,000-square-foot building downtown,
and he needed to lease the space. &quot;Puerto Rico is having an influx
of telecommunication companies come in, and they're all looking for technical
assistance,&quot; says the native. </P>

<P>Morales made sure he visited HQ units every time he took a business trip
to the United States. &quot;If I was going to develop a franchise in a market
where I've been active for more than 20 years, I wanted to make sure the
company was solid,&quot; he says. </P>

<P>Morales was impressed by the high caliber of HQ franchise owners. &quot;The
owner of a Boston franchise had been in international operations with Coca-Cola
before he started in 1981,&quot; says Morales. &quot;Now he has four centers.&quot;
</P>

<P>He drilled the other operators about the system and what made them successful.
&quot;The New York franchisee had eight centers,&quot; Morales recalls.
&quot;He said that this business is all about location.&quot; For example,
his one unit at 666 Fifth Avenue in Manhattan has a more prestigious address,
but another unit on Avenue of the Americas is more profitable. </P>

<P>Excited about the opportunity, Morales drafted plans to open a state-of-the-art
facility with T1 lines, videoconferencing, and the like. The other operators
admonished him that as an HQ owner, the core value he can offer businesspeople
is four walls, a desk, and a telephone. </P>

<P>Morales wanted to open a big office center, with 95 offices in total.
Other HQ franchisees challenged his projections. &quot;I was looking to
open five offices every month for the next 18 months. They asked, 'What
if you don't meet that schedule?' I lowered my projection to 57,&quot; Morales
says. </P>

<P>Morales invested $1.2 million in the construction and infrastructure
of his HQ Business Center. This price included revamping the electric system
of his office center, buying furniture, installing security systems, and
adding new computers. It also covered such soft expenses as consultants,
payroll, and taxes. </P>

<P>&quot;When shopping for a franchise, you have to shift into high gear,&quot;
says the energetic entrepreneur. &quot;Be eclectic. Pick ideas from different
places.&quot; </P>

<P><B>Identify the Foolproof System </B></P>

<P>Too often, when franchise hunters visit a company's headquarters, they
focus their questions solely on the financial aspect of the business. They
want to know how much money they will make -- and how soon. But most franchisors
don't make earnings claims; they don't want to get locked into saying how
much a specific franchisee will or will not earn. Instead, when you visit
a company's headquarters, use the opportunity to learn about the system.
You want to be crystal clear about the support and services being offered.
</P>

<P>When Navin Bhatia went to the headquarters of Valvoline in Kentucky,
&quot;I wanted to understand their goals and their expansion plans,&quot;
he says. After 15 years in the marketing department of top financial companies,
Bhatia was interested in applying his skills at a franchise business with
a vibrant future. </P>

<P>&quot;I focused my search on retail service businesses, where I would
deal with customers,&quot; says Bhatia. He narrowed his pool of potential
candidates to automotive firms. &quot;As people get busier, they need help
to maintain their cars,'' he says. ''This business would not go out of style.&quot;
</P>

<P>Bhatia researched major automotive players and focused on Valvoline because
it had immediate openings. When he visited corporate headquarters, he didn't
ask how much he could expect to earn per year or the average profits per
unit. </P>

<P>&quot;I wanted to understand what kind of support they would give me
and how the licensing program was structured,&quot; he says. &quot;Had they
ever been in litigation? How much had the company invested of its own money
into the franchise program?&quot; Bhatia was encouraged to learn that most
Valvoline centers were company owned; it had only recently started franchising.
He was wary of firms with hot ideas that used franchisees to test them.
</P>

<P>Secure that the company was solid, Bhatia began creating his own pro
forma for sales. &quot;I visited oil change places and saw how many cars
they were doing,'' he says. &quot;I came up with my own set of sales assumptions.&quot;
He also studied Valvoline's audited financial statements, contained in its
Uniform Franchise Offering Circular. </P>

<P>At the end of the day, potential franchisees must know what strengths
the franchisor will bring to the table. Remember, there is always the option
of being an independent business owner. If you want to go the franchise
route, you want to know why and what you're getting. </P>

<P>&quot;Stop, think, talk, research, and analyze,&quot; advises Bhatia.
&quot;This takes a significant investment of your time and energy.&quot;
His careful due diligence has paid off. As the area developer for San Antonio,
he has four units open with sales in excess of $2.5 million. Another is
scheduled to open in October. </P>

<P><B>Grasp the Big Picture</B> </P>

<P>As one of the most successful franchisees in the Ace Hardware system,
Stewart Weis is used to fielding questions about his business. The Missoula,
Mont., Ace dealer does $4 million in sales at his one store. </P>

<P>&quot;When people call me, they're usually clueless about the investment,&quot;
says the 40-year-old franchisee. &quot;It costs a minimum of $750,000 to
buy a store like ours.&quot; His 25,000-square-foot store has half a million
dollars in inventory alone. </P>

<P>Even if you have the money to invest, Ace is a tough system to crack.
&quot;It's only going to accept the best of the best,&quot; says Weis. The
company can afford to be picky because of the popularity of the home improvement
industry. But the activity has brought in lots of competition, especially
&quot;big box&quot; concepts such as Home Depot. Ace's niche is the convenience
segment of the home improvement industry. </P>

<P>To stand out, the chain has become more retail-oriented. &quot;Before,
as Ace hardware dealers, we were free to do whatever we wanted. If we wanted
to open a hobby shop at our center, we could,&quot; says Weis. </P>

<P>Ace realized that this degree of store independence confused the customer.
The system needed standardization. Now, it's working to make stores more
alike. &quot;They're saying we have some new programs, and there are incentives
if you meet these retail standards,&quot; says Weis. &quot;You should have
Ace signage. You're encouraged to keep end-caps merchandised. You're encouraged
to run a clean store.&quot; As a result, Weis's store experienced an increase
of 33 percent in sales last year. </P>

<P>While potential franchisees may not grasp the cost of opening an Ace
store, Weis knew about the price tag firsthand when he signed on to the
system. He grew up in the Ace hardware system; both his father and his grandfather
owned units. </P>

<P>&quot;When I was 10 years old, my favorite thing was to go to a hardware
store for the day,&quot; says Weis. &quot;I quit college to become an auto
mechanic, and then my dad asked me to work at this store. I could learn
at his store, and someday it'd be mine. I knew that I'd like to make as
much money as I could.&quot; </P>

<P><B>Look at the Business From The Consumer's Point of View </B></P>

<P>Ever since she was a little girl, Terri Miller loved makeup. She became
intrigued by a Merle Norman cosmetics center near her home in Boise, Idaho.
When she wasn't working as a real estate agent, she'd go in and watch the
associates work and perform make-overs. </P>

<P>One day, the owner put the unit on the market, and Miller decided to
snap it up. &quot;I'd seen the numbers and knew the kind of business the
store was doing,&quot; she recalls. &quot;The sales were declining at the
time, but it was in a real small mall.&quot; Miller knew she could move
it to a bigger mall and be successful. </P>

<P>Before she signed the contract, she obtained a financial statement on
the parent company. Its 65 years in business assured her the company was
solid. The aspect that stood out was its superior products -- at a fair
price. Other competitive advantages included the renowned Merle Norman make-over
training and the option to test products before you buy. </P>

<P>&quot;Since I'd never owned a business, I wanted to know that I could
really learn it,&quot; says Miller. &quot;I was convinced they could teach
me.&quot; Merle Norman teaches new franchise recruits everything from dealing
with new employees to placing orders. And then there are the exhaustive
product training courses. </P>

<P>&quot;I've owned my Merle Norman center for more than 10 years and have
tripled the sales,&quot; says the former real estate agent. &quot;This year,
we'll do about $400,000. Boise is not a huge market. It has only about 200,000
people.&quot; She is so enthusiastic about the concept, she encouraged her
stepdaughters to open a unit in Portland, Ore. </P>

<P>&quot;In real estate, you have to be aggressive,&quot; Miller concludes.
The same can be said when investigating different franchise opportunities.
 </P>

<P>SUCCESS senior editor Katherine Callan reports on trends and leading
players in franchise businesses. 


	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
