</TABLE>



<BR><BR><HR><BR><A HREF="#6"><FONT SIZE="-2">BACK TO TOP</FONT></A><BR><BR>



<A NAME="2">Growth Tip #2:</A><BR>

<B>Delegate or Die</B>

<BR>

<P><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>

Jo-Anne Dressendofer started Imedia Inc., a high-technology marketing

company, in 1988 with a $400,000 job from AT&amp;T. A year later, she had

10 employees. Today, the Morristown, N.J., firm has 33 workers, partners

with an 18-member software-development company, and generates $10 million

in revenues. Dressendofer learned her growth lessons the hard way:

</P>



<P>

''You're working 24 hours a day, seven days a week, when you're kicking

off a business. I was just doing projects without thinking about the internal

organization I had. I said, 'I'll hire the best people. I'll surround myself

with people who can teach me things, and I'll be the salesperson.' I thought

that would be perfect -- until five of my employees teamed up and told me

they were quitting.

</P>



<P>

''People need their own identity and a sense of ownership. I had hired

professionals, and they had their own ideas. I had ignored that. I had diced

everything up and handed it to them like baby food, and they resented it.

</P>



<P>

''I realized I wasn't a very good manager. I never trusted anyone to

make the right decision for a client, because I had been with the clients

for six years. I had to build a management team with some authority over

projects, some voice in whether we took proj-ects and how we did them. I

had to walk away from some of the decision making.

</P>



<P>

''They had to go through a whole learning phase that I had already been

through. I had to let them offer things I knew the client would hate. Sometimes

I lost clients, and sometimes the staff actually came up with better ideas.

</P>



<P>

''I think it's a horrific experience for an entrepreneur to watch projects

go out the door that you know the client won't like, but you can't grow

without it. The big lesson is that there is no one right answer. Now, hundreds

of projects go out the door without my seeing them, but they have an Imedia

feel. It might not always be my idea, but it has my ideals.'' </FONT>

</P>

<BR><HR><BR><A HREF="#6"><FONT SIZE="-2">BACK TO TOP</FONT></A><BR><BR>

<A NAME="3">Growth Tip #3:</A><BR>

<B>Grab Free Publicity</B>





<P><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>

MET-Rx USA Inc., the Irvine, Calif.-based maker of high-protein nutritional

supplements, tested its products on a group of athletes in 1991. From there,

the word-of-mouth spread like wildfire, as sports and movie stars sang the

products' praises. First-year sales were a few hundred thousand dollars;

in1996 the company posted $90 million in revenues. Its founder, Scott Connelly,

relies on guerrilla marketing tactics:

</P>



<P>

''We couldn't afford to market MET-Rx on any broad scale when sales first

took off. But we were able to solicit the help of a number of notable professional

and amateur athletes. They all found the products extremely valuable, so

they lent their ambassadorship without any kind of monetary compensation.

We just gave them free product.

</P>



<P>

''We still do very little conventional print advertising. Instead we

have a kind of marketing SWAT team that tries to get us exposure through

product placement on TV, in movies, etc. Their marching orders are to go

out and take scalps, and don't come back unless you've got them.

</P>



<P>

''We pound the pavement for every little bit of free public exposure

we can get. For example, we give product to professional and college teams

all over the country in exchange for signage in their stadiums.

</P>



<P>

''We're also doing back-end movie promotions right now, so our product

will show up in at least seven upcoming major motion pictures. We'll offer

discounts on tickets and do point-of-purchase displays that promote the

movie.

</P>



<P>

''These things aren't really that expensive if you compare them dollar

for dollar with the cost of doing mass-market media on that level.

</P>



<P>

''This kind of exposure gives the impression that we're a much bigger

company than we actually are. And that helps fuel sales all over the place,

because people get the notion that, 'Jeez, what is this MET-Rx stuff and

why am I not taking it?' '' </FONT>

</P>

<BR><HR><BR><A HREF="#6"><FONT SIZE="-2">BACK TO TOP</FONT></A><BR><BR>

<B><A NAME="5">Just For Feet's Growth Plan</A></B>



<DIR><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>

	<LI>Open one store per 400,000 people in a market.



	<LI>Continue filling out markets in southern U.S.; open stores in New York City's Times Square, London, and Puerto Rico.



	<LI>Spend millions on advertising and glitzy grand openings.



	<LI>Nurture young managers through Just For Feet University; train staff through satellite system linking each store to headquarters.



	<LI>Control inventory and procedures through computer network that can grow with the company.



	<LI>Monitor progress of stores closely: Send top executives into stores frequently; run weekly profit-and-loss analyses on each location.



	<LI>Consider acquisitions of small athletic-shoe companies.



	<LI>Reach sales of $1 billion by the year 2000.</FONT>

</DIR>



<P>

<I>Can It Work? The Experts Respond</I>

</P>



<P><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>

Daniel W. DeHayes is director of the Center for Entrepreneurship and

Innovation at Indiana University's School of Business. He recently coauthored

a study on midmarket high-performance companies.

</P>



<P>

DeHayes believes that Harold Ruttenberg's decision to back away from

franchised stores is an excellent strategy. ''It's good for growth,'' he

says. ''You've got a particular formula that you want to stick with, but

with franchises, you don't have as much control over that. Sometimes the

formula slips.''

</P>



<P>

While DeHayes acknowledges the appeal of what he calls Just For Feet's

''carnival atmosphere,'' he questions its longevity. ''Some new gimmick

in retailing is likely to follow the carnival concept,'' he says. ''As long

as Ruttenberg stays in touch with the market and picks up ideas from other

forms of retailing, he can probably get past that.''

</P>



<P>

There's also the matter of Ruttenberg's need for excitement. ''This guy

thrives on adversity,'' says DeHayes. ''What happens if there is none? A

lot of entrepreneurs need it to focus their attention; otherwise they get

bored.'' He cautions Ruttenberg to start thinking about succession. ''He's

not old, but his whole family is involved with the company,'' he says. ''With

any family-controlled business, you have to deal with exactly how to get

it to the next generation.''

</P>



<P>

On the whole, DeHayes thinks Just For Feet is on the right track, having

built a solid infrastructure through technology and financial controls.

''An important aspect of high performance is setting up systems that will

support the company as it moves to the next level,'' he says. ''Most companies

don't do that.''

</P>



<P>

Jeffry A. Timmons is the Franklin W. Olin Distinguished Professor of

Entrepreneurship at Babson College in Massachusetts and author of New Venture

Creation.

</P>



<P>

''Ruttenberg has three or four major drivers of the future value of the

business,'' says Timmons. ''If you can keep in place the entrepreneurial

approach by the time a business gets to this size, then as you go to $500

million, $750 million, and $1 billion, you are going to create tremendous

shareholder value.''

</P>



<P>

Timmons believes Ruttenberg has the right focus on training his management

team. ''In retail, location, location, location is first, then it's people,

people, people,'' he says. ''I really like his satellite training system,

and I like that he sends his top people into stores frequently.''

</P>



<P>

The Just For Feet University training, along with Ruttenberg's practice

of promoting managers through the system, is bound to help him maintain

a high level of quality management as the chain grows. ''He's really cultivating

the training, almost like career military,'' Timmons says. ''He's bringing

up his managers in his system and his approach.''

</P>



<P>

Timmons thinks it's critical for fast-growing companies to share the

wealth -- something Just For Feet does, with an extensive stock-option plan

that reaches down to the store level. ''It isn't good enough to share stock

options with the top 10 or 15 managers,'' he says. ''Sixty percent of the

fastest-growing companies tend to have widespread ownership among employees.

That's how you attract more-committed people and get greater performance.''

</P>



<P>

Timmons notes that with $250 million in sales and 47 stores now, Just

For Feet would need to open roughly 140 stores by the year 2000 to meet

a $1 billion goal. ''That's nearly one store a week,'' he says. ''That's

pretty ambitious.''

</P>



<P>

Robert A. Compton is a general partner at CID Equity Partners in Indianapolis,

a venture-capital firm that specializes in high-growth Midwestern start-up

companies.

</P>



<P>

Compton believes that Just For Feet's unique structure -- big-box selection,

entertainment, a full-service staff -- will make it hard for other companies

to catch up and compete directly. By moving into the North, he says, Just

For Feet should have many years of good growth ahead of it. Ruttenberg's

challenge as he moves into the international arena will be adjusting to

different buying behaviors and cultures.

</P>



<P>

Compton is unconcerned about the future of the big-box concept in general.

''Given today's lifestyle, you have less time to do things,'' he explains.

''If you're going to shop, you want to have fun.''

</P>



<P>

On the other hand, he says, same-store sales growth at Just For Feet

is going to flatten out sooner or later. Since Wall Street looks at same-store

figures closely, he suggests that ''Ruttenberg may have to expand his concept

to bring in higher-margin items. The challenge with category killers is

keeping the concept fresh. But my sense of Ruttenberg is that he never goes

stale.''

</P>



<P>

Like Timmons, Compton is impressed by Ruttenberg's attention to corporate

culture through Just For Feet University and employee sales training. ''In

large-format, high-volume stores, it's rare to find a salesperson at all,

much less a knowledgeable one,'' he says.

</P>



<P>

Compton also lauds Ruttenberg's experimental nature: ''A culture of experimentation

makes for a great company, regardless of the industry. And in retail it's

particularly unusual.''</FONT> 

</P>

	</TD>





	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="300">

	

<P>

<FONT SIZE="+1">Harold Ruttenberg had nowhere else to go. His sportswear shop in the

mall was gone, even though its revenues had reached almost $4 million that

year. He had built it from nothing. After his landlord refused to give him

reasonable lease terms, Ruttenberg closed the store to start all over --

again.</FONT>

</P>



<P>

He went to the beach. Lying there, watching the waves and thinking, he

tried to come to grips with his self-imposed unemployment. He stayed for

four days, baking in the sun and cooking up a new plan for his future.

</P>



<P>

He came away with one resolution: For his next retail venture, he was

going to be his own landlord. All he needed was a site and a product to

sell. The demand for athletic shoes was increasing exponentially through

the '80s, a trend Ruttenberg had seen firsthand as shoes grew to be 80 percent

of his Birmingham, Ala., mall business. That was it. He sprang into action,

building a 10,000-square-foot, freestanding store right outside the city's

Galleria Mall. He christened it Just For Feet.

</P>



<P>

At the store's launch in 1988, Ruttenberg figured his annual revenues

needed to be $2 million for him to consider the business viable. To his

amazement, the store hit that sales target after only two months. After

four months, he was knocking down walls to make the shop as big as possible.

</P>



<P>

This was a new experience. Ruttenberg had always been confident, even

arrogant, about his entrepreneurial abilities, and he'd already built two

profitable businesses before this. But unlike those companies, Just For

Feet never struggled. It was an overnight success, on solid ground right

from the start.

</P>



<P>

Then it took off. Today, with 47 stores, Just For Feet Inc. is a $250

million behemoth. A darling of Wall Street, it is one of the 100 fastest-growing

companies in America, as ranked by Individual Investor magazine. It has

already outgrown the 15,000-square-foot headquarters Ruttenberg built in

Birmingham just 18 months ago; soon it will move into a more accommodating

25-acre spread.

</P>



<P>

Ruttenberg may have been stunned initially at the rapid growth, but he

recovered quickly. Today he's charging full speed ahead with ambitious plans

to take Just For Feet to the $1 billion mark by the year 2000. As with most

young, explosive companies, getting there means holding a lock-tight rein

to avoid stampeding out of control. Ruttenberg is determined to go the distance.

</P>



<P>

<B>An Eye for Retail</B>

</P>



<P>

As his father lay dying, a young Ruttenberg paid close attention to their

last conversations. ''Rather work for yourself for $100 a month,'' his father

advised, ''than work for somebody else for $500 a month.'' The words meant

a lot coming from the former factory worker.

</P>



<P>

Growing up in Johannesburg in the '60s, Ruttenberg worked for an upscale

men's clothier during school holidays. He spent four years with the company

after high school, earning a college degree in the evenings and eventually

leaving to pursue his own ambitions. ''Even as a student, I realized that

I had a kind of flair for the business,'' he says. ''I had no money, so

going out on my own meant starting at the bottom.''

</P>



<P>

He borrowed a few thousand dollars to import some Levi's jeans from the

States and sold them to stores from the trunk of his car. It was as basic

a business as you get: Ruttenberg would collect from the stores, pay off

his debt, then place a bigger order for the jeans the next time around.

</P>



<P>

By the time he was 26, Ruttenberg was distributing jeans, men's shirts,

and shoes from America, England, and Hong Kong. He went on worldwide buying

trips three times a year. Finally, he set up shop and became a retailer

himself. It provided a healthy living for him and his growing family. *

</P>



<P>

By the mid-'70s, however, Ruttenberg was ready to quit troubled South

Africa and try his luck in America. But it was going to cost him. South

Africa does not allow its citizens to leave the country with the money they

earned there. In 1977, when Ruttenberg, his wife, and their three children

were officially ready to go, his business and assets were worth half a million

dollars. By his estimate, Ruttenberg was in the top 5 percent of the wealthiest

people in the country. All he had to show for it, after the government decided

his ''settling in'' allowance, was $30,000.

</P>



<P>

Ruttenberg had been to the States a few years earlier to scout out opportunities.

He now hoped to open a store in San Diego. He went there first, before his

family, but found that prices had gone through the roof. He tried Houston

next, then Florida. ''Quite frankly, I discovered that America wasn't waiting

for me,'' he says. ''I never had any credit, so I couldn't get into a mall.

I didn't have a concept that particularly appealed to anybody.''

</P>



<P>

A friend in Birmingham suggested that Ruttenberg stop by on his way back

to South Africa. There, an opportunity presented itself. Ruttenberg found

a spot in a local mall, put together some financing -- including $20,000

of his $30,000 pittance -- and returned to South Africa to think about it.

Two weeks later he was back to sign the papers.

</P>



<P>

Ruttenberg's business, selling sportswear to the younger crowd, experienced

growing pains for its first five years. Not the least of his problems was

culture shock: He found the American South to be a different business environment

altogether. For one thing, he wasn't used to the customers' buying habits.

This wasn't the wealthiest place to start a business. And he was stocking

his store based on the preferences of South Africans. ''I used to buy men's

shirts like this -- maybe three smalls, six mediums, and three larges,''

he says. ''When I did that here, people said, 'Look, you're buying too many

smalls, you need more larges, and you'd better bring in extra-larges.' ''

</P>



<P>

Ruttenberg's personal style was at odds with the local culture as well.

''I was used to doing a lot of business with Northerners, New Yorkers in

particular,'' he explains. ''But this was a very slow-moving environment.

Even to this day I'm not always well understood by Southerners. I'm very

vocal -- I say it the way it is. But they're much more diplomatic, and you

never know where you stand with them.''

</P>



<P>

Despite the difficulties, Ruttenberg's shop made a profit every year.

His family lived on very little in those early days. He stuck to the same

formula he'd used as a distributor: Whatever he made in sales, he immediately

plowed back into buying more merchandise.

</P>



<P>

Customers loved Ruttenberg's sportswear selection, a mixture of high-quality

items and discount specials, which he handpicked on his buying trips to

New York City. His South African accent was charming and exotic -- it stuck

in customers' minds, says Ruttenberg, and brought them back to the store.

Eventually, he was packing them in.

</P>



<P>

Then came the lease negotiations in 1987. Because of the mall's pricing

structure, higher sales meant higher rents. Ruttenberg knew his store was

carrying practically the whole mall. But the landlord was not budging in

rent discussions. ''I could have gone anywhere in the world, even New York

City, and gotten cheaper space,'' Ruttenberg marvels. ''And this was just

a lousy mall in Birmingham.'' Unwilling to make an unfair deal, he gave

up and liquidated his inventory. Four months later, he was out of there.

</P>



<P>

<B>Fancy Footwork

</B></P>



<P>

Ruttenberg bought the site for his new business, then turned his attention

to plotting a retail strategy. Discount stores were becoming all the rage,

but he didn't feel the calling. His more pressing problem was luring customers

away from the malls.

</P>



<P>

''There weren't many big, freestanding stores in those days,'' Ruttenberg

says. ''Every last dime we'd made in the previous 10 years was on the line

here. So I talked to a lot of different people and looked at what was going

on in retail across the country.''

</P>



<P>

His chief strategy partner was his son Don, who had worked with him since

1980. The two decided to devote a small area of the store to discount shoes.

''We figured, if we could give value in this area, maybe -- because of selection

-- we could leave the rest of the store as it was and sell at full price,''

says Ruttenberg. As the building was going up, he and Don brainstormed on

different gimmicks to draw customers in.

</P>



<P>

They put in a restaurant, one of the first big-box concepts to do so.

They installed a glass-walled basketball half court. During Just For Feet's

infancy they tried just about every idea that came to them. ''Not one thing

was well planned in those early days,'' Ruttenberg admits. ''I'd say 90

percent of the things we tried didn't work. But the 10 percent that did,

we still have in practice.''

</P>



<P>

The restaurant and the basketball court have stood the test of time,

as have the miles of neon, blaring popular music, and giant video walls

showing sports-themed programs. Each of the stores still has a discount

section, now called the Combat Zone.

</P>



<P>

Among the concepts that weren't so hot were the children's nursery (''We

got so busy that we just didn't need it,'' says Ruttenberg) and a drive-through

window. ''People walked around town talking about that one for months,''

Ruttenberg says. ''It wasn't so much for buying shoes but more for returns

and exchanges and things like that.''

</P>



<P>

While the window didn't last, it was great for publicity -- something

Ruttenberg eagerly pursued. The grand opening of the first Just For Feet

was heralded with a huge media blitz, 12 professional athletes on hand,

and special in-store sales. It was a huge success. Ruttenberg learned to

put great stock in these grand openings.

</P>



<P>

When Just For Feet recently opened a new store in Knoxville, Tenn., for

example, thousands of people swarmed at the entrance as the doors were unlocked.

Celebrities signed autographs, a robot entertained children, and customers

signed up to win cash prizes or a car. The throngs never let up. By closing

time, Ruttenberg estimates, 30,000 to 50,000 customers had come through,

buying about 3,000 pairs of shoes.

</P>



<P>

''We spend a quarter of a million dollars on each grand opening,'' he

says. ''They're spectacular. We've hit some unbelievably high sales numbers.

Every year we keep breaking our records.'' The grand openings are just one

part of the advertising strategy. Ruttenberg advertises relentlessly, with

TV commercials on the four big networks every night in every market it serves,

plus a minimum of one half-page ad each Friday and Sunday in the city newspapers.

</P>



<P>

Ruttenberg followed up on the success of his first store with another

Just For Feet in Birmingham and the selling of three franchises outside

Alabama. In 1992, against everyone's advice, he opened a Just For Feet at

Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas. ''It was a huge risk,'' he says. ''But Las

Vegas always fascinated me. It has the most expensive real estate in America,

but when I saw the plans, I knew it was for me.'' Today it's the highest-volume

store of its kind in the world.

</P>



<P>

By 1993, Ruttenberg says, ''we were really making some serious money.

The company was getting too big just to sit on it; it needed to be expanded.''

</P>



<P>

Each new store required a lot of cash at start-up. Since he didn't want

to give up any control, Ruttenberg decided the best bet was to go public.

He opened two more stores, in Nashville and Kansas City, Mo., to grow the

business a little more. With sales at $23 million, Just For Feet made its

initial public offering in March 1994.

</P>



<P>

<B>Fast Forward

</B></P>



<P>

At the newest Just For Feet in Birmingham, two teenage boys -- their

sweatpants pushed up on their calves, skinny legs poked into enormous, fortresslike

high-tops -- play a game of one-on-one. A little girl in a sundress watches

with her nose pressed against the outside of the court's glass wall. Under

a store-length canopy of blinking neon, ''What You Need'' by INXS blasts

over the sound system.

</P>



<P>

It's the middle of the day on a Tuesday, so the store is not too crowded.

Still, salespeople are everywhere, offering to help with their pleasant

Southern lilts. As far as the eye can see, there are shoes, sectioned off

by brand name. The Combat Zone takes up one massive wall in the back. Islands

of athletic clothes and sports caps mercifully interrupt the layout so you

don't drown in the Reeboks, Nikes, Adidas, Avias. . . .

</P>



<P>

Ruttenberg prides himself on his company's distinction from other big-box

players. ''We are the only large box that is not a rack operation,'' he

says. ''With them, all of the store's goods are basically on the floor.

They slap a price on an item and tell the public to come and get it.'' Just

For Feet, in contrast, sells 80 percent of its merchandise from the back

room. Instead of picking out shoes from a stack and bringing them to the

register, you are waited on by a salesperson, as in a regular shoe store.

Here, though, you get your choice of up to 5,000 styles instead of a few

hundred or fewer. ''We've blended the big concept with the full-service

aspect of the small concept,'' says Ruttenberg.

</P>



<P>

Investment bankers were impressed with Just For Feet's innovations --

not to mention its sales numbers -- when Ruttenberg approached them with

his plan to go public in 1993. He says it's the best decision he ever made.

Since its initial offering, the company's stock has split three times, and

it has posted 14 straight quarters of meeting or beating Wall Street's expectations.

It has one of the highest price-earnings multiples of all publicly traded

retail companies in America. From sales of $23 million in 1993, Just For

Feet went to $56 million in '94, $120 million in '95, and approximately

$250 million in 1996. It is now sitting on $150 million cash in the bank.

</P>



<P>

After going public, Just For Feet bought back two of its three franchises.

The third, with stores in Ohio, still remains (Ruttenberg tried to buy it

back, he says, but couldn't come to terms). The stores now blanket the southern

half of the U.S., except for one store at the Mall of America in Minnesota.

Explains Ruttenberg: ''We tend to do the best where the sun shines. When

it gets cold, people wear shoes other than athletic shoes, but down here

just about everybody wears them all the time.''

</P>



<P>

Just For Feet's chief financial officer, Robert Wabler, helps keep the

company on a steady course of growth. ''Right now we're looking to fill

in some of our markets, such as Dallas, Orlando, and Phoenix, where we already

have stores,'' says Wabler. ''We're also keeping an eye out for good real-estate

opportunities.'' The company aims to have one store for every 400,000 people

in a given market. Plans are in the pipeline to have 65 stores by January

1998.

</P>



<P>

<B>The Race Continues

</B></P>



<P>

Ruttenberg prepared himself for growth early on by assembling a team

of managers. ''Some of these people have worked for me since high school,''

he says. ''These are real merchants -- not just Harvard MBAs -- all trained

by me. They'd jump off a building for me if I asked them.''

</P>



<P>

Members of the team include his two sons, Don and Warren, both vice presidents.

Their sister, Jodi, works at an advertising agency, where her father's company

is her sole client. Mom Pam manages the original Just For Feet store in

Birmingham.

</P>



<P>

The 54-year-old Ruttenberg is the undisputed last word at Just For Feet,

but his sons say the entire management team comprises distinct personalities

all focused on the brass ring. It's a young group, with an average age of

34. Ruttenberg fills out the team's ranks with more prot&eacute;g&eacute;s

-- and even a few professional managers -- just before every major expansion.

They talk of striking a good balance between ''offense'' (sales) and ''defense''

(building the brand name and keeping quality high).

</P>



<P>

''We're what we are today because we've applied retail concepts better

than anyone else,'' says eldest son Don. Where Just For Feet will go, and

how it will get there, is monitored closely by Wabler. He mentions culture

as an integral key. ''We have a strong infrastructure here,'' he says. ''Our

people work hard. We send managers through our Just For Feet University,

which has been an important tool.''

</P>



<P>

The university, which will ''graduate'' about 700 people this year, teaches

new hires about customer service and employee culture, as well as company

systems and procedures. Just For Feet upgraded its computer systems in 1995

with IBM hardware and Island Pacific software -- ''the Cadillac of the industry

for inventory management. That system alone can take us up to 500 stores,''

says Wabler. Every store is now equipped with a satellite dish as well,

through which headquarters can broadcast custom-produced motivational, sales,

and technical training for employees.

</P>



<P>

Top executives keep a vigilant watch on progress and sales, visiting

the stores almost every weekend. The head office scrutinizes the financials,

running weekly profit-and-loss analyses on each store, line by line. Wabler

takes these issues very seriously. ''You have to control the growth so that

it doesn't get out of hand,'' he says. ''You have to stay profitable while

making sure you have the correct controls and systems in place.''

</P>



<P>

Ruttenberg is characteristically bullish on Just For Feet's future. He

claims he's never been in a Foot Locker or another competitor's store; he'd

rather focus on what works for him. ''We're now moving into Denver, into

California, and into the North with Boston and New York,'' he says. He giddily

describes the new 25,000-square-foot megastore planned for Times Square.

Stores will also open in Puerto Rico (''probably the hottest market in the

world for athletic shoes'') and London within the next two years.

</P>



<P>

Acquisitions are another likely development: At press time, Ruttenberg

was in discussions with ''a number of companies we could possibly take over.''

He shrugs off suggestions that big-box concepts may be on the way out. ''These

things don't happen by mistake,'' he says. ''Eighteen months ago, people

said we could never do what we're doing. Since then we've had the most dramatic

climb ever.''

</P>



<P>

Despite the risks and the naysayers, Ruttenberg forges ahead. You get

the sense that he enjoys tempting fate, pushing his luck as far as it can

go.

</P>



<P>

''I need excitement,'' he states simply. ''What can I say? I don't need

to do this for the money anymore. If I weren't accomplishing new things,

I think I'd just quit.''      

</P>



<P>

SUCCESS associate editor Kristin Dunlap Godsey covers hot entrepreneurial

companies and trends. Additional reporting by executive editor Michael Warshaw.

</P>

	</TD>



 </TR>

 <TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">

