<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12EdNotes.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	EDITOR'S NOTE / By Scott DeGarmo</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="../toc%20art/scott.jpeg" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="180" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><!--art credti here--></FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>Micropreneurs</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">What Entrepreneurs Can Learn From Their Work-at-Home Cousins</FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Which breed is more successful -- the entrepreneur or the micropreneur?</FONT>
</P>

<P>
The answer depends on your definition of success, of course -- but it
may surprise you nonetheless.
</P>

<P>
Micropreneurs are an emerging species with some salient traits -- notably,
the fact they work at home.
</P>

<P>
Micropreneurs stand in contrast to all of you archetypal entrepreneurs
who have long comprised our audience -- men and women generally labeled
classic, authentic, or genuine entrepreneurs.
</P>

<P>
I know you well. You're hell-bent for growth. You have a burning vision
of the business you're going to create, and no obstacle will stand in your
way. For you, success is defined in large part in terms of market dominance.
As for leading a balanced life, you're likely to dismiss that as a Milquetoast
notion unsuited to entrepreneurs with a fire inside them.
</P>

<P>
Micropreneurs have more fun. They incorporate their personal lives and
their families into their definition of success.
</P>

<P>
While entrepreneurs aim at creating substantial companies -- often of
national or global scope -- micropreneurs want to create fulfilling, rewarding
lifestyles.
</P>

<P>
Entrepreneurs are willing to sacrifice on a heroic scale for lengthy
periods to achieve the big-time payoffs they seek. Micropreneurs sacrifice,
too, but enjoy living life for today as well as tomorrow.
</P>

<P>
Entrepreneurs are tough, embattled warriors committed to a never-ending
quest for growth -- men and women who have resolved to live with the burden
of what columnist Wilson Harrell calls &quot;entrepreneurial terror.&quot;
Most micropreneurs know they can be happy even if their faces don't appear
on magazine covers or their companies on lists of top-ranked businesses.
</P>

<P>
As they swell in numbers, these micropreneurs may have something to teach
us.
</P>

<P>
In recent years, they caught our interest mainly as a market for which
our readers might develop goods and services.
</P>

<P>
But then it dawned on us: Some of our entrepreneurs were in fact highly
successful micropreneurs.
</P>

<P>
Not only that, more than a few business owners told us they were seeking
to leave their traditional companies behind and enter the ranks of home-based
businesses. Often they were driven by developments of the information age,
which allowed them to shed their employees and their overhead.
</P>

<P>
I stole the term &quot;micropreneur&quot; from Michael LeBoeuf, once
a $20,000-a-year professor who now has a home-based business. LeBoeuf has
a net worth of nearly $2 million and he expects to reach $5 million in a
few years. His new book, The Perfect Business, tells how others can achieve
the same.
</P>

<P>
LeBoeuf sees micropreneurs as better educated than traditional entrepreneurs
and more satisfied. He cites statistics showing that the odds of succeeding
in your own business increase dramatically when the business is home based.
He also notes that the average household income of home-based businesses
is almost twice as much as the salary of the average employee and that 20
percent of all home-business households earn more than $75,000 a year. For
those pursuing independence for the first time, he advises you to focus
on:
</P>

<P>
<DIR>
	<LI>Opportunity instead of security
	<LI>What sells instead of what you know
	<LI>Getting results instead of following routines
	<LI>Earning a profit instead of a paycheck
</DIR>
</P>

<P>
LeBoeuf also cites figures showing that significant numbers of home-based
businesspeople are making six-figure incomes as business brokers, business-plan
writers, advertising and marketing copywriters, and desktop-video producers,
to name a few.
</P>

<P>
Sound advice for entrepreneurs almost always puts writing a business
plan high on the list of priorities. LeBoeuf doesn't think it's that important
for micropreneurs; he advises the creation of a mission statement and a
vision statement instead. A mission statement answers the questions: What
business am I in? Who are my customers? How do I create value for them?
</P>

<P>
A vision statement is an ideal picture of what your business is and how
you propose to carry out the mission. I'll seize this opportunity to add
that SUCCESS's mission is helping readers master the entrepreneurial process.
My vision for the magazine is that we will be widely viewed as the most
inspiring publication in America -- and the world.
</P>

<P>
As for inspiration, if you are looking for it, our cover story on the
joys of working at home is a great place to start. 
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


