<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12Eye.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="6" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	THE ENTREPRENEURIAL EYE / Edited By Kristin Dunlap Godsey</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><!--art credti here--></FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>WASHINGTON WATCH</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Make the Money Work</B></FONT><BR><BR><P>
Is the Small Business Administration's 8(a) program just a magnet for
abuse? Congresswoman Jan Meyers (R-Kan.) thinks so and has put the legislative
wheels in motion to end the program completely. ''In practice, 8(a) is fatally
flawed,'' she says. The 27-year-old program is designed to support start-ups
owned by the ''socially and economically disadvantaged,'' but, Meyers says,
the SBA subsidies seem to be reaching only a select few: ''About 1 percent
of the firms qualified to participate reel in an astounding one-quarter
of the business.''
</P>

<P>
To qualify, the majority owner of the company must have a net worth of
less than $250,000. Meyers charges that some users put their wealth into
their houses -- not counted under the program's calculations -- to stay
below the ceiling. Her Entrepreneur Development Program Act of 1996 would
include the business owner's house in a $250,000 cap.
</P>

<P>
The act would also eliminate racial preferences and the SBA's contracting
role. John Spotila, general counsel for the SBA, thinks this is a mistake.
''The aid that 8(a) provides allows small firms to get on their feet,''
he says. ''Companies that would not have otherwise succeeded have directly
created over 150,000 jobs. We need to make improvements, but the program
is too valuable to lose altogether.''
</P>

<P>
Meyers is unconvinced. ''Encouraging all classes and colors to expand
their stake in free enterprise is a worthwhile pursuit,'' she says. ''But
this program is clearly no way to do it -- 8(a) has had its day in the sun.''
</P>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><P>
STRATEGIES</FONT><BR>
<B>Take No Prisoners
</B></P>

<P>
Business is war, if you believe Daniel S. Pe&ntilde;a. The ex-military
officer built Great Western Resources Inc. to a $420 million corporation
in 10 years, partly by acquiring existing businesses and implementing his
own strategies. He now runs Great Western Development Corp. of Houston,
where he leads seminars on using military strategy at work. ''The discipline
and perseverance that the military teaches provide the foundation that makes
good businesspeople,'' he says. His advice for battle:
</P>

<P>
<DIR>
	<LI>Raising capital. No war was ever won without a strong military budget. ''I've always needed others to help me buy companies. You have to use your
	passionate attitude to persuade institutions to back you.''

	<LI>Solid management. Although you may be a great general, you still need well-trained lieutenants for support.

	<LI> Acquiring companies. Once you have your troops together, you have to
	know whom to attack, when, and why. ''Existing companies have already made
	their mistakes, and they are always for sale -- whether they know it or
	not.'' 
</DIR>
</P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+3">IPO UPDATE</FONT><BR>
<B>Coffee Achiever
</B></P>

<P>
<DIR>
	<LI><B>Spotlight:</B> Diedrich Coffee Inc. of Irvine, Calif.

	<LI><B>Description:</B> Coffeehouse operators, coffee roasters and retailers.

	<LI><B>FY 1996 Revenues:</B> $10.2 million.

	<LI><B>Amount Raised:</B> $15.2 million.
</DIR>
</P>

<P>
Diedrich Coffee Inc. is not the first coffee establishment to go public
to finance growth. But Steve Lupinacci, CEO and president, feels that his
company has something unique to offer its market. ''We present a different
spin on the industry,'' he says. ''We're a coffeehouse, while some of the
competitors are really espresso bars where you get something to go.'' Diedrich
Coffee provides live entertainment, designs its shops to reflect the communities,
and boasts three generations of experience in an upstart-heavy industry.
</P>

<P>
Lupinacci chose not to expand his 36-store operation through franchising.
''We felt we would have better control over our product quality and service
standards with direct company ownership,'' he explains. 
</P></TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


