<DOCHDR>
http://www.successmagazine.com:80/archives.html/DEC96.HTML/12DirSell.html 199.92.136.187 19970114141230 text/html 10478
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Tuesday, 14-Jan-97 14:09:38 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 10-Dec-96 21:30:53 GMT
Content-length: 10287
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12DirectSell.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="6" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	DIRECT SELLING / By Duncan Maxwell Anderson</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="300" >
	<BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><!--art credti here--></FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4"><BR>BOOM TIMES</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>ACN Rides the Wave in Telecommunications</B></FONT><BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">They say they're not geniuses. But they also say they're going to be bigger than Amway. SUCCESS talked to Greg Provenzano and Robert Stevanovski, two of the five founders of American Communications Network (ACN) Inc. based in Troy, Mich. They say the telecommunications business is growing so fast and its opportunities are so immense that the successful players will be giants within a decade.</FONT>
</P>


<P>
Essentially an agent that sells telecommunications services through network marketing, ACN offers residential and commercial long-distance telephone service, cellular and paging service, operator services, discount calling cards, and whatever else comes to market next. Sales for 1995 were $45 million, and the company projects $110 million for 1996, with 125,000 distributors. Provenzano (president) and Stevanovski (vice president) argue that new kinds of telecommunications services and the power of network distribution will combine to make ACN boom into the future.
</P>


<P>
<B>Why did you start ACN?
</B></P>


<P>
Greg: We were all frustrated with our previous careers in network marketing.
</P>


<P>
Rob: The companies we were with before did things like pulling the rug out from under the reps or making changes in the plan without warning. 
</P>


<P>
<B>What was the first step?</B>
</P>


<P>
Greg: When we started, in January 1994, we went to LCI International Inc. [McLean, Va.] and offered to be its agent. That took guts. We had nothing to show them. Then we had to sell to our own warm market with no materials.
</P>


<P>
Rob: We spent many nights on the road recruiting. First we'd be talking to groups of 5 people, then 25 people, and it really started to build.
</P>


<P>
Greg: We were living on savings.
</P>


<P>
<B>Isn't this a crowded marketplace?</B>
</P>


<P>
Rob: It's growing so fast. Long-distance service is an $80 billion to $90 billion business. Local service is now being deregulated -- and that's a $130 billion business. Cable deregulation is coming up -- it's $10 billion to $30 billion. And the cell-phone business is projected to go to $70 billion within five years. We're positioning ourselves to offer competitive electric power, Internet online services, personal communications systems [PCS], and interactive TV.
</P>


<P>
<B>What's your competitive strategy?</B>
</P>


<P>
Rob: The companies that spend the least money to acquire customers will win in the end.
</P>


<P>
Greg: We bring the customer to service providers at no up-front cost to them. They don't need to spend on media ads, direct mail, or outbound telemarketing -- they just do the billing and customer service. We talked to PacBell, which spent $700 million at an FCC auction for a license for a PCS network. The managers are hoping not to spend even more to acquire customers. 
</P>


<P>
Rob: We've been good for LCI -- we've brought more than $30 million per month to them. When we started ACN, LCI wasn't even a public company. Its stock is up 500 percent since then. We're 35 to 40 percent of its business. We're one of PageNet's top resellers, after six months with them.
</P>


<P>
<B>How much does it cost to sign up in ACN?</B>
</P>


<P>
Rob: To be a customer rep, $99. To be a field trainer, $499. The bigger fee is because field trainers can sell commercial accounts, plus operator services, paging, and pay phones. They get more support from the home office. For instance, if you can get a prospective business customer to give you a copy of his phone bill, send it to us, and we'll do a proposal based on his usage and send it back to you at no cost. Then we'll explain it on a three-way call.
</P>


<P>
Greg: We depend on our reps to supply the warm-market relationship and the credibility in dealing with a prospect. We supply the expertise. We don't believe in recruiting through ads or meeting people at trade shows, because we want long-term customer retention. Someone who knows you personally isn't going to switch away from you just because a telemarketer from AT&amp;T offered him $50.  
</P>


<P>
<B>Who joins?</B>
</P>


<P>
Greg: If you come to one of our national training sessions, you'll see a lot of corporate people, white-collar. They can't see themselves selling vitamins, but for some reason, they don't mind selling communications services. All you have to do is say to someone: ''Try my service; if you don't like it, we'll switch you back free.'' We can save most people 30 percent, depending on their calling patterns. 
</P>


<P>
Rob: As of now, we have 48 people who make $33,000 per month.
</P>


<P>
<B>What's the essence of your marketing idea?</B>
</P>


<P>
Rob: We're not a long-distance company. We want to become your agent for all your telecommunications business. Today, the average person has a phone bill of $33 per month. But over the long haul, he may buy $200 per month in services. When we recruit someone, we see beyond his current bill to his lifetime potential.
</P>


<P>
<B>Why did you decide to go into this?</B>
</P>


<P>
Greg: I'd like to tell you we're geniuses. But we're not. We have network marketing experience, and we hit the industry at the right time. We saw a huge opportunity in a growth industry because of deregulation. By the end of this year, we'll cover all the major U.S. markets.
</P>


<P>
<B>Do you have any other predictions?</B>
</P>


<P>
Rob: We're going to become the biggest MLM company in history. If you look at what's going on in telecommunications, and the fact that we're building on warm-market relationships . . . we'll definitely be bigger than Amway in 10 years.
</P>


<P>
Greg: It's going to be quite a ride.
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
<P>

<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

<P>
<H4><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>UPDATES</FONT></H4>

<FONT SIZE="+3">The TV Weapon</FONT>
</P>


<P>
Television can help build a network marketing organization. Over the past year, the Rose Marie Collection Group Inc. (RMC) of Charlotte, N.C., founded in 1993, has been airing TV infomercials for its skin-care products. ''People tell our distributors, 'Yes, I saw it on television.' They're more likely to buy,'' says RMC's CEO, Pete Monroe. The ads pay for themselves through direct product sales. RMC's goal is to help distributors create a database of 5 million customers. 
</P>


<P>
<DIR>
	<LI>Paul Meyer, founder of Success Motivation Institute Inc., the motivational seminar and products company in Waco, Tex., is now an investor in The People's Network (TPN), based in Dallas, which markets satellite dishes and motivational programming through MLM. 

	<LI>Upline magazine, the network marketing monthly headed by John Milton Fogg, has taken on two outside investors to finance growth. Upline's owners plan to take the 5 million company public, says CEO and publisher Dale McGlothlin.

	<LI>We Create Millionaires. Get our 64-page collection of the best network marketing articles to appear in SUCCESS. Price: $4.95. Call 

	<LI>1-800-388-3884. 
</DIR>
</P>
<BR><HR SIZE="1"><BR>
<P>
<H4><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>WINNERS</FONT></H4>
<FONT SIZE="+3">The Mind of a Millionaire</FONT>
</P>


<P>
Inside forklift operator Randy Stralow, there must have been an entrepreneur waiting to get out. He was raised on a farm in Illinois. His mother died when he was 7 years old. ''My father felt sorry for me, so he let me get away with a lot,'' he says. Young Randy raced motorcycles professionally and fell in with ''a wild crowd,'' drinking and partying.
</P>


<P>
By age 18, he wound up working at a steel mill owned by Northwestern Steel and Wire in Rock Falls, Ill. But after several years at the mill, his life wasn't going anywhere. He was divorced and had custody of his daughter. He'd developed an interest in nutrition but had never thought of making a business of it. He started listening to motivational tapes. Finally, five years ago, he saw an ad placed by a distributor for Body Wise International, a nutritional-supplement maker in Carlsbad, Calif. He resolved that this would change his life.
</P>


<P>
His first recruit was his foreman.
</P>


<P>
''In my mind,'' says Stralow, ''I was a millionaire.'' He bought $1,200 in product on credit cards to start and sold $48,000 worth in 70 days.
</P>


<P>
''Part of my success was that I was in the middle of nowhere with nobody,'' says Stralow. ''It's entertainment for me to be on the phone to people all over.'' 
</P>


<P>
Stralow is a seat-of-the-pants practitioner of one-to-one marketing, catering live testimonials to sell individual prospects: ''When someone calls one of my downline people off an ad with a weight or diabetes problem, the distributor calls me. I'll hook up the prospect on a three-way call with someone in Body Wise who's had the same problem.''
</P>


<P>
Stralow also does personal planning sessions for his own distributors, teaching them to focus on a product they like and use their time better. ''My income went up $100,000 when I started doing that.'' This year, he will make more than $300,000 in commissions.
</P>

<P>
He drives a Jaguar instead of a forklift.
</P>

</P></TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>


