<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>12books&Tapes.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="4" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	BOOKS AND TAPES / By Duncan Maxwell Anderson</FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT SIZE="+4">
	<BR><BR>LIFETIME PROFITS</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">Building Sales Through One-to-One Marketing</FONT><BR><BR><BR>
	</TD>
	<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="100">
	<B><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>BOOKS</FONT></B>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="400">
	<P>
<B>Enterprise One to One, <BR>
by Don Peppers and Martha Rogers.</B>
</P>


<P>
The best way to build sales is no longer to sell one product to an ever larger number of people. Today, high-powered computers and interactive communications media let you do something much more profitable: sell a wide variety of products and services to one customer at a time, for a lifetime. In Enterprise One to One, Don Peppers and Martha Rogers, authors of the best-selling The One to One Future, show some of the strategies and products you can create.<P>You gain a growing share of a customer's spending by catering ever more precisely to his needs. For instance, in the near future, virtually all appliances will contain chips that let them learn and remember their users' habits and preferences. Your car will recognize you by your weight as you sit down -- and immediately set the air conditioner, seat, shock absorbers, mirrors, and music the way you like them. When you get your next car, these preferences can be uploaded to it.<P>Toy companies like the makers of Lego could advertise their Web site on their packaging. The site would help the company collect information about how children use a specific toy -- not for statistical market research but to find out what related products those individual children would like.<P>The Custom Foot, based in Westport, Conn., delivers made-to-order shoes from Italy in three weeks for the price of off-the-shelf shoes. A scanner that looks like a mirror takes all the dimensions of a customer's foot in 7 to 10 minutes. Coming soon: Show or sketch a picture of a style you want, and Custom Foot will have the shoe made for you. The owner of the Custom Foot has a valuable asset for a mass-market shoemaker like Ferragamo: the names, measurements, and style preferences of individual customers. He could even sell Ferragamo shoes -- custom-made, of course -- for a licensing fee.<BR><BR><BR>
<B>The Witch Doctors, <BR>
by John Micklethwait and Adrian Wooldridge.</B>
<BR>In The Witch Doctors, two editors from The Economist, John Micklethwait and Adrian Wooldridge, skewer the pretensions of the modern management-consulting business, which generated $11.4 billion in fees for 1994 and probably will bring in $21 billion in 1999. The book is brimming with ideas for the global marketplace.<P>Britain's super-consultant Charles Handy says companies will soon consist of a ''core company'' -- a small squad of entrepreneurs and bureaucrats -- aided by unskilled workers he calls ''somebodies,'' as in ''somebody can do that,'' and knowledge workers with portfolios of creative or analytical skills they market to a variety of companies.<P>At Wipro Infotech, a software firm in Bangalore, India, engineers are redesigning General Electric's internal software system for one fifth of what it would cost in the West. The finished product is transmitted to GE in America by satellite dish. Elsewhere in India, companies are acting as security guards by watching video screens of warehouses and offices in America.<P>McDonald's didn't succeed in Tokyo until it let a local entrepreneur create little snack bars in the city center, ignoring the suburban marketing plan favored by headquarters. The company let him use fattier meat to please the Japanese palate and change Ronald McDonald's name to Donald McDonald, since the Japanese have trouble with r's.<P>But perhaps technical products are universal. The authors recount a Peter Drucker story about a neighbor of his in California who sells medical beepers to hospitals all over the world. ''What about the language and culture?'' Drucker asked when his neighbor returned from installing a system in Osaka. ''I don't need to understand Japan,'' the man said. ''I understand hospitals.''<P><BR><BR>
<B>Hope Is Not a Method, <BR>
by Gordon R. Sullivan and Michael V. Harper</B>.
<BR>Hope Is Not a Method is a book by two of the men involved with converting the U.S. Army from a ponderous, armed multitude into a mobile, high-tech force, a change completed after the Gulf War. The Army picked up technologies and management ideas from business. Entrepreneurs can learn much from the Army about leadership.<P>When planning for tomorrow's world, ''don't ask yourself what the 'next' organization will look like,'' say the authors, ''but rather, what the organization 'after next' will look like.'' Your idea of the next one will be constrained by today's realities. A man who works at an electronics firm told the authors that by the turn of the century, more than half the value added in his company's products and services will come from software. By staring that fact in the eye, the company is discovering that it has implications for everything from investment to personnel policies.<P>An American lieutenant-colonel in Vietnam beat back an ambush by a vastly larger Communist force over the course of four days by taking mental breathing spaces at regular intervals to ask himself three questions: What is happening? What is not happening? How can I  influence the action? 
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="100">
	<B><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>BOOKS</FONT></B>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="400">
	<P>
<B>The Bamboo Network,  by Murray Weidenbaum and Samuel Hughes.</B>
</P>


<P>
In The Bamboo Network, Murray Weidenbaum and Samuel Hughes draw back the curtain on ''Greater China'' -- an invisible network of ethnic Chinese entrepreneurs, whose family ties stretch around the world. Li Ka-shing's father died after bringing his family to Hong Kong in the 1940s to escape the Communists on the mainland. At 12, Li supported his family by working at a company that made plastic flowers and watchbands. He started his own company, Cheung Kong, at age 22, then diversified worldwide into real estate, telecommunications, infrastructure, and energy. Today, Li's personal net worth is nearly $6 billion.
</P>


<P>
The corporate giants of Greater China are closely held family businesses. Very often, a father will send his sons to become citizens of countries half a world away to open a branch or division of the main business. An incompetent family member is considered more trustworthy than a competent outsider. Displays of wealth are shunned and decision making is intuitive -- which can be a faster way to seize opportunity than systematic, Western-style due diligence.
</P>


<P>
The entrepreneurs of The Bamboo Network are by far the biggest outside investors in businesses in mainland China -- making use of long-term village and family relationships and operating there more profitably than do Western companies. Should there be another crackdown on capitalism, Greater China still will thrive elsewhere. As they say in The Bamboo Network, ''Keep your bags packed at all times.''
</P>


<P>
<B>The Digital Economy, by Don Tapscott.</B>
</P>


<P>
As Don Tapscott points out in The Digital Economy, the computer revolution won't leave agriculture or industry behind. Rather, computers are adding power and effectiveness to what we already do. Farms today are tilled by equipment whose performance is guided by computer chips.
</P>


<P>
On your computer, you can contact a bakery and order a customized loaf baked with ingredients you specify and have it delivered that afternoon. 
</P>


<P>
In Hong Kong, computer pattern making and cutting allow you to order a custom-made suit and pick it up the same day. 
</P>


<P>
In the digital economy, cattle auctions take place without the risk and expense of moving animals hundreds of miles to market. The Calgary Stockyard Ltd. does two-thirds of its cattle transactions in ''virtual'' yards.
</P>


<P>
Calyx &amp; Corolla is a virtual company selling cut flowers by catalog. The flowers are shipped from any of a dozen growers directly to customers. 
</P>


<P>
The new Boeing 777 is the first plane to be created without physical models or blueprints. It was designed using computer-imaging software and tested in digital ''wind tunnels'' at every stage before actually being built.
</P>
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE WIDTH="500">
<TR>
