<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12Franchise1.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="6" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	FRANCHISING: Hot Food Concepts / By Carol Steinberg</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1"WIDTH="200">
	<IMG SRC="../DEC96.HTML/fran.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="156" HEIGHT="84" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">Photograph by JEFF BRAVERMAN</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>CATERING TO A NEW MARKET</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">How Three Franchisors Plan to Carve a Unique Food Niche</FONT><BR><HR><BR><BR><BR><H5><A NAME="7">OPPORTUNITY MONITOR</A><BR>By Carol Steinberg</H5>

<FONT SIZE="+3">Hot Growth State</FONT><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+1">A Big Market, a Central Location: Franchisors Flock to Illinois</FONT> <BR>

<DIR><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	<LI><B>Spotlight:</B>  Driver's Mart Worldwide Inc.
	<LI><B>Founder:</B>  Thomas W. Eggleston.
	<LI><B>Concept:</B>  Late-model-used-car superstores, with on-site software to target selection and lot location,
	and a one-price, no-haggle sales policy.
	<LI><B>Total Initial  Investment:</B>  $10 million per store.
	<LI><B>Founded:</B>  December 1995.
	<LI><B>Headquarters:</B>  Grand Rapids, Mich.
</DIR>

<P>
If you've got a franchise chain or plan to have one in the future, odds
are you'll eventually roll out in Illinois. With its central location and
large market, Illinois, one of 12 states in which franchisors must register
to sell franchises, ''is a major registration state,&quot; says Jeffrey
Kolton, president of FRANDATA, a franchise-research firm in Washington,
D.C.
</P>

<P>
Initial registration applications were approved for 18 companies in September,
according to the Illinois attorney general's office. In addition, 15 companies
filed new applications, and five established franchisors refiled applications
in Illinois. Half of the approved companies are new to franchising; three
of those had only company units and are embracing franchising for future
growth. Other companies, which have franchised elsewhere, have targeted
the state to extend their national reach.
</P>

<P>
Of the 18 companies that got the nod, retail stores and food services
dominate. Three of the franchisors boast long histories of building company
units: Red Roof Inns Inc., a 239-unit economy-lodging chain headquartered
in Columbus, Ohio; San Francisco-based Chevys Fresh Mex!, which operates
70 Mexican restaurants; and Ruby Tuesday Inc., a 300-unit casual-dining
chain based in Mobile, Ala.
</P>

<P>
Concepts to watch on the Illinois franchising scene include an activity/entertainment
service for singles, a jewelry store, a fruit-smoothie bar, and a store
touting back rubs and stress-reduction items. One -- Driver's Mart Worldwide
Inc., a superstore selling late-model used cars -- is so young that the
pilot unit was slated to open in November.
</P>

<P>
<B>Targeting the Untapped Share of a Huge Market</B>
</P>

<P>
Thomas W. Eggleston, president and chief executive officer of Driver's
Mart, views the used-car industry as ''the last huge consumer market that
is highly fractionated.&quot;
</P>

<P>
Indeed, the industry rang up $311.3 billion in sales in 1995, but the
largest market share was just three-tenths of 1 percent. As a result, Eggleston
is launching a nationwide chain of superstores that specialize in late-model
used cars.
</P>

<P>
He is going up against some heavy hitters. Similar concepts are unfolding
from AutoNation USA, a seven-store Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based chain whose
founder is ex-Blockbuster Entertainment powerhouse Wayne Huizenga; and CarMax,
a five-store subsidiary of the Richmond, Va.-based giant Circuit City. Both
chains plan only company units -- about 80 to 100 across the country.
</P>

<P>
Eggleston envisions 100 Driver's Mart stores via franchising alone within
three to five years.
</P>

<P>
<B>Service That Changes the Image of Used-Car Dealers</B>
</P>

<P>
''Repeat business is critical,&quot; Eggleston says. ''Our franchisees
realize it's a relationship-based, not transaction-based, method of sale.
Our stores are a combination of selection and service.&quot;
</P>

<P>
A former chief operating officer of Amway Corp., Eggleston, 44, is selling
franchises to new-car dealers who rank in the top echelon for customer service
-- people who are likely to have the $10 million initial investment that
is required for the land, the building, and inventory. ''The entrepreneurial
energy of carefully selected franchisees will ensure the same elite-customer
satisfaction that they've demonstrated in new cars,&quot; he says.
</P>

<P>
Uniquely, 21 new-car dealers provided Driver's Mart's initial capital,
and these shareholders will open the franchises.
</P>

<P>
Having a franchisee-owned company, says Eggleston, ''keeps the focus
on the customer and not on issues of fairness between the franchisee and
franchisor.&quot; Eggleston also expects that national-brand identity and
sophisticated systems will upgrade the image of used-car salespeople.
</P>

<P>
Proprietary software on-site at every Driver's Mart franchise will track
each lot's 250 to 500 domestic and foreign cars. Typically these vehicles
will be two to four years old, have fewer than 50,000 miles on them, and
sell for $13,500 on average.
</P>

<P>
Car buyers can narrow their purchase selection by model, color, amount
of monthly payment, or other parameters. Armed with a computerized description,
customers can head directly to the vehicle for a test drive.
</P>

<P>
''It's far more efficient than walking around the lot,&quot; says Eggleston.
</P>

<P>
There is also a benefit for franchisees: The computer system will link
inventory chainwide so that they can transfer cars to meet customer demand.
</P>

<P>
Of the franchisees, Eggleston notes, ''many are the original architects
of the one-price, no-haggle sales process and see the same process being
applicable for used cars.&quot; And so it is at Driver's Mart, on both trade-ins
and sales. ''The focus of selling should be on what is the right vehicle,
not on negotiation of price, which is highly adversarial,&quot; says Eggleston.
And the right price will be approximately $1,000 below prices quoted in
such industry guides as The Kelly Blue Book and The National Auto Dealers
Association Guide.
</P>

<P>
Driver's Mart will initially supply cars to dealers for a $200 sourcing
fee each; other inventory will come directly from brokers and trade-ins.
Once the store opens, the franchisor makes money only on the back end: a
$200 royalty on each sale. The superstores also offer accessories, insurance,
and internal financing competitive with outside financing sources.
</P>

<P>
Driver's Mart Worldwide Inc. was set to open its pilot superstore in
Neenah, Wis. 
</P>
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>Tony Riviera is betting the future of his pizza-delivery chain on tomatoes that are canned within eight hours of harvesting. On pepperoni that hangs for 45 days. On hand-tossed, lard-free dough. In short, on gourmet, high-quality pizza. Riviera, president and chief executive officer of Tony Maroni's Famous Gourmet Pizza, has designed his business with a hook.</FONT>
</P>


<P>
Ron Paul, president of Technomic Inc., a Chicago-based food-industry consultancy, says, ''You have to have a point of differentiation that will help you as you leave your entry market. And without question, the concept must generate excitement.''
</P>


<P>
Technomic estimates that 100 food concepts emerge every year. The hottest have some distinctive feature franchisors believe will make them winners -- like Riviera's gourmet standard.
</P>


<P>
Kuni Toyoda has made quick-service Italian food, in a fun version of mom-and-pop-style eateries, the hook at his Fazoli's franchise chain. Jim Maruna will ride the health-conscious trend, offering open-kitchen cooking of top-quality foods at his Mexican Baja Tortilla Grill restaurants. 
</P>


<P>
Each of these entrepreneurs uses specific strategies, based on changing consumer trends, to bring about hot food concepts. 
</P>


<P>
<B>The Right Unit Economics
</B></P>


<P>
Tony Riviera, 39, grew up in Brooklyn, N.Y., the home of aromatic mom-and-pop pizzerias. In fact, his first job, at age 11, was making pizza at Nathan's in Coney Island. Later ventures, after a stint as an army chef, included a catering company that provided food for celebrities, as well as an Italian restaurant in Washington State. 
</P>


<P>
In 1987, Riviera embraced his roots by opening a ''New York pizza joint'' in Kirkland, Wash. Although New Age toppings were trendy, he vowed to serve traditional pies -- until 10 patrons asked for pineapple on their pizzas. He raided supermarkets for canned pineapple, and other ''gourmet'' toppings followed. ''You have to listen to your customers to succeed,'' he says.
</P>


<P>
Within a year, Riviera tested a takeout-and-delivery unit and found that it was seven times less work to sell a pie than a slice. By 1993, with the 500-square-foot store reeling in $10,000 a week, he had opened four more gourmet-pizza takeout-and-delivery stores. Here was a hot concept and niche that could be cookie-cuttered. But he had to gear up first. Financial problems from a partnership gone bad led him to reorganize under Chapter 11. He emerged from bankruptcy in 1994. Since January, he has raised nearly $1 million privately, and he began franchising units in March.
</P>


<P>
<B>Differentiation Counts Most
</B></P>


<P>
By targeting upscale consumers willing to pay for meal replacement in lieu of cooking at home, Riviera hopes to grab a distinctive slice of the crowded pizza market. ''If you want to succeed,'' he says, ''you need to find the void in the market and fill it.'' Sophisticated diners crave quality, he says. ''They taste pizza like mine and say, 'Why should I settle for Little Caesars or Domino's when, for a dollar or two more, I can get Tony Maroni's?' '' And he knows differentiation counts most.
</P>


<P>
About two years ago, he ''went crazy'' with pizza toppings -- everything from barbecued chicken to goat cheese to capers. As a result, store sales shot up 30 percent. Lasagna, calzones, and salad now round out the menu; in the future, other baked goods may be introduced, based on the home-meal-replacement trend.
</P>


<P>
Riviera handpicks high-profile sites near heavily trafficked businesses like Blockbuster video outlets for his units. And each shop has ''a very Starbucks look and feel,'' he says, ''so the image matches the quality of the product.'' The now nine-store Seattle-area chain (five stores are company-owned) avoids heavy discounting. Rather, it woos clients with its gourmet food and quality service, which every store monitors by calling 10 customers each night.
</P>


<P>
Riviera surrounds himself with franchising experts, including executive vice president and COO Larry Metzelaar, a former director at Domino's; strategic-planning director George Naddaff, founder and former CEO of Boston Chicken; and W. Berry Fowler, creator of Sylvan Learning Centers. Both Naddaff and Fowler own stock in Tony Maroni's Franchise Systems Inc., headquartered in Bellevue, Wash.
</P>


<P>
While the top-10 quick-service pizza chains rang up $11 billion in sales last year, Tony Maroni's rejects battling the giants. Pursuing middle- and upper-income customers creates its own niche. ''This is not a contest for the lowest-price pizza,'' says Naddaff, who eventually plans to develop Massachusetts. The average ticket at Tony Maroni's: $20. Total initial investment for a franchise: $106,300 to $169,500.
</P>


<P>
<B>Massaging a Concept
</B></P>


<P>
Ever since he became smitten with the restaurant business, Kuni Toyoda has seen great potential for quick-service Italian food. His former employer, Jerrico Inc., the parent company of Long John Silver's Restaurants Inc., had been developing a similar concept at a Fazoli's restaurant in Lexington, Ky., since 1988. But after a leveraged buyout, Jerrico wanted to divest itself of its five Fazoli's units -- and Toyoda wanted in. ''My rationale was that if I bought these units and fine-tuned them, I'd have two or three years' lead time over any imitator,'' says Toyoda, the Japanese-born president of Lexington-based Seed Restaurant Group Inc.
</P>


<P>
The pieces quickly fell into place. In May 1990, Toyoda tapped his long-standing relationship with Duskin Co. Ltd., a huge Japanese conglomerate that used to franchise Long John Silver's in Japan. Duskin anted up to buy Fazoli's and is Toyoda's 40 percent partner today. Toyoda immediately massaged the concept and began franchising Fazoli's in 1992.
</P>


<P>
''Our goal is to become the quick-service-industry version of Southwest Airlines,'' says Toyoda, 46. That is, he wants Fazoli's to be the fun version of mom-and-pop Italian eateries. Pasta, not pizza, is the focus at the restaurants, including combination platters of baked ziti and spaghetti, for instance, along with high-quality ingredients. Tables and red ice-cream-parlor-like chairs, surrounded by colorful murals, replace typical plastic booths. Garlic bread and breadsticks are baked in view of the customers. Associates are drilled to be ''Fazoli friendly''; in fact, cash bonuses are given to those who score well on company service-quality checks. Customers are treated to refills of all drinks at no charge; free breadsticks, the signature Fazoli's item, throughout the meal; and even occasional bursts of Italian song at the drive-in window. 
</P>


<P>
Quick Market Penetration, Then a Media Storm
</P>


<P>
Fazoli's swiftly penetrates a market, then follows with a blitz of TV commercials that emphasize quality and freshness. It mandates serving pasta within one minute of cooking and breadsticks within five minutes of baking. Value pricing for the mainstream consumer draws the high guest counts necessary to maintain freshness and quality. The typical customer, says Toyoda, visits the 3,000-square-foot units 3.2 times every two weeks.
</P>


<P>
Since June 1994, Tim Terry, whose family once owned 33 Long John Silver's restaurants, has opened four Fazoli's units in West Virginia. Opening-week sales of $48,000 at his first unit broke all Fazoli's franchise-unit records. ''The concept is what energizes everyone,'' he says. Indeed, Kuni Toyoda was right about the potential of the quick-service concept. The average sales volume at each Fazoli's restaurant has doubled since 1990, to $1 million. In six years the chain has swelled to 231 units in 24 states, and the company plans to add about 100 units annually. The average ticket at Fazoli's: $3.85. Total initial investment: $400,000 to $905,000.
</P>


<P>
<B>Acting on Megatrends
</B></P>


<P>
Jim Maruna is a confident entrepreneur. So confident that he says, ''There's enough of a segmentation that I have no problem putting a Baja Tortilla Grill right next door to a Taco Bell,'' referring to the $4.6 billion leader in Mexican fast food. Indeed, to Maruna, president and CEO of Tortilla Ventures Inc., headquartered in Hinsdale, Ill., a Baja Tortilla Grill ''is as different to Mexican concepts as Boston Chicken was to chicken.'' 
</P>


<P>
''This is not a bunch of amateurs with Aunt Sally's recipe. We've engineered the concept based on megatrends,'' says Maruna, a former senior vice president at the full-service Mexican restaurant chain Chi-Chi's Inc. One of those trends, he observes, is the maturing of consumer taste, to expectations of better flavor and higher quality. And so Baja's niche is 100 percent display cooking: tortillas made from balls of fresh dough, char-grilled vegetables and steak, and a free fresh-salsa bar. ''Customers don't mind paying a little more for steak, not mystery meat, in a taco,'' says the 50-year-old founder. 
</P>


<P>
Riding the health wave, Baja Tortilla Grill ''captures the 'what isn't in a product' marketing trend,'' Maruna says. No lard, no MSG, no microwaves, no freezers. Also, the chain hopes to capitalize on investors' thirst for maximum revenues per square foot. Annually, the 1,500-to-2,000-square-foot units can achieve $500 to $600 per square foot, he says.
</P>


<P>
In June 1995 Mike Platt, one of the first franchisees of Fuddruckers Inc., a gourmet-hamburger chain, opened the first Baja Tortilla Grill as a joint venture with Tortilla Ventures. Since then, he has purchased the Minneapolis unit outright. ''Tastes for Mexican food are established,'' he notes, ''but increasingly consumers have a desire for something better, which has been relatively unexploited.'' Sales in Platt's unit exceeded $530 a square foot for the first 12 months. He's convinced that the simple contemporary American decor will hold broader appeal for consumers not in the habit of eating Mexican food. He plans 50 to 100 units in Minnesota, Colorado, and Missouri.
</P>


<P>
Chainwide, Maruna expects a total of six units in Virginia, Florida, Minnesota, New Jersey, and Massachusetts by the end of this year. Current area-development agreements call for at least 61 restaurants in seven states and Washington, D.C. The average ticket at Baja Tortilla Grill: $7.75. Total initial investment: $150,000 to $350,000.
</P>


<P>
Contributing writer Carol Steinberg has been covering franchise businesses for national publications for a dozen years.
</P>
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


