<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">





  









WILSON HARRELL



Danger Ahead!



Entrepreneurs: Here's Why You Must Stay Out of Court



On a recent trip to Chicago I sat next to James, a senior partner in

a 400-lawyer law firm. For 20-odd years James has been litigating every

conceivable kind of civil case, usually for large companies. Like any entrepreneur,

I was seriously interested in the workings of large law firms -- and rightly

so, since I have been a major contributor to that constituency for the past

40 years. We also talked a lot about how juries are selected. By the time

our plane landed, I had decided the following: I will never again willingly

go into a courtroom, even if I know I'm right, even if the angels are singing

for my side. Never again, if I can help it, will I allow any jury to make

a decision that affects me or mine. And neither will you, by the time I've

finished this scenario.



During the course of our conversation, I told James about a terrible

courtroom experience I once had. I was forced to pay through the nose when

a jury found in favor of a drunk I had fired for cause. James smiled and

said: ''I could write a book on cases I've won and lost based on jury decisions

that were totally irrational. Let me tell you about the special training

session we run each year for our young lawyers to show them how unpredictable

juries are.''



The senior partners select an actual case from their files. They appoint

one of their young litigators to present the case for the plaintiff and

another to argue for the respondent. Next, they select three people unknown

to any of the players to act as a jury. One of the senior partners acts

as judge. There are usually 10 to 12 such teams involved in each session.



When all the evidence is presented and the final summations are made,

each jury retires to consider its verdict. It can award the plaintiff anything

between nothing and a huge sum of money. And in this case, the respondent

had countersued, so the possibilities were endless.



Since the evidence presented by each pair of young lawyers is exactly

the same, it seems logical to assume that the outcomes of the trials will

be about the same. Right? Wrong! According to James, it is rare that any

two juries end up with the same verdict.



James explained: ''Last year, my 24-year-old daughter sat on one of the

juries. She and the other members rejected the plaintiff's suit and found

in favor of the other guy, awarding him the maximum amount of punitive damages.

An outrageous amount.'' When James asked his daughter why, she said that

from the get-go she had detested the lawyer for the plaintiff -- that he

was a conceited, prissy show-off who utterly failed to make his client's

case.



A cold chill ran down my spine. I remembered that the lawyer who handled

my case with the drunk was a show-off, too. Is there a lesson in all this?

I think so. First: Stay out of courthouses. Second: If you must go to court,

don't hire a wise guy. Here's how I wound up with one: When the drunk I'd

fired sued me for breach of contract, I refused, in righteous indignation,

to consider any form of settlement. My lawyer was a general-counsel type

from a large firm, so he took me down the hall and introduced me to the

litigator who would handle my case. Since there wasn't a large amount of

money involved and the case looked like a slam dunk, I got a junior partner.

He looked like a college kid. To be frank, from minute one I didn't like

him. I should have told my lawyer to move on down the hall to another litigator.

I didn't listen to my gut and paid the price.



Who Are Your Peers?



Even with the right lawyer, you face a massive problem in a courtroom.

Our founding fathers guaranteed that we would be tried before our peers.

But on juries today, you won't find the peers of entrepreneurs like you

and me. You'll find the people who are left after all our peers have been

excused -- people who couldn't figure out how to get out of jury duty or

had nothing better to do. They include the unemployed and the unemployable,

retirees and bored housewives, mental incompetents and nighttime streetwalkers,

anyone receiving workmen's compensation, and perhaps gang members. Remember

the O.J. trial? Ask yourself if these are people with a natural sympathy

for business owners.



Is this a stupid system? Well, maybe, but we've fought wars to preserve

it and would again. Any alternative is unthinkable. Of course, you and I

could make things a little better if we reformed the system to allow entrepreneurs

to be tried by their real peers -- by people who would understand them,

their struggles, and their contribution to society. In other words, by other

entrepreneurs.



But in the meantime: May your day in court never come. 



To obtain Harrell's video on business strategy, The Entrepreneurial Revolution,

or his book, For Entrepreneurs Only, see page 80.



Wilson Harrell is a consultant and speaker to the entrepreneurial market

and the author of the book For Entrepreneurs Only. To reach Harrell, fax

him at 770-889-4030. 

</body>

</html>





