<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	INSIDE TRACK / The Entrepreneur / Edited by Kristin Dunlap Godsey</FONT><BR><BR><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	
	<IMG SRC="it.ent.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="144" HEIGHT="84" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">Photograph by JAY REED</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3"><BR>INNOVATION FROM ADVERSITY</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><!--deck goes here--></FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">
<P>
Ed Jarvis knew he had a winner, but he was nervous anyway. All-star defenseman
Ray Bourque of the Boston Bruins was trying out a distortion-free protective
eye shield made by Jarvis's company, One Xcel Inc. Bourque made a few rushes,
fired the puck once or twice, and then -- as only a hockey player could
-- colorfully voiced his approval.</FONT>
</P>

<P>
''I can't really repeat what he said,'' says Jarvis, ''but he was happy.
He noticed a dramatic improvement over his old shield.''
</P>

<P>
Jarvis, 45, was driven to start his own business after a painful accident.
During a high-school basketball game two years ago, his only son, Ryan,
was blinded in his right eye when another player poked him so hard that
it severed his optical nerve.
</P>

<P>
Jarvis allowed Ryan to play football the following fall on one condition:
He had to wear a plastic face shield on his helmet to protect his good eye.
But the normally sure-handed Ryan kept dropping the ball.
</P>

<P>
''We thought he was having trouble adjusting to having only one eye,''
says Jarvis. ''Then I put his helmet on and looked through the shield. It
was distorting everything.''
</P>

<P>
Jarvis decided to have an optically correct shield made, but the cost
to have a single shield designed and produced would have been astronomical.
Instead, with more than $1 million from BancBoston Ventures Inc. and $500,000
of his own money, Jarvis formed One Xcel in Danvers, Mass. Now Ryan can
have a proper shield for just $45.
</P>

<P>
To get the right design, Jarvis says, ''I went to the same company that
makes shields for the astronauts. I said, 'How about developing a commercial
application?' It was costly but worth it.''
</P>

<P>
The key, explains Jarvis, was making a shield like a contact lens: thicker
in the center and thinner on the periphery. The shield also has a special
coating to help keep it from fogging up.
</P>

<P>
Today, One Xcel is a $6 million company. The NHL, the NFL, and the American
Hockey Coaches Association have endorsed the shields. Several professional
athletes, including Bourque, Jaromir Jagr of the Pittsburgh Penguins, and
Barry Sanders of the Detroit Lions, wear them. One Xcel has an arrangement
with Riddell Inc. of Chicago, whose helmets for pro football teams now include
the shields.
</P>

<P>
But the real market for the shields is scholastic athletes like Jarvis's
son, who now plays football at Bates College in Maine. ''Ryan jokes that
I should give him a paycheck,'' says Jarvis, ''because if he hadn't been
injured, the company wouldn't exist. We're still negotiating -- right now
I think it's the amount of his tuition.'' *
</P> 
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


