<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12ITHotOps.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	INSIDE TRACK / Hot Opportunities in Women's Sports</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<BR><FONT SIZE="-1"><!--art credti here--></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+4"><BR>A WINNING TEAM</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>In the last 15 years, the ranks of females participating in sports have
swelled -- some say by as much as 800 percent. Pioneering entrepreneurs
are attracting their business -- and leveling the <BR>playing field.</B></FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">
<BR><BR><BR>
<P>
<B>The Windmill Group</B>
</P>

<P>
Bill Redmer hated the fact that local boys' teams were getting way more
attention than his daughter's fast-pitch softball team. But instead of getting
mad, he got even, turning his knowledge of the game into a $1 million business.
Today the 10-year-old Windmill Group of St. Charles, Ill., is a hit with
young female athletes starved for practical advice and a sense of recognition.</FONT>
</P>

<P>
The former banker now produces a magazine, FastPitch World, for which
he expects subscriptions to triple by mid-1997. The steady cash flow from
the magazine, as well as pitching seminars and 18 instructional videos,
has allowed Redmer to expand into television. His first show, FastPitch
U.S.A., premiered in 1993 and now has more than 40 million viewers on local
sports channels. He launched a women's-basketball show last year and plans
to add two more to the roster in 1997.
</P>

<P>
Redmer has also talked to big players like ESPN and Lifetime. ''If we
get one major break, this company will become a multimillion-dollar operation
in 12 to 18 months,'' he predicts. ''Girls and women are finally being recognized
as great athletes, and we've positioned ourselves to be the first to tap
into that.''
</P>

<P>
<B>Golf Fore Business Co.</B>
</P>

<P>
Arguably, the game of golf has been an old-boys' club for business wheeling
and dealing. Not anymore. About six million female golfers have muscled
their way in nationwide.
</P>

<P>
Still, the concept of swinging clubs to swing deals does not come naturally
to most women. Enter Austin, Tex.-based Golf Fore Business Co. The brainchild
of entrepreneurs Sandy Silver and Joene Grissom and professional golfer
Barbara Puett, the two-year-old company specializes in training seminars
aimed at bringing women up to par.
</P>

<P>
''You can't teach anyone to play golf in a day, but you can help them
find their comfort zone,'' says Grissom. So far, almost 400 women (and some
men) have attended GFB's workshops, shelling out $175 for pointers on golf
terms, appropriate attire, and business conversation.
</P>

<P>
Organizations like the Independent Bankers' Association and the LPGA
have commissioned seminars. Corporations like Motorola and Office Depot
have subsidized the cost for top women employees. ''These are the types
of customers we want to zero in on,'' says Silver.
</P>

<P>
Until now, Silver and her partners have focused solely on Texas. But
in 1997 they plan to take their show on the road to conduct more than 40
seminars in 20 cities. With the help of their newest partner, sales expert
Bob Peck, the GFB team plans to pitch their service to major sponsors and
hit revenues in the half-million-dollar range.
</P>

<P>
<B>Spectrum Sports &amp; Entertainment LLC</B>
</P>

<P>
Sally Sullivan knows about making a living as a woman athlete. A onetime
tennis pro, she abandoned the clay courts to get a law degree. As a sports
lawyer, she watched her favorite client, basketball forward Katy Steding,
grapple with limited options and relatively small endorsement contracts,
so Sullivan set Steding up with a long-term opportunity: the founding of
a basketball academy.
</P>

<P>
''The thing I enjoyed most as an athlete was teaching tennis to kids,''
explains the Issaquah, Wash.-based Sullivan, who found that 4 percent of
the region's girls played hoops. She approached local real estate guru Skip
Rowley with a business plan, and in 1994 the two founded Spectrum, a company
devoted to helping athletes -- especially women -- establish sports-related
businesses.
</P>

<P>
Spectrum's major stake in the new Katy Steding Basketball Academy (KSBA)
is beginning to bear fruit. The 40 girls enrolled in the year-round program
will contribute upwards of $60,000 in the next 12 months. Twenty week-long
camps will generate about three times that amount.
</P>

<P>
The company's new licensing plan allows others to buy KSBA's training
package, complete with appearances by Steding and her Olympic teammates.
Spectrum is negotiating with established programs in Missouri, Wisconsin,
and Nevada and expects revenues to hit $1 million next year. ''Our dream,''
says Rowley, ''is to extend the academy idea to other sports.'' *
</P>

</P></TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


