<HTML>

<HEAD>

  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">

  <TITLE>  12ITScope.html</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">





<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" WIDTH="500">

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">

	 <FONT COLOR=#CC000C>Inside Track /SUCCESS SCOPE</FONT></TD>

</TR>

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500"><BR>

	<FONT SIZE="+4">Cutting-edge concepts from business

journals and newsletters</FONT><BR><BR>

	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="111">

	<IMG SRC="scp.2.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="111" HEIGHT="96" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Illustrations by <BR>SCOTT MATTHEWS</FONT>

	</TD>

	

	<TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="300">

<B>	Evaluate Performance

</B>

<P>

Companies that formally evaluate the performance of their employees earn

more than companies that don't, according to a new study in the Harvard

Business Review. The findings suggest that sitting down with employees to

set goals and provide feedback helps them focus on the activities that will

help your company realize its objectives. &quot;When employees can see the

bigger picture and understand how their contribution fits with the greater

goals of the company, they will do a better job,&quot; says the publication.

Create a system to review employee performance periodically. Evaluate the

system on a regular basis and make changes as your organization grows.

</P>

	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="111"></TD>

	

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="300">

	<B>Build Your Database</B>





<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>

<P>

	A well-functioning database is the answer to successful one-to-one marketing.

	Industry Week offers the following tips to help you build a comprehensive

	database:

</P>



<P>

	Learn where information lies in your company. Chances are you have

	separate databases housed in such departments as accounting, sales, and

	distribution. Once you start to consolidate them, you'll be amazed at what

	you already know about your customers.

</P>



<P>

	Supplement this information with your own consumer research. Ask existing

	customers to fill out information cards associated with rebate programs,

	>warranties, and sweepstakes.

</P>



<P>

	Use external sources of information. There are many companies, such

	as TRW and Dun &amp; Bradstreet, that conduct consumer research and sell

	the data to other firms. This information can be invaluable in targeting

	your promotional efforts.</FONT>

</P>



	</TD><Td></TD>

</TR>

<TR>



	<TD ALIGN=right VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="411">

	<B>Trade Show Tactics</B>



Your salespeople may be terrific in the field, but when it comes to trade

shows they can fall flat on their face. That's because trade-show selling

requires special skills and training, according to Selling magazine. The

publication reports that salespeople who are trained in selling on the show

floor convert 68 percent more of their visitors into qualified leads than

those who receive no training. The key skill to master in the exhibition

environment is speed. &quot;A trade show visit is not like a sales call,&quot;

states the magazine. &quot;You've got people streaming in and out of the

booth. Salespeople need to be able to size up a lead quickly, decide how

they'll follow up, and then tactfully break away.

	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">

	<IMG SRC="scp1.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="144" BORDER="0">

	</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>

<TABLE WIDTH="500">

<TR>

