<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12ITNiches</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	INSIDE TRACK / Niches</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="it.nic.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="120" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">Photograph by <BR>SCOTT C. SCHULMAN</FONT><BR><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4">VIRTUAL TREES</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"><!--DECK GOES HERE--></FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Clients call Dennis Gabrick ''the pickled palm man.''When Dennis Gabrick started his business in 1987, he had a little trouble explaining to architects and interior designers just what he was selling.</FONT>

<P>
''People would look at me and say, 'You're trying to sell me an embalmed palm? What the hell is that?' '' says Gabrick, 47. ''And I would say, 'Please -- they're not embalmed, they're preserved.' ''

<P>
Gabrick's trees aren't exactly fake; they aren't exactly real, either. His Oceanside, Calif.-based company, Preserved TreeScapes International Inc. (PTI), takes branches and leaves from live trees (without killing the trees) and preserves them with a special chemical process. They are then attached to a metal-core trunk covered with real bark. The result is a virtual tree that never needs to be watered -- just cleaned occasionally and refurbished every four to five years with replacement branches and leaves.

<P>
''We discovered that one in every three live trees planted indoors dies or needs to be replaced each year,'' explains Gabrick. ''It becomes very costly.''

<P>
Before PTI, Gabrick was a sales and marketing executive in California for a Sweden-based company. Through that company he met Per Monie, a Swede who had invented a solution that preserved plant material. Together, with Monie's formula and Gabrick's $150,000 in savings, they started preserving small plants for the floral industry. They soon graduated to trees, and in 1989 the Mirage hotel and casino in Las Vegas contracted them to install 200 virtual palms. It was the company's big break.

<P>
PTI has grown steadily since 1991, as have the size, number, and types of trees it can preserve. Trees run from $100 to $300 per foot. Though the cost sounds high, saving clients money has been Gabrick's best marketing tool for carving a niche in a $3 billion-a-year industry. On a recent airport project, the company shaved $4 million from the architectural budget by replacing 12 live trees with 12 preserved ones. By doing so, PTI was able to eliminate planters with special irrigation and plumbing and scrap plans for skylights, which reduced the air-conditioning requirements for the building.

<P>
Gabrick says PTI will have sold at least 10,000 large trees, some as tall as 72 feet, by the end of 1996, with projected sales of about $6.5 million. In the past two years, it has opened offices in England, Thailand, and Australia. Says Gabrick: ''What we've done is started a whole new industry.''<BR> 
-David Carnoy
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


<TABLE WIDTH="500">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="500">
