</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>12TechClinic.html</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE/Tech Clinic / Edited by David Carnoy</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="1" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="tech.cl.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="120" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by MICHAEL J. BOWLES</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4"><BR>Smooth Sailing</FONT><BR><FONT 
SIZE="+1">Software to Help You Raise Capital</FONT><BR><BR><BR>
<BR><BR><BR>
<P><B><A NAME="9">Bulletin Board</A></B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">Personalize Your Mouse</FONT></P>

<P><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
CoStar Corp. has introduced the Stingray 4.0, an
updated version of its Macintosh trackball. It features new control-panel
software and other functional enhancements.
</P>

<P>
This Stingray looks very much like the old Stingray,
still ergonomically designed with a small, lightweight ball that conforms
to the natural arch of the hand. And it still comes in standard Apple Platinum
or Stealth Black. But now you can change the orientation of the Stingray
-- use it sideways or upside down -- and assign tracking speed and button
commands to specific software applications.
</P>

<P>
Stingray 4.0 is also compatible with the Turbo
Mouse 4.0 software from Kensington. This enables Turbo Mouse 4.0 users who
are uncomfortable with the Turbo Mouse's billiard-ball design to switch
to the smaller Stingray without abandoning their Turbo Mouse software. The
Stingray 4.0 retails for $59.95.
</P>

<P>
<B>Affordable Laser Quality
</B></P>

<P>
Down, down, down. That's the direction prices have
been going for laser printers in recent years. Now Okidata has broken the
$300 barrier with its new Okipage 4w (OP4w) laser-class printer.
</P>

<P>
Technically, the OP4w is not a laser printer. But
its LED (light-emitting diode) system, which is a dry-ink process, is closer
to laser technology than to inkjet technology. Labels aside, the OP4w offers
laser-quality 600-dpi resolution (monochrome only) and four-pages-per-minute
output. It's small, too -- not that much wider than a standard 8 1/2 --by-11-inch
piece of paper -- which means you'll be able to squeeze it into a tight
spot in your office.
</P>

<P>
Don't expect anything fancy. The OP4w comes with
a 100-sheet paper tray and 128K of memory. But it is Plug and Play compatible
with Windows 95, which makes it easy to set up. Cost: $299.
</P>

<P>
<B>A Truly Smart Phone
</B></P>

<P>
In 10 years, telecommunications experts say, everybody
will have one on his desk. But so far, smart phones haven't taken off, and
it's pretty clear why: the dumb price.
</P>

<P>
Enter the Intelifone from US Order of Herndon,
Va., and Colonial Data Technologies of New Milford, Conn. With a price tag
of just under $300, the Intelifone is the cheapest smart phone on the market
and the first to be sold in major retail outlets, such as Nobody Beats the
Wiz, Computer City, and Office Depot. 
</P>

<P>
Like other smart phones, the Intelifone has a built-in
keyboard and 
</P>

<P>
screen and can be used to send and receive e-mail,
look up stock quotes, and get sports scores. Intelifone also includes Advanced
Caller ID, which identifies the caller by name and number, and Polite Call
Waiting, with an audio message that asks the caller to &quot;please hold.&quot;
</P>

<P>
Another nice feature is the built-in national database
of telephone numbers and addresses; you can search through it, then store
the information in your personal phone directory, which holds up to 500
names and numbers. Of course, there's an additional fee for some of these
features, but that's a small price to pay to have the world at your fingertips.
	</FONT></TD>
</P>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><P>
For 28-year-old Chris Bent, 1996 was a good year. He owns a yacht, Tavernier,
on the Chesapeake Bay. He also happens to own the company that built the
yacht.</FONT>
</P>

<P>
When he cofounded Cal-Pearson Corp. of Bristol, R.I., last January, Bent
had little more than a few maxed-out credit cards in his wallet. By the
end of 1996, less than a year later, he plans to have raised $825,000 by
selling 165,000 shares of Cal-Pearson at $5 each. It took a smart idea,
a lot of sweat, and . . . a software package.
</P>

<P>
The package, Raising Capital Through SCOR, comes from Denver-based DataMerge
Inc. ''We wouldn't have had a chance at all without it,'' Bent says.
</P>

<P>
Bent owned a Pearson 31 boat in the early 1990s, when Pearson and Cal
yachts were the cream of the performance-sailboat crop. Both companies went
out of production during the recession, leaving thousands of loyal Pearson
and Cal owners high and dry.
</P>

<P>
Bent got in touch with his fellow sailors to see if they would be willing
to invest small amounts of money to revive the yacht lines. Encouraged,
he bought the manufacturing assets and marketing rights to the trade names,
then began raising money to build new boats (which sell for $89,000 to $185,000).
</P>

<P>
<B>A Simpler Road to Investors</B>
</P>

<P>
The Small Corporate Offering Registration (SCOR) is a streamlined alternative
to filing a traditional public-offering prospectus. Bent thought this might
be the way to go. SCOR allows a start-up or growing business to seek up
to $1 million every 12 months from investors without many regulatory restrictions
that otherwise apply. There is no limit on who can invest or when they trade
their shares. Audits aren't required if the company's offering is less than
$500,000 a year. Most important, the high fees for attorneys, accountants,
and underwriting are greatly reduced or eliminated.
</P>

<P>
Bent bought Raising Capital Through SCOR, a software-and-manual package
that walks the user through the 50-question SCOR disclosure form known as
U-7. The questions are fairly straightforward and readable. (Example: ''Describe
specifically the marketing strategies the company is employing or will employ
in penetrating its market or in developing a new market.'') The program
offers advice and strategy at every step to help the user stay within legal
guidelines and have a better chance of impressing investors.
</P>

<P>
''It asks you to take a very hard look at your goals,'' says Bent, ''and
to lay out in great detail your strategy to make money.''
</P>

<P>
In essence, Raising Capital Through SCOR is a business plan on a disk.
It also includes a timetable for a 120-day marketing campaign, tips for
creating an investor profile, and a ''tombstone'' ad to attract investors.
Plus, it tells you how to list the company on a stock exchange.
</P>

<P>
The program can be purchased with or without a database of 4,000 nontraditional
lenders, called The Financing Sources Databank. You simply enter in the
kind of financing you need, the type of lender you seek, your industry,
the location, and how much money you need. The computer does a search and
generates a list of appropriate lenders and investors. The database sells
for $139, or $299 when packaged with Raising Capital Through SCOR.
</P>

<P>
Bent found both products to be extremely worthwhile. With, on average,
$20,000 of permanent equity capital coming in weekly now, Cal-Pearson aims
to produce 50 boats in 1997.
</P>

<P>
But be warned: Raising Capital Through SCOR is no get-rich-quick scheme.
Raising money from dozens, or even hundreds, of investors is tough, no matter
how you go about it. Bent and his team spent months just completing the
SCOR form. ''It's not a magical thing, that you fill out the questions and
$1 million appears on your desk,'' he says. ''You really have to work very
hard.'' 
</P>
<HR>
<P>
<B>What You Need</B>
<BR>
S P E C S H E E T
</P>

<P>
RAISING CAPITAL THROUGH SCOR. Price: $199 alone;
$299 with databank. Requirements: Word 6.0 or better, DOS 3.3 or better,
4MB of RAM, 8.5MB of hard-disk space.
</P>
<P>
SUCCESS contributing editor Dan Gutman can be reached at <A HREF="mailto:DanGut1@aol.com.">DanGut1@aol.com.</A>
</P> 
	</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>


