<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="500">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE / Cyber Forum By Stephen R. Kelly</FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="300">
	<!--art goes here--><FONT SIZE="-1"><!--art credti here--></FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4">Page by Page</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">Novice or Expert, You Can Build A Great Web Site</FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3" WIDTH="300">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><P><BR><BR><BR><BR>
Building a Web site can be a daunting task. Even for Bob Virkus, an expert
on desktop publishing and director of Internet services for Alliance Entertainment Corp., the initial launch of the company site was a lot of work.</FONT>
</P>

<P>
The Coral Springs, Fla.-based Alliance Entertainment, a huge distributor
of CDs to music stores, recently overhauled its Web component (http://www.aent.com),
but this time Virkus used PageMill from Adobe Systems Inc. of San Jose,
Calif., to do it. What would have taken him two full weeks with other programs,
he says, took only two days with PageMill.
</P>

<P>
Alliance's prototype Web site went up in November 1995. ''We built it
because we saw that technology would soon be driving music distribution,&quot;
says Virkus. ''We also wanted to have a corporate presence on the Internet.
It shows that we're innovative. We have a lot of new information that people
need.&quot;
</P>

<P>
Virkus found that PageMill was the ideal Web-page builder because ''it
allowed me to take the raw data and put it up in a fraction of the time
it would have taken me to do in any other way. When the information on new
releases comes in on Monday mornings, I can have it up on the Web in an
hour.&quot;
</P>

<P>
Virkus had used Adobe's Illustrator and Photoshop programs for more than
a decade, and he thought PageMill had the same feel. Its simplicity helped
him get the site's 400 Web pages up in outline text, with basic navigation
tools, fast. ''If you can use a word processor, you can use PageMill,&quot;
he says.
</P>

<P>
<B>Easy-to-Use Features
</B></P>

<P>
PageMill also makes it really simple to handle text, Virkus says. ''I'm
very fussy about how I want the text presented because things are more difficult
to read on-screen. I can go in very quickly and format text easily without
worrying about the HTML coding behind it.&quot;
</P>

<P>
Virkus relies a lot on tables for better readability, and so he appreciates
PageMill's table-making features, especially the control it gives him over
the width of the text. ''That way it always looks good, no matter which
browser is pulling it up,&quot; he says. ''And it allows for the creative
use of white space.&quot;
</P>

<P>
PageMill lets the user toggle between edit and preview modes in order
to see exactly how the creations will look to the Web-site visitor. And
PageMill also allows you the freedom to include specific HTML coding on
your pages if you need it. For example, you can code a META tag to allow
the big search engines to index your page, making it easier for customers
to find your site.
</P>

<P>
Virkus also relies on another program from Adobe called SiteMill, which
manages the Web site as a whole. He uses it often to reorganize the site's
directory structure as the need arises, such as if the number of files in
a particular directory grows too huge to manage. ''You just drag and drop
files and update hundreds of links in the blink of an eye. I've had to reorganize
the site a number of times,&quot; he explains. ''The first time I did it
in SiteMill, it took 25 minutes. It would have taken me six hours to do
it manually. And, of course, if you try to do it manually, there will always
be something you typed wrong.&quot;
</P>

<P>
Together, the two Adobe programs make Bob Virkus's job a lot easier.
''Links are very easy to make with PageMill,&quot; he says. ''And SiteMill
is invaluable for managing a large Web site. And, you know, Web sites do
have a tendency to grow faster than you ever envisioned.
</P>

<P>
Stephen R. Kelly writes and publishes Internet Profit Report and lives
in Beulah, Mich.
</P>

<P>

</P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<B>What You Need</B>
<BR>
S P E C S H E E T
</P>


<P>
ADOBE PAGEMILL AND SITEMILL. Prices: $149 for PageMill, $279 for SiteMill.
Requirements (for either program): Mac System 7.1 or better, 3.5MB of RAM,
5MB of hard-disk space, 4-bit display or better. Windows 95 and Windows
NT versions of PageMill will be available in 1997. 
</P> 
	</TD>
</TR>


