<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>11EdNote</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0b1">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=1024 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	EDITOR'S NOTE / By Scott DeGarmo<BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">Affirmations </FONT>

<H3>The Powerful Words <BR>Of Og Mandino </H3>

<BR><BR><BR>



	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR>
<P>Dear Og: </P>

<P>As soon as I heard you had died, I remembered one of your affirmations:
I will live this day as if it is my last. </P>

<P>I had been meaning to write you a letter for some time. Now, we'll be
sharing it with a million SUCCESS readers. </P>

<P>I heard from one of those readers today when I walked into my office.
The phone was ringing, and on the line was one of our friends, Louis, telling
me you'd died on September 3 of an aneurysm. He was the first to call. Lou
told me your book sales were now up to 36 million, for all 18 of your titles,
with The Greatest Salesman in the World still selling more than 100,000
copies per month. I also asked Louis your age. Of course, 72 years old --
you retired from this magazine 20 years ago, at the age of 52, to write
and speak full time. You'd built our circulation to more than 200,000 during
your 15-year stint. Since then you've been called the most popular inspirational
writer of the last quarter century. Your novels, parables, and self-help
books developed a following among readers young and old, including such
celebrities as Willie Nelson, Burt Reynolds, Michael Jackson, and, more
recently, Matthew McConaughey, to name a few. </P>

<P>You'd wanted to become a writer even as a youth. But because of your
mother's early death, you joined the Army Air Force out of high school.
You later flew 30 combat missions over Germany, receiving the Distinguished
Flying Cross. Afterward, you spent a year in New York City, trying to break
in as a writer. But as you said, you weren't able to sell anything --''no
short stories, no fillers, nothing.'' In the ensuing years, you descended
into alcoholism, and were ready to end your life at the age of 35 -- and
perhaps would have, except, as you described, drinking had robbed you of
the courage you needed to pull the trigger. So, instead of spending your
last $29 on a handgun, you walked to the library and started devouring all
the books on achievement. It was a book written by W. Clement Stone and
Napoleon Hill, Success Through a Positive Mental Attitude, that rescued
you. Isn't it remarkable that Stone's life had also been galvanized by a
self-help book, as was the case with the editor of the original version
of SUCCESS, the 19th-century entrepreneur and author Orison Swett Marden?
Potent stuff, that self-help literature. </P>

<P>With your ambition roaring, you were hired by your hero Stone in the
late 1950s. You became an outstanding salesman and sales manager for his
insurance company. Then you seized a chance to write sales promotion bulletins
for the company. You said you loved writing those bulletins, that at last
you were fulfilling your lifelong goal of becoming a writer. That led to
a job as executive editor and then president of this magazine's precursor,
which you had to build up from scratch. The ideas, concepts, and philosophy
of Marden's publication had endured, though the physical product had not.
</P>

<P>Speaking of concepts, you said many times that success is based on enduring
principles, and you wrote passionately about those principles: overcoming
fear, withstanding rejection, defeating procrastination, laughing at failure,
renewing yourself each day. Nobody ever conveyed those ideas better than
you did in The Greatest Salesman. On the one hand, it had a spirit of competitive
zeal: My destiny is to become the greatest salesman in the world . . . I
will persist until I succeed . . . Today, I will be master of my emotions
. . . Good habits are the key to all success . . . My bad habits must be
destroyed and new furrows prepared for good seed. On the other, there was
a message of unrestrained hope and joy: I will greet this day with love
in my heart.<I> </I>You also emphasized the need for each of us to value
our own uniqueness. Ah, there's the rub. The spiritual content of your books
was unique indeed -- and though loved by your fans, went beyond the practical
boundaries of SUCCESS. </P>

<P>Yet your belief in the unlimited potential of the individual exactly
suits this booming new era of entrepreneurship. Your words of achievement
will remain with us: </P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Today I will multiply my value a hundredfold. 
	<LI>I will never commit the terrible crime of aiming too low.
	<LI>I will strive to make the next hour better than this one. 
	<LI>This is the time. 
	<LI>This is the place.
	<LI>I am the man.
	<LI>I will act now.
	<LI>My last must be my best. 
</UL>
We dedicate this issue to you, Og Mandino.

	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
