<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>9ArsenalLayout</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P></P>

<TABLE BORDER="0" WIDTH="550" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<FONT SIZE="+5">Management Arsenal</FONT><H4>Edited by Duncan Maxwell Anderson</H4>

	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275">
	<BR>CEO STRATEGIES </P>

<H1 ALIGN=RIGHT>Winning Systems </FONT></H1>

<P>When Eric Crown started college, computers still
worked with punch cards. In 1986, he and his brother Tim decided to convert
their inside knowledge of the revolution into a fast-growing business and
started Insight Enterprises Inc. of Tempe, Ariz., selling computer hard
disks. Insight now estimates $400 million in 1996 sales, selling computers
and components from its mail-order catalog -- it's among the biggest in
that business. His customers range from home-based businesses (30 percent)
to U.S. government agencies. </FONT></P>

<P><STRONG>Why did you start a business?</STRONG> </P>

<P>I had a job selling computers for a local retail
chain. I thought I could make more money on my own. I borrowed $2,000 on
my credit card, and my brother Tim and I started a business doing computer
consulting and sales. People lived in fear of me and my business card. But
I noticed that for all my hard work, I made more money in the 10 minutes
it took to sell a computer than I did doing three weeks of programming.
</FONT></P>

<P>My partners and I took all the money we had --
$5,000 -- and bought an ad offering hard drives at less than $300 each.
It was a gamble. That was $50 cheaper than we could buy them for at the
time. But we were banking on the price going down. In the four weeks till
the magazine came out, our cost fell by $70, so we made a profit. We sold
200 or 300. In retrospect, we didn't have enough information, but it worked.
Today we're basically doing the same thing, with a wider range of products.
</FONT></P>

<P><STRONG>How do you handle the risks?</STRONG> </P>

<P>Direct marketing is a people business, but it's
very systematic. We test upward of 30 marketing pieces in a month. We know
if we put out a catalog, 5 percent to 10 percent of the people will call,
and 40 percent of those will buy from us. Our average ticket price is $500.
We get 250,000 calls per month. The average shipper can ship 84 boxes in
a day. Everyone knows these rates. </FONT></P>

<P><STRONG>What's your job?</STRONG> </P>

<P>Systems analysis. I've seen so many businesses
that sell themselves into bankruptcy. Every department has to take a step
forward at the same time: ''If we go up X percent, where will we be stressed?''
</FONT></P>

<P><STRONG>What do you look for in an employee?</STRONG> </P>

<P>Someone who can think for himself. Say you're a
product manager in charge of printers. I'll say, ''We need to make so many
million with a 10 percent margin and low inventory. Good luck.'' </FONT></P>

<P><STRONG>What's your direction for the future?</STRONG> </P>

<P>We're up to 50,000 accesses per day on our Web
site. We do a couple of million in annual sales on the Internet. Our goal
there is $20 million in annual sales. It helps to have the newest gee-whiz
displays. We have rotational pictures -- you look at a product and spin
it. We'll ship you 3-D glasses. We've added real-time audio: As soon as
you click on it, it talks to you. </P>

<P><STRONG>What's ahead in the computer business?</STRONG> </P>

<P>Multi-processor systems with 10 or 20 pentiums
in the same computer. Desktops will be 10 times faster than a pentium today.
The business part of this industry will grow. There will also be more PCs
at home. The home education software business will continue to explode.
Everyone I sell to asks, ''What have you got for my kids?'' </P></TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
PUBLIC SPEAKING <BR><H1>Boldness Rules </H1>

<P>Business presentations often fail due to a fatal
lack of boldness, according to communications expert Granville N. Toogood
of Darien, Conn., author of The Articulate Executive. Because entrepreneurs
must constantly persuade, sell, and lead, they of all people need to know
the secrets of clarity and forcefulness. Toogood underlines the point with
a startling statistic: Audiences typically decide whether someone is worth
listening to within eight seconds after he opens his mouth. Business leaders
are quick-draw decision makers, too. Toogood describes riding up in an elevator
with two CEOs of chemical companies who hadn't seen each other in years.
By the time they reached the 30th floor, they'd agreed to merge their corporations.
</P>

<P>In a world that moves that fast, success belongs
to the bold. </P>

<P>When they speak publicly, most people are timid.
They ''cover'' a meandering list of subjects, as if afraid of leaving something
out. The result is disconnected, defensive, and dull. Instead, make every
word and idea in your speech point to a single inspiring idea, says Toogood.
A schematic diagram of your talk should be shaped like a rocket, with the
over-arching idea as the warhead, and each subject and its illustrative
examples pointing to it. </P>

<P>When it comes to showing slides, insecurity tempts
many to throw too much information onto a screen, which confuses and bores
audiences. Instead, restrict your graphics to a few powerful ideas. Make
one point at a time. What is worth presenting as an image? A business change:
growth; disaster; a vision of what's possible. </P>

<P>When creating your slides, cut the visual clutter.
 Your task is to dramatize movement -- so strip off
as many words, numbers, borders, and line-wiggles as you can. Use thick,
simple lines and bold, sweeping arrows. </P>

<P>The secret of persuading others to follow you is
to exercise dramatically the courage to say exactly what you mean. </P>

<HR><BR>
IDEAS <BR><H1>The Science Of Creativity</H1> 
<P>Principles of science can be powerful metaphors
for enhancing your creative performance, according to creativity consultants
Stephen Grossman, a former physicist, and Bryan Mattimore. </P>

<P> Resistant bacteria -- Antibiotics can foster
''super-bugs'' that are immune to that antibiotic by knocking out competing
bacteria. Applications: When you need to brainstorm a new idea or strategy:
1) Hold the session only after the participants have a chance to think about
the problem (to &quot;grow&quot; their responses); and 2) Constraining one
element in an environment fosters growth in others. Try adding various restrictions
to the parameters of the solution. This will cause suppressed solutions
to emerge. </P>

<P> Laser light -- In a conventional, incandescent
bulb, the bulb's brightness is reduced by the fact that the electrons are
out of phase with each other -- they neutralize each other's energy as they
alternate from a &quot;ground&quot; state to an &quot;excited'' state at
different times. In a laser light, the electrons are in phase and pulse
together powerfully. Application: Immersing yourself in a problem over time
brings perceptions and thoughts into phase to pulse out a powerful solution.
Inspiration ''out of nowhere'' usually strikes a prepared mind. </P>

<P>Stephen Grossman is president of Double Dominance
Inc. in Maple Shade, N.J. Bryan Mattimore heads The Mattimore Group in Stamford, Conn.
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

