<HEAD>
   <TITLE>10GlobalEnt</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0b1">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=1024 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	GLOBAL ENTREPRENEUR / By John R. Engen<BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">The Midas Touch</FONT>

<H3>Turning Businesses<BR>to Gold-- One After <BR>the Other</H3>

	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P>David Tang is a tough man to track down. The 42-year-old
entrepreneur, regarded as one of Hong Kong's most enigmatic yet
undeniably successful businessmen, has been crisscrossing the planet
in pursuit of his latest quest: creating the first globally
recognized Chinese brand name.</P>

<P>The vehicle for his ambitions is Shanghai Tang, a line of kitschy
clothing and accessories he launched with a splash last year in Hong
Kong. With labels that read ''Made by Chinese,'' the line includes a
snappy array of Chinese-style tunics and robes. The accessories
include off-the-wall items like lime-green photo albums and the
''waving Deng watch,'' with an image of the aging Chinese leader,
Deng Xiaoping, furiously moving his hand as the seconds tick by.</P>

<P>The items are now sold only in one very successful Shanghai Tang
store in Hong Kong's pricey central business district. But Tang's
company, D.W.C. Tang Development Ltd., aims to take the brand to
Europe and the States within the next year via mail order and a
handful of high-profile retail outlets.</P>

<P>''We've already managed to touch a nerve in Hong Kong,'' Tang says
in a prim British accent, a remnant of his English university days.
''We want to bring the world a cross section of barely known
traditional clothes from other places in China, like Tibet and
Sichuan.''</P>

<P>It won't be easy. Today, China is known as a low-cost
manufacturing center with a 1.2 billion-person market -- not as a
fashion mecca. ''The basic weakness of Chinese manufacturers is that
they don't produce quality stuff. They don't produce it in the right
sizes, or for the right function. And they certainly don't package it
right,'' Tang says.</P>

<P>''All they need is a bit of guidance, and that's what I'm doing.''
</P>

<P>A New Business Every Year</P>

<P>Shanghai Tang is just one of a growing line of businesses Tang has
built. But like many entrepreneurs, Tang had to stumble through the
corporate maze before finding his true path. He studied philosophy
and law as a college student in London, then trained as a solicitor
there. He returned to Hong Kong in the early 1980s, where he landed a
job with the giant Swire Group, escorting department store buyers to
clothing factories. ''These were all Americans and excruciatingly
boring,'' he recalls with his characteristic bluntness. When he asked
to be assigned to a different job, the answer was no. ''I concluded
that I didn't like working in a big organization.''</P>

<P>Frustrated, he took a teaching job at Beijing University and from
there assisted Cluff Resources plc, the British oil firm, with
management of its China holdings. Working with Cluff gave Tang
experience managing what he calls the ''holy trinity'' of business
knowledge: profit and loss, cash flows, and balance sheets. ''Without
an understanding of what these things are, you'll be handicapped in
any business,'' he says.</P>

<P>In 1991, aided by a few investors, Tang set out to start one new
business per year for a decade. He began by launching Hong Kong's
ritzy China Club, now a haven for the colony's power brokers. In
1992, he opened Pacific Cigar Co., a Havana-cigar distributor to
Asia. The year after that, he set up a fund investing in restaurants
and fast food in China. Three more businesses -- a flower-and-gift
shop, Shanghai Tang, and, most recently, a second China Club in
Beijing -- round out Tang's six businesses in six years. Together,
they generate upward of $50 million per year.</P>

<P>Past success bodes well for the future of Shanghai Tang clothes
and accessories, which now get the lion's share of Tang's attention.
And not just in terms of conquering outside markets. ''The Chinese
are quite snobbish. They are proud to wear a brand that is popular in
the West,'' he says. ''Once we get accepted outside China, we will be
more accepted inside.'' 
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
