<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>11OwnerEquity</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0b1">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=1024 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	OWNER'S EQUITY / By M. John Storey <BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">Pick Your Moment
</FONT>

<H3>Know When to Sell and Get the Most for Your Equity</H3>


	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
In 1816, James Hart Stark of Missouri grafted shoots onto crab apple seedlings. After 180 years, his experiments grew into the $10 million-plus Stark Brothers Nurseries and Orchards Co. of Louisiana, Mo. 

<P>
Stark's descendants -- John Logan and his sons, Clay Stark Logan and Walter C. Logan II -- had no intention of selling their tightly held company. But then they got an attractive offer from the right buyer: former customer Foster &amp; Gallagher Inc., a $220 million-plus horticultural powerhouse based in Peoria, Ill.

<P>
The golden moment to sell your company -- when the interest is hottest and the offers are highest -- is as unpredictable as sunspots. Experts have long preached that as long as you stick to your knitting and build value, it doesn't matter when you sell. But recently, there have been too many dollars chasing too few high-quality businesses to discount the timing. Entrepreneurs who sell now are getting better multiples than they ever have before.

<P>
Build a Foundation

<P>
Stark Brothers was not always well-positioned to sell. The company survived significant sales volatility in the 1980s. Then, the summer of 1993 brought the flood to end all floods, threatening to wipe out all of its nursery stock near the Mississippi in Atlas, Ill. ''It was down to the last levee,'' Walter Logan says. ''Our business would never have recovered. We did some real soul-searching after that.''

<P>
''My dad had charts that tracked sales levels and profitability for the past 70 years,'' says Clay Logan. ''None of us could figure out what caused the ups and downs. But it was clear that we needed to do some long-term planning.'' 

<P>
Fortunately, since the mid-1980s, Stark had been balancing its horticulture business by providing fulfillment services to direct-marketing companies. One of its longtime clients was the fast-growing Foster &amp; Gallagher, a family of 18 direct-marketing horticulture and gift companies. It had become Stark's largest single fulfillment customer and a major profit contributor. Its management saw a perfect fit between the two companies.

<P>
Foster &amp; Gallagher approached the Logans in the spring of 1994. They hired an investment adviser, then signed a letter of intent. The acquisition was completed within three months. ''We had received earlier offers,'' says Clay Logan, ''but the fit never seemed right. None met everyone's needs as well as the one from Foster &amp; Gallagher.'' 

<P>
Achieve Perfect Timing

<P>
How can you prepare for a successful sale?

<P>
* Stay in touch with business brokers and investment advisers who specialize in your industry. They can, and will, tell you who has recently paid what for a company not unlike yours.

<P>
* Hire an independent appraiser, savvy about your type of business, and get a valuation done on your company. This will get you well beyond whatever ''book value'' (generally described as retained earnings) figure you see on your balance sheet.

<P>
* Without announcing your intention to sell, stay close to your vendor partners, clients, and major customers. That helps reduce unpleasant surprises for both buyer and seller.

<P>
* Finally, be candid, perhaps as never before. ''One of the reasons this acquisition worked,'' says Walter Logan, ''is that Foster &amp; Gallagher gave us a very clear vision of how Stark Brothers would fit in their organization, and what changes seemed advisable -- in advance of our signing. Most of what they pointed out were things we already knew needed changing, and the acquisition simply accelerated those changes.''

<P>
Less than two years later, Stark Brothers has added three acres of greenhouses, hired 50 new employees, increased sales, and created an extraordinarily bright future. The Logans and the company's 300 jobs are still in Louisiana, Mo.

<P>
''My ancestors would not have taken the initiative to sell this company,'' says Clay Logan. ''To us, it was a clear business decision, a relationship with someone that we knew, had confidence in, and trusted. Something that was good for all stockholders, the community, and our staff. It was simply that right offer at the right time.'' a

<P>
M. John Storey is principal of Storey Communications of Pownal, Vt., and author of several entrepreneurial books.

	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<H5><BR><BR><A HREF="./11 TOC.html">NOVEMBER 1996</A> / <A HREF="../../info.html">INFORMATION</A> / <A HREF="../../index.html">HOME PAGE</A> / <A HREF="../../subinfo.html">SUBSCRIPTIONS</A></H5>
	</TD>
