<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>11MobileE</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0b1">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=1024 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	THE MOBILE ENTREPRENEUR<BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">Never Lose Touch</FONT>

<H3>Powerful On-the-Road Communications</H3>
<BR><BR><BR><BR><HR><BR>

<H3><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>TRAVEL TIPS</FONT></H3>

<STRONG>Check That Line</STRONG>


<P>
Trying to check your e-mail from the road can be hazardous to your fax/modem. Most hotels have digital lines with high voltage that will fry your fax/modem in two seconds flat. There are products that will help: PORT Inc. of Norwalk, Conn., has introduced an interface product called the Digital Telephone Enabler 250, which retails at $145. It provides a safe connection for your modem.
</P>


<STRONG>Protect Your Data</STRONG>


<P>
Never carry your laptop computer through the airport metal detector. Most owner's manuals will advise you that it's perfectly safe to send your laptop through the X-ray scanner, but the same isn't true for metal detectors. They can scramble your hard drive. 
</P>

	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
Streaking toward his office in Menlo Park, Calif., Paul Saffo, a director at the Institute for the Future, calls in to his PC's modem. His phone is automatically answered, and Saffo speaks one word: ''Wildfire.'' 

<P>
''I'm here,'' responds a soft female voice. With simple, spoken cues, Saffo orders his electronic assistant to play his messages, return several calls, and record notes. He never has to redial, jot down a note, or even take his eyes off the road. ''I do it all by talking to my Wildfire assistant,'' Saffo says. ''I can blow through all my messages in record time, and with a minimum of effort.''

<P>
It's Saffo's job to think about the future, tracking the technologies we will be using tomorrow. Once in a while, he gets lucky and finds tomorrow's technology available today. Such is the case with Wildfire, an electronic voice-messaging system designed for businesspeople who must remain connected to the office even while traveling around the world. Wildfire uses voice recognition to converse with you. It answers your phone, takes messages, responds to voice commands, and lets you leave automatic messages for certain callers. It recognizes the voices of those who have called before, greeting them with, ''Oh, hi!'' And if a call comes in while you are listening to messages, Wildfire will whisper in your ear to ask whether you want it to put the call through or take a message. 

<P>
Wildfire anticipates future electronic office systems by marrying several technologies -- telephone, database, PC contact manager, and voice recognition -- into a seamless whole.  

<P>
It's even an excellent way to beat the airline airphone racket.  Rather than pay as much as a flat $15 per call, you simply call Wildfire. It allows you to make and receive dozens of calls for the price of one, since you never hang up and redial.

<P>
Get Every Message

<P>
Wildfire represents the next generation of such services as follow-me numbers, available from phone service providers. These services do not require a PC link and can be the most cost-effective way to make sure you never miss a call. You are assigned a ''smart'' phone number; when it is called, the intelligent network finds you by running through a preprogrammed group of numbers: your office, cell phone, or home. As a last resort, the call will be forwarded to a voice-mail service. 

<P>
AT&amp;T's True Connections offers a follow-me 500 number in several different packages. The most expensive is $4.95 per month plus usage costs of 27 cents per minute at peak times (8:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m.), or 17 cents per minute at off-peak hours (5:00 p.m. to 8:00 a.m.). The charges are paid by the caller. 

<P>
MCI's One Number service is $4.95 per month and includes 30 minutes of calls.   

<P>
But none of these services pack the power of Wildfire. Bill Warner, founder of Wildfire Communications Inc. of Lexington, Mass., says, ''Wildfire is designed with the mobile entrepreneur in mind.''

<P>
AT&amp;T Wireless services and Packard Bell have jumped onto Wildfire's bandwagon, working to develop a network-based version that would be supplied to business users. 

<P>
When Wildfire first debuted, its cost was prohibitive. Today, a stand-alone Wildfire server can either be purchased directly from the company or ordered as a monthly service from service bureaus around the country, such as Overlook Communications International Corp. of Atlanta. Barry Thomas of Overlook says he offers packages starting at $99 per month for 400 Wildfire minutes. Extra minutes cost 22 cents each (which includes any long-distance charges).  

<P>
Users say Wildfire actually seems to have a personality. To experience firsthand what one user calls a ''Wildfire moment,'' call 1-800-WILDFIRE for a free demo. As Paul Saffo says, ''If you use it for a week, you're hooked forever. It'll change your life.'' a

<P>
Strategic adviser Jeffrey Kagan is founder and CEO of Atlanta-based Kagan Telecom Associates. He serves as industry analyst, columnist, speaker, and consultant to the telecommunications industry. You can e-mail him at jeff@jeffkagan.com.


	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
