<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	DIRECT SELLING / By Duncan Maxwell Anderson<BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">''Rocket Ship''</FONT>

<H3>New Vision Grows by Family Unity, High Technology</H3>
<BR><BR><BR><BR><HR><BR>

<H3><FONT COLOR=#CC000C><A NAME="2">WINNERS</A></FONT></H3>

<STRONG>Home-Based $300 Million</STRONG><BR>

Doris Christopher had a problem. She wanted to stay home and raise her two small daughters. But she also wanted to continue receiving the financial and intellectual rewards of her career. 

<P>
''That would have meant opening up a store in the morning and working who-knows-how-many hours per week,'' she recalls, ''or working in a nine-to-five corporation.'' A home economist, Christopher wanted to put her kitchen expertise to use. Her friends were always asking where she had bought the tools she used in her kitchen. She figured there was a huge demand for a company that provided good-quality kitchen tools and advice on how to use them. 

<P>
Her husband, Jay, kept suggesting she build a party-plan, direct-selling operation. ''But I didn't like the idea,'' she says. ''I thought home parties were a waste of time, that perhaps the products were overpriced. There wasn't a solid message of value. Finally, Jay said, 'You can make your home parties any way you want them to be!' ''

<P>
Start With $3,000. Stir Well

<P>
In 1980, the Christophers turned in a $3,000 life insurance policy and established The Pampered Chef. ''We created a kitchen show that was fun and educational, that sold kitchen tools and taught people how to use them,'' Christopher says. ''Our representatives don't stock inventory, and the initial investment is $100. Our message is that the products are consumer bound. We don't want people to be in the business of buying inventory.''

<P>
Christopher believes that philosophy helps Pampered Chef hang on to its distributors: ''We have a network of field managers to help people before we lose them. Our attrition rate is probably half the industry average.''

<P>
The Pampered Chef has sustained 16 years of growth. It has 550 employees serving a network of 30,000 distributors. This year, Christopher expects to top $300 million in revenues. ''A billion dollars isn't far in our future,'' she says. 

<P>
Today, Christopher's daughters are in their 20s, and her husband works in the business with her. ''Last week,'' she says, ''we had our national convention in Orlando, with 12,000 people, including children and spouses. All the boat captains and bus drivers commented on what well-behaved children we have. That's because these are families that really believe in what they're doing, that are connected to the mission of putting the family first. We think it shows.''

<P ALIGN="RIGHT">
-- Michael Warshaw
<BR><BR><HR><BR>
<H3><FONT COLOR=#CC000C><A NAME="1">RESOURCES</A></FONT></H3>

<STRONG>Covey and MLM</STRONG><BR>
EXTRA!! Stephen R. Covey, seminar superstar and author of The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People, will be the keynote speaker at the next annual meeting of the Direct Selling Association in Atlanta on May 19, 1997, at 9:00 a.m.
The number-one mistake in network marketing is ''wasting time on the wrong people,'' says Kim Klaver in her new audiotape, So . . . You Want to Be a Networker? Prevent downline dropouts by persuading your people to focus on the right people: the ones who are interested. (To obtain the tape, see p. 78.)
Network-marketing superstars such as Richard Brooke will tell their success secrets at the second Upline Magazine ''Masters' Seminar'' on October 26 and 27 at the Radisson Resort in Scottsdale, Ariz. Call 804-979-4427.

	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
New Vision International of Tempe, Ariz., is a family business. But you don't picture a mom-and-pop operation pulling in more than 100 million wholesale dollars in its second year. Family business isn't what it used to be. 

<P>
Brothers BK (Benson Keith) and Jason Boreyko wrote the first plan for New Vision in honor of their late mother, Dottie. Today, their father, Ben, and all the children -- BK, Jason, Karen, and Lynne, are partners in the company. Its use of old-fashioned personal relationships and high-leverage information technology make it the kind of corporation envisioned in John Naisbitt's Megatrends and Richard Poe's Wave 3. SUCCESS interviewed BK and Jason the high-tech, network-marketing way: on a three-way telephone call.

<P>
<STRONG>Why did you start New Vision?</STRONG>

<P>
BK: The company we were with cut off people's checks a little before Christmas 1994.

<P>
Jason: It went bankrupt.

<P>
BK: Our parents were the top distributors. With the six of us, there was $350,000 coming to the Boreyko family every month until that moment. Our downline leaders came to us and said, ''If you don't start something, we'll have to go somewhere else.''

<P>
Jason: But the odds against a start-up by distributors succeeding are 99 to 1. That's what the president of our old company told us.

<P>
<STRONG>What did you do?</STRONG>

<P>
Jason: We did the first plan for New Vision on a cocktail napkin in the back of a Southwest Airlines flight and started March 20, 1995, in Tulsa. Within six months, we were doing $500,000 per month. But it was too much for our fulfillment house. We had order-entry problems, mis-picked boxes. It was about to kill us. The president of our old company might have been right.

<P>
BK: We were about to sign a new lease. But one of our consultants was working with another company in Scottsdale that went Chapter 7 -- if we could move into its space, we could do our own fulfillment. We went into court, bid on the space, and got it. The racks were even in our colors.

<P>
Jason: If we'd signed the lease in Tulsa, we'd be out of business by now. But we moved and went from $500,000 to $1 million in two months. 

<P>
BK: That's why we tell each other that God has His hand on this company.

<P>
Jason: When we walk into some amazing opportunity, we say to each other, ''That is so 'God.' ''

<P>
<STRONG>How did you grow so fast right away?</STRONG>

<P>
Jason: Thirty percent of our sales is from our Essential Minerals liquid. The minerals have been depleted from our soil and our food, and your body can't manufacture them. When people hear the story, they say, ''Give me that product.'' New Vision sells a bottle of it every 10 seconds.

<P>
BK: It's also a tribute to my dad. We brought about 4,000 people from our other company to New Vision. They'd worked with him for 20 years. He always said, ''If you're not having fun, you're not doing it right.'' Network marketing is all about relationships. This is a volunteer sport. If people don't like you, they'll go to another company. We just had a $15 million month. 

<P>
<STRONG>That seems almost impossible.</STRONG>

<P>
BK: We keep it real simple. People don't want to sell. They want to be order takers at home. So we tell them to sit at home, mail tapes to a database, and wait for the phone to ring.

<P>
Jason: We have a tape that explains it, called I Hate to Sell, Don't Like Recruiting, but Wouldn't Mind Getting Rich in Networking. We have an arrangement with a list broker so our people can just call up and buy names. The person can sign up by a three-way telephone call. It costs $5.95.

<P>
<STRONG>It's an army of database marketers!</STRONG>

<P>
Jason: People ask how we're growing so fast, and we just say, ''We're blessed.''

<P>
BK: That's why I'm so excited about the Internet. We're launching a new program that lets distributors sign up, track orders, or track their genealogy by modem to our computer. No waiting on the phone. Next to each person's name is a 1, 2, or 3 -- that shows how many months since he ordered.

<P>
Jason: When we go international, people can call long-distance through their computers. The new PCs have video camera options. You could do your presentation over the Internet. And you don't have the rejection. You might lose your connection, but nobody's telling you no.

<P>
<STRONG>What are your plans?</STRONG>

<P>
BK: This thing is a rocket ship. When we started, Jason said, ''Let's set a goal of $8 million per month and 100,000 distributors by March 30, 1997.'' That's $100 million per year. I said, ''Man, are you crazy?'' We did it 11 months ahead of schedule. We just had a convention of 2,200 people in Vegas, and he stands up on the stage and says, ''We're going to do $1 billion by 2000 A.D. with one million members.''

<P>
Jason: ''Believe it and achieve it.''

<P>
BK: That's from Napoleon Hill. Neither of us went to college, but when we were kids, our father paid us $10 to read books like Think and Grow Rich and write a report. 

<P>
<STRONG>How are you going to get to $1 billion?</STRONG>

<P>
Jason: We're hiring a COO whose mind has been there. He's Bob Spacey, who runs a $1 billion division for Albertson's Inc. It was a direct consequence of Hill's ''Law of Attraction'': When you set a goal, it attracts the people to your life who will help you achieve it. 

<P>
<STRONG>How else are you preparing for growth?</STRONG>

<P>
Jason: We have a Big Five accounting firm audit our books -- Deloitte &amp; Touche. 

<P>
BK: Companies can clean up this industry by setting the example of high standards. There's been too much ego and too many charlatans. As my dad says: '' 'EGO' stands for 'Edge God Out.' ''

<P>
<STRONG>What's going to keep you out of trouble?</STRONG>

<P>
Jason: We decided that we won't make a big move without running it past the leaders. They're the marketers.

<P>
BK: We have a conference call every Friday morning. If you're open with them, and take the noes, the leaders become protective of the company. 

<P>
Jason: People in network marketing going from company to company are looking for a home. We never want to do another company.

<P>
BK: There is no Plan B. This is it.



	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

