<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>11WilsonHarrell</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0b1">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=1024 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	WILSON HARRELL <BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">Kill That Snake Now</FONT>

<H3>Figure Out Who Can Fire You. Then, Take Swift Action</H3>

	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P>
I have a friend and client, let's call him Joe, who, in seven years, went from one fast food store to more than 100, with profits that would choke a Wall Street analyst. Not since the signing of the Magna Carta has there been such a promising company. But Joe, the founder and biggest stockholder, got fired, and I want to tell you how, so it doesn't happen to you.

<P>
Two years ago, I visited Joe for the first time. I met all his management team. They were some of the greatest racehorses I'd ever met. After three days, I was convinced that Joe's company was an outstanding example of everything that's great about entrepreneurship. But as I delved into the company, I was alarmed to find that Joe did not have control. He and his management team owned less than 50 percent of the outstanding stock. Joe's brother, who was in the process of leaving the company, owned 32 percent; a group of private investors owned 20 percent. Now, I can add: 32 + 20 = 52 percent. But Joe wasn't worried in the least. After all, it was his brother and other close friends who had come in early and were rapturous about the company and its success. Even though Joe wasn't worried, I was. I'd been down the ''control'' path before. I kept asking Joe to add 32 to 20. He just kept shrugging his shoulders. 

<P>
As I reviewed Joe's personal objectives and his company's five-year plan, it seemed obvious that his company should go public in two or three years. But Joe's brother didn't want to wait that long. Neither did the 20 percent group. So, we agreed to pursue a strategy: 1) We'd find a venture capitalist (VC) to acquire all or part of the outsiders' stock. 2) Joe and his management group, through options and stock purchases, would control 51 percent of the company; the VC, 49 percent. 3) Joe would appoint a majority of the board. 4) The company would go public in two or three years, offering about 30 percent of the company. 

<P>
We interviewed more than 20 VC firms and culled them down to two contenders. Upward of $30 million was involved.

<P>
We got close, but in the end, Joe was unwilling to accept a couple of ''deal-breaker'' restrictions on management that the VCs demanded. Joe kept looking for other ways to finance the purchase of the outside stock, I kept worrying about 32 + 20. Joe told me to stop worrying; after all, we were dealing with family and friends. His racehorses were loyal to him alone. Without him and his team, the company would fall on its face.

<P>
Meanwhile, the financial soup had thickened. Before all the negotiating with VCs, none of the stockholders, including Joe, had a clear idea of the company's value. Now they did, and it was more than their wildest dreams. And the VCs were talking about cash on the barrel head -- right now. Overnight, everybody was rich. The only thing standing between them and their millions was Joe and his refusal to accept restrictions. So the 32 + 20 got together, called a special stockholders' meeting, appointed a new board -- and fired Joe. 

<P>
Were they wrong? Not really. Joe's brother had invested his life savings in the company. Now that he was out, he wanted to get on with his life. What about the 20 percent group -- did they do something wrong? I can't see how. They were investors. They'd been in for years and years, and now they wanted to sell at least half their holdings for the price the VCs were offering. What about Joe? Was he wrong to want to go on building the company as he had for seven years? He was now only a couple of years away from going public and making everyone very, very rich. Did it make sense to change his management style suddenly to satisfy a bunch of VCs? No way! Finally, what about the racehorses? Could they be blamed for being more loyal to the company, their jobs, and their families, than to Joe?

<P>
Each Morning at Dawn

<P>
Nobody was wrong. But there is a lesson here: 32 + 20 = CONTROL. As I always urge you to do, when you wake up in the morning, before coffee, think: Is there any way that any combination of stockholders could cause me to lose control? If there is, do not sleep again until you've killed that snake. 

<P>
Joe went out and found a banker who, together with him, bought 18 percent of the company. Joe is back as CEO -- but with the agreement that unless he takes the company public within the next nine months, he will join with the outside stockholders and put 100 percent of the company up for sale to the highest bidder.

<P>
Whatever happens, Joe will be very rich. But he's gone through a hell that he could have avoided if he had, from the beginning, worried about 32 + 20 = 52.

<P>
Never trust people who add up to more than 50 percent.
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<H5><BR><BR><A HREF="./11 TOC.html">NOVEMBER 1996</A> / <A HREF="../../info.html">INFORMATION</A> / <A HREF="../../index.html">HOME PAGE</A> / <A HREF="../../subinfo.html">SUBSCRIPTIONS</A></H5>
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

