<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>11ITEntrepreneur</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0b1">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=1024 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="2" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	Inside Track / Edited by Tom Stein <BR>THE ENTREPRENEUR<BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">Concentrating on the Cash-out</FONT>



	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

<P>
The only thing Faye Becker likes better than starting
a new business is selling it for millions. That's what she plans to do with
her latest venture -- an upscale Laundromat and dry-cleaning business called
Bubbles &amp; Bleach Coin Laundroplex LLC. 
</P>

<P>
Becker became an entrepreneur at the age of 18.
With just $27 in her pocket, she launched a computer programming school.
Two years later, she sold it to her main competitor for $325,000. 
</P>

Over the years, Becker has started and sold a variety
of businesses, from motels and restaurants to a high-end car wash. Her formula
is always the same: Whether it's a new or old concept, make it your own.
Now, the 50-year-old dynamo believes she's hit the jackpot with Bubbles
&amp; Bleach. 

''I went into a Laundromat for the first time in
1993,'' she says. ''It was filthy dirty, the equipment didn't work, and
I felt very unsafe.'' But Becker did notice one amazing thing -- the place
was packed. 

<P>
She hired a market research firm to investigate
whether all coin laundries were this poorly run. It turned out to be fairly
common, says Becker. Her idea was to create an amusement-park environment
where patrons could get a better-quality wash and have loads of fun, too.
</P>



<P>
With funding from a silent partner, she built her
first Bubbles &amp; Bleach Laundroplex in Milwaukee. Becker went wild with
the design. The $2 million facility includes 115 washers and dryers, dry-cleaning
service, exercise machines, juice and cappuccino bars, tanning equipment,
a big-screen TV, and a business center with fax and copy machines. Becker
instituted a singles night every Tuesday. The first couple to tie the knot
gets an all-expense-paid wedding at the Laundroplex. When that happens,
Becker is sure to garner national media attention. 
</P>


<P>
Today, she operates two Laundroplexes in the Milwaukee
area, with another under construction in Illinois. She also has nine express
drop-off centers and two dry-cleaning plants. Revenues for 1996 will exceed
$6 million. 
</P>

<P>
At last count, Becker says she has put 27 mom-and-pop
Laundromats out of business. She dominates 90 percent of the coin laundry
market in Milwaukee and is attracting new customers. ''Close to 75 percent
of our clients have a washer and dryer at home,'' she says. ''Here, they
can do their laundry faster and cheaper.'' 
</P>

<P>
Despite all the fun she is having, Becker is focused
on the final goal. ''The biggest thrill is taking your idea to fruition,
and then cashing out,'' she says. ''That's the climax for any entrepreneur.''
By the turn of the century, she predicts a big conglomerate will purchase
her company.
</P>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
