<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="5" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	INSIDE TRACK / GLOBAL MARKETS &amp; SCOPE <BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275">
	
<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

<H3>SUCCESS SCOPE</H3><BR>

<I>Cutting-edge concepts from business journals and newsletters</I><BR><BR>


<STRONG>Get in Your Customer's Face
</STRONG><BR>

Sales &amp; Marketing Management suggests these strategies for getting your salespeople where they should be -- namely, in front of customers: 

<P>
Create a process that takes pressure off salespeople to do tasks other than selling. A sales manager at an office-products company stopped using formal sales reports. ''Salespeople would make up information they thought managers wanted to hear,'' he says.

<P>
Train salespeople to conduct background research on customers before they make appointments. This will increase their efficiency on sales calls and give a buyer a good reason to meet with them. 

<P>
<STRONG>Successful
Acquisitions</STRONG><BR>


To grow as fast as possible, entrepreneurs like to gobble up other companies. While an acquisition strategy can make perfect sense on paper, the real challenge is integrating two separate companies. Industry Week offers these guidelines for ensuring a harmonious union: 

<P>
The product fit of the two companies must be complementary. 

<P>
There must be a good degree of chemistry between the two management teams. 

<P>
There must be both a short- and long-term win/win scenario for people, customers, and investors. 

<P>
The companies should be in close geographical proximity.

<P>
<STRONG>Win on the Web</STRONG><BR>


You've just invested in a Web site for your business. Now you want to know who's coming and what they're saying about you. The Internet Business Journal offers the following tips for measuring the effectiveness of your marketing campaign in cyberspace:

<P>
Make the most of the data you gather. Most servers have software in place to track Web visitations. Analyst software packages can take this information and easily convert it into graphs, charts, and tables that can help you identify trends and determine the effectiveness of online advertising.

<P>
Monitor areas of public opinion, such as listserv and usenet discussion groups. These places let you follow what people are saying about you and your product. The Alta Vista search engine at <A HREF="http://www.altavista.digital.com/">http://www.altavista.digital.com/</A> allows you to track the most recent usenet discussions by using keyword searches. 
	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="275">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">High Returns</FONT>

<H3><P>On Low-Income Housing
</P></H3>


<P>
Most visitors to Algeria are put off by the country's crumbling infra-<BR>
structure and political turmoil. Not Mickey Nocera. To him, the third- world nation represents unlimited opportunity.

<P>
Nocera first went to Algeria six years ago to scout real-estate deals. He was surprised to learn that in a country with a severe housing shortage, buildings never seemed to get completed. ''I saw a lot of aborted apartment buildings and unfinished housing projects,'' says Nocera.

<P>
In 1991, he teamed up with George Henderson, a former financier, to provide quality, affordable lodgings to some of the world's poorest nations. ''The world needs more than 500 million homes,'' says Nocera. ''We figured if we captured a fraction of that market, we'd have a substantial business.''

<P>
The two men formed Chadwick International Inc. of Fairfax, Va. The company manufactures modular homes and ships them to such countries as Algeria, Benin, and the Ivory Coast. They have agents in more than 40 countries and are close to signing contracts in the Philippines and Vietnam.

<P>
A key to Chadwick's success is its comprehensive financing program. It arranges five-year financing from international banks, and the deals are then underwritten by the U.S. Export-Import Bank. ''This way, we know whom we're working with and when we'll get paid,'' says Nocera.

<P>
Customers run the gamut from foreign government agencies to private entrepreneurs. Homes cost from $20,000 to $130,000, and the average purchase order is $10 million. Revenues for 1996 should reach $130 million.

<P>
Chadwick's first $20 million contract took four years of negotiating and relationship building to complete. ''We spent more time learning local customs than conducting business,'' says Nocera. ''To be successful in other countries, you can't be a carpetbagger. You need to create jobs.'' Chadwick's modular homes are assembled by up to 500 local workers. The homes come complete with air-conditioning, wiring, and heating systems.

<P>
Patience and perseverance have gone a long way for Chadwick. ''We've experienced earthquakes and bombings during construction,'' says Henderson. ''But we just stuck with it. We needed to build trust and credibility.''



	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<H5><BR><BR><A HREF="./11 TOC.html">NOVEMBER 1996</A> / <A HREF="../../info.html">INFORMATION</A> / <A HREF="../../index.html">HOME PAGE</A> / <A HREF="../../subinfo.html">SUBSCRIPTIONS</A></H5>
	</TD>
</TR>
