<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>11NewCEO2</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="1" CELLSPACING="5" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	TheTechnology Edge Edited by Kristin Dunlap Godsey<BR><BR><BR>THE NEW CEO
	</TD>
	
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2">
	
<FONT SIZE="+5">From Ribs to Riches</FONT> 

<H3>Go High-Tech Without Losing the Personal Touch
</FONT></H3>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<BR><BR><BR><P ALIGN=RIGHT><STRONG>Bulletin Board</STRONG><BR>Create Your Own Surveys
</FONT></P>

<P>Want to know what your customers think of you?
If you do any kind of survey work, there's a software package that puts
it all together. Apian Software of Menlo Park, Calif., has upgraded its
Survey Pro program to make it easier for business owners to gather information.
</FONT></P>

<P>Survey Pro 2.0 helps you design questionnaires,
enter survey answers into a database, analyze the information, and create
reports of your findings. It's a complete redesign of the original DOS product.
Survey Pro 2.0 is Windows based, so what you see -- as you're laying out
surveys and reports -- is what you get. New features include a spell checker
for all phases of the survey and better statistical analysis functions.
</FONT></P>

<P>Survey Pro 2.0 costs $795 and comes with a 120-page
guide of tips for getting your surveys right the first time. </FONT></P>

<P>Never Miss a Call </FONT></P>

<P>To stay accessible for clients and associates,
you can't go wrong with a pager. But if you still have to call your machine
or voice mail for other messages, that accessibility is obviously not complete.
Casio PHONEMATE of Torrance, Calif., seeks to bridge that gap with its new
TP-340 model, a digital answering machine that pages you immediately after
messages are left. </FONT></P>

<P>The TP-340 automatically programs your pager number
into the phone with its ''Pager Learn'' function. You can then set the answering
machine to page you every time someone leaves a message. If you prefer,
you can program the machine to page you only if the caller hits the pound
key after his message. </FONT></P>

<P>The new model also allows people from your office
or home to page you directly from the answering machine itself. One touch
of a button pages you from the unit with a ''777'' code, letting you know
the call's coming from your desk. The TP-340 includes a full-featured telephone
and retails for $149. </FONT></P>

<P>Super-Sharp <BR>
Graphics </FONT></P>

<P>Video graphics have come a long way, but you might
not know it if you have an older, low-resolution monitor. Panasonic's computer
peripheral division in Secaucus, N.J., now has a 17-inch monitor that's
designed to make the very most of your computer applications. </FONT></P>

<P>The P17 PanaSync/Pro has a maximum resolution of
1,600 X 1,280 and an ultra-fine dot pitch of 0.25mm. Designers, engineers,
or anyone else who works with video or CAD programs will best appreciate
the sharpness of this high-end monitor. Priced at $899, the P17 comes with
a three-year limited warranty. 

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	
<P>The Chicago rib joint Carson's raked in $18 million
last year with its homemade recipes and sit-down-and-stay-awhile ambience.
The last thing its owners wanted to do was turn it into a bland, robotic
clone of fast food. It's a challenge many growing companies will face: How
do you tap the benefits of high-tech tools to improve the business without
sacrificing a down-home identity? </P>

<P>Donna Giannis and her brothers Chris and Dean Carson
have grown their father's legacy from its one site 20 years ago to six Chicago-area
locations and one in Florida (where Dean, 39, now lives). They include carryout
stores at each restaurant for businesspeople who need a quick lunch or folks
who'd rather picnic at home. And they've kept up with the times in </P>

<P>terms of automation -- without forsaking quality
or atmosphere. </P>

<P>Giannis, at 43 the eldest of the trio, has kept
her technological priorities in line. ''The key to all this technology is
to not let it interfere with the customer,'' she says. </P>

<P>The Skokie, Ill.-based Carson's improves its efficiency
with a program called FactslinkPro from VF-Link Inc. of Evanston, Ill. ($1,495).
The restaurant relies on the program's fax-back and auto-attendant functions
in particular. One central phone number for all Carson's locations is shown
during the restaurant's TV ads, through which customers can place carryout
orders. Technical director Norman Skul uses the IBM operating system OS/2
to run the whole shebang on a Compaq 486/33 with 24 megabytes of RAM. While
many would consider this an out-of-date system, Skul says it's perfect for
Carson's needs. It can handle 12 simultaneous calls and uses two fax/ modems
to send out menus to customers at the same time.</P>

<P>Carson's brought brochure-making and ad creation
in-house as well, with Adobe Systems's PageMaker and Corel Corp.'s CorelDraw
software, which save a lot of money in ad agency costs. Skul is also networking
everyone's computer on an NT server for back-end accounting, inventory,
and other bookkeeping functions. Experts were hired to create customized
software applications tailored to the business. </P>

<P>Carson's even has a new Web site (www.ribs.com),
which functions as a free marketing and advertising tool. Eventually, it
will be able to take out-of-state orders in real time. Skul had Sportster
ISDN modems from US Robotics in Skokie, Ill., installed for speedy Internet
access ($299 each). Giannis also hopes to use the site to boost the educational
system in her community: Carson's will sponsor an Internet-based essay contest
for kids from kindergarten age to 12th grade. </FONT></P>

<P>Drawing the Line </FONT></P>

<P>But Giannis knows when to say when. ''Everything
having to do with customers getting food -- like order-taking -- happens
the old-fashioned way,''she says. She explains how aggressive vendors are
always trying to sell her systems that cost $50,000 per site and ensure
that food is delivered exactly 18 minutes after the order. But what if the
customer wants to relax and have a drink first? </FONT></P>

<P>''Forget that,'' Giannis says of the pricey systems.
''I never want our customers to hear 'I can't take your order, the computer
just went down.' '' </FONT></P>

<P>Carson's has built its automated back office for
about $40,000 over a five-year period. Giannis's ability to keep in mind
what she wants -- and avoid getting talked into more than she needs -- has
clearly served her well. </FONT></P>

<P>But she warns that the key to becoming master over
technology before it enslaves your business is hiring someone with technical
proficiency. ''You're running a business and don't have time to think of
all this,'' she says. ''What the computer age means, above all else, is
that you need an MIS person on staff.''  </FONT><P ALIGN=RIGHT>-- Rivka Tadjer </FONT></P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550"><BR><BR>
