<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	TheTechnology Edge Edited by Kristin Dunlap Godsey<BR>TECHNOLOGY AT WORK BY FRANK HERTZ<BR><BR>
	</TD>
	
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+5">The Best Business CD-ROMs </FONT> 

<H3>Programs That Cover
The Entrepreneurial Spectrum 
</FONT></H3>
	</TD>
</TR>
 

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<BR><BR>
<P><STRONG>Neighborhood ConnX</STRONG> </P>

<P><STRONG>And Business ConnX</STRONG> </P>

<P>In the business world, little fish that want to
play in the big pond better be well equipped to do research and marketing
before diving in. That's what Lee Sommie does. Before reaching out to new
customers, this independent writer, producer, and multimedia artist from
Orlando, Fla., checks in with Neighborhood ConnX and Business ConnX. These
CD-ROMs from Serious Business Software of Tampa, Fla., provide business
owners with demographic and business information for potential clients.
</P>

<P>''It's the first thing I use when I want to attract
new business,'' Sommie says. ''The fact that you're actually getting real
information from reliable sources goes a long way in determining my marketing
efforts.'' </P>

<P>Business ConnX crams the power of the TRW Business
Credit Database into its features list, which proves to be the most useful
information the software provides. You will thrive or fail depending on
the payment practices of your clients; Business ConnX lets you find out
instantly who your most reliable customers will be, before you spend the
marketing dollars to reach them. </P>

<P>When Sommie wants to expand his reach, he uses
Neighborhood ConnX to define a geographic region and find demographic information.
''I simply draw a circle around an area on a map,'' Sommie says. The software
tells him the number of consumers in that area who meet his criteria, then
gives profiles of the individuals. Sommie switches to Business ConnX to
help him narrow his search with business credit reports. </P>

<P>Business ConnX isn't cheap, though. The software
program costs about $200, but you also get charged each time you print or
export data from the TRW database. After you've used up the $50 ''complimentary
usage credit,'' it costs about 10 cents per name. Still, you get to narrow
your search to meet your exact criteria, which can save hundreds of dollars
in the long run. </P>

<P>Sommie especially likes the scalability of the
software. With Business ConnX and Neighborhood ConnX, Sommie can either
widen his client base nationally, or he can obtain detailed information
on his own geographic location. </P>

<P> Neighborhood ConnX and Business ConnX. Price:
$189.95 each. Requirements: 386 or better, 4MB of RAM (8MB recommended),
2MB of hard-disk space, CD-ROM drive, Windows 3.1 or better. </P>

<STRONG>Lifetime Encyclopedia of Letters 1.0 </STRONG> <BR>

<P>In the days of pagers, e-mail, faxing, and the
Internet, sitting down and writing a letter may be a lost art. For most
businesses, though, letter writing is still an essential form of communication
-- one that is often mishandled, even by the most senior executives. ''It's
tough to sit down and start from scratch,'' says Kurt Gebauer, a product
manager for BestWare Inc., a software company in Rockaway, N.J. Gebauer
isn't afraid to ask for help, which he usually gets from Lifetime Encyclopedia
of Letters 1.0 from Streetwise Software Inc. </P>

<P>Streetwise Software, based in Santa Monica, Calif.,
has put 850 ready-to-edit model letters in this CD-ROM to increase the effectiveness
of any type of written communication. Lifetime Encyclopedia of Letters shows
users how to craft a letter that praises a top salesperson, asks for a refund,
collects on a past-due invoice, or closes a contract. </P>

<P>Gebauer finds himself having to write so many different
kinds of letters in his job that he needs Lifetime Encyclopedia of Letters
to help him stay focused. He'll take bits and pieces of a particular letter
template, then customize the letter for a personal touch. </P>

<P>Lifetime also teaches users better communication
skills. A step-by-step tutorial proves useful in helping you understand
how to get your point across succinctly and clearly. In one of its best
examples, Lifetime shows you how to say no, yet still make a valiant attempt
at reaching an agreement on a contract. </P>

<P>''Sometimes you go into a situation where you feel
you'll need a bit of help to get your point across,'' Gebauer says. With
Lifetime, ''you've got a really good tool to help you get focused.'' </P>

<P> Lifetime Encyclopedia of Letters 1.0. Price:
$59.95. Requirements: 386 or better, 8MB of RAM, CD-ROM drive, Windows 3.1
or better. </P>

<STRONG>Small Business Start-Up</STRONG> <BR>

<P>When starting a new business, the textbooks don't
have all the answers. Right away, you're faced with questions: How will
I do marketing? What about hiring people and setting salaries? Will my cash
flow forecast actually work? Will I have time for public relations? </P>

<P>An expert to turn to for advice would be a big
help. And that's what you get with Small Business Start-Up from Adams Media
Corp. of Holbrook, Mass. </P>

<P>Hannah Gleisser, president of Datagroup Inc. in
Cleveland, needs this kind of advice as she continues to develop her business.
Her new company helps other businesses relocate their employees' families.
Says Gleisser, ''We often need to reevaluate the big picture.'' </P>

<P>Gleisser uses Small Business Start-Up as a ''navigator,''
to make sure she's taking the steps she needs to ensure success for her
business. For example, she consults with the CD-ROM before she implements
a marketing decision to check whether she's getting the most for her money.
</P>

<P>Indeed, Small Business Start-Up provides myriad
help for any small-business owner. When hiring new employees, Small Business
Start-Up can help you find out which interview questions will ferret out
the information you need. More than 700 multimedia clips, including 50 videos
and animations, detail every pitfall that a new business on the block can
encounter. Interactive charts are detailed but not overbearing, and narrated
slide shows can walk a user through, say, a business plan creation with
clarity and at any pace. </P>

<P>Gleisser often pulls up Small Business Start-Up
late at night: ''You know, just when I'm finishing up for the day.'' It
takes her mind away from nitty-gritty details and into a broader business
perspective. ''That's very hard to do when you're running the business day
to day,'' she says. </P>

<P> Small Business Start-Up. Price: $39.95. PC requirements:
386 or better (486 recommended), 4MB of RAM, 2MB of hard-disk space, 2X
CD-ROM drive, Windows 3.1 or better, audio card and speakers. Mac requirements:
4MB of RAM, 2X CD-ROM drive, System 7.0 or better. </P>

<STRONG>ClassAct 4.0 for Office 95 Pro</STRONG><BR>

<P>Software training can be a big productivity (and
bank account) drain for any company. Imagine, though, finding a personal
trainer for each employee, available on call, who's knowledgeable on just
about any software program. </P>

<P>It's not just a pipe dream, thanks to ClassAct
CD-ROM training software from Soft-One Corp. of Orem, Utah. The series is
perhaps the most comprehensive software training tool available today. </P>

<P>Cherlyn Bruns, an administrative assistant for
Midland-Grau's Heavy Duty Systems division in Kansas City, Mo., was in charge
of finding training software for employees who had just switched over to
the Windows operating system. </P>

<P>''We wanted to see if they really needed face-to-face
training,'' Bruns says. ''ClassAct was the best of the systems we tried.''
</P>

<P>Bruns had tried using video-based training, but
when she found that employees were spending just as much time stopping and
starting the VCR as they were learning, she stumbled upon ClassAct and gave
it a whirl. </P>

<P>''People got a lot out of it,'' she says. ''You
can go at your own pace, and you can always use it as a reference or manual.''
ClassAct can be set up to function as a guide while you're working in an
application. Users simply click over to the software, and it brings up a
help screen on their topic. </P>

<P>ClassAct 4.0 for Office Pro 95 includes training
for Microsoft Word, PowerPoint, Excel, and Access. The product gets kudos
for its detailed interactivity, including accurate simulation of the software
and simple navigational tools. It can be even more valuable with ClassAct
Trac, which tracks employee training and evaluations. </P>

<P> Class Act 4.0 for Office 95 Pro. Price: $349.95.
Requirements: 486 DX2/66 or better (Pentium P5-60 recommended), 8MB of RAM
(16MB for Windows NT), 4MB of hard-disk space, 2X CD-ROM drive, Windows
3.1 or better, 16-bit sound card and speakers recommended. </P>

<STRONG>Day-Timer Organizer 2.1</STRONG><BR>

<P>Filmmakers are notorious for keeping lousy schedules.
As a result, Michael Broomfield, a consultant to independent filmmakers,
has to keep an especially good one. As president of Broomfield Associates
in New York City, he uses Day-Timer, a personal information manager from
Day-Timer Technologies of San Mateo, Calif. It helps him keep up with his
clients as they hop from coast to coast or scene to scene. </P>

<P>''It's very versatile,'' Broomfield says. ''I can
input entries in any part of the program and then search on anything I want.
I can always find what I'm looking for.'' </P>

<P>If Broomfield needs to schedule an appointment
with someone, he enters in the first few letters of the client's name, and
a record pops up instantly. The file includes all the contact information,
as well as a detailed phone log. Broomfield can check on his last conversation
with the client, then have Day-Timer dial the phone automatically. </P>

<P>Even more practical is the ability to check the
log against a monthly phone bill. You can then allocate the phone calls
in your bill to your client, or allocate costs over an entire project. ''I
would never write down my calls with a pencil and paper, nor would I type
them into a word processing or spreadsheet program,'' Broomfield says. ''But
now it's done automatically.'' </P>

<P>Day-Timer 2.1 includes new Internet and e-mail
functions that allow users to access a Web site or address an e-mail with
a single mouse click. The program simply launches your Internet browser
or e-mail program when you click on a URL or e-mail address in the contact
information screen. ''It's a very intuitive program,'' Broomfield says.
</P>

<P> Day-Timer Organizer 2.1. Price: $79.95 for the
CD-ROM version, $59.95 for disk. PC requirements: 386 or better, 4MB of
RAM (8MB recommended), 2X CD-ROM drive, Windows 3.1 or better. Mac requirements:
Performa or better, 4MB of RAM, System 7.0 or better. </P>

<STRONG>The Right Site </STRONG><BR>

<P>When David Stuart makes a presentation to county
representatives, he can't pontificate about demographics without having
some real numbers to back him up. Stuart's company, MAP Systems Inc., is
an economic development, marketing, and consulting firm in Raleigh, N.C.
Like many businesses, it thrives on numbers. </P>

<P>Stuart uses The Right Site from Easy Analytic Software
Inc. of Fresh Meadows, N.Y., to ''completely amaze officials of economic
development who represent different geographic regions,'' he says. ''The
product lets me pinpoint the strengths and weaknesses of each county, so
that these officials can focus on developing those weaknesses and solidifying
the strengths.'' </P>

<P>Other businesses can certainly gain from the CD-ROM's
476 traditional U.S. Census demographic variables. These include population
figures, median age, median income, and education level. The Right Site
can actually tell you which geographic areas will potentially add the most
revenue to your coffers. Simply enter the variables that define your target
market, and The Right Site finds and ranks the regions that best meet those
criteria. </P>

<P>The Right Site also includes its own parameters
for companies looking to relocate. For example, a business can do a complete
analysis of the regions that it is considering. The Right Site can report
on quality of life, crime, weather, and the labor forces that are available
for the company's industry. </P>

<P>''It's extremely beneficial for a company to compare
its current location to a proposed one in every way,'' Stuart says. ''The
Right Site is very comprehensive in all data categories.''  </P>

<P> The Right Site. Price: $99.95. Requirements:
386 or better, 4MB of RAM, 2X CD-ROM drive, Windows 3.1 or better. </P>

<P>Frank Hertz is a freelance writer based in Brighton,
Mass. He can be reached at 74774. 1160@compuserve.com. </FONT></P></TD>
</TR>
