<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	TheTechnology Edge Edited by Kristin Dunlap Godsey<BR>CYBERFORUM / BY CAROLINE FARMER <BR><BR><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="200">
	<FONT SIZE="+6">Take Your Catalog Online</FONT>

<H3>A Paper Company Goes Paperless in
Cyberspace</H3>

<BR><BR><BR>

<H3 ALIGN=right>SPECSHEET </H3>

<P> WEBCATALOG 1.6. Price: $695. Requirements: Macintosh
or Windows NT-based Web servers, 2MB of RAM (4MB to 6MB recommended), 2MB
of hard-disk space.


	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="350">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P>The idea of a Web business -- the ultimate paperless
environment -- for buying and selling paper undoubtedly sparked a few snickers.
But as Matthew Steele explains, &quot;We realized that there wasn't anything
like a real trading floor online for our industry, and the Web seemed like
an ideal place for that.&quot; Now vice president of systems development
for The Paper Site (<A HREF="http://www.papersite.com">http://www.papersite.com</A>), Steele sees the Web as the
perfect venue for presenting details about paper size, color, and quantity.
</P>

<P>Created by a San Francisco brokerage firm called
Presidio Paper Co., The Paper Site was built using WebCatalog, a database
and catalog publishing application from Pacific Coast Software of San Diego.
The software lets customers set their own parameters to search the database
for products, then ranks the search results. WebCatalog tracks customers
as they move through the site. Customers -- in this case, fine paper merchants,
brokers, printers, converters, and mills -- are even provided with a &quot;scrapbook&quot;
for collecting items they like in the catalog. </P>

<P>Any company can take its mail-order catalog and
convert it to an electronic version for the Web, complete with photos, using
WebCatalog. The Paper Site is interactive, and the presentation is modified
based on user input. For example, if a customer places a bid on an item
or buys it, the system contacts the owner of that item. The system then
modifies the item on the screen, so that when other customers inquire about
it, they'll see that it has been bid on or purchased. The system responds
to user requests and updates the inventories in real time. </P>

<P>Sophisticated Searches </P>

<P>WebCatalog uses custom Hyper Text Markup Language
(HTML) tags to create search pages. This means that your catalog's search
forms can be highly detailed or quite simple. The software also detects
which Web browser a customer is using and displays information in a format
that is best viewed by that browser. So you can present results in tables
to users whose browsers support tables, or just lists of results to other
users. </P>

<P>Several features of WebCatalog made it compelling
for Steele. For one thing, he says, &quot;our searches are complex, and
it turns back really fast search times.&quot; WebCatalog also offers flexibility
in the types of searches that a user can define. </P>

<P>The stand-alone database was another benefit. &quot;Everything
is built into it,&quot; Steele says. &quot;Other products I looked at needed
to interface with a separate database.&quot; WebCatalog is easy to configure,
and applications can be quickly developed, implemented, and deployed, he
adds. </P>

<P>WebCatalog also has a number of security features,
including password protection for adding, editing, and deleting records.
At The Paper Site, members (vendors who pay $100 to $250 per month to have
their products listed) have access codes so they can update their inventories.
Members also can give certain customers access codes so that they'll be
privy to special items. Steele says that members that have national sales
forces can use WebCatalog's security features to share specific data with
salespeople, creating a sort of intranet accessible from anywhere. </P>

<P>When a Paper Site customer is ready to buy, the
system creates a purchase order and then sends an e-mail to the inventory's
owner. The final aspects of the sale are done off-line, Steele says, because
of the size of the transactions -- a minimum of 40,000 pounds of paper.
However, WebCatalog can do online transaction processing for users with
smaller needs. </P>

<P>The Paper Site has helped its members gain a global
audience, since many of its customers are from Asia and Europe. &quot;There
are definitely people out there using it as a business tool,&quot; Steele
says. The site averages a thousand hits per day. </P>

<P>The Paper Site is developing other revenue-generating
functions, such as customized sites for members. It is also using WebCatalog
to create an automated system by which, if a customer has a standing preference
for a product, the system automatically searches for that preference. </P>

<P>Steele believes that The Paper Site and its WebCatalog
setup have broader implications. &quot;Any industry with a distribution
chain that involves brokers, distributors, importers, and manufacturers
could use this model,&quot; he says.  </P>

<P>Caroline Farmer is a San Francisco-based freelance
writer. Contact her at carfarm@aol.com. </P>


	</TD>
</TR>
