<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10Eye</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE=+4>The Entrepreneurial Eye </FONT><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">WASHINGTON WATCH</FONT> </P>

<FONT SIZE="+2">A New Pact With Russia</FONT>

<P>The Small Business Administration (SBA) wants to help you crack the Russian
market. It has signed an agreement with its counterpart agency in Russia
to provide much-needed contacts and assistance to American firms. <BR>
<BR>
''You just can't open a storefront in Russia like you can here,'' says the
SBA's Eileen Cassidy. ''It's a challenge just to install a phone line.''
<BR>
<BR>
As part of the agreement, the Russians will set up a liaison office that
will connect U.S. companies with local distributors and help with such issues
as finding property and solving tax problems. <BR>
<BR>
The SBA also hopes to stimulate the growth of Russian small businesses by
encouraging local banks to lend them money. ''Now, these companies can borrow
only from the government or the mob,'' says Cassidy. ''Once they get the
loans they need, they will be able to buy U.S. goods and services.'' <BR>
<BR>
The SBA is planning its first trade mission to Russia. ''The only way to
do business in Russia is to go there in person,'' says Marylou Foley, the
founder of a Washington, D.C.-based travel company who will join the mission.
She expects the SBA initiative will substantially boost commerce between
the two countries. <BR>
<BR>
''In one year, we want to increase by 25 to 30 percent the number of American
businesses in Russia,'' says Cassidy. <BR>
	</TD>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">SURVEY</FONT> <BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">Create Your Own Dream Team </FONT><BR>
<BR>
Entrepreneurs create millions of jobs a year. But they can't always find
qualified workers to fill them. <BR>
<BR>
According to a recent survey, nearly a quarter of CEOs believe the lack
of skilled workers is a major threat to their growth and continued survival.
<BR>
<BR>
But entrepreneurs aren't moaning. They are dealing with the shortage of
qualified labor by implementing various strategies such as job sharing and
flextime and enlisting experienced retirees to fill important part-time
positions. <BR>
<BR>
To retain key employees, more than half of the nearly 1,000 survey respondents
said they reward workers with bonuses and other performance-linked incentives.
In addition, 23 percent share profits with employees to keep them satisfied.
<BR>
<BR>
The survey was conducted by Arthur Andersen's Enterprise Group and the Washington,
D.C.-based National Small Business United (NSBU). <BR>
<BR>
Ken Heller of NSBU says compensation is important, but it is not the only
factor in keeping quality workers. He recommends that entrepreneurs involve
employees in the decision-making process. <BR>
<BR>
Among those who complained about unqualified workers, 88 percent plan to
invest in training programs. On average, business owners will spend 3 percent
of their revenues on employee training next year. <BR>
	</TD>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">IPO UPDATE</FONT> <BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">An Intoxicating Offering </FONT><BR>
<BR>
Ninety companies went public in June, according to Securities Data Company
of Newark. The median amount raised was $37 million; total proceeds topped
$5.5 billion. Spotlight: Michigan Brewery Inc. of Gaylord, Mich. <BR>
<BR>
Description: A microbrewery and steakhouse. <BR>
<BR>
1996 First-Quarter Revenues: $890,000. <BR>
<BR>
Amount raised: $12.25 million. <BR>
<BR>
''Though we had a net loss of $1 million our first year, we sold investors
on our long-term potential,'' says Bill Rolinski, CEO of Michigan Brewery
Inc. ''Microbreweries are a fast-growing sector. We'll use the money to
expand rapidly throughout the Midwest. <BR>
<BR>
''Private investors didn't think we had enough years under our belt,'' he
says. ''But we didn't want to wait and risk somebody else moving into the
metropolitan areas we were targeting. Institutional investors were more
attuned to our growth strategies. <BR>
<BR>
''I would advise anyone going public to hire a good law firm and check out
its references,'' says Rolinski. ''That means asking for its last three
IPOs. Call the CEOs of those companies and say, 'I'm thinking of using this
law firm, would you use it again?' ''
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
