<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>10CreativeFinancing</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">CREATIVE FINANCING</FONT> </P>

<center>By Carol Steinberg</center><BR><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Friends or Foes?</FONT>
<H3>Forge a Win-Win Relationship With Venture Capitalists </H3></CENTER>




By 1994, David Blundin had blown through $150,000 developing his pattern
recognition software. He needed a fresh source of cash, and venture capitalists
seemed a natural choice. They were falling all over themselves to fund high-tech
companies. When one VC showed serious interest, Blundin laid out a smorgasbord
of potential applications of his product, such as voice recognition and
Internet services. <BR>
<BR>
But Blundin quickly discovered that venture capital wasn't the answer. The
VC firm offered the 29-year-old MIT graduate $600,000 for a 30 percent equity
stake, with the option to seize majority ownership for $1 million. More
troubling than the low valuation, the VC firm insisted that Blundin target
only one niche. Blundin would not cede his broad vision for his company,
Cirrus Recognition Systems Inc. of Reading, Mass. Instead, he struck a $200,000
licensing deal with a software firm. <BR>
<BR>
Flooded by investment opportunities, venture capitalists clearly have the
upper hand. In 1995, VCs disbursed a near-record $3.859 billion to 1,128
companies, according to Boston-based Venture Economics. At first blush,
venture capitalists can seem like your best friend, dispensing the desperately
needed funds to grow your business. But before you know it, they can also
seize control of your company and leave you high and dry. At their best,
though, VCs supply the needed expertise, contacts, and cash to take your
company to the next level. <BR>
<BR>
When entering into negotiations with a venture capitalist, the first step
is to determine your company's worth. A CEO's perceived value of his company
can be worlds apart from a venture capitalist's. Notes Dennis Costello of
Advent International Inc., a Boston venture capital firm: ''Each time a
company progresses, it will get a higher valuation. So if you're worried
only about dilution, the later you wait for venture capital, the better.''
<BR>
<BR>
Next, determine how much equity you're willing to give up. Most venture
capitalists don't want majority interest. ''Generally, we don't want to
demotivate the entrepreneur,'' says Susanne Harrison of Poly Ventures, Farmingdale,
N.Y. Start-up businesses are riskier propositions. New entrepreneurs must
be prepared to give up more ownership. <BR>
<BR>
Be prepared for intense scrutiny and intervention. Even with minority positions,
VCs traditionally gain a board seat. Their preferred stock gives them veto
power over, say, mergers and public offerings. They might be empowered to
change management if a company misses performance thresholds. <BR>
<BR>
A Value-Added Relationship <BR>
<BR>
Venture capitalists can add much more than cash to your company. According
to Rich Kalenka of the Jericho, N.Y., office of Price Waterhouse LLP, a
venture capital-backed company has greater chance of success. ''The company
has been professionalized at an early stage,'' he says. And venture capital
financing is a calling card for subsequent rounds. <BR>
<BR>
In 1994, Michael Levy started SportsLine USA Inc., an online sports service
in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. After rejections from 50 venture capitalists, he
obtained $2 million privately. In May 1995, Levy teamed up with Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &amp; Byers, a premier high-tech VC firm in Menlo Park,
Calif. Levy gave up roughly 30 percent equity for $3 million. The cash allowed
him to launch his service. <BR>
<BR>
By December, SportsLine needed more money. Kleiner Perkins loaned Levy $1.5
million without strings. Levy, 49, has received advice on expansion, key
management, and media alliances. ''It's not like they're breathing down
on me,'' Levy says. ''Most of the advice I get, I ask for.'' Kleiner Perkins
recently held a conference for CEOs of its Internet-related companies. Levy
hopes to develop alliances with some. SportsLine, which will do $2.5 million
in revenues this year, plans to go public in 1997. <BR>
<BR>
Typically, venture capitalists strive to recoup 5 to 10 times their investment
in three to five years via an IPO or merger/acquisition. Their relationship
with top-notch investment bankers can ease the IPO process for entrepreneurs.
Some companies seek venture capital just before going public. Blundin of
Cirrus expects to do just that. Even though his first experience didn't
pan out, ''We're always talking to venture capitalists,'' he says.  <BR>
<BR>
Contributing writer Carol Steinberg specializes in finance and fast-growing
businesses. <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.2 -437838. -->
