  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10BooksandTapes</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">REVIEWS: BOOKS AND TAPES/Edited By Duncan Maxwell Anderson

	</TD></TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2">
	<BR><FONT SIZE="+6">Reach New Heights</FONT><BR>
<H4>Don't Fear Danger -- Exploit It: Lessons From Intel's CEO </H4><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
	

<P><FONT COLOR="#000000"><FONT SIZE="+3">BOOKS</FONT> </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN=LEFT><B>Only the Paranoid Survive,</B> <BR>
by Andrew S. Grove.<BR>
<BR>
One day recently, Andy Grove, president and CEO of Intel Corp., learned
that doom had arrived for his $10 billion company: A television crew from
CNN was on its way to do a piece announcing that hundreds of thousands of
Intel's Pentium processors had been sold with a flaw. </P>

<P>In Grove's book, Only the Paranoid Survive, he calls this moment a ''strategic
inflection point'' -- when the life of a business turns toward new heights
or oblivion. He realized his scrappy company was now an institution. Not
knowing what it would cost, he offered to replace any customer's chips,
which wound up costing $475 million. Intel prospered -- operating in a new
way. <BR>
<BR>
No amount of formal planning can anticipate the changes we'll be called
upon to make one day: Banks were revolutionized with the advent of ATMs.
<BR>
<BR>
Grove says the only defense is to stay in touch: with past and present customers,
with low-level employees, and with analysts and journalists. Look for early
warnings -- and exploit the unexpected. </P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>-- Michael Warshaw </P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P ALIGN=LEFT><B>Payback</B>, <BR>
by Daniel Fischel.</P>

<P>What do Federal Express, Turner Broadcasting, and MCI have in common?
Two things: 1) They exploded to success in the 1980s; 2) They got their
growth capital from &quot;junk&quot; bonds, invented by Michael Milken,
who went to jail for his actions. <BR>
<BR>
According to Daniel Fischel, author of Payback, Milken is innocent: He got
rich by helping other entrepreneurs grow. He was railroaded into jail by
the corporate competitors he humiliated and their friends and allies in
government and the media. Fischel, a professor of law and business at the
University of Chicago Law School, has been a consultant to most of the agencies
he says framed Milken. In a real-life horror-thriller, Fischel describes
how ambitious regulators -- led by prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani (now Mayor
of New York) -- used tainted testimony, destroyed innocent third parties
who refused to help them, and turned standard financial practices into crimes
in order to get their man. Fischel's conclusion: The regulators need regulating.
<BR>
</P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P ALIGN=LEFT><B>Best Boss, Worst Boss,</B> <BR>
by Jim Miller.</P>

<P>''We call her the warden,'' an employee writes of her boss. ''She locks
up the coffee, soap, paper towels, and toilet paper. Wages have been frozen
for three years.'' <BR>
<BR>
Best Boss, Worst Boss by Jim Miller is a collection of real letters people
wrote to him about their bosses. Do you inspire loyalty and achievement
-- or are your people resentful timeservers? <BR>
<BR>
''My boss forced me to take elderly residents in our rest home on an outing,
knowing the bus had a severe mechanical problem,'' writes an employee. ''We
got stranded on the highway in 90-degree heat. His reaction was, ''These
people are 80 years old. What are their lives worth, anyway?' '' <BR>
<BR>
If you show that you understand employees, you'll inspire them: ''During
a family emergency, my boss told me to leave at once. He said, 'When you
get to Heaven, God won't ask you what you did for the corporation. He'll
ask you what you did for your family.' '' </P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>-- MW </P>

	<TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<P><FONT SIZE="+3"COLOR="#000000">TAPES</FONT> </P>

<P ALIGN=LEFT><B>Multiple Streams of Income,</B> <BR>
by Robert G. Allen.</P>

<P>Founding a $100 million company wasn't good enough for financial guru
Robert Allen, author of the best-sellers Nothing Down and Creating Wealth.
Companies and jobs are too vulnerable to weather the 10 recessions you'll
see in your lifetime; Allen says to protect yourself by designing ''multiple
streams of income'' that come to you automatically. Some sources: <BR>
<BR>
Network marketing -- ''the wave of the future,'' according to Allen. You
get a commission on products or services you sell, and on the sales of those
you recruit as distributors -- and on their recruits. . . . Once built,
the organization generates cash. <BR>
<BR>
Offer specialized books, tapes, CD-ROMs, and seminars through the Internet.
Buy and sell discounted mortgages for a profit. They pay you over time with
no money down. Or buy tax-lien certificates -- you pay other people's delinquent
tax bills. The government pays you back with huge interest.
	
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
 
