<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10Franchising1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">FRANCHISING / By Carol Steinberg</FONT><BR><HR>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>


	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT SIZE="+4">The Next Generation</FONT>
<H3>Create a Winning Plan for Family Succession </H3>
	</TD>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="20%">
	<IMG SRC="fran.gif" ALIGN=left WIDTH="180" HEIGHT="180" BORDER="0">
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD></TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="20%">
	<FONT SIZE="-2">David Langsam Photographed by Mark Katzman</FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<BR><BR>
<P>Sig Langsam's employment franchise was stuck in the Dark Ages. There
were no computers, no fax machines, not even a copier. The owner of a Snelling
Personnel Services Inc. franchise, Langsam believed in doing business the
old-fashioned way. </P>

<P>But Langsam's son, David, saw untapped potential in his father's business.
In 1987, he chucked his job as an accountant and, despite his father's resistance,
joined the family firm. Six years later, he bought it. He quickly set about
automating the franchise and adding staff. For the first time, he advertised
heavily in the Yellow Pages. The year after David took over, revenues soared
40 percent. He had to fight his father for every change, but the battles
were worth it. Today, the Langsams' franchise is Snelling's 11th-highest
performer. Before, its best rank was 35th. </P>

<P>More than 80 percent of all businesses are family owned, according to
The Family Business Center at Loyola University. They are undergoing the
largest transfer of ownership from one generation to another in the nation's
history. Most of today's family businesses were started after World War
II, and astonishingly, fewer than half have written plans for transferring
the business. </P>

<P>Passing the torch to the next generation can be a professional and emotional
roller coaster. Experts estimate that one-third of all companies that survive
10 years make it to the second generation. Probably one-third of those make
it to the third generation. Here are some steps to ensure a successful transfer.
</P>

<P> Build credibility. Joseph Astrachan, Ph.D., teaches entrepreneurship
and management at Kennesaw State University in Kennesaw, Ga. He says that
three factors contribute to a successful family business: a strategic plan,
a board of directors that includes outsiders, and frequent family meetings.
A smooth succession is a natural outgrowth of the three. </P>

<P>Work experience outside the family firm is another important success
component. It allows second generation franchisees to prove their worth
to employees and to gain a broader perspective. Then, when you join the
family business, Astrachan says, you can take on more responsibility and
risk upsetting your parent with business decisions. ''If you make bad decisions,
you're not CEO material,'' he says. ''If you make a bunch of good decisions,
it's easier because the organization looks to follow you anyway.'' </P>

<P> Transfer knowledge from generation to generation. In 1969, Greg Chirrick's
grandfather opened a Taco John's restaurant in Billings, Mont. When his
grandfather died, Greg's mom and dad relocated to Montana to run the Mexican
restaurant. By 1987, Margaret and Terry Chirrick had opened three more thriving
units. </P>

<P>Greg worked at the restaurants in high school, but neither he nor his
older brother, Rick, wanted in. Then, in May 1994, Greg's dad became gravely
ill with cancer. It was d&eacute;j&agrave; vu. But this time Greg, who is
now 27, felt obligated to step in and help. ''When the business fell into
my lap, and I saw the opportunity, I wanted it,'' he says. </P>

<P>Greg would run the restaurants all day, and then go home and ask his
ailing dad for advice about everything from the best way to spend co-op
marketing dollars to improving traffic and customer relations. In June 1994,
Terry died, leaving Margaret as president and CEO and Greg as director of
operations. </P>

<P>''My father taught me more in two months than a father can teach in a
lifetime,'' says the third-generation franchisee. At his bank's advice,
Greg attended classes on succession. He's continued a remodeling effort
for his four restaurants. Last November, he fulfilled his father's plan
to open a fifth Taco John's. It cost $700,000 to build and should hit $750,000
in sales year one -- the highest among the Chirricks' five units. Systemwide
sales total about $3 million. </P>

<P> Allow for breathing space. Squabbling siblings can ruin a perfectly
good family business. You have to build into your company a mechanism for
resolving conflict. In the most successful family enterprises, each family
member has clearly defined roles and areas of authority. </P>

<P>Fred Jones opened a One Hour Martinizing Dry Cleaning in Madera, Calif.,
in 1968. By 1981, three of his five children had come on board; the other
two are absentee owners. Today, the family-run firm, Team Enterprises Inc.,
has 26 stores in California and Arizona. </P>

<P>Team Enterprises works largely because everyone keeps his distance --
literally and figuratively. Tom runs the Fresno office. Eric manages the
eight-store Modesto region two hours away. Their sister, Melinda Hayes,
oversees four stores in Arizona. ''We each have control over our own business,
so we're happier and more productive,'' notes Eric. </P>

<P>At first, Fred gave the children ''possibly too much supervision.'' He
gave them more freedom as they learned to make their own decisions. About
10 years ago, Tom met some resistance when he wanted to computerize the
operation. He convinced Fred of the benefits of inventory control and customer
database management. When his dad's interest level was piqued, he went forward.
</P>

<P>''I let them learn from their mistakes . . . I wasn't over their shoulder
all the time,'' says the 74-year-old chairman. </P>

<P> Choose the right successor. It's difficult for an entrepreneur to face
his own mortality. But failure to do so can have devastating consequences
for heirs, employees, and the community at large. Many family members have
been forced to sell their business to cover huge estate taxes after the
founder's death. </P>

<P>A few years ago, Fred Jones was at a crossroads. He wanted to diminish
his role in the business, but he hadn't yet named a successor. ''If he were
to pass away and we were all still involved, there would be too big a possibility
of conflict,'' son Tom says. </P>

<P>When it comes to succession planning, experts advise siblings to pick
successors -- without parental guidance. Ideally, siblings should work out
the pecking order or get input from an outside board of advisers and company
employees. </P>

<P>Fred didn't follow this rule of thumb. For many months, he mulled over
the issue of succession. He evaluated each child's strengths. In 1993, he
named Tom president. Tom's strong suit was his good business sense and CPA
experience. Employees respected him; he'd earned their trust. And he had
stepped up to the decision-making plate. </P>

<P>But Tom, 42, is also a middle child. Several factors helped keep any
animosity in check. First, each of the siblings had migrated to a position
he felt comfortable with. Second, says Fred, the other siblings ''became
aware that Tom was headed in that direction (of president) early in the
game, so it wasn't a shock to them.'' Finally, Melinda, 49, and Eric, 47,
joined the executive committee so they could get more involved. </P>

<P>According to a survey by MassMutual Life Insurance Co. of Springfield,
Mass., successful family businesses are more likely to use voting in decision
making. </P>

<P> Separate work and family. Team Enterprises's executive committee meets
four times a year to go over the company's financial health and review management
decisions. At first, the meetings were tied to family functions. But the
Joneses found that any feather-ruffling interfered with their ability to
all get along afterward. </P>

<P>They initially gathered around the family's dining room table. ''We'd
put on our employee hats, and then at 6:00 p.m., we'd set the table and
we were the children,'' Melinda recalls. She insisted that the group choose
a neutral location for business meetings. </P>

<P>Melinda works hard at ''trying to keep business, business'' with other
little things as well. She introduces her dad as Fred or Mr. Jones in business.
And when she calls the family on family affairs, she uses her personal line.
For business, she taps the company credit card. </P>

<P> Know how to pass the baton. Typically, franchisors must approve intergenerational
transfers. Successors usually must meet a company's current policy on qualifications,
explains Eric H. Karp, an attorney for the American Franchisee Association.
''It's a moving target. You can't plan in advance.'' </P>

<P>McDonald's Corp. of Oak Brook, Ill., for one, does not consider blood
to be an advantage. It offers no guarantee to family members. Like any new
franchisee, they must meet its rigorous standards and training. ''It's not
a pass-through or autopilot,'' says spokesman Walt Riker. </P>

<P>Robert Purvin, president of The American Association of Franchisees and
Dealers, says the franchisor should be able to determine the competence
of new franchisees. But he cautions that franchisors should not use the
opportunity to charge another franchise fee or to block the transfer so
it can buy back the franchise. </P>

<P> Create common goals. David Langsam, now 41, entered his family's employment
franchise with a five-year plan. He wanted to build a niche by becoming
the premier provider of accounting and office service professionals. He
learned every aspect of the business before moving into management. Says
his father, ''He took off like a ball of fire.'' </P>

<P>The road was bumpy, however. David and Sig collided on major issues,
such as updating the office and marketing. David wanted capital expenditures
for personnel and advertisements, and a transition strategy. Esther Langsam,
his mother, works at the office as a sales consultant, and David often asked
her to intervene. </P>

<P>''It was his way or the highway,'' David recalls of his father. ''I was
the new kid on the block.'' </P>

<P>In addition, David couldn't pin his dad down on a definite transition
date. As a result, his five-year plan dragged into a sixth year. It's usually
much more urgent for the second generation to accelerate the process and
keep their eyes on the goal. </P>

<P>''I felt if I kept producing, he'd have no other alternative,'' David
says. </P>

<P>Sig Langsam, now 74, sees how his son's entrepreneurial initiative has
energized his Snelling Personnel Services franchise. He formally transferred
the business to his son in 1993. This year's sales should hit $740,000.
 </P>

<P>SUCCESS contributing writer Carol Steinberg has been covering franchise
businesses for national publications for a dozen years.
	</TD>

<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="20%"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><HR>
