<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10CanThisBiz</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=center VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">CAN THIS BUSINESS BE FRANCHISED? / By Katherine Callan<BR><HR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD></Td>
	<TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+4">Totally Wireless</FONT>
<H3>Our panel of experts examines a business <BR>to determine its franchise potential.</H3><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="40%"><BR><BR><BR><BR><HR>
<FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="#CC000C">Panel Of Experts</FONT>

<FONT SIZE COLOR="#CC000C"><P>Robert E. Kushell, president of Kushell Associates Franchise Advisors
Worldwide Inc., a Pittsboro, N.C.-based firm that advises entrepreneurial
companies on developing franchise programs. <BR>
<BR>
Stephen Spinelli Jr., a cofounder of Jiffy Lube International Inc. and franchise
and entrepreneurship professor at Babson College in Wellesley, Mass. <BR>
<BR>
Anthony Vidergauz, president and CEO of California Closets, a 116-unit chain
based in San Francisco. <BR>
<BR>
By phone, fax, and e-mail, all the experts expressed enthusiasm for the
concept of Totally Wireless and the proven profitability of its five stores.
<BR>
<BR>
''Merrill has put together a business that makes a lot of sense,'' says
Anthony Vidergauz. ''He's done well in a competitive industry.'' <BR>
<BR>
''When I look at deals, I take a basic approach,'' says Stephen Spinelli.
''Is there a real economic opportunity? It appears there may be.'' The ability
to serve a network of stores from centralized suppliers is critical for
this franchise's success, he says. <BR>
<BR>
The experts cheered the fact that Merrill has already demonstrated a flexibility
to change with the demands of the marketplace. If he can continue to do
this, he'll have a greater chance at success. The young entrepreneur has
spent four years learning about the wireless industry: how to sell and what
to sell. He's successfully duplicated his stores several times. Also in
Merrill's favor: an accomplished board of advisers to help him achieve his
business goals. <BR>
<BR>
While acknowledging the many factors in Totally Wireless's favor, the experts
encourage Merrill to examine several aspects of his strategy. The first
is his expansion plan. <BR>
<BR>
Using a conversion strategy, Merrill will identify successful independent
dealers of wireless products and get them to convert to his franchise system.
The experts aren't certain that converting existing retailers is the best
way to go -- at least initially. <BR>
<BR>
It's tough to ask people to forget what they've already done. ''The most
difficult sale is the conversion sale,'' says Robert Kushell. ''Merrill
wants franchisees who are highly programmable and who will follow the system
like a recipe book.'' <BR>
<BR>
''If you have a good solid business operator, that's more important than
someone who knows the industry,'' says Vidergauz. ''When we started California
Closets, we thought that carpenter types would make the best franchisees.
But they weren't necessarily good businesspeople.'' <BR>
<BR>
Kushell suggests that Merrill first sell a few single units. If the units
meet cash-flow and profit projections, then Merrill has a basis for pursuing
conversions. He's proven his concept will work in the hands of others. <BR>
<BR>
If Merrill does pursue a conversion plan, he must also perform extensive
interviews to uncover people's ability to embrace a new system. Kushell
advises having all prospective franchisees work in a Totally Wireless store
for several days to get a practical feel for running the franchise. <BR>
<BR>
Area development deals offer several major advantages, including quick market
coverage with lots of cash coming in. The big con is loss of control. Franchise
units are successful because the people running them own the units and have
a vested interest in moving the product. Spinelli believes when you sell
area development agreements, you lose some of that direct contact at the
store level. <BR>
<BR>
Totally Wireless will require franchisees and salespeople to have much more
sophisticated product knowledge than, say, Boston Market does. With a process-oriented
franchise like Boston Market, Spinelli notes, ''if I get you in the door,
I've done most of my marketing job. There's a line of people who perform
services.'' A customer walking into Totally Wireless may have lots of questions
about technological trends and product capabilities. That's a huge marketing
job. A customer walking into Boston Market just wants a piece of chicken.
<BR>
<BR>
Training is critical to the success of Totally Wireless, but with an area
developer agreement, whom do you train -- and at what cost? ''Obviously,
area developers and store managers must go through the program, but what
if, after nine months, the store manager leaves?'' Spinelli asks. ''You
have to fill in with an untrained manager. That's where the system can break
down.'' <BR>
<BR>
The experts would like to see Merrill beef up his management team. His board
of advisers is impressive, but now it's time to assemble the team who will
be on the front line making things happen. <BR>
<BR>
Spinelli is also concerned about whether Merrill has done enough to lock
out the competition. <BR>
<BR>
''If Totally Wireless is as successful as Merrill believes it will be, then
can Absolutely Wireless be far behind?'' Spinelli asks, adding that there
is an advantage to being a leader. ''He has in his favor four years of truly
understanding market demand.'' <BR>
<BR>
''The biggest thing to understand is that if he franchises, Merrill is entering
a new business,'' says Vidergauz. ''You can't lose sight of the partnership
aspect of franchising. Merrill's sole desire must be to make franchisees
as successful as they can be. He will provide the value, training, marketing,
and operational support. In the best scenario, they should feel happy to
pay him because of the value they're getting in return.'' <BR>
<BR>

Senior editor Katherine Callan reports on leading franchise businesses.</FONT>
<BR>
<BR>
If you know of a business you would like examined, we will send you an analysis
form. Write: Can This Business Be Franchised? Katherine Callan, SUCCESS,
230 Park Ave., New York, NY 10169. 

	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	

<B>Founder:</B> Michael Merrill. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Concept:</B> Retail stores that carry wireless products such as cellular
phones, pagers, wireless modems, and wireless Internet services. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Number of Existing Stores:</B> Five. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Average 1996 Sales Per Store:</B> $650,000. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Year Founded: </B>1988. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Headquarters:</B> San Jose, Calif. <BR>
<BR>



	
<FONT SIZE="+1">
Michael Merrill is never far from reach. When he doesn't have his Apple
Powerbook fired up at his desk, he's online with his Ricochet Wireless modem.
While standing in line or stepping off an airplane, he can retrieve e-mail
from his Motorola Envoy Wireless Communicator or conduct business on his
Motorola digital phone. For shorter messages, he uses his SkyTel two-way
pager.</FONT> <BR>
<BR>
Merrill is betting that a lot of other people will want to be connected
using wireless communication devices. Two years ago, he opened his first
Totally Wireless retail store; now he has five profitable locations, and
he wants to become a national retail chain. <BR>
<BR>
It took a while for Merrill to identify this precise opportunity. Just before
the cellular phone craze first hit, the young West Point graduate launched
a moderately successful company called Skyway Cellular to sell several major
brands as well as fax machines. Soon, large retailers began selling phones,
and fax machines became ubiquitous. Merrill realized the real pot of gold
was new wireless products, especially those that transmit data over the
air. <BR>
<BR>
''The cellular industry is enjoying phenomenal growth,'' says the 34-year-old
entrepreneur. ''It's growing at 30 percent to 50 percent per year. The breakup
of AT&amp;T created different carriers, but there are no national retail
players today. There's nothing like a Blockbuster Video.'' <BR>
<BR>
Merrill will use Blockbuster Video's business model to expand. He wants
to sell area developers the rights to open stores in different regions.
<BR>
<BR>
''We're looking for home-run locations,'' he explains. ''We have no interest
in being tucked away in a strip mall. We need to be front and center, with
excellent signage.'' When he opens his next company-owned units in Seattle,
he plans to locate next to the hot concepts Noah's Bagels, Starbucks, and
Boston Market. <BR>
<BR>
He has a broad customer base. Teenagers buy pagers. Tech-savvy engineers
from Silicon Valley want the latest sophisticated electronics. <BR>
<BR>
But there's a lot of competition. Every Wiz and Circuit City in America
carries cellular phones and pagers, and there are many small players that
specialize in these products. Totally Wireless stands apart from the rest
by providing broader product selection than the small retailers, and the
same competitive prices -- but better service -- than the giants. ''Wireless
products aren't Circuit City's main interest,'' says Merrill. ''They are
mine.'' <BR>
<BR>
Clearly, Totally Wireless salespeople must know the product intricacies
in this fast-moving market. All employees go through Wireless University
-- a four-week training program that teaches them about business basics,
product features, customers, and sales techniques. Vendors teach different
electives. The more training that employees receive, the higher their commissions.
Merrill plans to centralize support in a hub-type operation as he rolls
out his concept. <BR>
<BR>
The cost of a new store will be about $175,000 -- $125,000 for the capital
expenses and another $50,000 to cover operating expenses. The first franchisees
will be experienced tech-product retailers who convert to the Totally Wireless
system. For the second tier of franchisees, Merrill wants well-financed
people with a solid business track record and education. <BR>
<BR>
To help him grow, Merrill has secured George Naddaff, one of the founders
of Boston Chicken (now Boston Market), on his board of advisers. Diane de
Stefano, who wrote the business plan for Boston Chicken, will serve as a
strategic consultant. Franchise attorney Andrew Sherman will help create
a Uniform Franchise Offering Circular, the legal document required for selling
franchises. 
	</TD></TR>


</TABLE>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
