<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>10WilsonHarrell</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">WILSON HARRELL</FONT> </P>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Move to the Future</FONT>
<H3>Entrepreneurs Are Migrating to America's Small Towns -- and Loving It</H3></CENTER>





The explosion called the entrepreneurial movement is creating changes in
America almost beyond comprehension. For example, at this moment there is
a massive migration of entrepreneurs away from large cities and their suburbs,
back to small towns and villages. They are abandoning overpriced, crime-infested
metroplexes like fleas from a dying dog. <BR>
<BR>
Simply stated, in this age of rapid communication, entrepreneurs do not
need or want anything big cities have to offer, with one exception -- airports.
So any town, however small, that is within reasonable driving distance of
a major airport will become a new home for entrepreneurs. Let me give you
an example: <BR>
<BR>
My friend John invited my wife, Charlene, and me to spend a weekend with
him and his wife ''near Washington, D.C.,'' as he put it. John picked us
up at Washington National Airport and began driving and talking about his
company. I was so interested that I paid no attention to his driving. <BR>
<BR>
But after an hour, I looked up and asked, ''Where are we going?'' <BR>
<BR>
His answer was, ''We're almost there.'' After another hour of driving, I
realized he had overstated the case. Finally, we came to a small, historic
Virginia village. ''We're here,'' he announced. ''Let me give you a quick
tour.'' The town had one red light, so it didn't take long. But as John
was pointing out the various historic sites, I noticed he was continually
waving to people as we passed. I jokingly asked, ''Are you running for office?''
<BR>
<BR>
About two miles out of town, we turned into a winding road that ended in
front of a typical Southern mansion with four white columns. It was beautiful,
though obviously in disrepair. John explained, ''I just bought this house,
with 50 acres of land. Renovations should take about three months.'' <BR>
<BR>
I could not resist asking, ''What did it cost?'' <BR>
<BR>
John gave an entrepreneurial grin and said, ''Just over $500,000, which
is a little less than what I got for my house in Washington.'' We walked
his 50 acres while he unfolded his vision. ''The horse stable will be right
over there. The dog kennel, over there. My putting green, just behind the
house.'' The only people more excited than John were his wife and two children.
<BR>
<BR>
On our way back into the little town, I said, ''It's a great place, but
I sure don't envy you the commute to Washington.'' <BR>
<BR>
John smiled and said, ''My commute will soon be about four minutes, because
we're at our new executive office and manufacturing facility right now.''
John gave me a tour of the site, soon to be built. ''Wilson, every member
of my executive team is getting out of that disaster called Washington and
moving his family out here. All our employees are being invited to do the
same, but for those who don't come, we'll train local people as replacements.''
<BR>
<BR>
The town fathers had been extremely eager to entice John's company to move
there and become its number-one employer. By the time he finished telling
me the deal he had cut and the unbelievable savings in overhead, I could
only wonder: ''Why wouldn't any reasonable company owner and father do exactly
as John is doing? Why would he allow his children to be bused to some gang-ridden,
drug-dealing school where the objective isn't learning, but solving social
problems that have no solution?'' I'm talking about Washington, D.C., and
every big city in this land. And I'm talking about most suburbs, which are
being invaded by the same forces that destroyed the cities. <BR>
<BR>
A Better Way <BR>
<BR>
As entrepreneurs lead America back to its small-town roots, life is getting
better for the people who live there and the people who move there. Entrepreneurs,
as new community leaders, are invoking their sacred beliefs: that bigger
is not better; that individuals are responsible for their own lives; that
the education of children is the responsibility of parents and teachers,
not politicians; that ''affirmative action'' should mean rewarding the worthy.
<BR>
<BR>
I know I'm going to hear from a lot of well-intentioned people who will
tell me that entrepreneurs should stay and help change the system, not run
away from it. But to do that, the entrepreneurs of America would have to
become politicians. By the time the cities were turned around, our retired
grandchildren would be panhandling. No, I think entrepreneurs have found
a better way: Go where it's fresh, out where rednecks and gentlefolks still
believe that ''family values'' are an assumed way of life, not a political
slogan. <BR>
<BR>
Long live the revolution.  <BR>
<BR>
Note to Readers: For the second consecutive year, Wilson Harrell has garnered
top honors from the American Society of Business Press Editors for this
regular column on entrepreneurship. Congratulations, Wilson! <BR>
<BR>
To obtain For Entrepreneurs Only, see page 82. <BR>
<BR>
Wilson Harrell is a consultant and speaker to the entrepreneurial market
and the author of the book For Entrepreneurs Only. To reach Harrell, fax
him at 770-889-4030. <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.2 -437838. -->
