<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10ITEntrep</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" WIDTH="100%">

<TR>

	
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">INSIDE TRACK/THE ENTREPRENEUR
	</TD>
	
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="ent.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH="199" HEIGHT="130"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3">PORTRATE OF A TYCOON</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1"></FONT>
	</TD>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<P>As a young boy, Christian Riese Lassen knew he would one day become a
famous artist. But he never dreamed that by the age of 40, he'd also be
running a $30 million business. </P>

<P>Today, Lassen is one of the world's leading environmental artists. His
paintings, which feature dazzling seascapes and vibrant colors, sell for
$100,000 apiece. His company, Las Vegas-based Lassen International Inc.,
produces posters, T-shirts, and other products based on the original artwork.
Lassen has also set up a lucrative licensing arm. His trademark images are
splashed on more than 400 products, from water bottles to watches. </P>

<P>Growing up in Lahaina, Hawaii, Lassen decorated his friends' surfboards
with far-out designs. By the age of 17, his work was in Hawaii's top gallery.
But Lassen was unhappy with the way his paintings were marketed. ''I always
pushed the gallery to give me the best wall space, but I met with a lot
of resistance,'' he recalls. ''They were dealing with Picassos and Chagalls,
and I was just a surfer kid.'' </P>

<P>Lassen came away from the experience determined to gain control over
how his work was sold. In 1982, he scrounged together $1,000 and made his
first limited-edition poster collection. A Japanese distributor bought the
whole lot. From then on, ''everything I painted, I printed,'' he says. ''It
makes more sense to create limited editions that end up in the hands of
5,000 people, not just one person. '' </P>

<P>Lassen realized he could extend his notoriety through licensing. At first,
he attended licensing shows to showcase his talent and sign up partners.
Now the big names come to him. He has inked deals with major players such
as Disney, Panasonic, and card company American Greetings. ''Licensing can
be big business for artists, if they choose to pursue it,'' he says. </P>

<P>While most artists scorn the unsavory world of commerce, Lassen embraces
it. He typically spends half the day painting and the other half conducting
business. Sometimes, he does both at the same time. ''While I paint, I'm
often on the phone negotiating a licensing deal or discussing a new gallery,''
he says. </P>

<P>Lassen currently employs 150 people. The company operates seven art galleries
that sell Lassen originals and the works of other environmental artists.
His goal is to form a stable of best-selling artists and become the biggest
art distributor in the United States and Japan, where he is already wildly
popular. </P>

<P>''For both artists and entrepreneurs, a blank canvas represents opportunity,''
he says. ''You need unbelievable tenacity and a strong sense of completion
to turn your vision into reality.'' 
	</TD>
<BR>
</TABLE>

