<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10ITScope</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=center VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">INSIDE TRACK / SUCCESS Scope</FONT><BR><HR><FONT SIZE="+4">Cutting-edge concepts <BR>from business journals and newsletters</FONT><BR>

	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
	<H2>Productivity Booster</H2>
<BR>
Most companies are skeptical about basic skills training, according to the
Harvard Business Review. Managers think that hourly employees should have
skills already or should get them on their own. But companies that equip
employees with basic reading, writing, and arithmetic skills that pertain
directly to the job benefit from increased productivity, better morale,
and reduced absenteeism. ''If the job requires employees to add and subtract
pounds and ounces on shipping forms,'' says the journal, ''then the training
should focus on teaching those math skills.'' <BR>
<IMG SRC="scp1.gif" ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH="142" HEIGHT="199" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-2">Illustrations By Scott Matthews</FONT>
	</TD>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="scp.gif" ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="124" BORDER="0"><BR><BR>
<H2>Hot Marketing Tips</H2>

To secure lifelong customers, follow these low-cost, easy-to-implement marketing
ideas from Small Business Success. <BR>
<BR>
 Wow every customer. Ticket City of Austin, Tex., doesn't sell just ''tickets,''
but the ''best seats'' available. After every event, staffers call customers
to say, ''I want to make sure you had a fantastic time.'' <BR>
<BR>
 Keep narrowing your niche. Successful companies focus on narrowly defined
groups. Compile a comprehensive list of your prospects and customers. Then,
narrow the list to a profitable group that you can serve better than the
competition. By identifying the traits of your niche market, you can customize
your products, services, and advertising. <BR>
<BR>

 Constantly educate customers. When callers to your company are placed
on hold, play an audiotape that can answer callers' questions and even inform
them of products and services they need but didn't know you offered. 
	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<H2>Win on the Web</H2><BR>

You've just invested in a Web site for your business. Now you want to know
who's coming and what they're saying about your company. The Internet Business
Journal offers the following tips for measuring the effectiveness of your
marketing campaign in cyberspace. <BR>
<BR>
 Identify your audience. Collect basic demographic information from visitors
by using questionnaires. Request that they fill them out before they get
what they are looking for or before they exit the site. <BR>
<BR>
 Make the most of the data you gather. Most servers have software in place
to track web visitations. Analyst software packages can take this information
and easily convert it into graphs, charts, and tables that can help you
identify trends and determine the effectiveness of online advertising. <BR>
<BR>
 Monitor areas of public opinion such as listserv and usenet discussion
groups. These places let you follow what people are saying about you and
your product. The Alta Vista search engine at <A HREF="http://www.altavista.digital.com/">http://www.altavista.digital.com/</A>
allows you to track the most recent usenet discussions based on keyword
searches.
	</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
