<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>10ITTrend</TITLE></HEAD>



<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">INSIDE TRACK</FONT> </Center></P>

<center>Trend Setter</center><BR><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Executives for Rent</FONT>

<P>
The founder of a struggling plastics firm in Kansas City needed an experienced COO to turn his company around. He couldn't afford to hire someone full-time, so he called on Dinte Resources Inc., a leading executive search firm that provides executives on a temporary basis. The new COO returned the firm to profitability before stepping down less than a year later. 

<P>
The ''executive-for-rent'' concept has gained momentum in a business culture obsessed with downsizing and reengineering. About 10 years ago, Paul Dinte, a former management consultant from Australia, was among the first to capitalize on the trend. While working for Peat Marwick, a large consulting firm, Dinte was given a tough assignment. He had no idea how to accomplish it. 

<P>
''I thought, 'Wouldn't it be great if companies really could wave a magic wand and bring in the expertise they needed for a specific project,' '' he says.

<P>
In 1987, he got the chance to test the idea while working at a traditional executive search firm. The Wall Street crash had sent shock waves through the Australian economy. Within six months, Dinte found temporary assignments for 27 top-notch CFOs. He moved to America to introduce his concept to a broader market. 

<P>
In 1993, he formed Dinte Resources Inc. of McLean, Va., with $30,000 in savings. The start-up capital paid for an office and a telephone, which Dinte primarily used for cold-calling. His idea struck a chord in the American marketplace.

<P>
''The whole concept that you join a company and stay for 35 years was decimated at the end of the '80s,'' says Dinte. ''There is a younger generation of executives that is bred on accountability and responsibility. They'd rather invest in their own expertise than in the bricks and mortars of a corporation.''

<P>
Companies can ''test-drive'' executives before hiring them permanently. Nearly half of Dinte's interim workers go on to take full-time jobs. 

<P>
Today, Dinte's clients range from entrepreneurial start-ups to corporate titans. Assignments typically last from three months to one year, and recruits earn an average annual salary of $100,000. Dinte, who takes a set percentage of an executive's weekly or monthly salary, expects to generate $3.5 million in sales this year. He is now one of a handful of entrepreneurs building big companies in the executive temp field.

<!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.2 -437838. -->
