<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10NewCEO</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE: The New CEO / Edited By Kristin Dunlap Godsey</FONT><BR><HR><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=right VALIGN=bottom COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+4">Better By Design</FONT>
<H3>Meld Creativity and Technology to Get More Work Done </H3>

	</TD>
	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="ceo.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="180" HEIGHT="180" BORDER="0">
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD></TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by Andrea Bucci</FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
Dominick L. Segrete calls himself a creative dinosaur. And yet, he has built
his small New York architectural design firm into a high-tech success story.
Over the last 10 years, Segrete says he's spent about $350,000 on technology,
including 30 networked PCs loaded with extra hard-drive space, laptops,
file servers, and high-speed modems. <BR>
<BR>
''High technology is no longer optional,'' he says. His firm, Tucci, Segrete
&amp; Rosen, brings in $6 million per year designing retail space for clients
like Saks Fifth Avenue, Eatons in Canada, and Printemps in Paris. Like many
designers these days, the firm uses drawing software (such as AutoCAD) instead
of relying on pen-and-ink blueprints. But its pi&egrave;ce de r&eacute;sistance
is ProShare, a $199 conferencing and document-sharing program from Intel
Corp. of Santa Clara, Calif. Coupled with AutoCAD, ProShare helps Segrete's
designers get more work done, more efficiently. <BR>
<BR>
''We can be in and out of Paris in 15 minutes,'' says Segrete. ''It saves
about $4,000 in travel expenses every time we need to deal with clients
there.'' <BR>
<BR>
To initiate one of these virtual meetings, Segrete calls the client on one
phone line and sends the AutoCAD file of the floor-plan blueprint on a second
line. The client receives the document within minutes as they're chatting.
''We can both then call up the same file and are literally reading off the
same page,'' Segrete says. ''We can type text back and forth while we talk,
and it's all in real time.'' <BR>
<BR>
Electronic pens allow either party to mark up the blueprint on the screen.
So if, for example, a client wants to move the Ralph Lauren department from
the second floor to the fourth, Segrete's designer can do it right <BR>
<BR>
on the screen while the client watches. <BR>
<BR>
Segrete says the technology has actually opened up creativity and the collaboration
process. Designers can brainstorm with clients more easily, throwing out
ideas as they occur during the conversation by quickly drawing them into
the program. <BR>
<BR>
Boost Your Bottom Line <BR>
<BR>
The company's high-tech face-lift has not only made Segrete and his designers
more productive, it is also directly responsible for bringing in new business.
<BR>
<BR>
Recently, Segrete beat a competitor to the contract-bidding punch by sending
a floor plan to a prospect via ProShare before the other company's plane
touched down at the site. Tucci, Segrete &amp; Rosen will earn an extra
$800,000 from that contract. <BR>
<BR>
Both parties must have ProShare for it to work, so Segrete sends the program
to his clients and prospects. He'll even send modems if they need them.
It has gotten to the point where no one in Segrete's office draws any presentation
files manually. Still, the personal touch cannot be ignored completely.
<BR>
<BR>
''Virtual meetings do a lot, but they don't replace that first physical
meeting where you have the chance to wow them,'' Segrete says. ''That's
when the client gets to know you.'' <BR>
<BR>
Segrete says that the great thing about technology is that you can add components
little by little. And when the right technology gives such a competitive
edge, he says with a smile, it will pay for itself in no time. <BR>
<BR>
''Once all of it is in place, you really start to see the creative process
take over. It enhances the way we think, the room we have to create,'' says
Segrete. ''We can now include perspectives in drawings, as well as take
clients on virtual walk-throughs with video. When designers actually think
in 3-D, it opens up worlds like never before.''  </P>

<P>-- Rivka Tadjer <BR>
</P>

	</TD>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<BR><BR><BR><BR><HR>
<H3><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">SPEC SHEET </FONT></H3>

<P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C"> PROSHARE. Price: $199. Requirements: 386 or better,
8MB of RAM, 11MB of hard-disk space, DOS 3.3 plus Windows 3.1 or better,
mouse, VGA monitor, 9600bps modem or better. TheTechnologyEdge Bulletin
Board Pump Up the Juice 
<BR><BR><BR><HR><BR><BR>

<H3>BULLETIN BOARD</H3>
<B>Pump Up The Juice</B><BR>
What's good for you is good for your battery. At least, that's the theory
behind the Exerciser Battery from ORA Electronics of Chatsworth, Calif.
This nickel-cadmium rechargeable battery puts itself through regular workouts,
helping it lead a longer, healthier life. <BR>
<BR>
If you have a nickel-cadmium battery in your cell phone now, you probably
know about memory effect. This happens when you repeatedly recharge the
battery before it's fully drained. The battery will remember how much charge
you added last time and add only that much the next time -- even if it really
needs more. The result is sluggish performance. <BR>
<BR>
By ''exercising'' itself with a built-in conditioner, the Exerciser Battery
gets rid of memory effect. Press a button on the battery before you put
it in your battery charger, and it stretches itself (so to speak) before
recharging. Afterward, it automatically recharges to full capacity every
time. The Exerciser Battery comes with a three-year warranty and retails
for $59.95. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Speedy Delivery</B> <BR>
<BR>
Perhaps a full-scale mail-management software program seems a little much
for your needs. But you still want your business mail to get where it's
supposed to. If peace of mind on that front is worth 20 bucks to you, consider
Address Fixer for Microsoft Word and Office. <BR>
<BR>
This add-on product from CoStar Corp. of Greenwich, Conn., checks any address
you have in Microsoft Word against a CD-ROM database of addresses in the
United States. It then corrects mistakes, including misspellings, and adds
the full nine-digit zip code. <BR>
<BR>
Once you install Address Fixer, it's easy to use: A ''Check Address'' option
is added to Word's Tools menu, and the whole process takes seconds. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Keyboard Calisthenics</B> <BR>
<BR>
Head off all the little kinks and aches that can plague your body when you're
feverishly typing away at the computer all day. ErgoBreak for Office from
Vanity Software of Toronto provides periodic breaks to your routine. It
interrupts your work and leads you through a few brief stretches -- for
hands, neck, back, eyes, and shoulders -- all designed to reduce the risk
of repetitive strain injury. <BR>
<BR>
ErgoBreak tracks keystrokes, mouse activity, and time, so it knows when
you're ready for a breather. Animated characters pop up on the screen to
lead you through the exercises; you don't even have <BR>
<BR>
to get up from your chair. The result is a decreased chance of suffering
from carpal tunnel syndrome, eyestrain, headaches, or tendinitis. <BR>
<BR>
For networked employees, ErgoBreak includes an onscreen ''BreakBoard'' that
dispenses company news, financial tips, motivational messages, or even jokes.
The cost starts at $59.95 for one user but goes down when you buy in bulk.
	</TD>
</TABLE>

 
