<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10TechAtWork</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE: Technology at Work / By Frank Hertz</FONT><HR><BR><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4">Behind the Scenes</FONT><BR>
<H3>Powerful PRograms for Running Your Business Smoothly </H3><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="25%">
	

<P><FONT SIZE="+2">Big Business 2.0 </FONT> <H5>MAC</H5></P>

<P>When Ken Dattmore founded Pegasus Stringed Instrument Co. in Elkhart,
Ind., he wanted a business software package that would do everything --
and he means everything. He needed inventory management, invoicing, bookkeeping,
and check cutting. He wanted to print financial statements for his company,
which imports and finishes musical instruments. He wanted to work on a Mac,
and he didn't want to have to buy 10 different software programs. </P>

<P>Big Business 2.0, from Big Software Inc. in Cupertino, Calif., delivered.
After using a number of separate applications at his previous company, Dattmore
says, Big Business ''gives me everything I need, and then some.'' </P>

<P>Big Business keeps track of Dattmore's suppliers of prefinished stringed
instruments in its vendor database and adds incoming shipments to inventory.
When Dattmore pays those suppliers, he creates an entry in the software
package. After adding finishing touches to the instruments and reselling
them to retail music stores, Big Business creates Dattmore's invoices, subtracts
inventory, figures in discounts, and tracks customer accounts. </P>

<P>Big Business creates professional quotes on the fly. It helps turn those
quotes into orders automatically, giving users a seamless transition from
inquiry to closed sale. It even has a Web page creator, which Dattmore says
he's sure to use in the future. ''I feel I can really grow with the software,''
he says. ''There are features I don't use now that I know I'll use down
the road.'' </P>

<P><B>Big Business. Price: $199. Requirements: Power Macintosh or compatible
recommended (68040-based Mac minimum), 16MB of RAM for Power Mac (8MB of
RAM for 68040 Mac), 40MB of hard-disk space, System 7 or better.</B> </P>
<BR><HR>
<P><FONT SIZE="+2">Office Hours </FONT><H5>PC</H5></P>

<P>Keeping track of your own schedule can be a daunting task, much less
trying to find your coworkers at any given moment. At Moss Adams, a law
firm in Tacoma, Wash., employee tracking used to consist of a big sheet
of paper posted by the receptionist's desk. Employees would -- if they felt
like it -- update their whereabouts as they passed by on their way in or
out of the office. </P>

<P>When the firm bought Office Hours, an employee-tracking software package
from Teamaker Corp. of Beaverton, Ore., the sheet-of-paper method was promptly
canned. John Buechler, network administrator for Moss Adams, says that employees
at the firm rave about the new convenience. ''People around here really
need to know where everyone's at,'' he says. </P>

<P>When the employees come into work, they ''punch in'' on Office Hours'
Electronic In/Out Board. As people leave throughout the day, Buechler says,
they're not only able to post where they're headed, but also important contact
information, like a client's phone number or their beeper number. </P>

<P>By checking the Employee Browser, users get instant access to colleagues'
schedules, meeting locations, and other important information. Office Hours
lets you configure the employee browser by name, extension, or department.
You can even look at the entire office on one screen. </P>

<P>''It lets you really track people down during the day, without wasting
time walking over to someone's desk,'' Buechler says. </P>

<P><B>Office Hours. Price: $149.95. Server requirements: 486-compatible or
better; Windows NT Server, Novell Netware, Windows for Workgroups Network,
or others; 5MB of hard-disk space. Client requirements: 386 or better (486
or Pentium recommended), 5MB of hard-disk space, Windows 3.1 or better.</B>
</P>
</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="40%">

	<P><FONT SIZE="+2">DacEasy <BR>
Accounting &amp; Payroll 95</FONT> <H5>PC</H5></P>

<P>While ceramic tile may look nice and simple on your kitchen floor, it's
actually quite complicated to keep track of when it's up on inventory shelves.
In fact, says Mike Wujcik, owner of The Tile Shop in St. Angelo, Tex., it
can drive you -- and your accounting software -- completely nuts. </P>

<P>''I've had trouble with accounting programs that just couldn't handle
keeping count of that type of inventory,'' Wujcik says. The problem is that
each product line has a number of different parts. Each line is also part
of a series, and each series comes in a number of different colors. The
result is more than 50,000 pieces of inventory to track on The Tile Shop's
shelves. </P>

<P>DacEasy Accounting and Payroll 95, a robust bookkeeping system from DacEasy
Inc. of Dallas, was up to the challenge. ''DacEasy handles everything, and
I'm thrilled with it,'' Wujcik says. </P>

<P>DacEasy knows which auxiliary pieces to subtract from Wujcik's inventory
when he enters a sale into the books. It also automatically tabulates discounts
for certain customers and does all the invoicing with the click of a mouse.
</P>

<P>Its banking features are top-notch. It handles recurring transactions
with ease, automatically backs out checks that are returned as ''insufficient
funds,'' and tracks your cash balance in real time. </P>

<P>Wujcik, though, is most impressed with the ease with which DacEasy handles
his complex products. ''There's a lot of information in there,'' he says.
''The software is starting to know more than I do about the ceramic tile
business.'' </P>

<P><B>DacEasy Accounting &amp; Payroll 95. Price: $149.95. Requirements: 386
or better; Windows 3.1, 95, or NT; 4MB of RAM (8MB recommended and required
for Windows 3.1); 20MB to 40MB of hard-disk space. </B></P>

	<BR><HR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">Let's Keep It <BR>
Simple Spreadsheet</FONT> <H5>MAC</H5>

<P>Admittedly, Dan Shafer isn't a numbers guy. The director of technology
at the online magazine SALON, Shafer prefers to take the creative approach
to problem solving. ''I never really liked pulling out the calculator and
pencil, although I knew I should,'' Shafer says. Let's Keep It Simple Spreadsheet,
a number-wrangling product from Casady &amp; Greene of Salinas, Calif.,
has eased Shafer's troubles. </P>

<P>The program takes advantage of Macintosh's simple drag-and-drop setup,
making it quite unlike any other spreadsheet program. Shafer uses it to
analyze the traffic statistics on his Web site and make decisions based
on usage. </P>

<P>When Shafer wants to create a spreadsheet, he simply drags and drops
the initial layout (i.e., number of columns and rows, and size of the table)
to begin. He then types in labels for the headings and drops in the operations
-- add, subtract, or multiply -- he'll need to analyze the data. </P>

<P>''Entering the data is the only thing I have to do manually,'' Shafer
says. He can view the data in many different forms, including charts, graphs,
and reports, all of which are easy to customize to his specifications. The
program's ''smart operators'' also allow the user to adjust the size of
a column or row without risk of reconfiguring any formulas. </P>

<P>Another feature that Shafer enjoys is the accessibility to the formulas
that are crunching the numbers. With other spreadsheet products, Shafer
found it difficult to manipulate the cryptic equations that often worked
behind the scenes within the spreadsheet. ''Here, the formulas are right
in front of you,'' Shafer says. ''It makes it really easy to debug.'' </P>

<P><B>Let's Keep It Simple Spreadsheet. Price: $189. Requirements: System 7
or better, 8MB of RAM, high-density 1.4MB floppy drive.</B> </P>
<BR><HR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">FocalPoint</FONT><H5>PC</H5>

<P>The user interface of FocalPoint software looks a little like the command
center on the Starship Enterprise. But don't let that fool you: This communications
package from Global Village Communication Inc. of Sunnyvale, Calif., is
easy to set up and use. Then it can answer all your calls, e-mail, and faxes.
</P>

<P>''I need programs that work as soon as you install them,'' says user
Dick Willet. ''Not only does this work, it does everything!'' </P>

<P>Willet creates greeting cards at his home in Miami, and he does a lot
of his business through e-mail, fax, and voice mail. FocalPoint, Willet
says, handles all of that and organizes his messages in one place. </P>

<P>When he turns on his computer in the morning, FocalPoint loads automatically
and gives Willet a ''waiting for call'' message. ''When I come in, I look
right at the taskbar,'' he says. If he's got new e-mail, an envelope icon
appears; a phone icon indicates new voice mail, and a fax machine means,
of course, a fax. Willet then checks all his messages from there. </P>

<P>The clean and easy-to-read interface may make you forget that you're
looking at a software product and not just a fancy telephone with extra
features. The speed dial and speakerphone prove especially useful for the
multi-tasking user. </P>

<P>At times, Willet says, FocalPoint could ''run my entire business without
me.'' FocalPoint stores numbers and dials his phone, goes out and checks
his online services for messages, and even reads his e-mails to him from
a remote location. ''If it had the ability to write a greeting card, it
would take all my business away,'' Willet jokes. </P>

<P><B>FocalPoint. Price: $99. Requirements: 386 or better, 8MB of RAM, 10MB
of hard-disk space (30MB maximum), Class 1- or Class 2-compatible modem.</B>
</P>

	</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"  WIDTH="25%">
	
<FONT SIZE="+2">Ca$hGraf Home Office Plus </FONT><H5>PC</H5>

<P>Most computer illiterates -- unless they have the IQ of a genius -- will
have two choices if they want to run a successful small business: Try to
run the company without a computer (good luck!), or get a computer and hope
for the best. When Stacy Binder started Events By Stacy Inc., a party planning
business, out of her home in Northbrook, Ill., she chose the second option.
And while Binder may or may not be a genius herself, she gives much credit
for her success to the intelligence of one software package. </P>

<P>Binder relies on Ca$hGraf Home Office Plus, from Ca$hGraf Software Inc.
of St. Petersburg, Fla., to help her with all aspects of running her business.
When a potential client calls, she uses the contact-management feature to
capture important information about the customer and take notes on the conversation.
She then schedules a meeting using the day planner. After her meeting, she
jots notes in the customer's electronic file and uses the word processor
to create and send a follow-up letter. </P>

<P>''Six months ago, I never thought I'd be doing all this in my home office
on one computer,'' Binder says. She also uses Ca$hGraf for invoices and
to keep track of purchases. Her accountant, who happens to be her husband,
uses the monthly ledgers and the reporting and charting tools to give her
a clear financial picture. </P>

<P>Ca$hGraf includes a unique financial calendar, which gives you an overview
of where your business sits in relation to your financial goals. ''What's
scary is that I know it does a lot more,'' Binder says. ''I just don't have
the time yet to learn it all.'' </P>

<P><B>Ca$hGraf Home Office Plus. Price: $100. Requirements: Windows 3.1 or
95, 4MB of RAM (8MB recommended), 12MB of hard-disk space.</B> </P>
<BR><HR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">Peachtree Complete Accounting</FONT> <H5>PC</H5>

<P>For some business owners, tracking incoming receivables is better than
a coffee break. You get to count your money -- everyone likes that -- and
perhaps ease your mind when you see that the customer with a questionable
reputation has paid this month's bill. But for Don Glidden, owner of the
Lisbon Falls, Maine-based Lisbon Bookkeeping Services, retaining the right
information about his receivables is essential to customer service. Glidden
uses Peachtree Complete Accounting, from Peachtree Software Inc. of Norcross,
Ga., to satisfy his demanding clients. </P>

<P>''Every client wants to know different things about his payment history
and his account,'' Glidden says. ''This program is flexible enough to record
just about everything I need.'' </P>

<P>Every Sunday, Glidden processes the week's batch of checks. Upon entering
a receivable for a client, Glidden fills out simple information, like the
date and amount of payment. He then can specify which invoice the client
is paying and check on other invoices that are past due. If a client has
paid early, a discount is automatically applied and subtracted from the
account balance. All the appropriate modules are then updated automatically,
and Glidden moves on to the next check. </P>

<P>Peachtree Complete is just about the most robust accounting package you
can buy in its price range. It has all the modules of the larger, pricier
packages, and what it doesn't have, you probably won't miss. The ''smart
guides,'' which lead users through complex accounting procedures, are quite
comprehensive. </P>

<P>As Glidden puts it, ''Updating my books is now a lot easier.''  </P>

<P><B>Peachtree Complete Accounting. Price: $199. Requirements: 386 or better,
DOS 3.3 or better, Windows 3.1 enhanced or Windows 95, 8MB of RAM, 24MB
to 38MB of hard-disk space.</B> </P>

<P>Frank Hertz is a freelance writer in Brighton, Mass. He can be reached
at 74774.1160@ compuserve.com.
	</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 
