<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE: Cyber Forum</FONT> </P>

<center>By Ren&eacute;e Gotcher</center><BR><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Always on Call</FONT>
<H3>Mailbots Respond to Customers Instantly </H3></CENTER>






<P>The Internet may seem an unlikely marketing tool for a localized business
such as a beauty parlor. But it was the perfect place for Jesse Briggs,
owner of the Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based Yellow Strawberry Global Salons
Inc. The salon's year-old Web site (www.bizflorida.com/bizflorida/<BR>
mr-hair/mr-hair.htm) stirred immediate interest and requests for more information,
and it now gets about 25,000 visitors per month. </P>

<P>But its real success can be measured by a feature found in the site's
customer service center. Briggs offers an e-mail auto-response service --
or &quot;mailbot&quot; -- to entice new clients into his 37 locations worldwide.
Thousands of prospects every month use the service to get Briggs's specialty
hair care tips delivered straight to their e-mail. The mailbot also adds
prospects' names to an e-mailing list for salon products and updates. </P>

<P>Mailbots are convenient for both business owners and customers -- and
they cost a lot less than direct mail, fax-on-demand, or 800 numbers. To
set them up, all you need is e-mail access and existing customer information
that can be easily channeled over the Internet. </P>

<P>Mailbots work similarly to fax-on-demand systems, where customers request
faxes by calling your automated phone system and pressing the right keys.
Customers send you either a blank e-mail message or one that requests specific
data, and the mailbot will find that pre-formatted message and send it back
almost immediately. </P>

<P>Internet service providers charge between $10 and $50 per month for mailbot
service with a one-time setup fee. The fee will vary based on system complexity,
how much information you want to dispense, and how many customers access
each message. Most Internet service providers offer mailbot service as part
of an e-mail package, so the cost to you is minimal. Talk to your provider
and make sure you understand how you will be charged, whether monthly fees
include unlimited customer requests, how often you can update your messages,
and whether you'll have to pay for storage space. </P>

<P>Your job is to take existing information -- such as frequently asked
questions, product troubleshooting tips, company history, price lists, or
sale announcements -- and package it into smaller, more specific messages
to be sent out at your customers' beck and call. As long as the information
is ready to go, they can get it 24 hours a day. </P>

<P>Net More Sales </P>

<P>Halted Specialties Corp., a high-tech products retailer based in Santa
Clara, Calif., set up its mailbot to deliver an early-bird special for its
existing store customers. The special features different products every
month. </P>

<P>&quot;We noticed the competition stirred up by the Internet and decided
to give it a try,&quot; says Halted's Dave Joseph. Even though Halted didn't
have a Web site until recently, he says that &quot;the mailbot significantly
increased our mail-order business, and the advantage was seen immediately.&quot;
</P>

<P>To keep your mailbot messages valuable to customers, assign some employee
time to keeping them current. You'll also have to keep on top of special
requests and unusual questions that can't be answered automatically. You
have less space and readability than in a printed brochure or manual, says
Paul Thomas, VP of applications for Cuenet Systems of Santa Clara, Calif.,
an access provider. So adapt what you have to e-mail form, or use e-mail
attachments for easier transmission. </P>

<P>Five double-spaced pages, which make up about 10K of data, should be
the maximum, according to Alfred and Emily Glossbrenner, authors of Making
Money on the Internet. If you reformat these pages into a single-spaced,
business letter style, it will be easier to read. Use bullet points and
other visual breaks to make the message easy to follow on a computer screen.
</P>

<P>Tom Argue, Yellow Strawberry's Internet guru, says many of the salon's
cyberspace visitors become real clients. The Web site averages 30 to 50
new mailbot customers per day. &quot;People use the Internet for information,&quot;
he says. &quot;And e-mail is probably the fastest way to get it. Once people
leave their e-mail addresses with you, you know they want to hear from you.
Those are interested customers.&quot;  </P>

<P>Ren&eacute;e Gotcher is a freelance writer based in San Francisco. <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.2 -437838. -->
<HR><BR>
