<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>9HotTips</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE: Hot Tips</FONT><BR><HR><BR><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Productivity Patrol</FONT><BR>
<H3>Keep Tabs on Employee Internet Use </H3><BR><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>



<TR>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<P><FONT SIZE="+3">Big Brother has a name, and it's Net Access Manager.</FONT> <BR>
<BR>
Instead of being productive, your employees (you suspect) are actually spending
all of their time on the Internet reading Dilbert. Well, now there's a software
program that lets you monitor and control your employees' Internet and in-tranet
access. <BR>
<BR>
Net Access Manager 1.0 from Sequel Technology of Toronto is loaded onto
your communications server, where it links into all the networked computers.
Type in each user's name and e-mail address for the company account. You
can then set detailed access privileges by user or by groups of users, limiting
when and where they go on the Internet (as well as online services like
CompuServe or America Online). For example, if you're pretty sure your product-repair
staff has no business use for the World Wide Web, just lock out access until
after working hours. <BR>
<BR>
You can also restrict the type and size of files to be downloaded from the
Internet. If you decide that huge image files -- say, the Web's complete
photo collection of Pamela Anderson Lee -- are of little value to your sales
department, zap out all JPEG and GIF files. <BR>
<BR>
For evaluation purposes, Net Access Manager lets you generate different
kinds of reports on your company's Internet, intranet, and online service
use. The software is designed to be easy to use even if you're not an MIS
manager.  </P>
	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+3">Professional Printing <BR>From Your PC</FONT><BR>

<P>Here's a software package that doesn't offer just professional-looking
print jobs from your ordinary PC. Printovation, from Deluxe Corp. of St.
Paul, actually lays out and sends your print jobs straight to a real print
shop -- where they can also be folded, bound, mailed, and/or delivered.
<BR>
<BR>
The Printovation Connection Kit costs $39.95 and includes sample documents,
$40 worth of coupons for printing services, and a book of binder colors
and paper samples. It works like this: Create a document using Printovation's
templates and Microsoft Word (or Microsoft Publisher). The software guides
you through the selection of printing, binding, mailing, and delivery choices.
<BR>
<BR>
You can then send your document to Deluxe via a free modem transfer; if
you prefer, you can put the information on a disk, which Deluxe will pick
up at no charge. Get a proof of the order the next day, if you wish. Deluxe
will send the finished order to you or deliver it to whomever you've designated.
<BR>
<BR>
Hot Web Site Office Furniture If you're starting up a new business, the
last thing you want to do is go broke buying office furniture. On the other
hand, the thought of sitting on an orange crate with a computer balancing
on your lap is probably less than appealing. Leasing your furniture, fixtures,
and business equipment may be the answer. FSFG Leasing Corp. of Covina,
Calif., has a Web site (<A HREF="http://www.internet-is.com/fsfg">http://www.internet-is.com/fsfg</A>) just for this purpose.
If you have good credit, FSFG provides lease financing at reasonable rates.
The plan is government funded. You won't be charged any points or commissions.
The site lays out the company's leasing plan characteristics and tells you
what you need to do to be considered for funding. You can also get detailed
information about leasing and why it might make more sense for your business.
</TR>
	</TD>
</TABLE>

