<BODY>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<BR><BR><CENTER><P>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Choosing the Best</FONT>

</CENTER>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> Survey Criteria and Methodology</H3><BR>

</CENTER>



<P>The growth of these programs is amazing,&quot; says research expert William

M. Madway. &quot;They're spreading like wildfire, integrating entrepreneurship

studies into an incredible number of other disciplines: finance, engineering,

medical training. And this at universities, which are usually creatures

of habit and very slow to change!&quot; </P>



<P>Madway, founder and president of Pennsylvania-based Madway Business Research

Inc., has just completed the statistical portion of SUCCESS Magazine's survey

of the leading entrepreneurship programs at graduate business schools. A

former director of the Wharton School's Small Business Development Center,

Madway left his position at The Gallup Organization to form his own research

firm five years ago. </P>



<P>Madway had not been in such close contact with business schools since

he earned his MBA at Wharton in 1985. They've changed. &quot;At first, these

schools focused on bringing entrepreneurs into the classroom,&quot; he says.

&quot;Then they started to teach students to write business plans. Now,

they're putting students out into the field, consulting to businesses and

working as interns.&quot; </P>



<P>The survey was conducted using a six-page mail questionnaire developed

by SUCCESS, Madway Business Research, and a committee of renowned experts

in the field of entrepreneurship including: </P>



<P>Karl H. Vesper, business text author and management professor at the

University of Washington; </P>



<P>Gary M. Cadenhead, senior lecturer in entrepreneurship at the University

of Texas at Austin and director of the MOOT CORP business plan competition;

</P>



<P>George T. Solomon, of the SBA's Office of Business Initiatives and George

Washington University; </P>



<P>Jay McGoodwin, president of the Costa Mesa, Calif.-based venture capital

firm McGoodwin, James &amp; Co.; and </P>



<P>Stephen Spinelli Jr., a founder of Jiffy Lube International Inc., and

now a professor at Babson College. </P>



<P>To be eligible for consideration, a school had to offer at least three

distinct courses in entrepreneurship in its MBA program. We surveyed 137

graduate business schools across the country. The survey focused on five

areas that the research team deemed to be the most important components

of a top-level entrepreneurship program: </P>



<P>*The overall quality, longevity, programs, resources, and community outreach

of the school's entrepreneurship program; </P>



<P>*The qualifications of the school's entrepreneurship faculty and the

role faculty members play in supporting students' entrepreneurial endeavors;

</P>



<P>*The depth and breadth of the entrepreneurship curriculum; </P>



<P>*School resources and special programs to provide students with &quot;hands

on&quot; entrepreneurial experience; and </P>



<P>*The caliber of the students attending the school. </P>



<P>We indexed many of the numeric measures in the survey to, in effect,

grade the schools on a curve. Schools were evaluated based on how they compared

with their peers. This helped offset the inherent advantage that larger

schools have. a </P>



<P>The Top Five </P>



<P><FONT COLOR="#000000">Which schools do the schools themselves believe

to be the best? We asked all the survey respondents to rank their peers.

Here is their top five: </FONT></P>



<P><FONT COLOR="#000000">1) Babson College </FONT></P>



<P><FONT COLOR="#000000">2) Wharton/University of Pennsylvania </FONT></P>



<P><FONT COLOR="#000000">3) Harvard University </FONT></P>



<P><FONT COLOR="#000000">4) University of Southern </FONT></P>



<P><FONT COLOR="#000000">California </FONT></P>



<P><FONT COLOR="#000000">5) UCLA </FONT>



<HR><BR>

