<HTML>

<HEAD>

  <TITLE>9SchoolsMoot</TITLE>

  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">

</HEAD>



<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<BR><BR>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE="+4">Battle of the Business Plans</FONT>

</CENTER>

<CENTER><H3> How Top MBAs Fight for Cash and Credibility</H3>

</CENTER>

<BR>

<P>By the time Andrew Maxwell turned 30, he had helped launch 60 Circle

K convenience stores in his native Australia. He'd worked in New Guinea

developing new businesses. He'd also opened a brewery and a food and liquor

wholesaler in Cambodia. </P>



<P>Despite his track record, Maxwell had trouble raising money. ''An entrepreneur

is seen as a risky proposition,'' he says. Maxwell enrolled in Bond University

in Australia to get his MBA in entrepreneurship. </P>



<P>At school, the young entrepreneur was introduced to the inventor of a

self-cleaning swimming pool filter. Maxwell and classmates Prue Kellahan

and Kim Goriss immediately saw its international potential. </P>



<P>The trio formed EcoClear to sell the product in America. A professor

told them that winning the University of Texas at Austin's MOOT CORP business

plan competition would provide them with credibility and connections to

crack the market. </P>



<P>Every year at MOOT CORP, MBA students from around the world present business

plans to the venture capitalists, business owners, and experts who make

up the judging panel. The winning team receives $10,000 -- and a highly

marketable stamp of approval. </P>



<P>In May, Maxwell and his partners competed with 19 teams from 17 universities.

Four teams, including EcoClear, made the finals. </P>



<P>The Australians outlined their plan to license their technology to a

major U.S. pool products manufacturer. The judges awarded them first prize.

Maxwell and his teammates are now performing additional testing while they

wait for their U.S. patent to go through. </P>



<P>''We had our plan reviewed and pulled apart,'' says the 33-year-old Maxwell.

''The process gave us a great deal of confidence.'' </P>



<P>MOOT CORP creates a bridge between the academic theories of entrepreneurship

and the tough realities of launching a business. It allows MBAs to test

the viability of an idea without actually having their house or life savings

on the line. This world-class competition provides lessons that every entrepreneur

can use to bolster his business. </P>



<P>When pitching a business to investors, the ability to convey passion

about an idea is as important as the idea itself. Get people emotionally

charged, or you're likely to fail. </P>



<P>David Brown exuded energy as he explained how Fast Track Applications

would be a win-win hit for students and colleges. He and his teammates had

an interactive college brochure and application that business schools can

send to prospective students. ''This company is a bull's-eye!'' he barked.

His enthusiasm excited the judges. </P>



<P>Says one venture capitalist judge, ''I'd rather invest in an A team with

a B idea than the reverse.'' </P>



<P>Founder Bob Carton came up with Fast Track after he waded through tons

of useless information when applying to B-school. Carton wanted to simplify

the process for other potential students. At the University of Georgia,

he recruited fellow MBA candidates David Brown and Bernd Muehlfriedel to

help launch his plan. </P>



<P>The trio are testing Fast Track Applications at the University of Georgia

before rolling it out at other colleges. </P>



<P>''We found out that [poor] communication can be a barrier to success,''

says Carton, 38. ''Some people have great ideas, but they do not have dynamic

personalities.'' </P>



<P>Listen to everyone; <BR>

follow the advice of few. </P>



<P>As a globe-trotting consultant with Price Waterhouse, Mark Jamison became

very familiar with frequent flier clubs. But it was hard to keep track of

all his hotel, car rental, and airline miles. </P>



<P>Jamison designed a software product that would allow consumers to track

and manage their frequent flier miles. He left his job and enrolled in the

entrepreneurship program at the Kellogg Graduate School of Management. </P>



<P>Last year, Jamison competed in MOOT CORP and used the feedback to improve

the plan for his company, Syphrosyny LLC of Chicago. </P>



<P>At first, judges questioned whether the world needed the MaxMiles program.

Jamison wasn't flustered. He knew that if every entrepreneur with a new

idea were intimidated by his critics, there'd be no FedEx or Microsoft.

</P>



<P>The judges pointed out flaws that saved him from disaster. ''We had a

naive assumption that we'd do some direct-mail pieces and receive a 2 percent

to 3 percent response rate,'' says Jamison. One expert told Jamison his

numbers were completely unrealistic. He'd be lucky to get a 1 percent response

rate. Jamison reworked all his projections. </P>



<P>In February, the young entrepreneur rolled out MaxMiles and has since

sold 17,000 units at $39.95 each. </P>



<P>''As an entrepreneur, you get so excited about your product,'' says Jamison,

29. He credits outside experts with identifying his blind spots and putting

him on the path to success. </P>



<P>Create realistic <BR>

management duties. </P>



<P>Jill Brosig conceived of 3D Precision Analytics before she worked as

a development engineer at Motorola. There needed to be a more precise way

to test and design electronic parts in products. Brosig used holographic

interferometry and three-dimensional computer modeling to measure and analyze

design components with great accuracy. </P>



<P>She presented her idea at an entre-preneurship class at Kellogg. ''I

didn't think I'd get a team,'' says Brosig. ''The idea is so technical.''

Four fellow engineers saw the potential of her idea. </P>



<P>At MOOT CORP, Brosig explained her responsibilities as CEO: handling

the engineering and generating all the sales. </P>



<P>Brosig had already been advised she might be taking on too much. ''We

adapted our plan to bring more technicians on board quickly,'' she says.

</P>



<P>Think big. </P>



<P>While at New York University's Stern School of Business, Risa Fisher

developed her idea for an online bridal registry. Her instincts told her

to keep the idea ''manageable.'' </P>



<P>''It started out as a cute 'quality of life' business concept,'' says

Fisher, 26. She wanted $250,000 to launch in the New York area. </P>



<P>But then Fisher won San Diego State University's business plan competition,

which guaranteed her a seat at MOOT CORP. As she pitched her company, her

vision changed dramatically. </P>



<P>''Risa, $250,000 is pocket change,'' one judge told her. ''Ask for a

million and roll this out big.'' </P>



<P>''Everyone told me to think national,'' says Fisher. ''They encouraged

me to think that I'll be the next wave of retailing.'' </P>



<P>Since graduating in May, Fisher has turned down a job at a major corporation

to forge ahead with her business. She may even be financed by a competition

judge.</P>





