<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>9MutualFunds</TITLE>
   
</HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAC="1"COLSPAN="2">
	<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">SPECIAL SECTION </FONT></TD></TR>
	
	
	
	<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="2" WIDTH="40%">
	<IMG SRC="mutial.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH="216" HEIGHT="161"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
	<FONT SIZE="-1">Illustration by Stuart Bradford</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3">SCOUR THE INVESTMENT LANDSCAPE</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1" COLOR="#CC000C">
If you are an entrepreneur, dancing with risk is an integral part of
your identity. You ride the edge to reap the rewards, so taking chances
makes sense -- sometimes. When it doesn't, you must make every risk work
for you. * That's why you should not have all of your eggs in one basket,
even if it's your company -- the one you're transforming into a giant.
Stash part of your fortune somewhere else. Ensure it against catastrophe
by building a portfolio of mutual funds.  Invest strategically and reduce
the risk of taxes nipping away at your earnings. Minimize your exposure
with funds that have outperformed in bad markets as well as in good ones.
Index part of your portfolio to reduce the risk of picking a bad fund.
And learn where to get the best advice from fund experts. </FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>
	<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2"><P>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Make Your Money Work</FONT></P>

<P>The first step toward measurement and control is to assess your psychological
risk tolerance. How big a loss could you comfortably take on your fund
portfolio? Would a 10 percent market drop scare you? A 20 percent or 30
percent drop? </P>

<P>Time plays a big part in defining risk. Historically, the riskier assets
-- such as stocks -- have produced bigger gains over time than more conser
vative ones, like bonds. You can be a long-term investor even if you
periodically skim off some income, or even a small amount of principal.
</P>

<P>Take a look at your investment goals. The closer you are to meeting
your goals, the less risk you can afford to take. </P>

<P>For example, retirement savers can invest very aggressively when they
are still years away from retiring. But it makes sense to shift Keogh or
401(k) plan assets into less-risky types of stock funds or bonds as retirement
approaches to preserve the capital that has built up over the years. </P>

<P>Risk changes over time. The volatility that penalizes short-term investors
fades. Instead, outpacing inflation becomes the biggest risk. Moreover,
risk can lie dormant for years. That was illustrated by junk bonds, which
didn't demonstrate their ample credit risk until the market collapsed in
1989. </P>

<P>It's important to remember that a diversified mutual fund portfolio
minimizes risk. One fund that performs badly will be offset by better ones.
That's the meaning of diversification. </P>

<P>How is risk measured in mutual funds? One common yardstick is &quot;beta,&quot;
which measures the average changes in a fund's return over time relative
to the S&amp;P 500 (for stock funds) or the Lehman Brothers/Government
Corporate Bond Index (for bond funds). </P>

<P>Funds whose returns closely mimic the market sport betas of 1.0. A beta
of 1.5 means that a fund's return vacillates more than the market; betas
under 1.0 mean less fluctuation. Betas can range from more than 1.5 for
some volatile technology funds to less than 0.5 for steady utility funds.
</P>

<P>Betas are only as useful as the indexes that measure them. Gold funds
have very little correlation with the S&amp;P 500, for instance. And betas
penalize funds for performance that is superior to the market as well as
for poor performance. </P>

<P>By contrast, &quot;standard deviation&quot; measures the probable variation
in a fund's expected return. Like betas, standard deviation penalizes funds
for variations on the upside. </P>

<P>To compensate for the problems with these risk measures, Morningstar
Inc., a mutual fund data provider in Chicago, has created its own. It measures
downside volatility by subtracting the risk-free return on a three-month
Treasury bill from a fund's monthly returns. The negative monthly results
are added together, divided by the number of months in rating periods,
and compared with other funds. The average risk score is set to equal 1.0.
</P>

<P>This method penalizes funds for losses, not unusual gains, and avoids
comparisons with irrelevant indexes. But it's a historical rating, not
a predictive one. And market conditions can sometimes be so favorable that
risk is understated. </P>

<P>How does this translate into real mutual fund portfolios? Susan Belden,
San Francisco-based senior editor at The No-Load Fund Analyst, would structure
a static high-risk portfolio as follows: mid-/large- cap growth funds (15
percent), mid-/large-cap value funds (20 percent), REITS (5 percent), small-growth
(30 percent), core international (20 percent), emerging markets (10 percent).
</P>

<P>The static medium-risk portfolio contains mid-/large-cap growth (10
percent) and value (15 percent) funds, REITS (5 percent), small-growth
(15 percent), core international (15 percent), emerging markets (5 percent),
investment-grade bonds (25 percent), and junk bonds (10 percent). </P>

<P>The static low-risk portfolio consists of mid-/large-cap growth (5 percent)
and value (10 percent) funds, small-cap growth (10 percent), core international
(15 percent), REITS (5 percent), investment-grade bonds (50 percent), and
junk bonds (5 percent). </P>

<P>Recommended funds for each category: core international (Hotchkis &amp;
Wiley International); emerging markets (T. Rowe Price Emerging Markets);
small-growth (Strong Opportunity or Baron Asset, which is more aggressive);
mid-/large-cap growth (Selected American Shares or Harbor Capital Appreciation,
more aggressive); mid-/large-cap value (Oakmark); REIT (Fidelity Real Estate);
junk bond (Vanguard High-Yield Corporate); investment-grade bond (Fremont
Bond). However, investors in taxable accounts should use Vanguard's intermediate-term
municipal bond fund for the entire bond allocation, Belden advises. </P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#222169">Tax Strategies</FONT> </P>

<P>Use these mutual fund tax strategies to reduce taxes and boost investment
returns: </P>

<P>* Never buy shares just before the fund pays a dividend. At first glance,
buying shares in a fund that's about to pay a dividend looks smart. But
because you will owe taxes on the dividend, it isn't. </P>

<P>For example, on December 1 you buy 100 shares of ABC Fund for $2,000
at $20 per share. </P>

<P>The fund pays a $2 per share dividend on December 15, and the share
price drops to $18. You now own $1,800 of shares plus $200 cash. Tax owed
on the dividend is $79 (39.6 percent of $200). In two weeks, your original
$2,000 investment has shrunk to $1,921. </P>

<P>Avoid problems by waiting to buy fund shares until dividends are paid.
Call the fund company for the exact date. </P>

<P>* Never sell fund shares just after a dividend payment is made. When
you sell shares for a profit, you can pay capital gains taxes on the gain
and avoid the higher taxes that would be due on the dividend. </P>

<P>Say you own 100 shares in ABC Fund worth $5,000, and for which you paid
$3,500. The fund pays a $5 dividend in December, and the share price falls
to $45 from $50. If you sell before the dividend is paid, you owe $420
in capital gains tax (28 percent of $1,500 profit). If you wait until after
the dividend is paid, you owe $280 in capital gains tax (28 percent of
$1,000) plus $198 of ordinary income (39.6 percent of the $500 dividend),
for a total of $478. </P>

<P>* Don't pay taxes twice on mutual fund dividends. Many people automatically
reinvest dividends or capital gains in additional fund shares. But taxes
are owed in the year the dividends are paid, even though you receive no
cash from the fund. So sloppy bookkeeping can result in paying taxes twice:
when dividends are paid and again when you sell the shares. </P>

<P>Instead, add reinvested dividends and capital gains distributions to
your &quot;tax basis&quot; in the fund shares. Because capital gains tax
is owed on the difference between the sales price and your basis, increasing
the basis reduces your tax bill. </P>

<P>For example, you invest $2,000 in ABC Fund. During the three years you
owned it, the fund paid $500 of dividends, which you reinvested. When you
sell the shares for $3,000, you owe gain on $500, not $1,000. </P>

<P>* When you own shares in municipal bond funds, watch out for funds that
own large amounts of &quot;AMT paper.&quot; Interest paid by &quot;private
purpose&quot; municipal bonds is free from regular tax but subject to the
alternative minimum tax. To compensate, they pay slightly higher yields
than regular municipal bonds. </P>

<P>* Don't lose tax losses by reinvesting sales proceeds in the same fund
within 60 days. Under the &quot;wash sales&quot; rule, you can't deduct
a loss when you sell shares in a mutual fund and then buy back shares within
30 days before or 30 days after the original sale. </P>

<P>To claim a loss quickly, invest the money in a similar but not identical
fund. Or wait 31 days to reinvest in shares of the original fund. </P>

<P>* Be sure to deduct fund investing expenses. These are the costs of
investment books, newspapers, and magazines; investment counseling and
advisory fees; tax planning fees; and postage and telephone costs related
to investing. </P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#222169">Mutual Fund Newsletters</FONT> </P>

<P>If you're bewildered by the vast array of mutual funds, you're not alone.
Hence investment newsletters, which offer guidance in picking funds. To
sort through the newsletters, try The Hulbert Financial Digest, which tracks
the performance of investment newsletters' recommendations. About half
of the nearly 160 newsletters tracked by Hulbert offer advice to fund investors.
</P>

<P>For an average of $100 to $125 per year, you can buy newsletters that
follow all funds or only Fidelity funds. How can you choose among the 75
or so fund newsletters? Review the editor's philosophy, profiled in the
book The Hulbert Financial Digest or in advertisements for the newsletters
in the financial pages of newspapers or magazines. There are three essential
elements: time, risk, and performance. </P>

<P>Many newsletters have telephone hot lines that investors can call for
updates between issues. Avoid them if you prefer a strategy that doesn't
require daily attention. </P>

<P>Next, match the newsletters' risk levels to your own, either by devising
your own measure or relying on rating services like Hulbert. </P>

<P>Before committing yourself, take out a trial subscription. When you
decide to adopt a newsletter's strategy, follow the advice. That may seem
self-evident, but experts say the biggest mistake investors make is to
deviate from the prescribed course. </P>

<P>Hulbert suggests that investors who want to test a newsletter's strategy
should track the investments on paper first. Or, you could review the newsletter's
approach when the market is strong, since you have less of your ego invested
then. </P>

<P><FONT COLOR="#222169">Power Strategy: Indexing</FONT> </P>

<P>Selecting a fund from among 3,000-plus stock funds is risky. It's easy
to pick managers who lag the overall market. Why take that risk if you
don't want to squeeze the last dollar of return from your money? There's
a better strategy. </P>

<P>Invest in stocks through funds that track a market index like the S&amp;P
500. Simplicity and assured market returns have made winners of index funds.
</P>

<P>But they must be assembled in ways that make sense. </P>

<P>Index funds own all or a representative sample of the securities in
a market index. Their biggest edge over actively managed funds: cost savings.
You can offset bad stocks with lower investing costs. </P>

<P>Because index funds use a buy-and-hold strategy, they should have extremely
low transaction costs. Low turnover means fewer taxable distributions for
people who invest outside 401(k)s, Keoghs, and other tax-deferred accounts.
</P>

<P>Management fees should be low, because index fund managers don't have
to research investments. The Vanguard Group is the benchmark, running an
S&amp;P index fund on just .2 percent a year. </P>

<P>Any cons to indexing? Because the funds always stay fully invested,
they tend to be volatile. Managers cannot retreat to cash when they see
tough times ahead. </P>

<P>Some experts say indexing is the way to go because most stock funds
lagged the S&amp;P 500 from 1983 through 1990. </P>

<P>Others say the 1980s were an aberration because corporate raids and
leveraged buyouts priced big stocks higher than earnings warranted, and
foreign buying focused on those stocks. </P>

<P>However, stock funds basically beat the index for seven years before
1983, and in 1991 through 1993. </P>

<P>How to put indexing into action? Divide your portfolio into two parts.
Fill the passively managed portion with index funds, giving you more time
to spend on the actively managed part. Use that for niches not covered
by index funds, or to adjust the portfolio's risk levels. Or buy funds
that let you make small bets on the market's direction without making major
changes in your overall portfolio. </P>

<P>Carole Gould is a mutual funds columnist for The New York Times and
author of The New York Times Guide to Mutual Funds. <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.1 -437838. --></P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>


