<HEAD><TITLE>9EdNote</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">EDITOR'S NOTE </FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>BY SCOTT DeGARMO </P></CENTER><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Schools for Millionaires</FONT>
</CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> The Passionate Debate Behind This Issue</H3><BR>
</CENTER>

<P>
As entrepreneurs know better than anyone, innovators are often viewed with doubt and suspicion. 

<P>
That's as true at magazines as anywhere.

<P>
I can now reveal that a furious controversy took place among SUCCESS's editors prior to the launching of our annual education issue.

<P>
Since its creation three years ago, this yearly listing of the best entrepreneurial programs at graduate schools of business has been wildly successful.

<P>
But if you think the decision to introduce it was a no-brainer, you're wrong. Here are excerpts of the passionate debate that preceded its birth:

<P>
<B>PRO</B> Entrepreneurship is an incredibly hot topic among business school students. Schools are finally being forced to change their traditional offerings. But hidebound institutions are dragging their feet. Here's a chance to tell SUCCESS readers where they can get the best entrepreneurial education.

<P>
<B>ANTI</B> It's a terrible idea. To focus on obtaining credentials from an institution is exactly the opposite of what SUCCESS has always stood for -- namely, accomplishment in the real world.

<P>
<B>PRO</B> Are you daft? Since its founding in 1891, SUCCESS has understood the importance of education. The magazine's original creator, Orison Swett Marden, was a poor orphan whose life was galvanized with purpose when he read a self-help book. He struggled to get a secondary education. He later earned two prestigious degrees, one in law from Boston University School of Law, and an M.D. from Harvard Medical School -- degrees, incidentally, that he obtained simultaneously!

<P>
<B>ANTI</B> What a distortion! Marden did not practice law or medicine. He became an entrepreneur, with a magazine aimed at helping "the strugglers and strivers of the world" seize opportunities and pull themselves up by their bootstraps. He would roll over in his grave at the thought of our perpetuating myths about him while telling people they need formal educations in order to become entrepreneurs.

<P>
<B>PRO</B> A truly dangerous myth -- one that you are implicitly endorsing -- is that a business education is irrelevant to entrepreneurship.

<P>
<B>ANTI </B>And a far more harmful fallacy that you are underwriting is that without a piece of paper, you're out of the game. Not only is that exclusionary and elitist, it destroys the hope and optimism upon which entrepreneurship is founded. What about the people who do not have an education, entrepreneurial or otherwise? Should they forsake having dreams and ambitions? The stories we tell in every issue belie such a notion. The field is full of famous dropouts -- Richard Branson, Steve Jobs, Michael Dell, Bill Gates.

<P>
<B>PRO </B>Here's the real point, one that seems to elude you: Evidence shows that the better your knowledge of entrepreneurship, the greater your chances of succeeding. Entrepreneurship is a complex, growing body of knowledge. It's not something you just do by the seat of your pants -- not if you want a sustained success. And, obviously, few of us are born with an innate understanding of how to write business plans, raise capital, or do cash flows.

<P>
<B>ANTI</B> The harsh reality apparently escaping your attention is that most of our readers are already successful entrepreneurs with growing businesses. Why would news about business schools such as you are proposing have any appeal to them?

<P>
<B>PRO</B> Simply because our education issue will convey the latest ideas from the field of entrepreneurship. And our readers represent the leading edge of business -- the most competitive, forward-looking, enterprising group of individuals in the economy. They always seek to be as well-informed as possible. 

<P>
<B>ANTI</B> Hmmpf! Well, no one can argue with you there.

<P>
<B>PRO </B>So, we agree after all. I knew you'd see it my way.


When it comes to serving readers, our passions run high. Class is in session!



<HR><BR>
