<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>9EntEye</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR>

<P>

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">


<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>WASHINGTON WATCH<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	<FONT COLOR=#CC000C></TD>

</TR>
<BR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	<FONT SIZE="+6">Owners Need Champions</FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
<BR><BR>
Entrepreneurs want a President who will champion their cause in Washington. But according to a Gallup poll, business owners have little faith in either Bill Clinton or Bob Dole. 

<P>
The survey, conducted for the online service CCH Business Owner's Toolkit, measured the election-year concerns of 1,000 entrepreneurs.

<P>
''Small businesses have at least a $3 trillion impact on the U.S. economy and employ more than half of all workers in this country,'' says CCH's Martin Bush. ''Yet many feel their critical business needs are being ignored.''

<P>
The survey shows that the candidates have done a poor job selling themselves to entrepreneurs, according to Bush. When asked which candidate best represents their interests, 28 percent of respondents answered, ''Don't Know.''

<P>
The survey asked respondents to rank the issues most important to them. High health care costs topped the list, with 69 percent of business owners saying it was ''Very Important.'' Less government regulation came in second. The third biggest complaint was high taxes. 

<P>
While 44 percent of respondents strongly supported government programs and agencies designed to help small businesses, a dramatic 74 percent said the Small Business Administration (SBA) did not affect them at all. And 6 percent said the SBA has a negative effect. ''The SBA is a valuable source of information for small businesses,'' says Bush. ''Maybe this is a sign that people aren't taking advantage of it.''

<P><BR><HR><BR>
<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>THE INTERNET</FONT>

<P>
Ernie -- A New Online Consultant

<P>
Ernst &amp; Young LLP of New York City has launched Ernie, an online consulting service that lets growing companies obtain answers to all their business questions.

<P>
Subscribers gain access to a private site on the World Wide Web where they can pick the brains of top consultants. 

<P>
Simply type in your question and any background information, and send it electronically to Ernst &amp; Young. Your query is routed through the company's intranet to the appropriate expert. Within two business days, the answer arrives at your e-mail address. 

<P>
For those in need of immediate advice, Ernie offers a database of Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs). FAQs contain everything from the names and numbers of experts to the lowdown on import duties of various countries to detailed tax information.

<P>
The service costs $6,000 per year, but there are cost-saving benefits. Ernie allows multiple users on one subscription. Your employees can submit questions from their personal computers. And there is no limit to the number of questions that can be asked. 

<P>
For more information, contact Ernst &amp; Young at 1-800-892-1732.
<BR><HR><BR>
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>IPO UPDATE</FONT>

<P>
Price of Going Public

<P>
Ninety-four companies went public in May, according to Securities Data Company of Newark, up from 35 firms one year ago. The median amount raised was $37 million.

<P>
Spotlight: Children's Wonderland Inc. of Agoura, Calif.

<P>
Description: Provides specialized child and senior day-care services.

<P>
1995 Revenues: $3.7 million.

<P>
Amount raised: $7 million

<P>
''Whatever anyone tells you, going public will run much longer and cost more money than you ever thought,'' says Debby Bitticks, founder of Children's Wonderland. ''Our IPO cost more than $600,000.

<P>
''Prepare your people to understand that they're going to be stretched like a rubber band ready to break during the time that they're trying to run their operations and deal with the IPO,'' she advises. ''Make sure that your management team is strong enough to handle it. I've heard of companies that ran out of money prior to coming out and didn't have enough of a team to hold everything together.

<P>
''I am thankful that we put our money into management and into systems,'' says Bitticks. ''It may not look good on your balance sheet the day you go out, but you have many years ahead to have the profits.''



<HR><BR>
