<HEAD><TITLE>9GlobEntrepreneur</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">GLOBAL ENTREPRENEUR </FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>BY KRISTIN DUNLAP GODSEY </P></CENTER><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>A New Wrinkle in Time</FONT>
</CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> Don't Just Serve a Niche -- Capture It</H3><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Michael McCready never intended to work for anyone but himself. As a young American living in Cardedeu, a town in the Spanish province of Barcelona, he tried to find his entrepreneurial calling. Multilevel marketing wasn't it; Spanish customers stigmatized the profession and made it tough for McCready to make a living. A stint as a cultural liaison between the U.S. and small towns in the province went well at first, but the local government's lax attitude toward payment stymied cash flow.

<P>
McCready finally found his niche in the early '90s, putting a new face on a product as old as time itself.

<P>
''A friend of mine came to me in 1991, wearing this watch he'd had made by a local jeweler,'' explains McCready, 27. ''The numbers were all out of place. I had no idea what he was showing me, but as soon as he explained it, I knew that was it. I told him, 'You've got to market this!' ''

<P>
The friend, Xavier Casanovas, had designed the watch face to represent the manner in which people tell time in Catalonia, the northeast region of Spain (Barcelona is the capital). Catalans tell time based on quarter hours, so Casanovas replaced the 3, 6, and 9 on the classic watch face with 1&#142;4, 2&#142;4, and 3&#142;4. Other subtle design changes made the watch uniquely Catalonian.

<P>
At the time, Casanovas had no interest in mass-producing his design. But McCready couldn't get the idea out of his head. A few years later, he went to Casanovas and hammered out an agreement: Starting with just three watch models, McCready would do all the work, and Casanovas would get a 7 percent royalty on every sale. McCready scrounged together $30,000 and launched W.E.I. (World Enterprises International).

<P>
''I was clueless about the industry,'' admits McCready about the early days. As a result, he got fleeced. McCready signed on a manufacturer in Barcelona who was assembling the watches from imported components. One of W.E.I.'s models had to be recalled just days after it was put on the market. Customers complained that their watches were broken by the time they got home.

<P>
Still, the market's response was remarkable. ''We originally made about 5,000 watches,'' says McCready. ''We went to seven or eight of the best design and gift stores in Barcelona -- and sold them all in less than five days.''

<P>
Spring Forward, All Others Fall Back

<P>
McCready reinvested the profits, found a better factory in France, and developed 15 new models in two months. ''As far as I know, we were the first company in the world to change the numbers on a watch dial to standardize them to a certain language,'' he says. To keep any direct competitors at bay, McCready immediately patented the designs. Like ''Coca-Cola,'' he explains, no one can imitate the brand's name -- or look -- without risking legal consequences. With 27 different design patents, W.E.I. has virtually closed the loop on copycat manufacturers.

<P>
But that doesn't mean others haven't tried. Soon after W.E.I. introduced its first line, another watchmaker aggressively came onto the scene. ''They were going around to the stores and telling everybody that we were copying them,'' McCready says. ''They even carried false documents.'' 

<P>
The Catalonian government stepped in and put a stop to it. Now, W.E.I.'s presence in Catalonia has grown to the point where serious competition poses little threat. The Catalan watch line has expanded to dozens of models. Some feature caricatures of famous Catalans, including sports and film stars, artists, and fashion models. Others sport the official logo or mascot of Barcelona's soccer team. ''We've relied on a lot of marketing techniques, since advertising is so expensive,'' he says. ''These collections got us a lot of attention and did wonders for our credibility.''

<P>
A few months ago, W.E.I. started exporting its watches to Taiwan, where the novelty of the design has fueled brisk sales. McCready expects to pull in $3 million this year.

<P>
Now McCready is eyeing potential markets in South America and the United States. ''I think it's important for start-up businesses to realize that to succeed, you don't have to do everything right,'' he says. ''You just have to do enough things right, and it will compensate for the mistakes.''

<HR><BR>
