<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>9DirSell</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">DIRECT SELLING </FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>BY DUNCAN MAXWELL ANDERSON </P></CENTER><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Building to $1 Billion</FONT>
</CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> Shaperite's Strategy: Quiet and Unstoppable</H3><BR>
</CENTER>

<P>
Greg Martin says his family's company, Shaperite Concepts Ltd., is ''the biggest company that nobody's heard of.'' With $50 million in wholesale sales for 1995, Shaperite has kept a low profile since Greg, his brother Scott and their mother, Donna, started it seven and a half years ago in Salt Lake City. Greg, 37, is Shaperite's CEO. This year, he is a regional finalist for the Ernst &amp; Young ''Entrepreneur of the Year'' award. 

<P>
<B>Why did you start Shaperite?
</B>
<P>
We were looking for a business we could do as a family -- a ''pleasant opportunity.'' We were all self-employed at the time. I was running a company that recovered platinum from catalytic converters on automobiles and resold it. My brother Scott had a small ad agency.

<P>
<B>How did you decide on a business?
</B>
<P>
We were introduced to a fellow who was importing an herbal product from Belgium and selling it to weight lifters through a catalog for energy enhancement and weight control. We called it Metabolite. We considered mass-market retailing, infomercial marketing, and a few other methods, but we didn't have much money, so direct selling made the most sense. 

<P>
<B>Was it easy to sell?
</B>
<P>
Well, we needed to explain that there was a tradition of botanicals. At this point, in 1989, the only herbs most people were familiar with were illegal -- the kind you rolled up and smoked. We put together about $100,000 from personal savings and so on, enough for a computer system and inventory. We called and wrote to people we knew to get them to come to our kickoff meeting. Our second month in business, we did more than $100,000 in volume. 

<P>
<B>That's quite a growth curve.
</B>
<P>
It was. Then we developed quality-control problems -- tablets were breaking during shipment from Belgium. By the fourth month, our sales were down to $25,000. We didn't know what to do. We'd put all our money into this. We got local suppliers and started doing the blending ourselves. There were days we didn't feel like coming to work, but we just persisted. 

<P>
In 1991, we created Shapefast, a weight control product. That really put us on track. We went from $1 million to $19 million in 1992. We've added products to the line, such as antioxidants, enzymes, and a fruit-and-vegetable supplement, so we don't have all our eggs in one basket.

<P>
<B>What did you study in college to prepare for running a company like this at 36?
</B>
<P>
I majored in Japanese at Brigham Young University. Like a lot of young men in the Latter-Day Saints Church, I did missionary work for two years. Mine was in Japan -- knocking on doors, stopping people on street corners. It was selling, really. 

<P>
<B>Is this why there are so many direct-selling companies in Utah? All those young men who get practice as missionaries?
</B>
<P>
I don't know that I could make that generalization. . . . But it's true that for missionaries, development is centered around keeping motivated, energized. * You are taught to sell the idea of the faith. Maybe there is a connection.

<P>
<B>Does it worry you that you have so many competitors with similar products?
</B>
<P>
It's true that a lot of companies offer good products that do about the same thing. What's going to make the difference is being innovative in designing products, in developing leaders, and in recognizing achievement. When people are new, you teach them the science of the business: selling techniques, sponsoring, lead generation. At the top levels, we're talking about the art of the business: financial skills, emotional skills, leadership.

<P>
<B>What are your plans for Shaperite?
</B>
<P>
We've been building a foundation to be a mammoth company. By design, we've stayed relatively unknown. We wanted to position ourselves outside the flash and hoopla of the industry. We haven't attracted the kind of people who are in it for the quick hit. We're building to be a $1 billion company by 2002.

<P>
<B>That sounds incredibly ambitious. 
</B>
<P>
Our observation is that $50 million is the point at which a number of companies entered ''momentum.'' Nu Skin, Microsoft, Reebok, and Federal Express grew by multiples when they reached that number. We did $50 million in wholesale sales in 1995, and we're on track for $100 million in 1996. With 150,000 distributors and the foundation we've built, we'll be ready. *

<P><BR><BR><HR><BR>
<FONT COLOR=#5A0158>WINNERS</FONT><BR>


<FONT SIZE="+3">A Broker's Richest Deal</FONT>
<P>
With a smile built into his voice, he has the smooth confidence of a veteran deal maker with a will of iron.

<P>
In his early business life, Jim Moyles worked for IBM and then for the famous investment firm Lehman Brothers. Then he went into the mergers and acquisitions business on his own in Clearwater, Fla., where he now lives, helping $5 million-to-$10 million companies buy each other. But he got the network marketing bug when a friend of his son's invited him to an MLM opportunity meeting.

<P>
The first few companies Moyles joined didn't work out, but in 1991, he heard that Rexall Showcase International Inc. was growing fast. He decided to try it. 

<P>
Moyles brought his broker's skills to the task of building his organization. He says: ''This business is based on four critical skills: sponsoring; training; teaching others to sponsor; and teaching others to train. If I want to show someone the business, most often I'll say, 'Let's have lunch,' but I never pretend it's purely a social occasion. I explain on the phone, 'I've been doing some interesting things I want to tell you about.' I use a 'rifle-shot' approach. I don't try to sponsor someone unless I think he'd be successful.''

<P>
When Moyles's sales and commission checks came to $4,000 per month, he phased out his M&amp;A business and devoted himself to Rexall. When he hit $50,000 per month, he was able to sign his skeptical sister. When he made it to $80,000 per month, he signed his even more skeptical brother, who is a podiatrist.

<P>
At this point, Moyles makes more than $1 million per year in commissions. ''This is the biggest thing I've ever done,'' he says. ''And I'm looking forward to next year.'' a

<P><BR><HR><BR>
<FONT COLOR=#5A0158>UPDATES</FONT>

<P>
<FONT SIZE="+3">A Time for Action
</FONT>
<P>
At this year's annual meeting of the Direct Selling Association in Phoenix, two freshmen U.S. Congressmen proclaimed that they're long-time Amway distributors. Rep. Sue Myrick of North Carolina and Rep. Jon Christensen of Nebraska told the crowd of 500 honchos and distributors that they must become more politically active this fall to protect their businesses against anti-entrepreneurial forces such as the liability lawyers and organized labor.

<P>
* According to the famous polling organization Wirthlin Worldwide, 42 percent of the generalpublic have a favorable impression of direct selling. The main reason 54 percent have an unfavorable impression: pressure to buy or to join the organization. . . . The DSA says direct-sales distributors in the U.S. now number 7.2 million. They were responsible for $18 billion in retail sales last 
year -- up from $16.6 billion the year before.

<P>
FreeLife International of Milford, Conn., has introduced a supplement that features pharmaceutical-grade DHEA (dihydroepiandrosterone), a ''youth'' hormone produced in the body's adrenal glands that appears to forestall age-related diseases, such as obesity, cardiovascular disease, diabetes, cancer, and osteoporosis. Your body's production of this hormone plummets after your early 20s. Articles on the benefits of DHEA supplements have appeared in The Lancet and The New England Journal of Medicine.

<P>
After his interview in SUCCESS ("Direct Selling," June 1996), Prof. William Crookston of the University of Southern California got so many phone inquiries, he's planning a one-day seminar this fall at USC in Los Angeles on ''An Entrepreneurial Approach to MLM.'' For details, fax your mailing address to 310-395-7293. 

