<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>9PersPower</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">PERSONAL POWER </FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>BY KATHERINE CALLAN </P></CENTER><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Your Warrior Spirit</FONT>
</CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> An Olympic Coach's Formula for Mental Toughness</H3><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Sports psychologist Jim Loehr says stress can be good for you. Just as athletes protect themselves by practicing the skills they need in performance on the field, entrepreneurs should do exercises that build the strengths they need most in business. Exposure to the right stress trains you to face your fears and continue the fight. Loehr says his strategy can toughen your mind for victory. 

<P>
''Entrepreneurs are the athletes of all athletes,'' says Loehr, who has trained golfer Nick Faldo, tennis stars, and speed skater Dan Jansen. ''But they don't train to become tougher. The brutality of their playing field can take them apart.'' 

<P>
From their headquarters in Orlando, Fla., Loehr and his partners, Jack Groppel and Pat Etcheberry, have applied their studies in sports science to teach corporate players to perform at their best. They combine exercise, recovery patterns, and visualization techniques to achieve an ''Ideal Performance State.''

<P>
''If you took a group of 50 business owners and determined who could endure the most physical stress, it would be those who'd been exposed to the most physical stress,'' says Loehr. ''We teach people to charge forward and become stress seekers.''  

<P>
The goal of increasing your capacity for stress can be achieved by following these principles:

<P>
* Strengthen your midsection. ''The foundation of mental toughness is grounded in the physical,'' says Loehr. ''You want to develop a tremendous capacity for absorbing physical stress.'' Your midsection determines your posture and breathing. It also supports the lower back -- one of the core places where corporate warriors store stress and anger. Excessive stress can cause your back to go out.  To build your midsection, Loehr prescribes 100 stomach crunches daily.

<P>
* Practice interval training. ''Life is very stop and go,'' says Loehr. ''You've got to be able to charge forward and then shut down in an instant.'' Corporate warriors should work out for 30 minutes every day, practicing interval training. If you're a walker, walk fast and then slowly. Contrast stress with recovery. ''Recovery is when the actual growth takes place,'' says Loehr. On the field or in business, you've got to push yourself hard and then recover by sleeping, eating well, and establishing outlets for stress, which can be as simple as laughing or listening to music. 

<P>
Your Ideal Performance State

<P>
Your Ideal Performance State (IPS) is relaxed, confident, and highly energetic. It is a unique response to stress that allows your talents to surface. Loehr studied top athletes to determine what was going on when they were performing at their best. Historically, most coaches and players focused on actual playing time. But in many sports, such as tennis, as much as 80 percent of a match is spent between points. Clearly, what players think between points is crucial to their performance. Champions told Loehr they flooded their minds with positive images to prevent negative ones from hurting their performance. They used every free second to recover from the previous point and put themselves in their best emotional state to win the next one. 

<P>
Use time in between critical tasks to recover from job-related stress and prepare for your next challenge. Replace unstructured breaks with powerful recovery breaks. Loehr recommends rotating exercise, breathing, and nutrition breaks. 

<P>
* Develop performer skills. Acting ''as if'' you feel a particular way can get the chemistry moving in that direction. If you're giving a deal-clinching presentation, focus like a laser on a past event loaded with the emotions you are trying to summon. Recreate what you were like, and your body will respond with real biochemical changes. 

<P>
* Practice winning rituals.  When you feel most energized, how much sleep did you get? Try to go to bed and wake up close to the same time every day. Establish a consistent schedule of eating and drinking, with a minimum of five small meals a day. With so much of your life out of control, highly ritualized routines will increase your effectiveness. 

<P>
''World-class stress is the basis for world-class toughness,'' says Loehr. By training your body for peak performance, you can rise to the occasion when the pressure is on. 
<HR><BR>
<DIV ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="1" CELLSPACING="5" WIDTH="470">

