<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">REVIEWS: BOOKS AND TAPES </FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>BY DUNCAN MAXWELL ANDERSON </P></CENTER><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Success and the Soul</FONT>
</CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> ''How We Made $3 Billion by Putting God First''</H3><BR>
</CENTER>


<P>* The Soul of the Firm, <BR>
by C. William Pollard, Chairman of ServiceMaster Industries Inc.</P>

<P>When C. William (Bill) Pollard reported for his first day's work as
a senior vice president at ServiceMaster in Downers Grove, Ill., in 1977,
he was handed a mop and told to join the crew cleaning floors, bathrooms,
and toilets over at Lutheran General Hospital. His salary as senior VP
was less than he'd earned five years earlier as a lawyer -- but like all
ServiceMaster employees, he had stock options and incentives. He did quite
well, with the mop and as a manager, and today he is chairman. The company
has grown 20-fold. Shares are worth $3 billion, and the payroll numbers
200,000. Return on investment is 100 percent today. In short, it's doing
something right. </P>

<P>In The Soul of the Firm, Pollard cheerfully insists that ServiceMaster
makes all that money not by focusing on the bottom line -- but rather,
by putting God first. Few chairmen would operate that way, let alone admit
it to shareholders. The company mission is chiseled into the marble at
headquarters and emblazoned on its annual reports: ''To honor God in all
we do/To help people develop/ To pursue excellence/To grow profitably.''
</P>

<P>ServiceMaster companies specialize in doing menial work well. Pollard
says that its Christian tradition, in recognizing the dignity of manual
labor, inspires employees, makes customers happy, and returns profits back
to employees, who own 20 percent of the company. ''People want to work
for a cause, not just for a living,'' says Pollard. </P>

<P>Shirley, a ServiceMaster employee, wields a mop at a 250-bed hospital.
She knows her work is important, partly, says Pollard, because ServiceMaster
continually improves her tools, such as her equipment and cleaning chemicals.
But mostly, she knows because she is always reminded that she is working
for people. As she puts it, ''This place would be closed if we didn't have
housekeeping.'' </P>

<P>Pollard says it is conducive to profit to see management questions as
moral ones. Bureaucracy's ineffectiveness grows out of the fact that it
commits evil. Borrowing from Catholic tradition, Pollard (a Protestant)
cites the principle of subsidiarity: ''It is a grave injustice to steal
a person's ability to make a decision'' by hijacking the matter to a higher
level of authority than necessary. </P>

<P>Pollard argues that Henry Ford had it backward when he asked, ''Why
is it that I always get the whole person, when what I really want is a
pair of hands?'' People aren't production units. The value they put into
their work grows out of their value as persons -- not in spite of it. Says
Pollard: ''It is not just what we are doing, but what we are becoming in
the process that gives us our distinct value.'' </P>

<P>* Sales Shock, <BR>
by Mack Hanan.* </P>

<P>In Sales Shock, sales consultant and guru Mack Hanan says, ''Selling
has proved to be a failed concept.'' Prepare for a new reality. </P>

<P>How much value does a salesman or saleswoman add for the customer? As
goods become commodities, almost nothing. It's no coincidence, says Hanan,
that in the final quarter of John Aker's tenure at IBM, there were record
sales and a record, multimillion-dollar loss on the bottom line. Wal-Mart
simply refuses to do business with salesmen. It just buys what it wants
and deducts what the commissions would have been from the purchase price.
</P>

<P>In the future, which is here, price is so competitive, it's no longer
even set by suppliers. Here are some of Hanan's rules for playing the more
creative, less stressful, and highly profitable ''co-management'' game
-- an alliance for joint gain. </P>

<P>* Improve your customer's competitiveness -- not your own selling strategy.
</P>

<P>* Generate new revenues for customers -- don't just cut their costs.
</P>

<P>* Make your objective profit accumulation -- not market share. </P>

<P>Become a ''general contractor'' for your ultimate customer. Drug companies,
instead of just selling drugs, become partners with HMOs to take over patient
care, specializing in major chronic diseases such as asthma, diabetes,
ulcers, epilepsy, and depression. The idea is that everyone who is involved
(including the patient) has a stake in prevention, in keeping the patient
healthy, and everyone shares in the profits. </P>

<P>Memos From the Chairman, <BR>
by Alan C. Greenberg. </P>

<P>According to Alan C. Greenberg, the chairman of The Bear Stearns Companies,
the incredibly successful investment bank, the basic business temptation
is to ascribe your successes to your innate wonderfulness, rather than
to action you have taken. In his book, Memos From the Chairman, Greenberg
says, quoting a fictitious consultant: ''Thou wilt do well in commerce
as long as thou dost not believe thine own odor to be perfume.'' </P>

<P>Greenberg's style bespeaks a kind of stinginess with leverage: ''It's
been pointed out to me that the tendency is to cut expenses when things
are tough. . . . When things are good, you should be even more careful
of expenses because it is ridiculous to leave anything on the table when
you hold a royal flush.'' He instructs employees to save paper clips. </P>

<P>He looks at the seemingly small things as critical to the future of
the company, such as employees who don't return phone calls promptly. He
asks to be informed directly if anyone has been lax in this area, and he
offers a cash bounty to anyone who reports possible ethical violations,
such as concealing trades or disclosing client information. </P>

<P>Greenberg also uses positive thinking when others might be negative:
''The best time to hire productive people is when conditions are difficult.
Areas of Wall Street are having problems, and that means opportunity once
again is knocking.'' </P>

<P>Greenberg's personnel policy: ''Our first desire is to promote from
within. If somebody with an MBA degree applies for a job, we will certainly
not hold it against him, but we are really looking for PSD degrees.'' PSD:
''poor, smart, and a deep desire to become rich.'' </P>



<P>* The Genius Formula, <BR>
by Tony Buzan With <BR>
Raymond Keene. </P>

<P>Tony Buzan is a brain specialist -- not a surgeon, but someone who makes
a business helping people discover more inside their minds. With his collaborator
on this audiotape, Raymond Keene, he offers a short course in genius. </P>

<P>Boxer Muhammad Ali used his psychological genius to make his own victory
seem inevitable in opponents' minds. </P>

<P>Before a fight, Ali would call a press conference to predict a string
of events -- most were within his own power to fulfill, and irrelevant
to the fight. He called it his vision. ''I see me training in the mountains
while my opponent breathes air pollution in the city. . . .'' Ali goes
on to say he will have a special chef making special food to make him strong.
On fight night, Ali will be wearing a purple robe, he predicts. He goes
on to predict events in each round of the fight: ''In the second round,
he's gonna be sweating. . . .'' Ali intones. As the fight draws near, Ali
issues press releases that confirm each prediction to date, which are dutifully
noted in the papers -- and in his opponent's camp. Ali has sparring partners
leave his own training camp, telling reporters they've suffered broken
noses and ribs. By the time the fight comes, the opponent has seen an intimidating
string of predictions come to life. In the second round, Ali grabs his
opponent in a clinch and growls ominously, ''I told you you'd be sweating;
and you're sweating.'' Of course the man's sweating -- it's an athletic
contest. But it's a ''prediction come true.'' Cumulatively, these devices
destroy the opponent's concentration and effectiveness, and start him unconsciously
playing his part in Ali's script -- and getting knocked out on schedule
in the round predicted. </P>


<P>. </P>

