<HEAD><TITLE>9Fran1</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">FRANCHISING: POWER PLAYERS </FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>BY CAROL STEINBERG </P></CENTER><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Aaron's Amazing Journey</FONT>
</CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> How a Franchising-Shy $240 Million Company Plunged In</H3><BR>
</CENTER>

<P>
In the corporate boardroom at Aaron Rents Inc., an old folding chair shines in a glass case like a million-dollar piece of art. Emblazoned with an Aaron Rents sticker on its back, the relic was discovered at a barn auction in Georgia. It's part of the original inventory R. Charles (Charlie) Loudermilk Sr. rented when he founded the company in 1955.

<P>
The stature given this basic commodity symbolizes the history that drives the $240 million Atlanta institution. In its hometown, the Aaron name is as recognizable as Coca-Cola. 

<P>
For most of its 40 years, the furniture, electronics, and appliance rental company flourished with corporate stores. But in 1992, Loudermilk made a tough decision: He hesitantly turned to franchising in order to allow his company to grow further. For this Atlanta powerbroker, the very idea of abdicating control was heartrending. Protective of the company's stellar reputation, he didn't want to chance tarnishing it. The risk of losing what he had built was enormous.

<P>
The restructuring of this old-line company illustrates how an entrepreneur can implement a franchising strategy without losing sight of his company's past and his vision for the future.

<P>
Discovering the Rental Market

<P>
It's easy to understand Loudermilk's hesitancy to launch into franchising when one hears him talk about the company's origins. The gray-haired Loudermilk's eyes glitter with pride. His voice gets animated, revealing his excitement. It sounds as though he's telling the story for the first time, yet he can likely recite it in his sleep. 

<P>
At 26 years old, he had put an ad in the Yellow Pages to rent ''almost everything.'' He borrowed $500 from a local bank; a pots-and-pans salesman contributed $500. They bought 300 used Army surplus chairs and rented them for 10 cents each a day. Loudermilk's partner quickly bailed out. Loudermilk opened a tiny store in Atlanta. He listened to customers and expanded inventory to include chafing dishes, china, tents, and sickroom supplies. He opened more stores, captured in black-and-white snapshots on the wall. 

<P>
''I thought if I did $1 million, it would be the end of the world,'' says the chairman and CEO. The core rental division now has 110 company stores. 

<P>
About eight years ago, Loudermilk ''wanted to find another horse to ride.'' He saw the emerging rent-to-own concept as the wave of the future. Customers can own necessities and luxuries -- even diamond rings -- at the end of a payment plan or return them beforehand. In 1988, Loudermilk opened rental purchase boutiques in several rental showrooms. By 1992, the company had 19 rental purchase stores. Loudermilk decided he wanted to build a national chain. 

<P>
But, because of its long-term payment plans, the rental business is management intensive. Aaron grew via company stores only as fast as its ability to find good managers. To grow at the rate he wanted, Loudermilk turned to franchising ''out of necessity.'' 

<P>
For years, he held the business close to his vest. The company went public in 1982; Loudermilk owns 59 percent of voting shares and 20 percent of nonvoting shares. Franchising would mean further disclosure -- sharing day-to-day operating information.

<P>
''Aaron Rents is like a child to me,'' Loudermilk waxes sentimentally. At one point, he even considered franchising under a different brand so Aaron Rents wouldn't be tarnished if it turned out that things went amiss. 

<P>
Well-connected, Loudermilk shunned franchise consultants in favor of seeking advice from local friends/franchisors. Among them: Guy Millner, chairman of Atlanta-based Norrell Corp. Loudermilk is now treasurer of Millner's senatorial campaign.

<P>
Calculated Growth

<P>
In 1992, Loudermilk forged ahead with his franchising program -- with two caveats. ''We decided to franchise only if we could structure it so that the stores would be run in the same quality that we've run our stores over all these years,'' he says. ''Therefore, we are demanding franchisees to hold a higher standard than maybe someone would like to do.'' Second, Loudermilk wanted hard numbers from company prototypes so potential franchisees could ''taste it, smell it, feel it.''

<P>
Loudermilk quietly recruited a director of franchise development, Todd Evans. Although young and not a heavy hitter, Evans had ''get up and go . . . a fresh perspective,'' says Ken Butler, president of the rental purchase division. Evans learned the business inside out. He worked at stores and even built furniture at a company factory. Today, franchisees must train 10 days in an Aaron's store. ''I don't want anyone in the system who doesn't really feel good about our company,'' says Loudermilk. 

<P>
Aaron paid for its franchise development and experimentation through its solid rent-to-rent division. The game plan was to go slowly, ''proving each step of the way before we take the next step,'' says Loudermilk. 

<P>
He learned this lesson when he tried to expand his rent-to-rent division too quickly. In 1989, with 186 rental stores, Aaron had grown beyond its management capability. It sold or swapped about 50 stores. Loudermilk notes, ''My job is to monitor how fast we grow so that doesn't happen again.'' 

<P>
In 1993, the company hit 10 franchises. Now, one new Aaron's Rental Purchase -- corporate or franchise -- premieres every six days. The rental-purchase division has 112 company stores and 42 franchises with $88.2 million in systemwide revenues. In the next 30 months, at least 95 more franchises should open. 

<P>
Learning From Mistakes

<P>
In the process of building its franchise division, Aaron Rents has experienced some glitches. Notes C. Marks Hinton Jr., managing director of Equitable Securities Corp., Nashville: ''Aaron Rents hasn't always done everything right, but [the principals] have done pretty well learning from their mistakes.''

<P>
Loudermilk may be his own worst critic. This street fighter bluntly admits errors and accepts blame. His vision was to move rental purchase stores from back alleys to main street locations -- just as Blockbuster Inc. did. Dwarfing the industry's average 2,500-square-foot store, he built a 5,000-square-foot prototype. Aaron pushed the envelope further to 10,000 square feet.

<P>
Then, nearly two years ago, the company built six corporate stores at 25,000 square feet. But these giants proved cumbersome, inventory intensive -- and unprofitable. After nine months, the company put in clearance centers to absorb excess space. It now believes 8,000-to-10,000 square feet is the magic number.

<P>
Originally, Aaron Rents looked for mom-and-pop franchisees. The maintenance was enormous. ''We spent more time and effort on franchised stores than our own, and it simply did not work out,'' concedes Loudermilk. 

<P>
The company now pursues area development. Total capital expenditures for a franchise is $183,850 to $373,400. Unlike start-up franchisors, it eases the way for multistore ownership by guaranteeing 100 percent inventory financing through SunTrust Banks Inc. Evans keeps mentioning the chain's ''store stupid'' approach. ''We do everything to make the stores operate more efficiently and to make it as easy as possible for the store managers just to sell,'' he says. Sophisticated software tracks product orders and invoices.

<P>
Redefining a Market

<P>
Loudermilk wants to go down in history as rewriting the rules in the rental-purchase market. Industry experts and franchisees credit him with revamping a poor industry image. ''Charlie is probably more of a quantified risk taker than others,'' says Bill Keese, executive director of the Association of Progressive Rental Organizations, Austin, Tex. ''He's a leader in a lot of areas.'' 

<P>
Initially, Aaron's Rental Purchase mimicked competitors. Even Evans says he was appalled at the stores' ''sleaziness.'' Loudermilk again tapped his deep-rooted practice of listening to customers. 

<P>
The first policy to change: In 1991, Aaron rolled out a 12-month payment plan. The industry norm is 18 to 24 months. Aaron benefits from shorter turnaround time and increased rentals. Consumers end up paying less money. 

<P>
Then, Aaron opened brighter and more spacious stores in A-plus locations. Larger stores enable the company to showcase furniture. Half of its inventory is made by its manufacturing division, MacTavish Furniture Industries. High-tech merchandise includes satellites, computers, cellular phones, large-screen TVs. 

<P>
The goal was to create an atmosphere where customers would walk in the door and say Wow! ''It's just a simple philosophy of how you present the product,'' says Loudermilk. 

<P>
Loudermilk, who was raised in a poor Atlanta neighborhood, wants customers to hold their heads high when they shop at Aaron. The chain's motto is: ''Kill 'em with kindness.'' Managers are instructed to greet customers by name. For thirsty customers, stores stock Cokes and coffee. Customers receive $100 if they find a lower price elsewhere. They're asked to fill out satisfaction surveys.

<P>
Loudermilk still wants more customer input and more inventory.

<P>
''We're doing a good job, but we could be doing better,'' he says. 

<P>
Like Wal-Mart, Aaron passes on volume discounts to customers. ''Our strategy is to see how cheaply we can rent it, yet make the desired profit,'' says Loudermilk. Some analysts and competitors question the profitability of larger stores and shorter payments. Few have followed. For example, Mitchell Fadel, CEO and president of ColorTyme Inc., says he ''can't make the 12-month numbers work'' at his 314-unit franchise chain.

<P>
Aaron insiders say critics are missing the point: the domino effect. Monthly revenues at an average industry store are $40,000.

<P>
Butler agrees stores won't make money on the 12-month plan at that volume. But Aaron averages $80,000 per month. Average profit margins match the industry's 12 percent to 14 percent. ''The secret to our success is 80 percent of our customers re-rent something else,'' says Butler. ''If you offer better products and terms, you'll get more revenues.'' 

<P>
The new image works wonders for franchisee Greg Smith, who converted three independent shops in 1993. He recently moved a store to Prichard, Ala., for its more visible location at double the size. In three months, revenues rose 40 percent.

<P>
Becoming a National Giant

<P>
The franchisor pursues area developers who are sophisticated businesspeople with retail or rental backgrounds.

<P>
They must understand Aaron's customer base. ''It's not glamorous,'' declares Butler. Drawn by the company's successful, decades-old history, well-heeled investors are buying in. 

<P>
Area developer Mike Kelly was an Aaron customer in the sixties. He's impressed by the chain's longevity and operating prowess.

<P>
Kelly used to own five Blockbuster franchises and was closed out of opening more in Georgia. Here, he says, ''I feel I have a window of opportunity on the ground floor. I'm trying to carve out as much territory as possible.''

<P>
Kelly; his partner, Ron Herman; and vice president of operations Ken Faulkner plan 15 stores in Georgia, Kentucky, Ohio, and Tennessee. They've opened nine so far, earning 15 percent to 20 percent pretax profit on $6 million in revenues. 

<P>
This breed of high-flying franchisee garners corporate attention. ''Corporate staff pays us respect as elitist entrepreneurs, not as stepchildren,'' says Herman. 

<P>
The company believes strongly in company/franchise coexistence. ''If franchises fault, and they will, we have the ability to go in and run these stores,'' explains Loudermilk. So far, it's bought back four stores from two franchisees; one relocated, one was undercapitalized. It intentionally tests ideas in corporate units to spare franchisees hard knocks. Energetic corporate executives are challenged to operate out of the box. The company is expanding in concentric circles from its four distribution centers. Franchises fill smaller markets, while company units dominate major metro areas.

<P>
Franchisees' Healthy Criticism

<P>
Today, Loudermilk, 69, concedes franchisees help him see ''the forest for the trees.'' He calls owners for operating feedback. ''When a company is as large as ours, people get intimidated and are afraid to make criticisms,'' Loudermilk says. ''Franchisees are not. That's very healthy.'' Still, Loudermilk's vision clearly steers the company. ''His finger is on every button,'' says Kelly.

<P>
Loudermilk takes a commanding position in his hometown, too. He fields calls about a new community bank he's starting. A replica of an Olympics memorial he funded in downtown Atlanta sits in his office. He ran Andrew Young's mayoral campaign. Photos flaunt Loudermilk with former Presidents at his sprawling plantation in Coolidge, Ga. He revitalized that small shanty town with two furniture factories, sewer systems, and baseball fields. 

<P>
The company also guards an enviable banking relationship. Half of a $75 million line of credit is untapped, providing ready funds for acquisitions. Aaron, the fourth-largest player in the industry, is considering that strategy. So far, a demanding Loudermilk has been turned off by potential candidates' inflated prices and poor management. The chain's biggest competitors are growing through consolidation: Rent-A-Center operates 1,206 franchise and company units; Renters Choice Inc., together with recently acquired ColorTyme, has 644 stores. 

<P>
No question, Loudermilk wants to catch up to the Goliaths. His thirst for recognition and growth is enormous. Toward that, he recently launched a $500,000 national ad campaign, tied to the Atlanta Braves games. Notes Loudermilk: ''To me, it's a statement saying, 'We aren't national now, but we will be.' '' 
