<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">CAN THIS BUSINESS BE FRANCHISED? </FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>BY MEG WHITTEMORE </P></CENTER><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Auto Tech Inc.</FONT>
</CENTER>


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>
<TH ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>Founders:</TH>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	Walter Fritz Sr. and Walter Fritz Jr. 
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>
<TH ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>Business:</TH>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	An auto repair shop for luxury cars. 
	</TD></P>
</TR>

<P>><TH ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>Headquarters:</TH>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	Stamford, Conn
	</TD>. </P>

<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>
<P><TH ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>Year Founded:</TH> 
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	1968.
	</TD> </P>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>
<P><TH ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>Number of Locations:</TH>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	 One.
	</TD> </P>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>
<P><TH ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>Capital Requirements: </TH></P><P>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>
	$170,000.
	</TD> </P>
</TR>

<P><TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP>
<TH ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP>1995 Annual Sales: </TH></P>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="2">
	<P>$1 million.</P>
	</TD>

</TR>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P>Our panel of experts examine a business to determine its franchise potential.
</P>

<P>By the year 2000, Walter Fritz Sr. and Walter Fritz Jr. hope to have
the dominant auto repair franchise for expensive European cars. They're
off to a roaring start. Last year, father and son tallied more than $1
million in sales from Auto Tech Inc., their independent repair shop. </P>

<P>The 28-year-old company began specializing in European cars about 10
years ago. ''The car industry changed a great deal back then,'' explains
Fritz Jr. ''Cars built in the mid-1980s to early 1990s were more reliable,
which meant less work for independent repair shops like ours.'' </P>

<P>The advent of computerized devices under the hood also forced independent
shops to rethink their strategy. ''It was too tough to service all kinds
of cars,'' says Fritz. ''So much equipment and in-depth know-how is needed.''
</P>

<P>Fritz did some market research and discovered that high-end European
cars such as Mercedes-Benz and Saab were being serviced primarily by local
dealerships -- not independent shops. He bought customer lists and launched
a direct-mail campaign, listing specials for oil and filter changes, air
conditioning service, wheel alignment, and 15,000- and 30,000-mile tune-ups.
Coupons for added services such as cleaning and waxing were also part of
the direct mailer. And Fritz made sure that his prices were 20 percent
lower than the competitions'. </P>

<P>Fritz loves challenging the European car dealers head on. ''They've
had their chance at this market niche,'' he says. ''Now it's our turn.''
Fritz offers his repeat customers more discounts through a membership club
savings plan. He undercuts other independent auto shops in parts, too,
because he can afford to keep stock in-house instead of always having to
reorder. ''It keeps the turnaround time for the customer down to a minimum,''
he says. </P>

<P>The toughest part is persuading car owners to give Auto Tech a try.
Fritz still uses direct mail to reach customers. There is a separate mailer
for each type of European car. Every direct-mail piece offers a free item
and highlights Auto Tech's reputation as a well-established family business.
Last year, the company posted pretax profits of $240,000. </P>

<P>Fritz rolls out the red carpet for every customer. ''We make sure they
are comfortable while they are here,'' he says. ''Our mechanics specialize
in the cars they service.'' He believes his prices and direct mailers get
customers to his shop, and his personal approach and quality service keep
them coming back. </P>

<P>Fritz currently has six full-time employees. In the future, he plans
to go after Asian-made cars. He also wants to target domestic cars as well
as sport utility vehicles. Fritz would like to expand regionally through
franchising but questions the viability of translating his highly specialized
business into a turnkey operation. </P>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT COLOR="#5A0158">Expert Analysis</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P><B>Ann Dugan, </B>director of the Small Business Development Center
at the University of Pittsburgh. </P>

<P><B>Edward Kushell, </B>president of Franchise Consulting Group, Los
Angeles. </P>

<P><B>Warren Lewis, </B>a Washington, D.C.-based franchise lawyer. </P>

<P>''Auto Tech is dedicated to customer satisfaction and reliable service
in an industry notorious for its poor treatment of customers,'' says Edward
Kushell. ''Franchisees are going to have to be vigilant about that area
of the business, since it's been the cornerstone of the company's success.''
</P>

<P>Fritz concedes that finding good mechanics is the biggest challenge.
''We keep our mechanics by paying them well, keeping them fully trained,
and deepening their knowledge of the industry,'' he says. He plans to train
franchisees personally to ensure consistency from location to location.
</P>

<P>Kushell gives Auto Tech the thumbs up on its profitability and marketing
know-how. But he doesn't like the idea of expanding into domestic vehicles.
''By doing that, they start to look like every other auto repair shop,''
he says. ''The more you go into other areas, the less you are really specializing.''
</P>

<P>Concerns were raised about the company's expansion outside Connecticut.
Fritz plans to grow cautiously but intends eventually to have a national
presence. ''Care has to be taken when looking at the markets that will
support this kind of business,'' says Warren Lewis. Fritz agrees, saying
his intention is to make sure the market resembles Stamford before opening
a location. </P>

<P>The experts were split on whether new start-up locations or conversion
expansion was the best strategy. ''I have a gut feeling that they would
be better off with new start-ups,'' says Kushell. Traditionally, conversions
of existing businesses are most successful when there is a nationally known
name coming in. </P>

<P>But Dugan likes the idea of conversions, reasoning that it will keep
start-up costs down and give struggling independent shops a new lease on
life. </P>

<P>Kushell thinks that the start-up costs of $170,000 may be low. He cautions
Fritz to consider raising the amount to reflect leasehold improvements
and the costs of attracting and retaining topflight mechanics. </P>

<P>Fritz says he is scouting for a single franchise consultant who will
''take care of the necessary documents and paperwork.'' The experts advise
against this. They suggest he get a lawyer who specializes in franchising
and augment that with an accountant who understands the franchise paradigm.
</P>

<P>Overall, the experts were attracted to Auto Tech as a business concept.
''These guys have a nice business with solid financials,'' says Dugan,
''and they know how to manage properly, reward their employees for good
work, and communicate with their customers. They should continue in their
success.''</P>



<P>If you know of a business you would like examined, we will send you
an analysis form. Write: Can This Business Be Franchised? Katherine Callan,
SUCCESS, 230 Park Ave., New York, NY 10169. </P>


