<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>9Harrell</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">WILSON HARRELL </FONT></P></CENTER>

<BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>This Is Your Future</FONT>
</CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> Every Entrepreneur Must Know How to Survive These Changes</H3><BR>
</CENTER>

<P>
The biggest difference between fast-growing companies and doomed dinosaur companies is ''which god they worship'' when it comes to business. Fortune-500 CEOs eagerly await the morning paper so they can turn to the financial section to see what grade their god -- Wall Street -- gave them yesterday. I know the Wall Street congregation is huge, and growing by leaps and bounds. But as the Good Book says, worshiping false gods is a sure path to torment. Wall Street, or any investment source, is a false god. If you design your business around pleasing it, in the end the business won't create anything of value to customers -- and will die. 

<P>
Successful entrepreneurs worship three gods -- their product, their customer, and their people. Once I said this in a presentation, and an entrepreneur raised his hand and asked, ''Do they worship all three gods all the time?'' My answer was, ''Yes, of course,'' and  I went on. But the question, which seemed simple at the time, wouldn't go away. I'd like to offer a more thoughtful answer.

<P>
At the early, or ''genius'' stage, when the entrepreneur is giving form to his inspiration for the first time and creating the company, he worships the product. From the time he awakes to the end of the day, and during most of the night, he's thinking: ''How can I make it better? How can I make it less expensive? How can I package it better? What should the advertising do?'' And so on. He knows that if he's defined a niche and fulfilled a consumer need, customers will come. And they do.

<P>
Once the company has grown to employ a team of racehorses, the entrepreneur becomes a ''benevolent dictator'' conforming them to his vision. And what is his vision? More and more customers. The customer becomes his new god. Customers are his obsession. Once he earns their loyalty, he becomes arrogant, an insufferable egomaniac -- because he has accomplished the impossible, changing people's lives from an inspiration in his genius mind. As far as he's concerned, he's on a roll, and nothing can stand in his way. If a Goliath -- a big company -- raises its head, there are plenty of rocks around for his slingshot.

<P>
As the company grows, the entrepreneur is forced to begin delegating real authority and responsibility, becoming a ''disinterested director.'' Not surprisingly, he begins to spend more and more of his time thinking about the human resources of his company. It isn't that the entrepreneur's product or service has become less important; it's that by now, there are specialists handling R&amp;D. As to customers, there are lots and lots of people serving them full-time. In this ''letting go'' stage, there is great danger. At many companies, the entrepreneurial world begins to disintegrate as bureaucracies form and internal politicking creates a deeply anti-entrepreneurial culture.

<P>
A new god has appeared that the entrepreneur must worship: his people. He wonders: ''How do I train them? Whom should I promote, and when? What incentives should I give them?'' And above all, ''How do I keep my vision from getting muddled as it passes through channels of command?'' 

<P>
Next, the entrepreneur enters the fourth and final stage of development: the ''visionary leader.'' He's running a large, professionally managed company. He's made it. And now a terrible temptation rears its ugly head. A dazzling but false god enters his domain, demanding his worship: money. Sometimes it goes by the name of Wall Street. Sometimes it's a venture capitalist partner. But always, it urges him to forget his product, his customers, and his people. Oh, he can give those things lip service, and even do some wonderful things; but unless he is a rare leader, he spends most of his time worrying about this quarter's profits compared with last year's -- and about how he will come off at the next directors' or stockholders' meeting. All those good things.

<P>
Visionary Dinosaurs?

<P>
If you start following that false god, I must warn you that there is a fifth stage to look forward to: I call it the ''dinosaur's trek.'' It's easy to find the way. You'll pass a number of guideposts: ''downsize,'' ''right-size,'' ''reengineer,'' ''fire the CEO,'' ''management takeover.'' And finally, one that says, ''Here lies the ghost of a great entrepreneur.'' Are there exceptions to this scenario? Of course. Is there an alternative? Absolutely. Just make sure all your people spend their time copying what you did back in Stage Two -- worshiping the customer. 

<P>
And you: Keep the faith, and take care of your people. If you do that, the entrepreneurial spirit of your company will be reborn in them again and again. 
<HR><BR>
