<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>ITEntrep</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">THE ENTREPRENEUR </FONT></P></CENTER>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Growing Up With Golf</FONT>
</CENTER>

<P>
Dominic Chang loved golf, but every hour he spent on the links meant time away from his wife and two young sons. His guilty conscience prevented him from thoroughly enjoying the game.

<P>
Chang figured plenty of other fathers shared his problem. So he designed an elaborate driving range where parents could perfect their swings while kids enjoyed miniature golf, a video arcade, and a snack bar. In 1992, he launched Family Golf Centers Inc. of Melville, N.Y.

<P>
But Chang didn't start the company just to ease his conscience. After 18 years in the banking industry, he'd risen to the top -- overseeing a staff of 1,000 and billions of dollars in assets. Despite his success, Chang felt unfulfilled. ''The job wasn't fun anymore,'' he says. ''I couldn't do it for the rest of my life and retire at 65.''

<P>
Chang was much more excited about his family golf concept than banking. He researched the golf market and discovered that during the real estate boom of the late 1980s, many driving ranges had been converted into shopping malls and condominiums. Golfers were in desperate need of places to practice.

<P>
His first Family Golf center cost $2.7 million to build. Chang put up 40 percent of his own money and got SBA and bank loans to cover the rest. Chang's plan was to build one new center every year. But his climate-controlled facilities were such an immediate hit, it became clear that this pace wasn't fast enough.

<P>
''Our model is fairly simple to duplicate,'' says Chang, who grew up in Taiwan. ''I didn't want to create a market for someone else.'' To gain critical mass and ward off potential competitors, he set about building a powerful, nationwide chain. To fund his aggressive expansion, Chang took the company public in 1994. Last year, Family Golf's 15 locations had revenues of $12.6 million. By the end of 1996, Chang expects to have 26 units generating $1 million to $2 million each.

<P>
In addition to constructing his own golf centers, Chang is buying out mom-and-pop operations. There are currently about 2,000 driving ranges in America. Chang plans to consolidate the industry and market golf to a broader audience.

<P>
''The demographics for golfers are changing,'' says the 47-year-old entrepreneur. ''Now, many women and kids are getting into the game. These people need a place where they can learn.''

<P>
Family Golf facilities have in-house pros who give clinics and private lessons. A summer golf camp caters to children. ''When you see parents coming back with their kids, you know you have done your job,'' says Chang. ''Besides, a family of four brings in a lot more revenue.''

<HR><BR>
