<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>ITHotOps</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">HOT OPPORTUNITIES </FONT></P></CENTER>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Excellent Expos</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
Trade shows are estimated to be a $16.5 billion-a-year industry. Entrepreneurs are leaping into this scintillating field by putting on their own shows and finding ways to improve existing ones. S.C. Promotions Inc.

<P>
Shael Buchen and Chris Huke have found a rewarding life through entrepreneurship. They are devoted to helping others do the same. Their $7 million company, S.C. Promotions Inc. of Englewood, Colo., produces a series of business opportunity shows across North America. 

<P>
Back in 1988, the partners attended dozens of entrepreneurial trade shows looking for a venture to start together. Nothing excited them, so they rented space at a Los Angeles hotel, contacted potential exhibitors, and put on their own show. 

<P>
Today, their Entrepreneur Expo is held in 68 U.S. and Canadian cities and showcases opportunities from franchise concepts to home-based businesses.

<P>
''We try to have different opportunities than typical business shows have,'' says Buchen, 34. ''We were frustrated entrepreneurs looking to get into our own business, so we know what the people who attend our shows are looking for.''

<P>
Exhibitors pay about $1,000 for a booth, and fledgling entrepreneurs pay $6 for the chance to find the business of their dreams. 

<P>
''Trade shows can do what no other medium can,'' says Buchen. 

<P>
American Exhibition Services

<P>
As an investment broker, whenever Charles Allen attended a trade show, he'd get to see only a small fraction of the displays. "The model was antiquated," he says. "Most attendees reached so few booths.''

<P>
In 1989, he founded American Exhibition Services (AES) of Birmingham, Ala., to bring order to the burgeoning trade show industry. Allen's first innovation, Exhibitor Preview, is a state-of-the-art display that guides attendees to the offerings inside the exhibition halls. Exhibitors pay for inclusion and placement on the lobby display, which is now considered standard fare for U.S. trade shows.

<P>
Allen and his partner, Jeff Culton, keep churning out innovations. Audio Billboard allows exhibitors to advertise through speaker towers. The partners have patented Marquees in Motion, a system for shuttle-bus advertising. CNNvention News, an eight-foot-tall kiosk with television monitors, features CNN Headline News interspersed with commercials for exhibitors and sponsors, show information, schedules, and updates. To protect himself from outside competition, Allen asks trade show producers to sign exclusive contracts. 

<P>
AES is now the largest trade show marketing company in North America, with annual sales of $7.5 million and 96 employees who serve 337 shows a year.

<P>
Eco Expo Inc. 

<P>
Marc Merson has produced TV shows and feature films such as Doc Hollywood. But his biggest production is Eco Expo, a blockbuster trade show that features environmentally friendly products and services for consumers and government agencies. 

<P>
Over the years, Merson had protested against nuclear weapons and war. But after attending a Healing the Planet symposium, he became convinced that damage to the environment was a much bigger threat. 

<P>
''Since I came from show business,'' he says, ''I decided to put on a show.'' With help from his actress wife, Nina Wilcox Merson, he founded Eco Expo Inc. of Sherman Oaks, Calif., in 1991. 

<P>
"There are 'green' products in so many industries, including fashion, health care, office equipment, and transportation,'' says Merson. ''The challenge was how to best serve the marketplace.'' Eco Expo exhibitors include chemical-free dry cleaners, organic gardening products, and wildlife preservation firms. 

<P>
His first year, Merson lost $350,000, but he has since fine-tuned Eco Expo into two three-day shows per year. An additional show in Washington, D.C., caters entirely to government representatives. This year, revenues from booths, attendance, and sponsorships will total $1.5 million. 

<P>
''We have dealt with the simultaneous evolution of two separate industries,'' says Merson, ''the trade show business and 'green' products."

<P>
Eager to remain on the cutting edge, Merson recently launched an online version of Eco Expo on the Internet's World Wide Web, and revenues from the 500 exhibitors already in place are reaching ''thousands of dollars a day,'' says Merson. ''It's a perpetual, virtual trade show, and that offers unlimited possibilities.''

<P ALIGN="RIGHT">
&#009;-- Gianna Jacobson

