<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>ITScope</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">SUCCESS SCOPE</FONT></P></CENTER>


<P>
<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>Develop a Winning Style</FONT>

<P>
CEOs should develop a leadership approach that best suits the needs of their company.  Leadership is ''a coherent, explicit style of management, not a reflection of personal style,'' says the Harvard Business Review. ''This is a critical distinction.'' HBR interviewed 160 CEOs around the world and found that in the most successful companies, the CEO scrutinizes the business situation, determines what the organization requires from its leader, and chooses the leadership approach that fulfills those requirements. The best CEOs learn to repress certain personality traits and develop new ones in order to run their organizations effectively.

<P>
<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>Plug the Leaks</FONT>

<P>
''Employees who talk too much jeopardize a company's most valuable asset -- proprietary information,'' warns Nation's Business. The publication outlines steps to help you plug information leaks and prevent competitors from stealing your ideas. 

<P>
* Create a hush-hush policy. Regularly remind workers not to talk about company activities in public places. One corporate spy recalls eating at a local restaurant and overhearing a group of employees discussing confidential company strategies.

<P>
* Get it in writing. Have all employees promise to safeguard company secrets. Even a simple document specifying that workers are forbidden from disclosing, taking, or copying confidential information can make violators legally liable.

<P>
* Display trade-show savvy. Trade shows are notorious arenas for eavesdropping. Competitors typically check out rivals' booths to examine their product and catch stray conversations. Be on guard for corporate spies. 

<HR><BR>
