<DOCOLDNO>IA059-000315-B022-142</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.successmagazine.com:80/archives.html/sept96.html/9NewCEO.html 199.92.136.187 19970114144235 text/html 8103
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Tuesday, 14-Jan-97 14:39:38 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 13-Sep-96 20:13:31 GMT
Content-length: 7914
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>9NewCEO</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="2"><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>
	THE NEW CEO </FONT>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="2" COLSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="tech.jpeg" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE WIDTH="210" HEIGHT="168"><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">Photograph by Vern Evans</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+3">ONLINE ADDICT</FONT><BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">Use the Internet to Get targeted Databases, Cheep Phone Connections.</FONT>
	</TD>
	</TR>	
	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP ROWSPAN="3">
<P>''Database marketing is where it's at,'' Monte Hamilton says with confidence.
''I've heard it said that in the future, there'll be two types of companies:
those that use database marketing, and those that are out of business.''
</P>

<P>Hamilton is the former president of EntreMKT, a specialized Internet
service provider in Palm Springs, Calif. The company helps franchises establish
a presence on the Web to attract new franchisees. It also sets up intranets
so that franchisees can communicate with one another and the home office.
Hamilton, now a consultant to EntreMKT, digs for the best ways to exploit
technology and the Internet and then passes that knowledge on to his clients.
</P>

<P>''For years I've been using online databases in my own businesses to
get focused information,'' says Hamilton. When he was an executive recruiter,
he'd use services like Dun &amp; Bradstreet's Million Dollar Directory
to find candidates. When he started working with American Leak Detection
Inc. and its franchisees, he logged onto CompuServe's Biz*File database
to pinpoint potential customers. </P>

<P>''It gave me excellent, inexpensive information I could download and
put right into my contact-management program,'' he says. ''CompuServe has
an outstanding number of databases that are identified when you conduct
an online search using its 'find' utility.'' The Internet is chock-full
of databases as well, which can be found by doing keyword searches with
Yahoo!, Alta Vista, or other search engines. </P>

<P>For EntreMKT's clients, says Hamilton, the Internet holds much promise
-- especially when used to set up company intranets. He says that Java,
touted as the next wave for creating turbo-interactive Web sites, ''is
going to let companies take huge databases and allow their system to find
information through their own search engines. That's the most exciting
part of what the Internet is going to be.'' </P>

<P>Long Distance, Local Rate </P>

<P>Meanwhile, Hamilton has found another new tool that he's introducing
to clients. While people talk a lot about making telephone calls over the
Internet, Hamilton has actually been doing it with VocalTec Inc.'s Internet
Phone. Now he's persuading franchise companies to do the same. </P>

<P>''Initially, I just got it out of curiosity,'' he says. ''I picked it
up, installed it, and tried it out. I thought it would be a good tool for
international operations.'' </P>

<P>Hamilton sent a copy of the software to a client in Brazil. The two
were able to set up a private topic group on the Internet where they could
have a one-on-one voice conversation. It cost Hamilton only a local phone
charge. </P>

<P>''If both parties have full duplex sound cards on their computers, it
works just like a regular telephone,'' he says. ''If you don't have full
duplex, it works like a CB radio: You have to take turns speaking.'' </P>

<P>Now, when EntreMKT teaches its clients about Internet bulletin boards,
download directories, and mailing lists, the company also recommends Internet
Phone. ''It's a way to connect with franchisees all over the world, and
it's less expensive.'' 

<P>* INTERNET PHONE. Price: $49.95. Requirements: 486; 8MB of RAM (12 recommended);
Windows 95; Winsock 1.1-compatible Internet TCP/IP, SLIP, or PPP connection;
microphone; speakers; Windows-compatible audio board.</P>

<BR><HR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Bulletin Board</FONT><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE="+3">Password Protection</FONT> </P>

<P>If you're really paranoid about keeping your passwords
and PIN numbers secure, or if you just have too many to keep track of,
check out Password Master from International Systems Inc. of Chicago. Password
Master uses DES (Data Encryption Standard) to lock up your information.
</P>

<P>Finding your stored passwords for various applications
(e.g., for Internet or online service access) is easy, thanks to the ''always
on top'' option for Windows. Even better, you never have to bring your
actual passwords up on the screen for prying eyes to see. Password Master's
hinting system lets you type in up to three clues to jog your memory for
each password. So instead of &quot;magenta,&quot; for example, your screen
might display &quot;favorite crayon color.&quot; Password Master costs
$29.99.</P>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE="+3">Painless Plug and Play </FONT></P>

<P>You've been up all night putting together a killer
PowerPoint presentation. You've bought a brand-new CD-ROM multimedia accessory for your laptop and
plan to blow away the client with a spectacular sound-and-light show. You've
got Windows 95, so hookup will be a cinch.</P>

<P>Wrong. You plug in your accessory, but it won't
play. Your show is poised for disaster -- unless you get CardWizard Pro from SystemSoft Corp. of
Natick, Mass., which automatically configures PCMCIA accessories. </P>

<P>With CardWizard Pro installed, you simply plug
in a new device -- LAN card, CD-ROM, fax/modem -- and up pops a graphic
screen to show you the slots on your computer and critical information
about the new card. </P>

<P>It even configures multifunction PCMCIA cards, allowing up to seven devices to
run from one slot.</P>

<P>A feature called Autocorrect will fix conflicts
or network problems. If the card still won't work, right-click the mouse
to perform a diagnostic check. CardWizard Pro costs $69.95. </P>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE="+3">Kills Bugs Dead</FONT> </P>

<P>Computer viruses are still a very real threat
to business users today, especially as traffic on the Internet increases.
IBM AntiVirus software can detect and disinfect more than 6,800 virus strains
on most PC operating systems. </P>

<P>The software scans your hard drive, memory, floppy
drives, and network servers behind the scenes. The Desktop Edition supports
OS/2 Warp, DOS, Windows, and Windows 95 systems for small businesses or
home offices. The Enterprise Edition also works with Novell NetWare and
Windows NT. </P>

<P>IBM offers an AntiVirus upgrade subscription plan,
through which you receive quarterly software upgrades to deal with any
new strains of viruses. Cost for the Desktop Edition (single user) is about
$49; price varies per user for the Enterprise Edition.
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
 <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.1 -437838. --></P>

