<BODY>





<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<BR><BR><CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C"></FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><H1>Technology at Work</H1></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>BY FRANK HERTZ </P></CENTER><BR><BR>



<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Focus Your Goals</FONT>

</CENTER>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> Software Helps You Be a Better Manager</H3><BR>

</CENTER>





<P><H3>The Art of Negotiating</H3> </P>



<P>''Negotiation'' is a polite word for it, but you know what your goal

is: to get what you want, on your terms. </P>



<P>You don't want to waste any time stewing over tactics, either, so get

right down to business with The Art of Negotiating from Experience In Software

Inc. of Berkeley, Calif. This tool provides you with a structured plan for

even the most delicate negotiations. </P>



<P>The program walks you through a set of modules, helping to define your

arguments and -- more important -- the probable tactics of your opponent.

''Being able to think constructively of the other side's arguments is very

productive,'' says Jeff Dangler, executive director of Merkley Jewelers

of Louisville, Ky. ''The Art of Negotiating gives you that perspective --

it puts you in the other person's shoes.'' </P>



<P>Dangler likes the way the program guides him through a discussion, then

gives him a printout of key ideas and strategies. ''It really breaks down

the arguments into basic ideas,'' he says. </P>



<P>Dangler consults with The Art of Negotiating before every meeting, if

only to focus on the bare bones of a deal. ''You're always thinking in such

a broad scope,'' he explains. ''The Art of Negotiating lists my main arguments,

such as superior product quality or top-notch customer service, and that

helps me stick to the point.'' </P>



<P>* The Art of Negotiating. Price: $79.95. Requirements: 286, 256K of RAM,

DOS 2.0. </P>



<P><H3>Smart Business Plan</H3> </P>



<P>To catch the eye of an investor these days, a business plan has to be

more than just a simple graph of financial projections and a list of your

intentions. Smart Business Plan, from the American Institute for Financial

Research Inc. of Chapel Hill, N.C., rolls up a business consultant, financial

adviser, writer, modeler, and strategic planner into one easy-to-use package.

Then it walks you through the steps for creating a standout business plan.

</P>



<P>Craig Pate, business plan consultant and president of Pate Golf &amp;

Trade Co. of New Berlin, Wis., is especially impressed with the ''instructions

and example area'' screen, which provides sample charts, graphs, strategies,

and more. ''I use that feature all the time, even though I've written lots

of different types of business plans myself,'' he says. </P>



<P>With its ability to create sharp 3D graphs, Smart Business Plan aims

to make investors leap out of their seats. ''It develops the graphs on its

own from the data you enter,'' says Pate. ''It's an exciting look to add

to the normally drab plan. It really impresses people.'' </P>



<P>For comparison purposes, Smart Business Plan can split your screen in

half, displaying your plan on the bottom and example plans on top. ''It's

great to have a model right there to go up against,'' says Pate. Users can

toggle between screens to choose an example they like from the top screen,

and then enter it into the personalized plan on the bottom. </P>



<P>Smart Business Plan, along with its sister products in the Smart Business

System, can soon be accessed through the Internet. Users will actually be

able to use the software without installing it on their PCs. </P>



<P>Here's how it will work: You log on to the American Institute for Financial

Research's Web site at http://www.smartonline.com. Thanks to the programming

languages Java and Livescript, you can work in the program right there and

pay for it on a per-use basis, or ''rent'' it through a subscription service.

</P>



<P><FONT SIZE="2">* Smart Business Plan. Price: $149. Requirements: 486, 20MB of hard-disk

space, 8MB of RAM, Windows 3.1, VGA display. </FONT></P>



<P><H2>Proposal and Marketing FastPlan </H2></P>



<P>The word ''fast'' in front of a software product may cause you to expect

something basic, simplistic, or less valuable than a ''full-service'' program.

Not so with the FastPlan line from Village Software Inc. of Boston. Proposal

and Marketing FastPlan, in particular, does an excellent job of sorting

information into spreadsheets, word processing documents, and presentations.

It produces clear, concise proposals and marketing plans. </P>



<P>Tom Burger, president of Superior Turf &amp; Landscaping Inc. in Richboro,

Pa., likes Proposal and Marketing FastPlan's intuitive integration with

Microsoft Office 95 products, such as Microsoft Word, PowerPoint, and Excel.

''We used to have to reenter data to produce different results,'' says Burger.

''But when we started using Windows a lot, we wanted a program that we could

learn easily and still get professional results.'' </P>



<P>Burger lauds Proposal and Marketing FastPlan's use of templates that

plug selected information into your documents automatically. ''We just go

in and tell the program which files we want to use, which text, which numbers,

and it does the rest,'' he says. </P>



<P>Burger recently submitted a job estimate to a customer; the customer's

neighbor saw it and asked to get an estimate for his property. ''All we

had to do was plug the right numbers into the Proposal Template, and the

program produced a professional report in minutes,'' he says. ''The customer

loved the clarity -- it's the only way we do proposals now.'' </P>



<P> <FONT SIZE="2">Proposal and Marketing FastPlan. Price: $99.95. Requirements: 486,

4MB of RAM (8MB recommended), Windows 95, Microsoft Office 95. </P>

</FONT>

<P><H2>Crystal Ball </H2></P>



<P>Risk analysis can be a tall order, especially if there seem to be a multiple

of options and factors to consider. Many business managers are finding that

straight analysis using a standard spreadsheet doesn't give them a clear

enough picture of their ''risk landscape.'' </P>



<P>Crystal Ball from Decisioneering Inc. of Denver lets users visualize

which courses of action will be worth the risk. </P>



<P>''You can actually see the risk probability with Crystal Ball,'' says

Doug Garfield, president of ExperCorp Inc. in Naperville, Ill. ''It brings

it all home in a way that's easy to understand, not in a way that's a statistical

abstraction.'' </P>



<P>Garfield uses Crystal Ball specifically to analyze his company's distribution

models. Crystal Ball takes numbers from his spreadsheets, such as revenue

projections and inventory, and crunches them to determine which distribution

model requires the most acceptable level of risk. </P>



<P>Garfield particularly values the graphics formats, such as the single

chart that analyzes all possible outcomes in a risk-taking situation. </P>



<P>''People say, 'Hey, I can see what's going on here!' when I show them

what Crystal Ball can do,'' says Garfield. </P>



<P>The product's compatibility with Microsoft Excel is another benefit that

reduces the learning curve dramatically. Crystal Ball actually acts as an

integrated Excel add-in program with its own toolbar and menus within the

spreadsheet application. </P>



<P> <FONT SIZE="2"<FONT SIZE="+2">>Crystal Ball. Price: $395. Requirements: 4MB of RAM, 1MB of hard-disk

space, Excel 4.0 or Lotus 1-2-3 4.0. </FONT></P>



<P>Mac requires System 6.0.4 or better, Excel 4.0. </FONT></P>



<P><H2>allCLEAR III</H2> </P>



<P>Take the drudgery out of communicating complex ideas in a simple format

with allCLEAR III. This flowcharting and diagramming tool comes from Clear

Software Inc. of Newton, Mass. </P>



<P>Judith Campbell, business process consultant for Maryland Insurance Group

of Baltimore, delegates work to fellow employees. She likes allCLEAR because

''it's the most intuitive package I've ever used. I can bring in new people

on a project and have them pumping out quality stuff within minutes.'' </P>



<P>Campbell often has to analyze the effectiveness of a business process,

so she uses allCLEAR to map out visually the steps of, say, accounts payable.

With allCLEAR, she types in the different steps needed to complete a task.

The software automatically takes those steps and maps them out in a flowchart.

</P>



<P>With allCLEAR's Final Touch feature, Campbell can change the shape and

flow of any document, as well as reposition and maneuver relationships as

they change. She can also make any special annotations to the document.

</P>



<P>''AllCLEAR works in an outline format, so all you have to do is type

in your story, and it automatically diagrams it,'' says Campbell. ''But

that doesn't mean I'm stuck with what the program gives me. It's really

easy to make changes.'' </P>



<P><FONT SIZE="2"> allCLEAR III. Price: $299.95. Requirements: 386 or better, 4MB of RAM,

6MB of hard-disk space, Windows 3.1.</FONT> </P>



<P><H2>DecideRight</H2> </P>



<P>When Bill Pike, president and CEO of Western New York Healthcare Association,

needed to make a tough decision on a controversial issue, he turned to DecideRight,

a decision analysis software program. ''I thought it would be helpful to

add some structure to the decision process,'' he says. </P>



<P>As it turned out, DecideRight not only organized Pike's options and the

influencing factors of his decision, it brought consensus among a tough

board of directors. </P>



<P>DecideRight, from Avantos of Emeryville, Calif., helped Pike lay out

his dilemma in its Decision Table. This easy-to-use worksheet allowed Pike

to type in his decision criteria -- the information he needed to take into

consideration -- as well as his available options. </P>



<P>He rated criteria on a scale of their importance, from ''poor'' to ''excellent.''

The Option Rating Tool then helped him rate the available choices against

his criteria. </P>



<P>''All at once, you can see the decision you should make,'' says Pike.

''It's very visual and shows you with hard numbers which option makes the

most sense.'' </P>



<P>DecideRight's reporting and charting capabilities were the key to helping

his tough board of directors see the light. ''It allowed us to document

what we did in very informative charts and tables,'' says Pike. ''As the

chairman put it, it took the emotion out of the decision-making process.

And that's always the goal with a really tough decision.'' * </P>



<P><FONT SIZE="2"> DecideRight. Price: $149. Requirements: 4MB of RAM (8MB recommended),

4MB of hard-disk space, Windows 3.1, pointing device, VGA monitor.</FONT> </P>







<P>Frank Hertz is a freelance writer based in Brighton, Mass. He can be

reached at 74774. 1160@compuserve.com. </P>

<BR>

<P><H4>What's New</H4>



<H2>Get Your Fix </H2>



<P>Windows 95, for all its earth-shattering, PC standard-changing

glory, is not without its faults. Thankfully, CyberMedia's First Aid 95

Deluxe -- an upgrade to its best-selling First Aid 95 -- can help you smooth

over little glitches (and big ones) in a flash.</P>



<P>Like the previous version, First Aid 95 Deluxe

saves you from spending hours on the phone with technical support staff.

Install it and follow its simple instructions to ferret out hardware and

software configuration problems. First Aid 95 Deluxe scans your PC to identify

every software application on your hard drive, so you don't have to configure

it manually for each one.< </P>



<P>New features include RetroFix, which takes a snapshot

of configuration changes when you add something like a CD-ROM drive, sound

card, or new </P>



<P>application. RetroFix thus can restore your old

configurations if something goes awry. Another feature lets you update Windows

95 or First Aid 95 applications instantly through the Internet with one

mouse-click. </P>



<P>CyberMedia is in Santa Monica, Calif. </FONT>



<HR><BR>

