<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>9TechClinic</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>



<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR>

<CENTER><P>BY DAN GUTMAN </P></CENTER><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4"> <CENTER>Design Your Product in 3D</FONT>
</CENTER>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER> Avoid the Old Drawing Board</H3><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Businesspeople who can't draw a straight line often need to generate pictures. Reg Dunbar, general manager of Urethane Technologies Inc., falls into this category. ''We're basically engineers,'' he explains, almost apologetically. ''As far as drawing a picture, none of us is too good at that.'' 

<P>
The company designs and manufactures buoys from its small office in Denham Springs, La. To make up for the staff's collective lack of artistic talent, Dunbar uses DesignCAD 3D. This modeling software, by ViaGrafix of Pryor, Okla., helps him create excellent renditions of new buoys designed to his customers' needs. 

<P>
''Gosh, it's almost like looking at a photograph,'' says Dunbar. ''I've had customers look at the printout and say, 'You already made the product.' ''

<P>
If, like many people, you immediately break out in hives when you see the acronym CAD (computer-aided design), relax. You don't need an engineering degree just to read the instruction manual. With nearly all the features of high-end CAD programs, DesignCAD 3D is less expensive and easier to use.

<P>
Say, like Dunbar, you wanted to design a buoy. In DesignCAD 3D, you could click on the cylinder tool from the tools palette (other options include spheres, cones, and cubes). Type in the diameter of the cylinder and use the mouse to stretch it like a Slinky to the desired height.

<P>
Now you can do all kinds of things to it. Rotate the cylinder and flip it to any angle you want. Or slice off a piece to see what the object looks like in the middle. By manipulating the direction and intensity of the simulated lighting source, you can see how that affects the object's shading. 

<P>
''Once you get used to drawing in three dimensions,'' says Dunbar, ''you can model almost anything you can imagine.''

<P>
It used to take Dunbar all day to design a 3D buoy on the drawing board. Now it takes an hour or two. And when customers want changes (as all customers do), it's an easy fix -- no redrawing artwork from scratch.

<P>
The DesignCAD image you create goes beyond a mere mechanical drawing. You can cover the object you've drawn with a simulated surface texture -- brass, wood grain, marble, chrome, leaves, or more than 20 others. This may not be so handy for buoys, but it's excellent for something like furniture design or room layouts. A ''hammer'' command lets you sculpt the image, which you can view from several different angles. On a good color printer, the output is incredibly realistic.

<P>
The computer can also calculate the object's surface area and volume, making it easy to tell how much material you'll need and what it'll cost to manufacture the item. Objects drawn in DesignCAD can be pasted into a word processing or desktop publishing document, or you can add text right to the image. Dunbar, for example, pours his buoy designs into PageMaker layout software to create brochures, catalogs, and product data sheets. If he wanted to, he could transmit the images over a phone line or network. 

<P>
The realistic drawings provide an obvious selling advantage. ''We don't just send the customer a drawing with dimensions on it,'' says Dunbar. ''We send it in full 3D perspective. The customer has a good idea of what it's going to look like -- and that really helps us sell these things.'' 

<P>

<P>
SUCCESS contributing editor Dan Gutman can be reached at DanGut1@aol.com.



<P>
* DesignCAD 3D. Price: $499.95 for PC, $299.95 for Mac. PC requirements: Windows 3.1 or better, 8MB of RAM, 6MB of hard-disk space. Mac requirements: System 7 or better, 8MB of RAM, 10MB of hard-disk space.
