<h1 align=center><font size=5><A NAME="top1">Press Releases</A><br>
</font><a name="september"><font size=5>September 1996 </font></a></h1>
<p align=left><a href="#entrepreneurs">SUCCESS MAGAZINE'S 3RD ANNUAL -- THE 25 BEST BUSINESS SCHOOLS FOR 
ENTREPRENEURS: SCHOOLS THAT MAKE MILLIONAIRES.</a> <br>
<br>
<a href="#year">BABSON RATED BEST SCHOOL FOR ENTREPRENEURSHIP: VOTED #1 BY PEERS 
FOR THE THIRD CONSECUTIVE YEAR.</a> <br>
<br>
<a href="#failure">A HARVARD PROFESSOR&#146;S FORMULA FOR ENTREPRENEURIAL CREATIVITY:<br>
Dr. Teresa Amabile&#146;s recipes for entrepreneurial success and failure.</a> <br>
<br>
<a href="#funds">HOT MUTUAL FUNDS FOR ENTREPRENEURS: Soup to nuts for entrepreneurs smartly 
hedging their bets in mutual funds.</a> </p>
<hr size=3>
<p align=left>Contact: Stephanie Rabinowitz, (212) 551-9789<br>
FOR RELEASE: 9:00 AM, ET, Tuesday, AUGUST 20, 1996<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="entrepreneurs">SUCCESS MAGAZINE'S 3RD ANNUAL<br>
THE 25 BEST BUSINESS SCHOOLS FOR ENTREPRENEURS</a>:<br>
<br>
SCHOOLS THAT MAKE MILLIONAIRES<br>
Everybody Wants to be Their Own Boss<br>
-- LEARN WHAT THEY TEACH -- September Issue<br>
<br>
New York--In its proprietary 3rd annual listing of &quot;The 25 Best Business Schools for 
Entrepreneurs,&quot; (September issue) SUCCESS scours the nation for the premier educational centers 
that deliver the skills, the confidence, the creativity, the contacts, and the seed money/venture 
capital know-how to start your own business, or improve an existing one. The listing, produced in 
concert with the nation's foremost academic experts and Pennsylvania-based Madway Business 
Research Inc., tracks the explosive growth in entrepreneurship programs that is revolutionizing 
graduate business education in America and the world.<br>
<br>
Where We've Been, Where We're Going--The number of universities that teach entrepreneurship 
has grown from 16 in 1971 to well over 370 undergraduate and graduate programs in 1993, 
according to the most recent comprehensive study (Karl Vesper, 1993). Bill Bygrave, director of 
Babson's Center for Entrepreneurial Studies says, &quot;There's no other paradigm in the management 
sciences about which we've learned so much in so little time.&quot; <br>
<br>
Making Millionaires--The 25 Best package includes: <br>
<br>
&#183; &quot;Unlimited Genius,&quot; an in-depth look inside the classroom of Teresa Amabile, Harvard&#146;s expert 
on entrepreneurial creativity - the piece covers her indispensable recipes for (entrepreneurial) 
creativity and success, as well as failure.<br>
&#183; The secrets of the smartest MBAs in the world: Profiles of &quot;Top 25&quot; grads who are making 
millions putting the invaluable lessons of entrepreneurial study into practice. <br>
&#183; The secrets of 3 of the world&#146;s top entrepreneurs: Reporting from the front lines of the recent 
induction to Babson College&#146;s Academy of Distinguished Entrepreneurs: Richard Branson.<br>
&#183; The University of Texas at Austin&#146;s MOOT CORP Business plan competition: Top MBAs from 
around the world fight for cash &amp; credibility, and a highly marketable stamp of approval. <br>
<br>
Choosing the Best: Survey Criteria and Methodology--To be eligible for consideration, a school 
had to offer at least three distinct courses in entrepreneurship in its MBA program. The magazine 
surveyed 137 graduate business schools across the country. The survey focused on five key areas. 
(Each key area accounts for a specified percentage of a school's total score:) <br>
more...<br>
*Qualifications of faculty - 25% (qualifications/role faculty plays in supporting student endeavors) <br>
*Curriculum - 25% (depth and breadth of entrepreneurship curriculum)<br>
*Student programs - 20% (resources and special programs to provide &quot;hands-on&quot; experience)<br>
*Caliber of students - 15% (caliber of students attending the school, academic records, etc.)<br>
*Overall program - 15% (quality, longevity, resources, and community outreach of the program)<br>
<br>
AN ALPHABETICAL LISTING OF SUCCESS MAGAZINE&#146;S <br>
THE 25 BEST BUSINESS SCHOOLS FOR ENTREPRENEURS:<br>
(This survey is a listing, not a ranking.)<br>
<br>
University of Arizona, Karl Eller Graduate School of Management (Tucson, AZ)<br>
Babson College, F.W. Olin Graduate School of Business (Wellesley, MA)<br>
Ball State University, College of Business (Muncie, IN)<br>
Baylor University, Hankamer School of Business (Waco, TX)<br>
Brigham Young University, Marriott School of Management (Provo, UT)<br>
University of California at Los Angeles (UCLA), The Anderson School (Los Angeles, CA)<br>
Carnegie Mellon University, Graduate School of Industrial Administration (Pittsburgh, PA)<br>
University of Colorado, The Graduate School of Business Administration (Boulder, CO)<br>
Cornell University, Johnson Graduate School of Management (Ithaca, NY)<br>
DePaul University, Charles H. Kellstadt Graduate School of Business (Chicago, IL)<br>
University of Georgia, Terry College of Business (Athens, GA)<br>
Harvard University, Harvard Business School (Boston, MA)<br>
University of Illinois-Chicago, College of Business Administration (Chicago, IL)<br>
University of Maryland at College Park, The Maryland Business School (College Park, MD)<br>
University of Nebraska-Lincoln, College of Business Administration (Lincoln, NE)<br>
New York University, Leonard N. Stern School of Business (New York, NY)<br>
Northwestern University, J.L. Kellogg Graduate School of Management (Evanston, IL)<br>
University of Pennsylvania, The Wharton School (Philadelphia, PA)<br>
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Lally School of Management &amp; Technology (Troy, NY)<br>
St. Louis University, School of Business Administration (St. Louis, MO)<br>
University of St. Thomas, Graduate School of Business (Minneapolis, MN)<br>
San Diego State University, College of Business Administration (San Diego, CA)<br>
University of Southern California, School of Business Administration (Los Angeles, CA)<br>
University of South Carolina, College of Business Administration (Columbia, SC)<br>
The University of Texas at Austin, Graduate School of Business Administration (Austin, TX)<br>
<br>
Educators Rank Educators--Which schools offer the best entrepreneurship programs? Here's how 
the schools themselves rank their peers (SUCCESS asked all survey respondents to rank their 
peers.):<br>
<br>
A RANKING OF THE TOP FIVE BEST BUSINESS SCHOOLS<br>
ACCORDING TO THE SCHOOLS THAT WERE SURVEYED: <br>
<br>
1.) Babson College<br>
2.) Wharton/University of Pennsylvania<br>
3.) Harvard University<br>
4.) University of Southern California<br>
5.) UCLA<br>
</p>
<p align=center># # # </p>
<p align=center><a href="#september">List of September 1996 press releases.</a></p>
<hr size=3>
<p align=left>Contact: Stephanie Rabinowitz, (212) 551-9789<br>
FOR RELEASE: 9:00 AM, ET, Tuesday, AUGUST 20, 1996<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="year">BABSON RATED BEST SCHOOL FOR ENTREPRENEURSHIP:<br>
VOTED #1 BY PEERS FOR THE THIRD CONSECUTIVE YEAR</a><br>
<br>
New York, August 20--The top business schools in the nation credit Babson College of <br>
Wellesley for the 3rd year running as the premier program for training entrepreneurs. Details <br>
about Babson and other top entrepreneurship schools of the peer review survey appear in<br>
SUCCESS Magazine's 3rd annual &quot;The 25 Best Business Schools for Entrepreneurs.&quot; The <br>
listing, produced in concert with the nation's foremost academic experts and Pennsylvania-based <br>
Madway Business Research Inc., tracks the explosive growth in entrepreneurship programs that is <br>
revolutionizing graduate business education in America and the world.<br>
<br>
Educators Rank Educators--Babson, relatively unrecognized outside the realm of <br>
entrepreneurship, was chosen by its peers for the 3rd year running because &quot;Entrepreneurship is <br>
Babson's distinctive competence. Entrepreneurship--the creation of value through innovation--has 
influenced the Babson College curriculum since its founding by entrepreneur Roger Babson in 
1919. The individual enterprise fostered by Babson Institute has evolved into an entrepreneurial 
emphasis that pervades the undergraduate and graduate school curricula and much of campus life. 
Our undergraduate major in entrepreneurial studies was first offered in 1979, well ahead of the 
recent emphasis on entrepreneurship education,&quot; says Bill Bygrave, director of Babson's Center for 
Entrepreneurial Studies.<br>
<br>
The Proliferating Paradigm--With Babson leading the flock, and Wharton, Harvard, <br>
USC, and UCLA emerging as 2-5 respectively, these 25 schools are at the vanguard of Business <br>
education. Bygrave notes, &quot;The e-word has become ubiquitous in business schools. There's no <br>
question, a sea change is taking place. Up until five years ago, entrepreneurship educators were a <br>
bunch of pioneers; most schools taught it, but it tended to be one small class. Now, significant <br>
schools are building in-depth entrepreneurship programs.&quot; Fifteen years ago, when traditional <br>
business schools with &quot;Fortune 500 company&quot; teaching philosophies presided over the business <br>
education landscape, &quot;we knew very little about angels or venture capital. Today we can be very <br>
precise. There's no other paradigm in the management sciences about which we've learned so <br>
much in so little time.&quot;<br>
<br>
Secrets of the Empire Builders--The current (September) issue also reports from the front lines of 
the 1996 induction to the Academy of Distinguished Entrepreneurs of Babson College. This year&#146;s 
inductees are Richard Branson, Ely Callaway, and Andronico Luksic. <br>
<br>
SUCCESS has been writing about entrepreneurship for more than a century. It is published by 
New York-based Success Multimedia Enterprises, publishers of Working at Home.</p>
<p align=center># # # </p>
<p align=center><a href="#september">List of September 1996 press releases.</a></p>
<hr size=3>
<p align=left>Contact: Stephanie Rabinowitz, (212) 551-9789<br>
FOR RELEASE: 9:00 AM, ET, Tuesday, AUGUST 20, 1996<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="failure">A HARVARD PROFESSOR&#146;S FORMULA FOR ENTREPRENEURIAL CREATIVITY:<br>
Dr. Teresa Amabile&#146;s recipes for entrepreneurial success and failure</a> <br>
<br>
New York, August 20--Dr. Teresa Amabile, Harvard&#146;s expert on entrepreneurial <br>
<br>
creativity, says &quot;At Harvard, we define creativity as generating novel and useful ideas to solve any <br>
<br>
problem or take advantage of any opportunity. Creativity is the only way humans progress,&quot; <br>
<br>
according to the current issue (September) of SUCCESS Magazine. Here is the Dr.&#146;s recipe for <br>
<br>
creativity and success that appear in this issue:<br>
<br>
RECIPE FOR CREATIVITY and SUCCESS:<br>
&#183; Freedom for individuals to decide on their own how to accomplish a task. Most important is 
operational autonomy: freedom in the day-to-day conduct of one&#146;s own work.<br>
&#183; Good project management. An effective manager serves as a good role model, is enthusiastic, 
communicates well, protects his team from outside distractions, sets clear direction, and matches 
tasks to a worker&#146;s skills and interests.<br>
&#183; Sufficient resources, including facilities, equipment, budget, information, and people.<br>
&#183; Organizational atmosphere that prizes innovation and allows room for some failure.<br>
&#183; Sufficient time to consider creative approaches to a problem.<br>
&#183; Pressure. A sense of challenge that is personalized to the individual&#146;s skills, and a sense of urgency 
based on the desire to accomplish an important goal.<br>
<br>
CREATIVITY KILLERS:<br>
&#183; Evaluation and surveillance. Employees who are watched as they work or who expect negative 
critical judgment will not be highly creative.<br>
&#183; Constraint within the organization: a sense that one lacks control over one&#146;s own work/ideas.<br>
&#183; Indifference: lack of support, interest, or faith in a project.<br>
&#183; Competition. Political problems shut down communication between people.<br>
&#183; Time pressure can destroy motivation - although it can be a stimulant if there is a feeling that the 
pressure is not arbitrary. If people feel it&#146;s somebody else&#146;s show, and they&#146;re told to get it done 
by September 1 without understanding why, the pressure will function as a constraint.<br>
<br>
CAVEAT: REWARDS CAN GO EITHER WAY<br>
&#183; If people believe they are just being bribed, they will feel controlled, and their intrinsic motivation 
will drop. But if they feel the reward signals the value of their work, or if they feel the reward is 
enabling them to meet a personal goal, it will stimulate intrinsic motivation.</p>
<p align=center># # #</p>
<p align=center><a href="#september">List of September 1996 press releases.</a></p>
<hr size=3>
<p align=left>Contact: Stephanie Rabinowitz, (212) 551-9789<br>
FOR RELEASE: 9:00 AM, ET, Tuesday, AUGUST 20, 1996<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="funds">HOT MUTUAL FUNDS FOR ENTREPRENEURS:<br>
Soup to nuts for entrepreneurs smartly hedging their bets in mutual funds</a><br>
<br>
New York, August 20--By definition, entrepreneurs are people who invest the vast majority of 
their resources in their own growing companies. However, given the volatile nature of today&#146;s 
economic landscape, a new, intriguing, hybrid entrepreneur has emerged in recent years, according 
to the current (September) issue of SUCCESS Magazine. That entrepreneur is the 
TRADITIONAL, FAMILY-BASED ENTREPRENEUR; someone who is pursuing the 
entrepreneurial way of life, while simultaneously finding traditional ways to safeguard a portion of 
their investments. This issue offers an exclusive package, &quot;Hot Mutual Funds for Entrepreneurs,&quot; a 
customized discussion of mutual funds geared specifically for this new breed of traditional 
entrepreneur. Renowned personal finance expert Carole Gould takes great care to stress that 
entrepreneurs should hedge their entrepreneurial investments by building a portfolio which 
&quot;minimizes exposure with funds that have outperformed in bad markets as well as in good ones.&quot;<br>
<br>
Flirting with risk is an integral part of the entrepreneur&#146;s identity. Therefore, these creatures of 
adventure already have more exposure than the average investor. Gould urges this particular group 
to &quot;index part of their portfolios to reduce the risk of picking a bad fund.&quot; Gould&#146;s special report 
covers four key areas of mutual funds that are essential to the entrepreneurial investor. (Pages 
42-46 -- ripped out) Those areas are: <br>
<br>
&#183; Make Your Money Work: This section defines risk in the context of mutual funds and explores 
&quot;the assessment of psychological risk tolerance.&quot;<br>
&#183; Tax Strategies: Gould discusses mutual fund tax strategies to reduce taxes and boost investment 
returns.<br>
&#183; Mutual Fund Newsletters: This section creates order out of the chaotic and intimidating array of 
mutual fund newsletters, letting you know how to find those that perform the best.<br>
&#183; Power Strategy: Indexing: &quot;Indexing&quot; explores the fundamentals of the fund selection process, as 
well as the merits of simplicity and index funds.<br>
<br>
Recommended funds for entrepreneurs include (in each category--investment percentages 
discussed) core international (Hotchkis &amp; Wiley International); emerging markets (T. Rowe Price 
Emerging Markets); small-growth (Strong Opportunity or Baron Asset which is more 
aggressive);mid-/large-cap growth (Selected American Shares or Harbor Capita Appreciation, 
more aggressive); mid-/large-cap value (Oakmark); REIT (Fidelity Real Estate); junk bond 
(vanguard High-yield Corporate); investment-grade bond (Fremont Bond). However, investors in 
taxable accounts should use Vanguard&#146;s intermediate-term municipal bond fund for the entire bond 
allocation. </p>
<p align=center># # #</p>
