<BR><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE="+7">Early-Stage IPOs</FONT> </P>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Companies Are Going Public Without Products or Revenues
</H2>

<CENTER><P>By Gianna Jacobson</P></CENTER>
<IMG SRC="ipo.GIF" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="144" HEIGHT="170">
<P>When pitching her company to stockbrokers and
investors, Audrey Contente focused on the future. She had to -- she didn't
yet have a product. Contente had poured millions into developing a plastic
tampon alternative called Instead. This new product promised to revolutionize
the feminine hygiene market. Made of a soft plastic, it molds to each individual
and can be worn twice as long as a regular tampon. </P>

<P>But a nationwide launch of a new consumer product
costs millions just to get to the prototype stage. Contente believed a
public stock offering would give her the cash she needed to finish development
and roll out Instead across the country.</P>

<P>Typically, road shows consist of the entrepreneur presenting his or
her company's proven history and charts revealing increasingly profitable
quarters. Contente's offered little of the traditional fare. After she
introduced her management team, shared testimonials from financial experts,
and showed samples of the product, she explained how the female reproductive
system worked. After 76 presentations in 22 days, she'd answered every
question in the book. </P>

<P>Despite no product and zero revenues, investors clamored for a piece
of her company, Ultrafem Inc. of New York City. </P>

<P>''We had a patent, FDA approval, and a proprietary manufacturing process,''
says Contente. ''That's a lot for a young company.'' She successfully raised
$39 million -- one of the largest start-up IPOs in recent memory. </P>

<P>Similar scenarios have been replayed dozens of times in the past year,
as entrepreneurial companies go public at earlier stages than ever before.
In 1995 alone, 575 companies sold $29 billion worth of new stock; and 1996
is well on its way to surpassing that figure. Traditionally, underwriters
would consider taking a company public only if it could claim $4 million
in assets and $2 million in net worth. </P>

<P>But the rules have changed. Both private and institutional investors
are scrambling for stocks that promise tremendous gains. Underwriters,
hungry to make the deals, are willing to take chances on companies that
meet none of the old requirements. Among the new breed of IPOs are many
firms just beginning to collect revenues. Others, such as Ultrafem, have
yet to place their products on the market. </P>

<P>''The window is open to IPOs,'' says James Arkebauer, president of Venture
Associates in Denver and author of The Entrepreneur's Guide to Going Public.
''Investors are looking for ways to increase their returns, so underwriters
are able to push the envelope on the quality of projects.'' </P>

<P>No one knows how long this sizzling market will last. As some of the
riskier ventures fail, underwriters and investors may stop backing upstart
companies. And the market's natural cycle means the current expansion will
wind down. The fact that no expert can predict the market's timing is pushing
entrepreneurs still in the start-up mode to rush their companies into the
public market for funding. * </P>

<P>Early-stage IPOs started in the late 1980s with biotech companies. Strong
on technology and applications but low on cash, these enterprises became
known for spending millions on research and development but returning many
more millions when the products hit pay dirt. Public investors were willing
to bet on a new stock for the possibility of staggering returns. </P>

<P><B>The Hottest Market Segments </B></P>

<P>''The question now is which other areas without revenues and profitability
are open to public offerings,'' says Martin Bell, vice chairman of D.H.
Blair Investment Banking Corp. ''Every Internet company wants to be the
next Netscape, and the staggering valuations that Internet companies are
generating are difficult to justify by any historical standard of analysis.''
</P>

<P>Software and Internet companies are the brightest IPO stars now. ''If
you've got a business plan and a (computer-related) product with broad
applications, you can go public,'' says Bell. </P>

<P>Five Internet-related companies that went public in the first quarter
of this year were trading an average of 36 percent more than their opening
prices within one week of their public offerings. </P>

<P>CyberCash Inc. of Reston, Va., is one of these five firms. Touted as
another Netscape during its frenzied IPO, it raised nearly $60 million
earlier this year. Just like Ultrafem, it didn't have a penny in sales
at the time. On the day of its offering, CyberCash closed at $28.25 per
share, after its 2.4 million shares opened at $17, the top of its filing
range. </P>

<P>Bill Melton founded the company in 1994, after he spent months studying
the Internet and wondering how money could be securely exchanged. He created
a plan for conducting bank transactions electronically and developed software
to provide security for credit card, check, and cash services for the Internet.
</P>

<P>Melton successfully negotiated agreements with CheckFree Corp., CompuServe,
Wells Fargo Bank, American Express, and MasterCard. But right about the
time of its IPO, CyberCash had just begun delivering the software, and
the earliest estimates for profits are late 1997. </P>

<P>As Melton watched other Internet companies cash in on the market's frenzy,
he knew he couldn't wait. He believes the Internet is more revolutionary
than the printing press and that the Information Age will have a greater
effect on our society than the Machine Age. </P>

<P>''To compete in this rapidly growing market with other major potential
players -- most of which were being funded with high-value public stock
-- we too would need public funding,'' says Melton. ''The public is trying
to participate profitably in these changes. The public market is taking
on the role of venture capitalist, with all the risks and potential for
profit.'' </P>

<P>Many investors and brokers in the IPO feeding frenzy look strictly at
companies such as CyberCash in the hot categories -- biotech, health care,
and especially software and Internet services. But beyond the market trends,
the real key to a successful IPO rests on the relationship between the
company and its underwriter. </P>

<P><B>Create an Alliance With Your Underwriter </B></P>

<P>''The underwriter and the company have a mutuality of interest, but
the process can go off track,'' says Bell. </P>

<P>In the financial world, especially with high-tech offerings, everything
moves at lightning speed. IPOs can be derailed by competing products, adverse
publicity, even litigation. Companies involved in an IPO have nothing to
lose by completing the offering, even if they raise less money than expected.
But underwriters, who count on particular value for the stock, may benefit
from pulling out. </P>

<P>''The more convinced the underwriter is in the strength of the company,
the more committed he will be to the success of the IPO,'' says Bell. </P>

<P>The best way to create an alliance with an underwriter is to develop
a long-standing relationship, as both Contente and Melton did with their
stock underwriters. </P>

<P>Hampshire Securities Corp., a small private investment banking firm
in New York City, had already been a source of funding for Ultrafem when
it provided a bridge loan two years before the company's IPO. </P>

<P>''Hampshire's managers had been aware of the company,'' says Contente.
''They did a tremendous amount of due diligence and expressed interest
in doing an IPO at some point. We talked continuously about investment
partners, and eventually the conversations turned to when we should do
this. There was no question about their participation.'' </P>

<P>In CyberCash's case, Melton's relationship with Hambrecht &amp; Quist
was less formal but equally ingrained. ''Steve Birer (an H&amp;Q analyst)
had been in frequent contact with me for over a year, trying to understand
how traditional banking transactions were going to be handled on the Internet,''
says Melton. ''Early in our discussions, I decided to go with H&amp;Q because
of its sincere interest in trying to understand the marketplace.'' </P>

<P>Underwriters offer companies two types of deals: firm commitments or
best efforts. Firm commitments obligate the underwriter to purchase all
of the stock issue, regardless of whether it can resell the securities
to the public. A best efforts agreement, most commonly used for low-priced
IPO issues, states that the underwriter will extend its best efforts to
sell the stock but doesn't make any guarantee to purchase any stock that
remains unsold. </P>

<P>Large underwriters usually offer firm commitments. ''All reputable underwriters
have a good-faith desire to sell the company's stock,'' says Bell. ''The
time, effort, and expense you put in as an underwriter increase your commitment.''
</P>

<P><B>Going Public on the Internet</B> </P>

<P>Not every company needs an underwriter to go public. Companies looking
for less than $5 million can raise money on the Internet. ''We are going
to see a greater trend toward offerings on the Internet, where you don't
need an underwriter anymore,'' says Alan Johnson, a St. Louis attorney
who specializes in public offerings. </P>

<P>Spring Street Brewing Co. made news last February when it raised $1.6
million in the first offering circulated on the Internet, bypassing underwriters
(along with their typical fee of 10 percent of the offering) altogether.
A month later, Interactive Holdings Corp. followed suit. </P>

<P>David Loring, Interactive Holdings's founder, has never taken the conventional
route in his business ideas. So it was only natural that he would seek
an alternative route like the Internet to raise money. </P>

<P>The son of entertainers, Loring developed viewer participation programming
for the Internet and television. His first program, Men Across America,
is a matchmaking service created for cable distribution. Revenues, when
they begin to flow, will come from viewers rather than advertisers. </P>

<P>While none of Interactive's programs are generating sales yet, Loring
expects to raise $2 million when his registration period ends this September.
He needs the money to distribute the programming he has already developed
and to create new programming. Since he founded the New York City company
in 1994, financing has proved a little harder than he expected. </P>

<P>''If you look at the Fortune-500 companies, most started as tiny companies
with a vision,'' says Loring. ''We're on the verge of a technical revolution.
The big winners will be those that develop and own content for that technology.''
</P>

<P>While online stock brokerages are beginning to boom, many market pros
are cautious about Internet offerings. Stocks need to trade on a market
to have value. Many question whether online brokerages constitute a market.
</P>

<P>At the end of the day, though, the right timing is the most crucial
component for a successful IPO. ''The market is dynamite for entrepreneurs
now,'' notes Arkebauer of Venture Associates. ''When it's hot, entrepreneurs
have to move on it, or they'll be left hanging.'' </P>

<P>You hear the same advice from underwriters such as Bell: ''We urge companies
who are looking to go public to do so as quickly as possible. I don't know
how long the window will stay open, but I know that each day, we get closer
to the day the window will close.'' </P>

<P>Contributing editor Gianna Jacobson of St. Louis specializes in entrepreneurial
finance. <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.1 -437838. --></P>

