<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4"> <center>The Entrepreneurial Eye</FONT>

<P>EDITED BY TOM STEIN</P>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#CC000C">WASHINGTON WATCH</FONT> </P>

<FONT SIZE="+3">Fight Unfair Penalties</FONT></CENTER>

<P>If the government slaps you with an unfair penalty, now's the time to
take action. The new Small Business Regulatory Enforcement Fairness Act
allows you to recover legal defense fees. </P>

<P>''In the past, due to prohibitive costs, small-business owners were
often forced to accept federal enforcements actions rather than mount a
defense,'' says Senator Christopher S. Bond, who crafted the legislation.
''This provision will level the playing field.'' </P>

<P>The law should also strengthen the Regulatory Flexibility Act of 1980,
which was designed to relieve the regulatory burden on entrepreneurs. ''Unfortunately,
there was no enforcement mechanism, so the act was ineffective because
agencies didn't comply,'' says Congressman Rob Portman. ''By allowing small
businesses to challenge regulations in court, the law has the teeth it
needs to be effective.'' </P>

<P>The new law requires federal agencies to prepare ''Plain English'' compliance
guides, which clearly explain how businesses can adhere to federal regulations.
An independent ombudsman will receive complaints and comments from business
owners about their dealings with federal regulators. </P>

<P>Not everyone is happy with the new measure. Arthur Levitt, chairman
of the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), says his agency's ability
to penalize rogue brokerage firms will be harmed by the law. He worries
the SEC's budget could be at risk if firms mount successful defenses and
recover legal fees from his agency. </P>


<BR><HR><BR>
<P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">THE INTERNET</FONT> </P>
<FONT SIZE="+3">Download the Perfect Business Plan </FONT>

<P>Devising a top-notch business plan can cause many sleepless nights.
You can avoid the frustration by downloading a successful model from the
Net. </P>

<P>The MoneyHunter Web site at http://www. moneyhunter.com. is attracting
thousands of visitors every week with its 40-page business plan template.
Just fill in the blanks, and you're ready to make a convincing pitch to
investors. </P>

<P>The template was created by experts who understand what investors want
to hear. ''We know how to get to the jugular immediately,'' says cocreator
Miles Spencer of Capital Express L.L.C., a venture capital firm. ''There
is no other business plan template that has been written by folks who see
2,000 deals a year.'' </P>

<P>The MoneyHunter template has 11 sections, including Company Overview,
Risk/Opportunity, and Capital Requirements. </P>

<P>Neville Vere Nicoll of Kryptonics Inc. recently used MoneyHunter to
raise $5 million. His company makes polyurethane wheels for such products
as in-line skates. </P>

<P>''I'm always afraid to leave something out of my business plan,'' says
Vere Nicoll. ''The template is a well-thought-out and thorough outline.''
</P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">IPO UPDATE</FONT> </P>

<FONT SIZE="+3">Tech Firms Big Winners</FONT>

<P>Sixty-three companies went public in April, according to Securities
Data Company of Nxewark, N.J., up from 34 companies a year ago. The median
amount raised was $31 million. Once again, high-tech companies, including
the first three Internet search engine firms to go public, were big winners
on Wall Street.</P>

<P>Spotlight: Excite Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., an Internet search
engine company. </P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Established: July 1994 <BR>

	<LI>1996 First-Quarter Revenues: $1.1 million <BR>

	<LI>Amount raised: $34 million <BR>
</UL>

<P>''One reason we went public is that we saw the need to compete in brand
building,'' says George Bell, CEO of Excite Inc. ''We're up against strong
brands like Yahoo!'' </P>

<P>''There's always danger that investors feel that there are enough of
you in any one category. They want to know the difference between the fourth
story and the last stories they heard. We didn't want to be sixth in line.
</P>

<P>''Most people think of going public as a process that takes the better
part of a year. It doesn't have to be that way. You can put pressure on
bankers and lawyers. You can say, 'Hey, I like you guys a lot, but I can't
work with you unless you can do X, Y, and Z by the following dates.' ''
</P>

<P>-- Brent Pollock </P>
