<head>
   <title>GlobEnt</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b4Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</head>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BR>
<center><p><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">GLOBAL ENTREPRENEUR </font></p></center>

<center><p>By Kristin Dunlap Godsey </p></center>
<BR>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE="+6">Sharp Antenna</FONT></CENTER>

<h3 align=center>Staying Tuned In to the Future </h3><BR>

<p>Entrepreneur Richard Price's ability to foresee change and exploit it
has guided him through three decades of television history. Price owns
the London-based Primetime Group, an independent, international distributor
and producer of programming. It was Price who sold Upstairs, Downstairs
to PBS in 1973 -- after all the other networks turned it down -- ushering
in an age of Anglophilia in the U.S. He started his business as Richard
Price Television Associates in 1968, after following the industry and plotting
the best time to make his move. </p>

<p>Price had been international sales director for the British distributor
Grenada Television Ltd. ''For various reasons, I decided I would much rather
own my own company,'' he says. ''I could see that television was an area
of great expansion. In particular, I knew the exchange of programming between
countries was going to increase immensely.'' </p>

<p>Price foresaw two important changes in the international arena. The
first was the technical ability to convert British programming to American
standards electronically. Until 1969, this was impossible; as a result,
British television translated very poorly on American channels. The second
change was the widespread arrival of color TV throughout Europe. </p>

<p>Price's new company was poised and ready. Established production companies,
impressed with Price's reputation as a distributor for Grenada, knocked
on his door within the first six months. </p>

<p>The United States was going through industry changes as well. At that
time, broadcast networks owned their own international distributors. But
in 1970, the FCC disallowed U.S. networks to sell prime-time shows internationally.
Another ruling required local stations in the U.S. to devote a portion
of the prime-time schedule to non-network programming. It was an ideal
opportunity for the few independent distributors that existed -- and Price
had several advantages over his competitors. </p>

<p>His aggressive selling, international experience, and quality product
made an impression in the States. His relationship with American companies
was excellent, partly because he'd spent four years during World War II
as a student in Boston. He understood American styles and tastes better
than most other international distributors. When he saw what he had with
Upstairs, Downstairs, he hit the U.S. networks hard. </p>

<p><b>Persistence Pays Off</b> </p>

<p>''It was just downright, bloody persistence,'' says Price. ''It took
me 12 presentations to the networks to finally get it on the air. Once
it took off, everybody said, 'Why the hell didn't anyone think of this
before?' '' </p>

<p>Today, Primetime Group is a $35 million company. It has sold hundreds
of dramas, music and arts programs, documentaries, comedies, and children's
shows around the globe. It has distributed and produced or coproduced such
international successes as The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby,
Porgy and Bess, and Les Mis&eacute;rables in Concert. Four years ago, Price
sold a quarter of Primetime to the Rockefeller family and its British counterparts,
the Flemings. Together, they formed a new entity called T.E.A.M. (Television
Enterprise and Asset Management). This umbrella group includes Primetime,
three independent production companies, and one distributor of videos and
CD-ROMs. T.E.A.M. has helped Primetime grow into the U.K.'s largest independent
distributor of international programming. </p>

<p>An office in New York and a recent merger in Germany are propelling
Primetime's growth. But it's Price's vigilant presence and consistent commitment
to quality that drive the company's success. Outside the office, Price
has run for Parliament, served as chairman of the British Academy of Film
and Television Arts, and consulted for the Department of National Heritage.
Today, although he has delegated most of Primetime's distribution responsibilities,
he keeps a firm hand on the production side, reviewing scripts and choosing
projects. </p>

<p>On his entrepreneurial philosophy, Price is succinct: ''A successful
entrepreneur backs his own ideas, then gets off his butt and makes them
work. Persistence is the most important thing.'' a </p>

<p>SUCCESS associate editor Kristin Dunlap Godsey covers international
entrepreneurship and business technology.</p>
