</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
   <title>MobileE</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b4Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</head>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">THE MOBILE ENTREPRENEUR</FONT></P></CENTER>
<CENTER><P>By Jeffery Kagan</P></center><BR><BR>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE="+4">Deliver a One-Two Punch </FONT></CENTER>

<h3 align=center>Put Your Cell Phone and Pager Together </h3><BR>

<p>Andrew Chonoles, partner in the Manhattan law firm Zukerman, Gore &amp;
Brandeis LLP, was heading out on a weekend ski trip with a couple of clients.
His cell phone rang. It was a client in the middle of a last-minute dispute,
desperate for advice. Chonoles was able to walk his client through the
dispute and save the day. ''The last thing I expected was to do business
that afternoon,'' he says. </p>

<p>More than 34 million Americans use cell phones today, up from only 16
million in 1993. The only problem is, most people leave their cell phone
off. They don't realize much of the anytime, anyplace power a cell phone
offers is useless unless it's turned on. </p>

<p>The use of pagers is also growing faster than ever imagined. There are
34 million people carrying pagers today, compared with 20 million in 1993.
The units they clip on are no longer simple, annoying beepers, but complete
message centers. They offer full-text messages and voice messaging on your
pager and store them for later review. You can even get two-way paging
and respond to the sender with the touch of a button on your pager. You
can get news on your industry, and even pick up your e-mail. Service can
be citywide, regional, or national -- critical to the entrepreneur who
spends much time on the road. Prices typically vary from $10 to $60 per
month, depending on the features and coverage. It's a small price to pay
to save one deal or close one extra piece of business. And prices are expected
to drop this year as more companies get into the paging business. </p>

<p>''Cellular used to be a status symbol,'' according to USA Today reporter
Melanie Wells, who covers the frenzied world of advertising. ''Today, it's
the price of admission.'' </p>

<p><b>Match the Service to the Tools </b></p>

<p>Just as people are jumping on the cellular-and-paging bandwagon, the
service choices are getting more confusing. Not only do you have the two
traditional cellular providers in each city, but MCI and AT&amp;T are moving
into cities all over the country, providing cellular service and paging
service, either on their own or with PageNet, SkyTel, and a host of other
local and national providers. Prices are being driven down, so now is not
the time to sign long-term contracts. </p>

<p>Soon a new technology called PCS (Personal Communications Services)
will burst onto the scene and send cellular prices plummeting. It happened
in Washington, D.C., when the first PCS service was rolled out several
months ago. PCS will provide paging and cellular-like services on a digital
network, at a much reduced price. </p>

<p>Chicago was hit by a massive ice storm, and Mike Nikolich, president
of public relations firm Tech Image Ltd., found himself out in the cold.
His office was without power or phones for 48 hours. </p>

<p>Just after the lights went out, an editor in New Jersey reached Nikolich
by pager. He returned the call on his cell phone. The editor needed a manuscript
from Nikolich, and he needed it now. But the East Coast was socked in even
worse than Chicago. ''Because road conditions were so bad in New Jersey,
traditional overnight delivery services wouldn't guarantee delivery for
one week -- that obviously wasn't an option,'' according to Nikolich. ''In
panic, I called a friend on my cellular phone and asked if he had a cellular
modem. He did. I hooked up my laptop to his car phone and completed transmitting
the story just as the power drained from the PC. We made our deadline and
received a cover story to boot!'' </p>
<BR><HR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+2">TRAVEL TIPS</FONT>

<p><b>Wireless Power </b></p>

<p>It may be time to trade in that fax modem on your laptop computer for
a cellular-ready fax modem. Prices have fallen below $200 at many computer
stores, and they allow you to plug your laptop into your cell phone from
anywhere to send and receive e-mail and faxes. </p>

<p><b>Airborne Performance </b></p>

<p>You can now fax and e-mail from 30,000 feet. Just plug your laptop into
the telephone in the airplane seat. At an average $2.50 per minute, you
won't want to surf the Net for an hour, but it gives you an edge to remain
connected to news, online services, home, your office, or clients. </p>

<p><b>Go Phone Free </b></p>

<p>Watch out for ''free'' cellular phones with car rentals. Those free
phones still charge hefty per-minute and long-distance charges, and at
more than a dollar per minute, your bill can add up quickly. </p>

<p>Analyst Jeffrey Kagan is founder and CEO of Georgia-based Kagan Telecom
Associates. He serves as strategic adviser, industry analyst, and consultant
to the telecommunications industry. <BR>
<BR><HR><BR>
