   <TITLE>DirSell</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">DIRECT SELLING</FONT> <BR><BR>

<center>By Duncan Maxwell Anderson</center><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE="+4">Motivation Formula</FONT>

<H3>Keep It Simple, Push Where You're Winning </H3></CENTER><BR>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">For the first two years after it was started in 1992, Achievers Unlimited
Inc. operated from founder Kathy Connelly's garage. Now, in more conventional
offices in West Palm Beach, Fla., Connelly and co-owner Gary Hanger have
a growth strategy like Napoleon's: Don't bother shoring up where you're
weak -- support the units that are gaining ground. Achievers, a nutritional
company, projects $57 million in wholesale revenues for 1996. </FONT></P>

<P><B>What got you started in network marketing? </B></P>

<P>Kathy: For several years, I was a flight attendant for Eastern Airlines
in Miami, and I distributed part-time for a series of companies. Gary was
a flight attendant, too, and I had him in my downline in several companies.
</P>

<P><B>Why didn't you stay with any of those companies? </B></P>

<P>Kathy: A few of them had problems with the authorities; one ran off
with the cash. But typically, my team and I were working hard, but not
making much money. When Eastern folded, that put us both out of work. We
decided we were going to start a company that did things right. </P>

<P>Gary: We wanted to know: For the majority of the people, what is their
best chance for success? If they're not making money, they'll go to another
company. A company dissolves from the bottom. So we adopted a plan that
was simple, and we paid the maximum commission with your first order. </P>

<P><B>How did you choose what product to sell? </B></P>

<P>Gary: In this business, you need to put impact products on the market,
where people get results in the short term. Where they lose weight, or
feel better, or get increased energy. The weight management industry was
huge. Chromium picolinate was just being licensed, and we were the first
to combine it with herbs that help burn body fat in our first product,
Tri-Chromaleane. </P>

<P><B>How much capital did you have? </B></P>

<P>Gary: We started with $15,000. We contracted everything out, so we didn't
have to make those investments: manufacturing, fulfillment, computer services,
payroll. Our first order from our manufacturer was for 25 cases. By the
end of that year, we were shipping 1,000 cases per month. </P>

<P>Kathy: Our office was a pool table in my garage, and each person got
one side of it. When sales started to get up around $35 million, we realized
we were outgrowing the garage. </P>

<P><B>How did you keep your growth from killing you? </B></P>

<P>Gary: Each month, I'd order the same amount we'd sold, plus 25 percent.
And to keep the growth going, we've always gotten the checks out by the
10th of the month. At most companies, you don't get paid on last month's
sales until the 25th of this month. That's not very motivating. We get
a burst of sales in the middle of the month, because people just got their
checks and want to do more. </P>

<P><B>What other &quot;impact products&quot; did you create? </B></P>

<P>Gary: Most people know that free radicals damage the body and may be
responsible for aging by ''oxidizing'' your cells. Our antioxidant, CytoPro,
is more powerful than others because we've added green tea extract and
other ingredients, which reduce free radicals all the way down to plain
water. CytoLife, our ''super-food,'' is made from a hydrilla plant that
grows on lakes in the Southeast. </P>

<P><B>What mistakes have you made? </B></P>

<P>We hurt our growth by putting out six new products in a year, without
properly educating our distributors. We've since created a tape series,
fax-on-demand, and satellite broadcasts. </P>

<P><B>Do you have a plan for geographic expansion? </B></P>

<P>Gary: No. We do statistical studies to see where we're growing. We find
out who the leaders are and send advisers to help them at meetings. </P>

<P>Kathy: You'd be amazed at what people can do. You see retired secretaries
speaking to big crowds and pulling down six-figure incomes. We have 40,000
distributors, and we should do better than $50 million wholesale this year.
</P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">TRENDS</FONT> </P>

<FONT SIZE="+3">Massive MLM Deal</FONT>

<P>It could be the biggest deal in direct selling history. Economist and
entrepreneur Paul Pilzer has an agreement with Amway Corp. to sell 180
educational CD-ROM titles through a new Amway catalog that will go to1.5
million American distributors this year. </P>

<P>America's public school system is a $450 billion industry. Pilzer says
that Amway and Zane Publishing Inc. of Dallas, which he started in 1989,
stand to grab a major piece of that business, because direct selling is
uniquely suited to educational products. </P>

<P>Pilzer has been buying up the electronic rights to widely used school
texts in science, literature, art, and music, and such ''name-brand'' reference
works as the Merriam-Webster Dictionary to offer on multimedia CD-ROM.
His products are available at most bookstore chains, computer stores, and
retailers such as Wal-Mart. But he says that information products like
these sell better face-to-face: </P>

<P>''If a parent tells a distributor, 'My child is having trouble in biology
class,' the distributor can say, 'Look -- here's a multimedia CD-ROM of
the same textbook he's using at school. Except it's interactive, so he
can learn at his own speed, with pictures and sounds.' To help the parent,
you have to have the whole library available, which is easy in a direct
selling catalog. But conventional retailers can't do that, because they
can't afford the shelf space to stock 180 titles.'' </P>

<P>Pilzer's catalog covers about 50 percent of the school curriculum from
first grade through high school, including science, literature, history,
art, and music. </P>

<P>There are 30 million multimedia PCs in homes, says Pilzer, and that
number is going up all the time. In a sense, software is already a direct
selling product, Pilzer contends: &quot;You don't buy a program without
having it recommended by someone else. Now, for the first time, the person
who recommends it will get his commission. And just think: Unlike the vitamins,
you can tell right away if this product works.&quot; </P>

<P>Sam Walton's retailing coup was increasing his volume per square foot:
$100 to $300 in 10 years. Amway is hoping to increase dramatically the
sales of existing distributors by helping them get a piece of the school
curriculum market. </P>

<P>&quot;Home school families already eat this stuff alive,&quot; says
Pilzer. &quot;But we expect to change the way education is done in this
country as parents get more involved in their kids' education. We're delivering
the best teacher in every subject affordably. Every parent will know his
kid can learn at his own pace and won't get bored or lost.&quot;  </P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">VITAL STATISTICS</FONT> </P>

<FONT SIZE="+3">Can You Retire?</FONT>

<P>Middle Americans want to retire early -- but most won't have the resources
to do it, according to a new nationwide poll by Louis Harris &amp; Associates
for Primerica Financial Services, a direct selling company. The Harris
organization polled people with incomes of $25,000 to $75,000 and found
that the median age at which they expected to retire was 61. </P>

<P>The median respondent was 45, with an income of $50,000 per year. To
retire at $40,000 per year by age 61, most of those polled will need to
save almost impossible sums to make the $1,257,791 nest egg they'll need,
assuming it's invested at 10 percent. </P>

<P>The chart below lists the monthly savings required for households
A, B, and C, which now have, respectively, $100,000, $50,000, and $0 in
the bank. Even prudent household A will need to put aside $1,283 each month.
</P>

<P>How will these people escape the bind they're in? One way would be for
them to increase their income drastically. One way to do that might be
direct selling. </P>

<BR><IMG SRC="retchc.gif" ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE><BR><BR>

