   <TITLE>Books</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">REVIEWS: BOOKS AND TAPES</FONT> </P>

<center>Edited By Duncan Maxwell Anderson</center><BR><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Secrets of the Future</FONT>
</H1>

<H3>How to Find Competitive Intelligence -- Everywhere </H3></CENTER>


<BR><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+3">Competitive Intelligence,</FONT><B> By Larry Kahaner.</B>

<P>As Sun-Tzu said, the critical ingredient of strategy is ''foreknowledge.''
What will happen next in your market, among your competitors, or in the
world that can offer you an advantage? Larry Kahaner, author of Competitive
Intelligence, is a private investigator and former journalist -- an expert
at ''foreknowledge.'' Virtually all the information you need to gain an
advantage for your business is not truly secret, he says. It's publicly
available, if you know how to look for it. </P>

<P>When Ray Kroc was building McDonald's, he took a direct approach: He'd
fly over expanding suburban areas in a light plane to see where new houses
and roads were going in, to be first with stores in the high-traffic locations.
</P>

<P>An aerospace company used a much subtler strategy to gather information,
sending someone wearing soft, rubber-soled shoes on a public tour of a
competitor's plant. The gummy bottoms picked up minute metal shavings from
the plant, and the aerospace company's laboratory was able to detect what
exotic metals were in use at the competing plant. </P>

<P>Sam Walton changed the retailing world by simply walking through Sears
stores and hearing customers complain that items were out of stock. He
surmised that Sears's distribution system was at fault and that he could
create an advantage by building a better system. </P>

<P>But some of the most valuable intelligence is not gathered from rivals.
Non-competing companies will often allow you inside their facilities to
benchmark the highest-performance parts of their operation. Motorola wanted
to improve its cycle time between order and delivery -- so it studied the
practices at Domino's Pizza, the leader in fast delivery. To increase its
strength against Japanese companies like Ricoh and Canon in copier service
and repair, Xerox benchmarked against L.L. Bean's world-famous warehousing
and distribution operation. </P>

<P>For an everyday diet of significant information, Kahaner says your sales
force is the best source: Collect strategic insights on an 800 line or
a dedicated e-mail account. Make sure the sales force profits from insights
learned elsewhere in the company. This will ensure that, quid pro quo,
the intelligence keeps coming. </P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+3">The Death of Competition</FONT><BR>
<H4>by James F. Moore.</H4>

<P>If you think you can succeed by simply besting your competitors, beware.
The world has become one fast-changing ''business ecosystem'' where danger
and opportunity arise from all quarters. It's no use being a great restaurant
in a failing neighborhood. The way to thrive in the future is to take part
in creating a new business ecosystem around you and make yourself essential
to it, says a new book, The Death of Competition, by James F. Moore, chairman
of GeoPartners Research Inc., a consulting firm in Cambridge, Mass. </P>

<P>Intel, for example, made itself highly profitable by specializing in
producing the chips that make computers more and more powerful -- working
closely with hardware and software manufacturers. The results have driven
a productivity increase that has touched every business on the planet and
created more demand for Intel's chips. </P>

<P>Essential to the ecosystem strategy is foreseeing how others will profit.
Starlight Telecommunications creates long-distance telephone service in
the backwaters of the world -- such as Somalia, which is run by gangs and
does not even have mail service. Somalians want to talk to relatives scattered
all over the world. With hard currency from relatives abroad, they buy
Starlight's computerized phone cards and talk on wireless pay phones the
company has installed at popular sheep-trading centers. These transmit
to an earth station in Norway. International companies and local potentates
pay to put their advertisements on the face of the cards. The company is
very profitable and will gain from its role in the eventual rebuilding
of the country. </P>

<P>The most successful entrepreneurs and executives create and maintain
what Moore calls a ''personal ecosystem'' -- a group of longtime friends
and associates who talk about new developments. You need these people,
says Moore, because ''managers have trouble scanning enough, analyzing
enough, and acting in a timely and forceful manner.'' </P>

<P>Power Plays by Robert Mayer is packed with relationship strategies that
will connect you more persuasively and effectively with customers, employees,
even competitors. Some examples: </P>

<P>Most people set their bargaining goals too low because they fear not
being nice. The reality is, the people who want more, get more. When you
bargain, extreme demands yield the best results. The rewards will far outweigh
the lost deals. </P>

<P>Use persuasive listening to redirect the other person's position to
your advantage. In Las Vegas, a show production manager answers her costume
maker, who has just told her the costumes won't be ready because she doesn't
have any orange taffeta and her seamstresses' time is fully booked. Manager:
Are you in effect telling me that if I can get orange taffeta to you and
if your seamstresses work overtime, the costumes can be ready? </P>

<P>There is a moment to shut up: when you have finally asked the other
person for a commitment on the major issues. It is a mistake to believe
that the more you say, the more you influence. You will have the urge to
talk, to sweeten your proposal somehow -- in effect, bidding against yourself.
Stifle that urge. If the response is a question, answer briefly and to
the point. Then refocus the conversation on your proposal. Do not repeat
yourself, resell, or rephrase. Let nothing impede the persuasive power
of your words. </P>

<DIV ALIGN=right><P>-- Michael Warshaw </P></DIV>
<BR><HR>

<FONT SIZE="+3">Cultivating an Unshakable Character</FONT>
<H4>by Jim Roh</H4>

<P>Jim Rohn is not fooled by your rationalizations -- or mine. His audiotape,
Cultivating an Unshakable Character, will motivate you to focus on what's
important, steel you against adversity, and prepare you for long-term victory.
</P>

<P>The origin of our word character is a Greek word that means ''chisel''
or ''the mark left by a chisel.'' To Rohn, the decisions you make in response
to the events and opportunities of your life are how you sculpt your own
character. </P>

<P>Character isn't charisma, which is the ability to win the favor of other
people. </P>

<P>In World War II, General Dwight Eisenhower was picked to head the Supreme
Allied Command because he wasn't a charismatic or dramatic man. Eisenhower
was tough. In a meeting with the top generals shortly before D-Day, he
reminded them of the importance of leading by example: ''An army is like
this piece of string,'' he said. ''If you try to push it from behind, it
just tangles. Soldiers have to be led from the front.'' </P>

<P>Courage is a crucial ingredient of character, according to Rohn. Those
who settled the American West in the 19th century faced incredible hardship
-- but it wasn't because they had no alternatives. They were shopkeepers,
farmers, and tradesmen who decided to make some big changes to find something
better. </P>

<P>Another ingredient is patience -- the ability to defer a goal. Patience
does not imply inactivity. According to Rohn, patience means putting out
your best effort, but detaching yourself from the outcome, accepting that
you may or may not win -- for now. It can mean taking off on another venture
while you give events a chance to run their course. </P>

<P>Finally, character requires confidence -- the optimism that you have
the power to make things happen. George Washington inspired confidence
in the Continental Army and in Congress because he was secure in his expertise:
He was rooted in America. He'd traveled with the British Army as a surveyor.
He knew the terrain, he knew the British, and he knew his own men. Confidence
-- and the character that backs it up -- begins with trusting others first
and bringing out the best in them.  </P>

<HR><BR>
<DIV ALIGN=CENTER>
