<HEAD>
   <TITLE>FranMain</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">FRANCHISING: Conversions</FONT> </P>

<center>BY Carol Steinberg</center><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+6">Instant Growth</FONT>

<H3>Why Independent Businesses Are Becoming Franchises</H3></CENTER>

<P>For 11 years, Keith Flouhouse and his wife, Ann, were independent real
estate agents in Charlotte, N.C. Their modest business provided them with
a comfortable lifestyle. Their agency held a 7 percent market share in
their region, and sales were growing at 7 percent per year. </P>

<P>But in the early 1990s, the real estate industry began to undergo dramatic
changes. Large regional and national players were emerging. Database programs
and other new software were making them highly efficient. The Flouhouses
were scrambling to keep pace. </P>

<P>In 1993, real estate giant Coldwell Banker Corp. approached Flouhouse
about converting to its system, and he eagerly accepted. ''There was no
place for a company in the middle anymore,'' says the 44-year-old realtor.
He thought the fastest way to grow would be to affiliate. ''Every industry
is brand name conscious today.'' </P>

<P>In three years, Flouhouse has captured 24 percent of his local market
share. He's grown from one office with 75 associates to seven offices with
400 agents. Gross commission income has skyrocketed, from $2.7 million
in 1993 to $14 million on $475 million in total sales currently. </P>

<P>Real estate, travel, and hotel chains were among the first to unite
mom-and-pops into one big franchise family. Now, businesses of all types
are adopting this growth strategy. GNC Franchising Inc. fields hundreds
of calls each year from independent vitamin retailers interested in conversion
or acquisition. Manhattan Bagel Company Inc. is incorporating conversion
as a growth tactic, prompted by inquiries from bagel store owners from
around the country. </P>

<P>By gobbling up independents, franchise chains gain quick entry into
new markets. They also get knowledgeable owners with a solid customer base.
This means that newly converted franchises can immediately begin paying
royalties. </P>

<P>But not every independent business can or should make the transition.
Some balk at a system's rules and what they get -- or don't get -- for
royalty payments. Those who find more pain than gain from the switch end
up defecting. But when conversion is done correctly, both sides can reap
huge rewards. </P>

<P><B>Build Brand Equity </B></P>

<P>Often, it can be faster and more profitable for a company to convert
independents than to build units from scratch. All Coldwell Banker start-up
units lack revenues for three to five months and usually take two years
to reach profitability.  </P>

<P>The chain includes 335 company units and 2,200 franchises -- almost
all conversions. Coldwell Banker's company division almost exclusively
acquires -- rather than starts -- agencies. Coldwell pursues only the number-one
or -two realtor in a rural community or the top four in a large metro area.
</P>

<P>Most converted franchisees gain an average of 20 percent sales their
first year. </P>

<P>''It's not like we're fixing something broken,'' says Chandler Barton,
president and CEO of the Mission Viejo, Calif., company. ''We're taking
something good and helping it to get even better. We enhance its performance.''
</P>

<P>Former independent Keith Flouhouse spent $75,000 to convert to Coldwell
Banker's standards. (The company has since reduced the fee to $20,000.)
He received an intensive one-week training course. A Coldwell support team
came in to review his business, set up systems, and educate his associates.
Even with the 6 percent royalties that he pays to the parent company each
month, his net profitability is up 4.8 percent. </P>

<P>The affiliation has provided Flouhouse with the muscle to grow through
acquisitions. Prior to conversion, Flouhouse had bought three small companies.
As a Coldwell Banker franchisee, he's acquired six more. ''We probably
would not have gotten half of them without the Coldwell Banker name,''
he says. ''It gives a lot of credibility.'' Now, Flouhouse is making moves
on five more companies. </P>

<P>Coldwell encourages its franchisees to buy competitors. Its sales force
helps franchisees identify potential candidates and structure deals. (Coldwell
itself was recently acquired by HFS Inc., the world's largest franchisor
of hotels and residential real estate brokerage offices.) Flouhouse attended
four how-to seminars. When he wooed his biggest competitor, corporate staff
tracked profitability and budgetary items and helped him negotiate a price.
</P>

<P>Coldwell's support materials are boosting agent productivity. The chain's
new Web site for buyers and sellers should drive sales. ''It's the difference
between having an unorganized system versus a highly organized system,''
says Flouhouse. </P>

<P><B>Follow the System </B></P>

<P>Manhattan Bagel Company CEO Jack Grumet was visiting upstate New York
when he saw an independent bagel store -- coincidentally called Cafe Manhattan
Bagel Shop. The unit had a prime location; Grumet wanted it for himself.
</P>

<P>Although conversion wasn't in his game plan, Grumet thought he could
knock out a potential competitor and obtain the site by incorporating the
store into his 175-unit chain. </P>

<P>The only problem was that the store's owner, Michael Lawrence, had never
thought about becoming a franchisee. Lawrence and his wife, Dee, had run
the shop in Scotia, N.Y., since 1988. He'd opened a second bagel store
with his brother Mark. </P>

<P>But Lawrence was intrigued by Manhattan Bagel's operating method. The
company delivers frozen dough from a commissary twice each week, and franchisees
boil and bake the bagels fresh daily. </P>

<P>He knew this would eliminate waste. Even better, he wouldn't have to
wake up at 3:00 a.m. every day to make bagels. </P>

<P>Lawrence visited about 15 Manhattan Bagel stores and met with executives
at corporate headquarters in Eatontown, N.J. He became convinced that converting
could improve his sales. In April 1995, he became a franchisee. </P>

<P>A successful conversion boils down to how much you give up and how much
you gain in return. Manhattan Bagel waived the franchise fee for Lawrence
and allowed him to maintain the same decor at his two units. Still, he
pumped in about $50,000 per store for new menu boards, grill, and signage.
</P>

<P>He's put his own stamp on the system. For example, his stores still
sell gourmet coffee beans -- something the chain may consider in the future.
He persuaded Manhattan Bagel to sell one of his best-selling bagels --
''oatgoodness.'' </P>

<P>Dan Levy, Manhattan Bagel's vice president of franchise development,
believes these accommodations are critical: ''You can't ask a guy to change
his whole life. You work within the framework of what already exists.''
</P>

<P>According to Lawrence, the relationship works because he was already
doing many things similar to his new parent's tactics. ''We had the basics
down,'' he says. ''They pushed us to look at the bigger picture.'' </P>

<P>By adopting Manhattan Bagel's operating system, Lawrence has cut costs
and improved productivity. He can focus more on customer service and marketing.
''We're stepping back and managing the store instead of working it,'' he
says. Before, he never spot-checked products or tracked inventory. He's
implemented Manhattan Bagel's promotions, direct mail campaigns, and fax
program for business orders. </P>

<P>Revenues are up 20 percent in Scotia and 50 percent at his second location
in Colonie, N.Y. Combined sales at his two units are $25,000 per week.
Net profit margins, after 5 percent royalties, have soared to 18 percent
from 14 percent in Scotia and break even at the newer store. Lawrence said
it would have taken a lot longer to hit these levels on his own. </P>

<P><B>On the Offensive</B> </P>

<P>Richard Davis had run a successful health food store in Brandon, Fla.,
since 1984. But he was anticipating pressure from larger vitamin retailers
and even supermarkets. In 1991, GNC Franchising Inc. sent him a solicitation
to become a franchisee. ''It took me five seconds to understand what I
had to do,'' says Davis, 59. ''I had two reasons. One was defensive; one
was offensive.'' </P>

<P>If he didn't convert, Davis knew GNC would open down the block, because
it has no fear of small competition. He estimated that a GNC store in a
planned regional mall nearby would slash his sales by 25 percent. ''You're
competing against people with deep pockets,'' he says. ''They'll out-merchandise
and out-advertise you. I had to cut them off at the pass.'' </P>

<P>Offensively, Davis wanted more stores -- something to leave his children.
He knew GNC would finance them more eagerly than any bank. </P>

<P>As part of his conversion agreement, Davis secured the right to open
a GNC in the regional mall. He moved fast to stake out other locations.
The GNC name helped him to negotiate more favorable lease terms. The company
financed three more units, which Davis operates with his wife, his two
sons, and his daughter-in-law. He's doubled sales at the original store.
His four franchise units generate seven-figure revenues. </P>

<P>GNC of Pittsburgh entices conversion franchisees with an initial $7,500
fee, which is $20,000 less than normal. </P>

<P>''We take out the competition and immediately add to market share,''
says Russell Cooper, GNC's senior vice president and general manager. ''It's
worth the difference in fees to do that.'' </P>

<P>The 2,651-unit chain holds 15 percent of the vitamin market and plans
to add 450 stores each year for the next four years. GNC manufactures many
of its own products and will spend $45 million on advertising this year.
</P>

<P>Of the 5,000 independent health food stores, 10 percent to 20 percent
have the location and sales volume appropriate for conversion/acquisition.
Cooper hopes they'll switch rather than fight. </P>

<P>The vitamin behemoth has slowed its conversion rate from 50 units to
about 20 units annually. Instead, it's focusing on buying out independent
units and sometimes selling them to franchisees or making them company
stores. The shift comes because ''more people were looking for an exit
strategy rather than a change of name,'' Cooper explains. </P>

<P>Not every conversion works out. A handful of GNC's franchisees have
converted back to independents. ''Some weren't born to be systems people,''
says Cooper. </P>

<P>Franchisee Richard Davis agrees. ''If you can't adjust to having outside
control and maintaining your personal dignity and your own mission statement,
you shouldn't do it.'' </P>

<P>Over the years, he's bumped heads with some corporate staff. ''If I
have problems, it's when corporate people talk to us like employees. I'm
president of my company,'' he says. </P>

<P>Franchisees are also at the mercy of systemwide programs. GNC's Gold
Card Program discounts merchandise 20 percent the first Tuesday of each
month. As a result, Davis's margins have dropped by one-fifth over one
year. He feels the pinch more than new stores because he has a customer
base and carries many low-margin food items, he says. </P>

<P>Cooper, however, calls the Gold Card a ''grand-slam success.'' He says
it adds one week's worth of sales in one day and affects margins only 2
percent in the aggregate. </P>

<P>Overall, though, Davis says that being on the GNC team has added tremendous
value to his business. The financing enabled him to become a multiunit
owner. He benefits from product recognition and massive buying power. </P>

<P>''No matter what happens, I'm in a safe zone as far as the ultimate
success of my business because of my tie-in to GNC,'' he says. ''I never
have to go to bed worried about being in the game.'' * </P>

<P>SUCCESS contributing writer Carol Steinberg has been covering franchise
businesses for national publications for the past 11 years. <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.1 -437838. --></P>
