<head>
   <title>Fran2</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b4Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</head>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BR>
<center><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">CAN THIS BUSINESS BE FRANCHISED</FONT><BR><BR>
<center>BY Meg Whittemore</center>
<BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Golden Bagel Cafe</CENTER></FONT><BR>

<CENTER>
	<B>	Founder:</B>
	Joe Sanfellipo. <BR><BR>
	<B>Year Founded:</B> 1995. <BR><BR>
	<B>Business:</B> Gourmet caf&eacute;.<BR><BR>
	<B>Franchise Program Started:</B> 
	1995. <BR><BR>
	<B>Franchises Open:</B>
	Six. <BR><BR>
	<B>Projected Systemwide Annual Sales:</B>
	$750,000 to $1.2 million. <BR><BR>
	<B>Capital Requirements:</B> 
	$200,000 to $450,000, depending on store size. </CENTER><BR><BR>


<p>Our panel of experts examines a business to determine its franchise
potential. </p>

<p>The golden rule in franchising is to develop a profitable prototype
before you roll out franchise units. But Golden Bagel Cafe is breaking
that rule. The Costa Mesa, Calif., company began franchising right out
of the gate. It has six units and commitments for a total of 300 by the
end of the year. </p>

<p>Founder Joe Sanfellipo believes he can make his concept fly without
a prototype because of his 20-plus years in franchising, which include
launching a deli and two auto-related franchises. Michael Owings, a principal
in the new company, is president of Fessel Design, an international restaurant
planning and design firm. The two men have invested three years and millions
of dollars to create their game plan. </p>

<p>''We want to target markets that show a demand for our concept,'' says
Sanfellipo. ''We'll get people in the restaurant business to open a flagship
store and then build around it.'' </p>

<p>Golden Bagel Cafes combine four concepts into one: bagels, fruit juice
smoothies, gourmet coffee, and sandwiches. ''We lure customers in for breakfast,
and while they're there, they can sample sandwiches and fruit smoothies,''
says Sanfellipo. The concepts are designed to capture customers throughout
the day. </p>

<p>Golden Bagel isn't the first franchise company to unveil a multi-concept
store. The Dallas-based Brice Foods Inc. has a combination coffee, sandwich,
and yogurt business. Brice was recently acquired by Yogen Fruz World-Wide
Inc. of Canada. </p>

<p>Golden Bagel stores vary in size, depending on location. Smaller units,
about 780 square feet, are reserved for nontraditional locations such as
hotel lobbies and corner areas in existing restaurants. Larger stores,
up to 3,000 square feet, will open in small strip shopping centers. ''That
way, we can get the breakfast business en route to work,'' says Sanfellipo.
Unless attached to office buildings, enclosed malls are unlikely. </p>

<p>Currently, there are six Golden Bagel Cafes in operation: five in California
and one in Charlotte, N.C. The company wants to roll out 1,000 locations
within five years. Sanfellipo says his commitments for 300 locations are
mostly from food service operators who plan to open multiple units in large
markets. Golden Bagel is modeling its regional expansion plan after Boston
Market. It will sell area development agreements and territories to developers
in the food service industry. </p>

<p>Menu offerings, supplied through corporate-approved national suppliers,
will be prepared fresh on the premises. The company's systemwide growth
will be financed through ongoing investments and an eventual initial public
offering. </p>

<p>Ideal franchisees are corporate refugees, noncompeting food service
operators, and retail professionals. </p>

<p><b>Expert Analysis </b></p>

<p>Roy F. Cammarano, president of Entrepreneurial Development Group of
Dana Point, Calif., and author of Entrepreneurial Transitions. </p>

<p>Jeffrey Kolton, president of FRANDATA Corp., a franchise research firm
in Washington, D.C. </p>

<p>Andrew Sherman, a Washington, D.C., franchise attorney. </p>

<p>In its favor, Golden Bagel has a strong management team, popular food
concepts, and an apparent commitment to supporting franchisees and area
developers. The experts challenge the firm's ability to provide franchises
with surefire marketing ideas and products. </p>

<p>''I'm concerned when companies with little operating history decide
to go out and recruit franchisees,'' says Roy Cammarano. ''Do they know
which promotions work and which don't? Without operating time under their
belt, how can they guide their franchisees in each market?'' </p>

<p>Sanfellipo counters that all promotions and marketing support will be
driven by regional markets, and the area developers will come with experience
in the food promotion area. </p>

<p>Cammarano gives Golden Bagel high marks on the four-concepts-in-one
approach. ''They've done a lot of research into the different concepts,
melded them together, taking only the best practices from each one,'' he
observes. </p>

<p>He'd like to see more of a push to build a national brand name. ''The
strength of a franchise is its national name recognition and the consistency
of its product and service,'' says Cammarano. ''If Golden Bagel is going
to focus on local markets, why would anyone want to buy a national franchise?''
</p>

<p>Jeffrey Kolton says Golden Bagel needs to define its unique competitive
advantages further. He researched 10 companies in the bagel and specialty
coffee business; eight had product offerings similar to Golden Bagel, minus
the fruit smoothies. ''Almost all of the bagel franchises have fresh orange
juice and sandwiches,'' says Kolton. ''This is no longer unique.'' One
distinguishing point for Golden Bagel could be a shorter preparation time.
</p>

<p>Andrew Sherman thinks that Golden Bagel could further differentiate
itself by focusing on a unique market penetration strategy. ''Every fast
food franchise has the same target customers. The customers want a product
that's fresh, they want convenience, and they have time constraints.''
</p>

<p>If Golden Bagel can better define its customers, it will also hone its
market penetration strategy. ''Many bagel chains are going up in the East
and West Coast markets,'' he says. ''Maybe the goal should be to introduce
a bagel to Omaha. The bagel frenzy hasn't hit the Midwest cities yet.''
</p>

<p>All told, the experts were intrigued by Golden Bagel Cafe's bold multi-concept
approach and the management team. ''They have a good team that can move
the company in the right direction,'' says Sherman. </p>

<p>Meg Whittemore, coauthor of Financing Your Franchise, reports on franchising
for national publications.</p>

<p>If you know of a business you would like examined, we will send you
an analysis form. Write: Can This Business Be Franchised? Katherine Callan,
SUCCESS, 230 Park Ave., New York, NY 10169. </p>
