<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Harrell</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">
<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>WILSON HARRELL</FONT><BR><BR>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Plan or Die</FONT></CENTER>
</H1>
<CENTER>
<H3>Are You Prepared for What Can (and Will) Go Wrong?</H3></CENTER><BR>

<P>
I have a sad story to tell, and a lesson to be learned.

<P>
My friend, whom we'll call Jim, was a paramedic who got fed up with working for the government. So he leased an ambulance and hung out a shingle advertising his private ambulance service. His competition was the local government bureaucracy, and not surprisingly, he found that competing with it was like shooting fish in a rain barrel. So he leased another ambulance, and then 10 more, and so on.

<P>
Jim also began leasing other kinds of vehicles -- from jeeps to buses -- to transport sick or elderly or disabled people wherever they wanted to go, whether it was to doctors' offices, to the store, or to the zoo. He installed a state-of-the-art satellite communications system that gave his dispatchers the ability to pinpoint the location of every company-operated vehicle at any time within a radius of 50 feet.

<P>
The first time I visited Jim's communications center, I thought I was in a spaceship. He told me he could have an emergency vehicle arrive at any address in any city where he operated within five minutes. Jim had taken a chapter from the old cowboy-and-Indian battles where the Indians were circling the wagons: He had his vehicles circling various areas of each city. When the phone rang, the dispatcher deployed the nearest vehicle. 

<P>
Another stroke of Jim's genius was to foresee that managed care organizations would replace the way we pay for medical services. He hired people a lot smarter than he was to figure out the average amount that would be spent per year on emergency transport services by the average person in several demographic categories. So when a managed care company came to Jim for a bid on providing service to 100,000 of their insured clients, he could come right back with an annual, guaranteed, all-inclusive, up-front price.

<P>
By combining his incredible communications and dispatching ability with his demographic research, Jim could go to any city and underbid all the good old boys with their horse-and-buggy-league operations. That's what he was doing when I first met him: expanding like crazy and making lots of money.

<P>
Then, a few days ago, I got a phone call from Jim: ''Wilson, I'm out of money. I can't meet payroll. I've got to find an investor quickly, sell out, or go bankrupt.'' I couldn't believe my ears.

<P>
What happened was that Jim had gotten a big government contract that required him to lease an extra 100 vehicles and expand his communications, dispatching, and computer systems, plus hire 130 new people. All of which Jim accomplished. Then the government informed him, ''We're not quite ready,'' and postponed the start date of the contract. 

<P>
When Jim said, ''Hey, you can't do that,'' the government's answer was ''We just did.'' Of course Jim can sue. But to what end -- to get his company back four or five years from now? And after how much money for legal fees? At this writing, Jim is scrounging for survival money. Maybe he'll find it. I surely hope so. But I must tell you, I've heard Jim's song before.

<P>
There's a lesson for every entrepreneur reading this. What happened to Jim was his own fault. Entrepreneurs get caught up in a growing frenzy. Like a bunch of sharks with their eyes hooded and their teeth bared, they start gobbling up everything in sight. Even stuff they can't digest. So it was with Jim: He was already growing at a preposterous rate. He didn't need the big government contract. 

<P>
Are You Invincible?

<P>
I haven't read that contract, but I don't have to. I know that buried somewhere in the fine print is a clause that allows the government to delay the start date. The truth is that Jim was on such a roll that he wasn't thinking rationally. He thought he was an irresistible, invincible, unstoppable force. But something can stop him: bankruptcy.

<P>
So hear me now, all you bright-eyed, bushy-tailed, sharp-fanged entrepreneurs. You are your own worst enemy. You are the greatest destructive force you will ever meet. So take some advice: Every morning of your life, take your coffee and go to a quiet place for a five-minute meeting with yourself. Ask, ''What can possibly go wrong today, and what will I do about it?'' The answer may get your attention. It may scare the hell out of you and cause you to do what you'll learn to do in any case after your first bankruptcy: Write a contingency plan for Murphy's Law, whereby anything that can go wrong, will. You will either plan for that possibility, or die.

<P>
Incidentally, don't worry about Jim. He hasn't slept in a while and won't for the next few weeks. He'll bleed awhile and then get up and look for another Goliath to throw rocks at. He is what he is -- an entrepreneur. 

<P>

<P>
Wilson Harrell is a consultant and speaker to the entrepreneurial market and the author of the book For Entrepreneurs Only. To reach Harrell, fax him at 770-889-4030.<BR><BR>
