<HEAD><TITLE>Entrepreneur</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P>



<BR><BR>
<CENTER>
<FONT COLOR=#CC000C>THE ENTREPRENEUR</FONT><BR><BR></CENTER>
<center><P>EDITED BY TOM STEIN</P></center><BR>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Build a Brand Name</FONT><BR><BR></CENTER>

<P>
Miles Handy is proof you can make a silk purse from a sow's ear. He's built a $10 million pet-food company by transforming pig ears into America's hottest dog snack.

<P>
Handy gives much of the credit to his beloved beagle, Heide. Five years ago, Handy was working as a pet-food distributor. He returned from an industry trade show in Germany with a roasted pig ear. Heide gobbled it up. ''She normally didn't eat dog treats, but she went crazy for this,'' recalls Handy. ''I figured there were a lot of dogs like Heide.''

<P>
Instead of importing the ears from Germany, Handy decided to produce them at home. In 1991, he launched Oink Oink Inc. of Detroit. 

<P>
First, he bought cast-off pig ears for 15 cents per pound and constructed his own smokehouse. Employing Heide as the official taste tester, Handy learned to roast his ''Oinkers'' pig ears to perfection. Today, he sells more than one million each month and has expanded his operation to include five smokehouses and a variety of products.

<P>
At the heart of the business is Handy's flair for marketing. He realized consumers might not want to buy slimy pig ears, no matter how much Fido loved them. So Handy created colorful packaging decorated with playful pigs and pooches.

<P>
Currently, the 31-year-old entrepreneur is unveiling a nationwide contest to recruit a board of advisers for Heide. ''We are taking submissions from pets around the country,'' he explains. ''They have to tell us why they want to be on Heide's board and why they love Oinkers.'' It's part of Handy's plan to broaden his brand's recognition -- and fend off new competitors that are flooding the pig-ear market he pioneered.

<P>
Despite the company's rapid growth, there have been a few bumps along the way. Until late last year, one of Oink Oink's best-selling products was the Pork Tenderloin, made from the penises of hogs. But the Agriculture Department stepped in and ruled the Tenderloins had to be dyed green to show they are not fit for human consumption. Handy felt the green dye made the product ''unappealing,'' so he scaled back production. He estimates government interference costs him $100,000 in lost sales each year.

<P>
''The government should be creating programs that give us incentive to grow instead of getting on our back,'' fumes Handy. He plans to run for office on a pro-business platform. His campaign slogan: ''Take the pork out of local politics.'' 
<HR><BR>
