<head>
   <title>HotOps</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b4Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</head>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><BR><BR>
<center><p><FONT COLOR=#CC000C>Hot Opportunities in Mail Order</FONT> </p></center><BR>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE="+4">The New Catalog Kings</FONT></CENTER>

<BR><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">Rising paper costs couldn't kill the booming mail-order industry. Catalog
sales hit a record $62.6 billion last year. Mail-order entrepreneurs are
customizing their products and turning to the Internet to accelerate sales.</FONT>


<p><FONT SIZE="+2">Gourmet Today Ltd.</FONT> </p>

<p>Philip Singerman had what he considered a decent two-year-old business:
He sold more than $100,000 of gourmet food baskets per year in the Chicago
area. </p>

<p>He wanted to take his concept nationwide but needed thousands of dollars
to buy mailing lists and send out his glossy, four-color catalogs. And
he couldn't be sure whether prospective customers would even be interested
in his line. </p>

<p>Last year, Singerman created Gourmet Today Ltd., an online catalog of
gourmet food items and gift baskets. Immediately, he gained an international
presence and new customers. Traditional catalogs often reach people who
have not requested them, Singerman points out. But when customers visit
Gourmet Today, they have taken the initiative. </p>

<p>Web surfers can examine the merchandise and place orders through their
computers. The electronic catalog pushed Singerman's sales up to an estimated
$750,000 this year. He expects Gourmet Today ''to be a multimillion-dollar
business shortly.'' </p>

<p>''It was clear to us that the Internet was the place to put our items,''
says Singerman. ''We can change our catalog instantaneously, add and subtract
items by availability, offer seasonal and even daily specials. It's a natural
place for a catalog to be.'' </p>
<BR><HR><BR>
<p><FONT SIZE="+2">Performance Products Inc.</FONT></p>

<p>Ron Rowen knew it didn't make sense to print one catalog for all types
of car enthusiasts. Instead, his company, Performance Products, sends different
catalogs to owners of different models of cars. One catalog targets owners
of Porche's 911 series; another is for Porche's 356 and 914 series. He
produces a catalog related to Toyota sports-utility vehicles and another
for Ford Explorers. Two more model-specific catalogs are in the hopper,
ready for a fall launch. Each catalog includes more than 100 pages of parts
and accessories. </p>

<p>That's a long way from the 12-page foldover Porche catalog that Rowen's
partner, Mel Kay, acquired in 1984. When he and Rowen teamed up in 1990,
they wanted to expand the scope of Performance Products. </p>

<p>The partners decided to become niche marketers in the high-end car business.
''One big catalog means a lot of wasted paper -- and paper is 65 percent
to 70 percent of our costs,'' Rowen says. </p>

<p>They formed their mailing lists from vehicle registration information,
available in 31 states. Advertisements in truck enthusiast magazines generate
an additional 3,000 catalog requests each month. </p>

<p>''By targeting our customers with exactly the type of products they
can use for their vehicle, it's almost a customized approach,'' says Rowen.
</p>

<p>Performance Products of Van Nuys, Calif., will generate more than $15
million in 1996 sales. </p><BR><HR><BR>

<p><FONT SIZE="+2">Overton's Inc.</FONT></p>

<p>In 1980, Vance Parker Overton reached his first million in sales with
a water-ski catalog. Five years later, he expanded to include marine accessories,
which he defines as ''everything but the boat.'' By 1995, sales at his
Greenville, N.C., company topped $60 million, derived from seven catalogs
mailed to 2.5 million customers. </p>

<p>Overton attributes his incredible growth to his telemarketing staff
-- which makes up nearly one third of his work force. Telemarketers are
encouraged to be relationship builders, not just order takers. All operators
have mirrors on their desks ''to see themselves from the customer's point
of view,'' says Overton. </p>

<p>Because many catalog items warrant detailed explanation, telemarketers
are supported by in-house technicians. ''If the operator can't answer a
question, the technicians can,'' says Overton. </p>

<p>Overton has succeeded by filling the niche that retail dealers are missing.
''We got into boat accessories because most people who water-ski also have
boats,'' he says. ''But most boat dealers don't sell accessories. And not
every town has a dealer. Most of our customers know what they want, they
just can't find it anyplace else in a short time. For a catalog, that's
fairly easy to do.'' </p>

<div align=right><p>-- Gianna Jacobson </p></div>

<HR><BR>
