<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Scope</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<BR><BR>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">SUCCESS SCOPE</FONT> </H4>

<CENTER><P><B><H2>Cutting-edge concepts <BR>from business journals and newsletters</H2></B>
</P></CENTER>
<BR><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE="+3">Online Market Research</FONT></P>

<P>Use the Internet to get instant feedback on products and to enter international
markets, advises the <I>Sloan Management Review</I>. New tracking software
allows businesses to identify visitors to their Web sites. As a result,
it's possible to target variations of products at different groups. Digital
Equipment, for example, demonstrates its new computer hardware online to
gauge consumer demand. The Net also allows marketers to adapt products
to local tastes inexpensively. Online Bookstore, a U.S.-based book publisher,
translates passages of new releases into many languages for customers worldwide
to sample. This strategy allows the company to determine which regions
have the most potential customers -- and to provide full translations for
those markets. </P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE="+3">A Proactive Approach<BR>
To Service </FONT></P>

<P>Most companies wait for customers to contact them with questions or
problems. Instead, <I>Sales &amp; Marketing Management</I> suggests you
pick up the phone and proactively interact with clients. The key is to
be direct. Find out whether they would buy from you again and whether they
would recommend your product or company to a friend or associate. Follow
up negative responses with open-ended questions -- such as ''Why?'' --
to solve problems, generate ideas, build loyalty, and uncover sales opportunities.
</P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE="+3">How to Sell in Japan</FONT></P>

<P>Japan has eliminated formal trade barriers. But its rigid distribution
system still poses problems for foreign companies. A recent study reported
in the <I>Harvard Business Review</I> shows how U.S. businesses can elbow
their way into the Japanese market. </P>

<P>* Distribute ''pioneer'' products. Because stores in Japan are relatively
small, there is little shelf space for ''me-too'' brands. U.S. companies
must introduce unique products that a domestic supplier cannot duplicate.
</P>

<P>* Go the extra mile. U.S. suppliers meet seemingly unreasonable demands
to build the loyalty and commitment critical to buyer-seller relationships
in Japan. Use your best judgment to make sure demands do not become excessive.
</P>

<P>* Adopt a caring attitude. A caring approach is the hallmark of committed,
long-term relationships that Japanese buyers and sellers value so highly.
<!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.1 -437838. --></P>

<HR><BR>
