<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>CEOBull</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">THE NEW CEO </FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER>Edited by Kristin Dunlap Godsey</CENTER><BR><BR>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE="+4">Small World After All</FONT></CENTER>

<CENTER><H3>Home or Away, This One-woman Show Is in business </H3></center><BR>

<P>Laurie Weber-Fritz needed to get out. The corporate advertising world
just didn't allow for enough time with her kids. So she planned several
mini-vacations for the family, then quit her job to become a consultant.
The vacations, she reasoned, would provide a needed rest before her consultancy
really got rolling. </P>

<P>Her clients had other ideas. </P>

<P>''All of a sudden, I got all this business,'' says Weber-Fritz. The
contacts she'd been making kicked in, and clients wanted her advertising
expertise now. Weber-Fritz already had a laptop with a modem, and she added
a cell phone and pager. With these tools, she was able to have her cake
and pay for it, too. </P>

<P>Weber-Fritz's business, called Weber Writes, helps mostly high-tech
companies with their advertising concepts, copywriting, and marketing communications.
''People in technology like to work with people who have technology,''
she says. ''My clients expect me to be up to speed with them.'' </P>

<P>Since they also expect her to be accessible, she knew a completely work-free
vacation was out of the question. ''I've taken my kids to Disneyland; Portland
Ore.; and Lake Tahoe in the last two months,'' says Weber-Fritz, who lives
in Half Moon Bay, Calif. ''If my clients have emergencies while I'm away
-- which they have, every time! -- I can just plug in my laptop. In some
cases, I can call directly into a client's server and make changes right
there.'' </P>

<P>These methods allowed Weber-Fritz to bill two days' worth of work from
Disneyland, where she toiled at night when the kids were in bed. At Lake
Tahoe, when her kids were out skiing with friends, she plugged her modem
into the condo's phone line and kept her cell phone glued to one ear. </P>

<P>''There's no reason to miss any opportunity,'' reasons Weber-Fritz.
''That's part of being in business for yourself. Clients have to know they
can find you when they need help.'' </P>

<P><B>Souped-Up Home Office </B></P>

<P>Weber-Fritz's home office is tech-friendly as well, including a separate
ISDN phone line and dedicated e-mail package. The ISDN line enables her
to receive large graphic files from art directors she works with through
the Internet. ''The difference between ISDN and a regular phone line is
basically the difference between putting a piece of thread through a needle
or through a large pipe,'' she explains. ''With ISDN, you can send or receive
huge files instantly.'' </P>

<P>Weber-Fritz's dedicated e-mail package gives her something most other
e-mail services -- like what you get with America Online -- do not. ''I
don't have to log on to check my mail,'' she says. ''It retrieves mail
constantly and alerts me when I have a message.'' </P>

<P>Both the ISDN line and the e-mail package cost Weber-Fritz surprisingly
little. ISDN will set you back only about $10 more per month, Weber-Fritz
says, but you also need to buy a digital router (priced between $200 and
$600). Her e-mail package, which includes her own domain, costs $100 per
year. </P>

<P>''People are intimidated by technologies like these,'' she says. ''They're
not particularly expensive, but most people don't understand the benefits.
I think ISDN is going to be like the Internet: A few years ago, nobody
had heard of it, and now it's ubiquitous.'' </P>

<P>She would eventually like to turn her business into a virtual agency.
She hopes to bring in a business partner and an account executive who would
work strictly through the Internet. </P>

<P>''Because of my clients, I'm used to dealing with all kinds of technologies,
so I've got a little bit of an advantage,'' says Weber-Fritz. ''I hear
about technology from all angles -- I can see things coming.'' * </P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><B>Bulletin Board</B></FONT>

<H3>Keyboard and Scanner in One </H3>

<P>With computers, fax machines, printers, and more
cluttering up our work spaces, any device that saves space would be welcome.
Compaq's new Scanner Keyboard fits the bill.  </P>

<P>This computer keyboard has a built-in slot along
its top edge to scan in images and documents. You can feed it mail or other
important papers, which can then be organized in your computer with Visioneer's
PaperPort software (included). Some documents can even be translated into
your word processing program, where you can edit them as you like.
</P>

<P>The integrated unit means you'll also have fewer
cables to get tangled up in: It has just one. The Scanner Keyboard comes
standard with Compaq's Presario 7232 PC, or you can buy it separately (it
works with any 486 industry-standard PC on the market). The cost is $349.
</P>

<H3>Shrink Files to Save Space </H3>

<P>Vertisoft Systems Inc. of San Francisco does its
part to help in the space-saving crusade, only its battlefield is your computer hard drive. If you store a lot of large files, share big files between
users, or spend considerable time downloading information from the Internet,
take a look at Vertisoft's Zip-It. </P>

<P>This compression utility shrinks the size of Windows
files up to 98 percent, and its drag-and-drop setup keeps things uncomplicated.
Zip-It archives these files for you and makes it simple to unzip them when
you need them. You can even run or edit files while they're still zipped.
If you need to find a zipped file fast, the archives are searchable by
file name or keyword. Zip-It costs $39.95.</P>

<H3>Make a Note of It </H3>

<P>Jot-it! 2.1 from Evergreen International Technology
Inc. takes a simple yet valuable concept -- little yellow sticky notes
-- and applies it to your computer. The software allows you to create those
little notes electronically, with text or sound, and stick them in any
Windows application you need. </P>

<P>It's helpful for jotting down instructions, lists,
reminders, or any epiphanies you may have during the course of your daily
computing. Using its patented technology, Concurrency, Jot-it! links each
note to where it was saved, so that any time you open the application (or
document, window, or menu), the note will show up. Jot-it! also works online,
so you can attach notes to Web pages. The North Vancouver-based Evergreen
offers Jot-it! for $39.95. </P>

<HR><BR>
<DIV ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="1" CELLSPACING="5" WIDTH="470">

<TR VALIGN=TOP>
<TH><A HREF="./TOC.html"><IMG SRC="c.gif"
	ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE BORDER="0"></A><BR>
	<A HREF="./TOC.html"><H4>TABLE OF<BR>CONTENTS</H4><FONT SIZE="-1">August 1996</FONT></A></TH>
	
