<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Cyber</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b5Gold (Macintosh; I; 68K)">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C"><B>THE TECHNOLOGY EDGE/CYBER FORM</B> </FONT></P></CENTER>


<center>
<FONT SIZE="+4" ALIGN=CENTER>Worry-Free Web Shopping</FONT></center>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Save Your Customers From Security Scares </H3><BR>


<P>While the debate raged on about the best way to secure financial information
over the Internet, Tony O'Brien quietly found a way to sidestep the whole
issue. It happened at the bank: O'Brien inserted his ATM card into the
machine, beeped in his PIN number, and was suddenly inspired. </P>

<P>O'Brien sells computer wares through his Internet superstore, Azteq
Direct (http://www.azteq.com). At the ATM machine, he recalls, ''I thought,
'Wouldn't this be great for people who either don't have credit cards,
or are afraid to use them online?' '' The idea is to enable customers to
use a PIN number, rather than a credit card number, to order items from
the Web site. It's easy, safe, costs little to implement, and builds customer
loyalty. </P>

<P>So why hadn't anyone done it before? </P>

<P>O'Brien wonders the same thing, but frankly, the answer is of little
concern to him now. He's turned the idea into a reality and now has about
800 subscribers. O'Brien wants to do everything he can to keep the shopping
experience pleasant and convenient. </P>

<P>''Sam Walton is a big hero of mine,'' he explains from his San Rafael,
Calif., office. ''Basically, I want to provide everything for all of my
customers.'' </P>

<P><B>Shopping by PIN </B></P>

<P>To set up a debit card account, customers call Azteq Direct on the phone.
Azteq takes down their credit card information, address, and phone number,
and assigns them a card with an 11-digit serial number. Customers then
select their PIN number. If they don't have a credit card or prefer not
to use one, they can send Azteq a check to apply toward the debit card.
</P>

<P>Now when the customer goes online to shop, he or she can simply key
in the card number and PIN. ''It makes the ordering process a lot easier,''
says O'Brien. ''Because they're preregistered, they don't have to type
in all their personal information again.'' </P>

<P>Orders are automatically sent the same day -- always to the address
that was given during the initial phone call. If a different address is
requested, Azteq calls the debit card holder to verify the order. As an
added incentive, debit card users get a 7 percent discount on purchases.
</P>

<P><B>Personal Checks Accepted </B></P>

<P>O'Brien's debit card brainstorm, however, has not been enough to sustain
him in his quest to Walton-ize Azteq Direct. Now his customers can even
write checks on the Web, simply and safely. With the help of a company
called PhoneChecks, O'Brien has created a blank-check template on his site.
</P>

<P>''All customers have to do is type in their checking account number,
the amount of the check, and their bank,'' he says. ''We can process it
without a signature.'' Checks are cleared first with the bank to make sure
no one has stolen that person's checkbook, and as with debit card orders,
products are shipped only to the customer's preregistered address. </P>

<P>The cost of these payment methods to the business owner is negligible:
Azteq pays only about 49 cents per debit card for production and mailing.
The I-checks cost an average of 1 percent of the total transaction amount
--half the cost for processing Web orders the usual way. </P>

<P>Azteq Direct was recently bought out by Summary Corp., a Houston-based
company that's launched a virtual city -- like a cybermall, but more comprehensive
-- on the Internet. Now, shoppers will be able to use O'Brien's debit cards
and I-checks for all the products and services offered there. (Azteq will
be part of the site; O'Brien is still its president.) </P>

<P>Although O'Brien firmly believes the credit card companies will solve
their perceived security problems, he doesn't see this as a threat to his
methods. ''Some people still don't want to use credit cards,'' he says.
''I've checked the numbers: 16 percent of consumers prefer credit cards,
53 percent prefer cash, and 31 percent prefer checks. With our new services,
we cover 100 percent of the market.''  <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.1 -437838. --></P>


<HR><BR>
