</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>mlm:king</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>


	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="40%">
	<FONT SIZE="+4">Services:</FONT><BR> <FONT SIZE="+3">The New Front<br>In the MLM Revolution</FONT>

<H3>Changes in Society and Dramatic New Technologies are Creating Unheard of Opportunities<BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">By Charles W. King<BR>
Professor of Marketing<BR>
University of Illinois at Chicago</FONT>
</H3>
	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=bottom COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="king.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="144" HEIGHT="144" BORDER="0">
	</TD>
	<TR><TD></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by Lauren Brill</FONT>
	</TD></TR>
</TR>

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	United States Direct-Selling Industry Sales <BR>
<BR>
1995 Retail Sales: $17.94 Billion <BR>
<BR>
<OL TYPE="1" START="1">
	<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">MAJOR PRODUCT GROUPS: </FONT><BR>
	<BR>
	<LI>Personal Care Products 38.8%<BR>
	<BR>
	<LI>Home/Family Care Products 34.4%<BR>
	<BR>
	<LI>Services/Miscellaneous 10.3%<BR>
	<BR>
	<LI>Wellness Products 9.2% <BR>
	<BR>
	<LI>Leisure/Educational Products 7.3% <BR>
</OL>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="-4">Source: The Direct Selling Association
</FONT>	</TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<BR><BR>
Network marketing is going through a revolutionary change. Companies are
cutting loose from their narrow focus on a few specialized products to compete
in the larger world of services. Their new offerings range from long-distance
telephone service to legal service to credit cards. As a result, network
marketing may be poised to grow faster in the decade ahead than it has in
any period in its history.<BR>
<BR>
Services are the biggest element in the U.S. economy, one that is still
growing. Approximately 79 percent of all jobs are service related, producing
74 percent of the GNP. In 1993, the 500 largest service companies earned
$93.7 billion in profits, compared with only $62.2 billion from the top
500 manufacturers. <BR>
<BR>
Services as a market is growing for several reasons: <BR>
<BR>
The growing ability to pay for services. The baby boomers are reaching their
peak earning period and can afford services. The growing two-income and
single-parent family segments are experiencing &quot;time poverty&quot;
and buy support services of all kinds to increase their free time. <BR>
<BR>
Services have become necessities. Long-distance telephone calls were once
considered luxuries. Today, for most people, long-distance voice communication
is an operational necessity. The same can be said of travel and legal services.
<BR>
<BR>
The expanding number of available services. A few decades ago, who would
have envisioned the time-share condominium, a service that replaces property
ownership? Who would have imagined shopping through the television, research
through the Internet, or special computer education courses for children?
<BR>
<BR>
Information technologies make delivering services easier. At one time, service
businesses were limited by how many employees they could put in personal
contact with customers. The development of information technologies has
multiplied the number of customers a company can serve and made it easy
to keep track of relationships and commissions. <BR>
<BR>
Product Pioneers <BR>
<BR>
In the 1940s, Nutrilite Products Inc. launched the pioneering era of network
marketing through the sale of food supplement products. Shaklee (1956) focused
initially on nutritional supplements; Amway Corp. (1959) emphasized household
products; Mary Kay Cosmetics Inc. (1963) offered cosmetics; NSA Inc. (1970)
featured water filtration and air filtration equipment. The seed of a service
revolution in network marketing was already present, since these products
themselves had a service element -- for the most part, they were not staple
supplies, but new products with special properties. <BR>
<BR>
From the 1970s through the 1990s, most new firms continued to be product
driven, selling from the traditional categories of personal care, nutritional
supplementation, home and family care, and leisure and educational products.
Amway had historically offered a range of services, but its major sales
volume continued to be product based. <BR>
<BR>
The Revolution Begins <BR>
<BR>
Change, however, had already begun in the 1980s. A.L. Williams Co., which
became Primerica Financial Services, achieved dramatic success in selling
personal life insurance through a form of multilevel marketing. That company,
now a division of The Travelers Inc., had $1.36 billion in 1995 revenues.
<BR>
<BR>
Network marketing also invaded the telecommunications industry. After deregulation,
MCI Communications Corp. began to sell long-distance telephone service through
Amway. Ultimately, MCI developed its own &quot;Friends and Family&quot;
network-marketing program and made itself the number-two long-distance telephone
service supplier positioned behind AT&amp;T. <BR>
<BR>
Before it was Sprint Corp., U.S. Telecom Inc. established a joint venture
with Network 2000, an independent network-marketing company organized specifically
to develop customers for a long-distance telephone sales program, attracting
more than three million customers. <BR>
<BR>
Excel Communications Inc. was founded in 1988, accelerating from $30.8 million
in 1993 revenues to more than $506.7 million in 1995. In May 1996, Excel
launched an Initial Public Offering (IPO) on the New York Stock Exchange
with a market valuation of approximately $150 million. Excel stock was offered
at $15 per share and closed at $29.38 the first day. <BR>
<BR>
Today, competition among MLM companies for the long-distance market is fierce.
Players include American Communications Network (ACN Inc.) of Southfield,
Mich., and National Telephone &amp; Communications (NTC Inc.) of Irvine,
Calif. -- each with its own market niche and strategic alliances with long-distance
carriers. <BR>
<BR>
New ways of packaging services continue to arise. In 1993, Jeff Olson, a
former top executive for the electronics MLM company Quorum, founded The
Peoples Network (TPN Inc.) of Dallas, focusing its marketing strategy on
selling access to satellite broadcasts that offer self-development and motivational
programming. Pre-Paid Legal Services Inc. of Ada, Okla., offers access to
legal services. Its publicly traded stock rose 435 percent in value last
year, with $37.5 million in revenues. World Class Network Inc. of Irvine,
Calif., a travel services company founded in 1995, had $22 million in 1995
revenues. Another network-marketing travel company, TravelMax of Newport
Beach, Calif., went public this year. <BR>
<BR>
A New Strategy <BR>
<BR>
Nu Skin International of Provo, Utah, the cosmetic and nutritional products
giant, has recently reported that it will create a division to market services.
Industry intelligence indicates the service package could include: a Nu
Skin debit/credit card; specialized travel planning and trip packaging;
discounts on air travel, lodging accommodations, and dining charges; prepaid
long-distance calling cards; and residential phone service. Still other
services could be added. <BR>
<BR>
Steve Lund, executive vice president of Nu Skin, in discussing network distribution
of services, believes that services offer a powerful advantage to network
marketers -- the same advantage they enjoy in selling nutritional or skin
products with special properties: &quot;Service products require explanation
because, on the surface, they are often indistinguishable from their competitors.
Technology-related services, in particular, benefit from face-to-face, personal
explanations that the buying public can understand.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Network distribution is an extremely adaptable marketing channel -- more
so than most observers have historically realized. We can expect a large
number of companies to enter the service arena, adding their unique twists
to the concept. And we can anticipate that services will widen the beachhead
of network-marketing companies in the years ahead, allowing them to gain
a vastly greater share of our economy.
	</TD>


</TR>
</TABLE>
 
