<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>mlm:lesh</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>


	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="40%">
	<FONT SIZE="+4">The New Class</FONT>

<H3>Network Marketing Liberates the World<BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">Q&amp;A: Dr. Richard Lesher,<BR>
President and COO, <BR>
U.S. Chamber of Commerce </FONT>
</H3>
	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=bottom COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<IMG SRC="lesh.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="180" HEIGHT="180" BORDER="0">
	</TD>
	<TR><TD></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by Michael J.N. Bowles</FONT>
	</TD></TR>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	

<BR><BR>
Richard Lesher says network marketing doesn't just set individuals free.
It helps liberate entire countries. As the president of the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce in Washington, D.C., since 1975, Lesher would know. In his new
book, <U>Meltdown on Main Street</U>, he tells the stories of fed up entrepreneurs
who ran for Congress in 1994 and won. Lesher travels the world promoting
free enterprise, and he believes that trade is the quickest way to undermine
the globe's remaining tyrants. He has a particular affection for network
marketing because of its ability to spread commerce around the globe ''under
the radar.'' He wrote the foreword to the new saga of Amway Corp., <U>Empire
of Free-dom</U> by James W. Robinson, and was interviewed for SUCCESS by
senior editor Duncan Maxwell Anderson. <BR>
<BR>
<B>What is it about network marketing that promotes world freedom? <BR>
</B><BR>
International commerce brings the truth with it. With tourism and modern
communications, people behind the Iron Curtain began to see the kinds of
products being made in other countries. The Communist governments couldn't
lie anymore about what life was like in the rest of the world. <BR>
<BR>
Direct selling is growing even faster overseas than it is here. There, you
don't have the retail outlets we have. All these places where you couldn't
get the simplest luxuries like cosmetics and vitamins -- suddenly, you're
overjoyed when you discover your neighbor is selling them. <BR>
<BR>
<B>When did you first get to know Amway as a company? <BR>
</B><BR>
When I got to the chamber in the '70s. In the first couple of years that
I knew Jay Van Andel and Rich DeVos, their sales went from $400 million
to $1 billion in the twinkling of an eye. This was a company two guys started
in a basement. Now it's in more than 70 countries. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Why is direct selling popular overseas? <BR>
</B><BR>
It's the American ideal of working for yourself and succeeding. You're putting
free enterprise in the hands of the common man. In Empire of Freedom, there's
a comment from a Japanese salaryman who quit his job to do his Amway business
full-time: ''There is an American Dream, but there's really no such thing
as a Japanese Dream. There is little chance for success here, but with Amway,
I see people succeeding all the time.'' <BR>

It could grow a lot more. Within a decade, it's estimated there will be
one billion people in the middle class in Asia with money to buy things.
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Will those people want to be in business for themselves? <BR>
</B><BR>
It's universal. Even under Communism. Right after the Berlin Wall fell,
East Germans were heading into the West, buying Amway products and bringing
them back to East Germany to sell. The black market had prepared them for
selling neighbor to neighbor. <BR>
<BR>
I was in mainland China in 1980, when it was very hard even to change jobs.
I met a guy who was grinding artifacts out of coral, jade, and ivory. He'd
been assigned the job out of grade school -- 40 years before. He had no
choice in the matter. Today, there are in excess of 500,000 distributors
there. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Can anything stop the global spread of network marketing? <BR>
</B><BR>
Free trade has always been under attack. Being opposed to it is always going
to get votes anywhere in the world -- the fear of that other guy getting
your job. Free enterprise is not well understood anywhere, including here.
Hollywood and the TV culture seem to believe in the Scrooge McDuck theory
of economics. That's Donald Duck's rich uncle, who had this huge bin full
of money he liked to swim in sometimes. They think there's no limit to business
resources: ''Let business pay for it.'' The worst thing governments do is
tax and regulate economic activity to death. It's a fragile flower. We cheer
for people who distinguish themselves as athletes in the Olympics, but we
penalize achievement in business. Equalizing people's results is not how
you generate excellence. <BR>
<BR>
<B>How do things look for the future?</B> <BR>
<BR>
Free enterprise and freedom are spreading to every corner of the globe.
When I came here, we had 35 chambers overseas for resident American companies.
Now there are 80. I believe China will become increasingly free, because
of the influence of trade. In the Western hemisphere, the only Latin American
country that was democratic in 1981 was Venezuela. Now Cuba is the only
country that isn't. <BR>
<BR>
We're turning the corner in this country. As far as I'm concerned, the last
liberal who's going to be in the White House is in there now. The American
people have demonstrated that they want less government. I think people
in independent business are to the right of that. It's absolutely mandatory
that they teach and preach and live free enterprise by example. They know
how fragile it is. They don't want to spend their time on politics -- but
when they do, they're more effective than anyone.
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
 
