<HEAD>

<TITLE>Student Profiles</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<BR><BR>
 <FONT SIZE="+4">THEY LEARNED TO WIN</font> 
<BR><H2>Students who Launched Business</H2><BR>


<P>Founders: Bill Pike and Steve Bleistein <BR>

<P>School: University of South Carolina (1993) <BR>

<P>Ages: Both 28 <BR>

<P>Company: PassAm Inc. <BR>

<P>Concept: Manufacturer of promotional products <BR>

<P>Headquarters: Columbia, S.C. <BR>

<P>1995 Revenues: $1.3 million <BR>

<P>''We founded PassAm in our last year at the University
of South Carolina,'' says Pike. ''We both worked as interns for companies
in Japan. In Tokyo, we met an American watch designer and negotiated a deal
to represent him in Japan. Now, our company customizes watches and other
products for Japan Airlines, Toyota, and Mitsubishi. We also have a complex
database program for tracking products that we sell.'' </P>

<P>''We wouldn't have been ready to do the things
we're now doing without an international business degree,'' says Bleistein.
''Running a company with offices in three different countries (U.S., Hong
Kong, Japan) is a tall task. You can't just pop out of undergraduate school
and do that.''  </P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P>Founder: Doug DeAngelis </P>

<P>School: Massachusetts Institute of Technology (Not yet graduated) </P>

<P>Age: 29 </P>

<P>Company: Lynx System Developers Inc. </P>

<P>Concept: Produces digital photo-finish systems for sports events </P>

<P>Headquarters: Woburn, Mass. </P>

<P>Founded: 1992 </P>

<P>1995 Revenues: $6 million </P>

<P>''I used to work weekends at track meets operating
the old technology for photo finishes. I decided to come up with something
better. I made that my project when I went to business school.  </P>

<P>''Our system produces images that can be delivered
to TV for instantaneous viewing.  </P>

<P>''While getting my MBA, I also worked for a computer
company. I took my savings and built a prototype. My first customers paid
me in advance,'' he says.  </P>

<P>''Studying entrepreneurship forces you to do the
tedious things that entrepreneurs least like to do, like drawing up business
plans and making financial projections. When you start, you think the product
is the key to everything. But the nitty-gritty stuff of planning a business
turns out to be just as important.''  </P>
<P>
 <BR><HR><BR>
<P>
Founder: John Buttery

<P>
School: University of Arizona (1989)

<P>
Age: 31

<P>
Company: Business Location Research 

<P>
Concept: Creates geographic databases

<P>
Headquarters: Tucson, Ariz.

<P>
1995 Sales: $4 million

<P>
 ''Our databases are used for site selection or network planning. We have a digital road map of the USA, which we can customize for our clients, creating road maps of bus routes, fast-food restaurant locations, cellular transmitters -- anything. 

<P>
 ''Before I went for my MBA, I used products like this, but they were very limited. I started the company to make those products better. 

<P>
 ''At the University of Arizona, I learned the necessary components for a good business, one that has growth potential. A lot of people have ideas, but at school you can discuss them with teachers, students, and guest speakers, and get a pretty good idea how viable they are without risking a lot of time and money. I was able to attend a lot of events and build a network of advisers I still rely on today.'' 
<BR><HR><BR>
<P>
Founder: Pamela Cole

<P>
School: New York University (1991)

<P>
Age: 34

<P>
Company: Cole Farrington Design Group

<P>
Concept: Architectural services for corporate clients

<P>
Headquarters: New York and Atlanta

<P>
1995 Sales: More than $2 million

<P>
 ''My husband is an architect -- I'm not -- and we've always wanted to work together. I went to the Stern School at NYU; my business school project was to start an architectural firm. I won the Slater Award for best entrepreneurial business plan, which included the seed money I needed.  

<P>
 ''Through computer technology and databases we built, we offer premium service. Say a client wants to reconfigure an architectural plan and wants to know what that will cost. We can turn around almost any request for information in two hours. 

<P>
 ''NYU gave me an ability to analyze and perceive an opportunity. It also taught me how to compete in the business world, which I really didn't know coming out of college. After business school, I had the tools to accomplish my goals as an entrepreneur.'' 
<BR><HR><BR>
<P>
Founders: Mark Bernstein and Degerhan Usluel

<P>
School: Rensselaer  
Polytechnic Institute (1994)

<P>
Ages: 32 and 26

<P>
Company: ILINC

<P>
Concept: Distance-learning software provider

<P>
Headquarters: Troy, N.Y.

<P>
1995 Revenues: $1 million

<P>
 ''Our third partner -- Dr. Jack M. Wilson, dean of undergraduate and continuing education at RPI -- is a world-renowned expert on distance learning. He provided the vision, and we put in $5,000 to start the company,'' says Bernstein. ''Our company comes directly from our experience at RPI. 

<P>
 ''We provide large organizations with the infrastructure they need to train people in a variety of locations, to videoconference on their PCs. You can see and interact with your instructor and peers just like in a real classroom. 

<P>
 ''Many software companies eat peanut butter and jelly for a year or two to develop a product, then go out to raise capital. Instead, we sold the product before we developed it. We sold about $300,000 worth of software to three major companies by showing them just conceptual prototypes.'' 
<BR><HR><BR>
<P>
Founder: Jonathan Coon

<P>
School: Brigham Young University (1996)

<P>
Age: 26

<P>
Company: 1-800 CONTACTS Inc.

<P>
Concept: A mail-order contact lens discounter

<P>
Headquarters: Orem, Utah

<P>
1996 Projected Revenues: <BR>
$3 million

<P>
 ''While I was an undergraduate, I needed contact lenses, and so did a lot of my friends. I called a distributor, and he agreed to give me a bulk rate. I started selling contacts at school. I got my MBA to take my business to the next level.  

<P>
 ''I used my professors as free consultants. I tried to take classes that I wanted for my business: marketing, international finance. I took the core classes and any electives that would help me with my company. 

<P>
 ''I needed a merchant account in order to process credit cards. A guy I met at BYU, the founder of a bank, gave us the account. The ability to accept people's credit cards over the phone was almost more important than the money we raised.'' 

<P> Student Businesses </P>
<BR><HR><BR>
<P>Founder: Steve Schueler </P>

<P>School: San Francisco State University (1996) </P>

<P>Age: 30 </P>

<P>Company: International Wine Connection </P>

<P>Concept: Markets wines on the Internet </P>

<P>Headquarters: San Francisco </P>

<P>Founded: 1996 </P>

<P>1996 Projected Revenues: $500,000 </P>

<P>''In May, I started marketing wine on my Web site,
onlinewine.com. My second Web site, Culinary Village, will look like a small
Austrian village, with mountains and little shops -- a wine shop, cheese
shop, tobacco shop, candy store, and restaurant. When you click on the shops,
you enter them.  </P>

<P>''I have a contract with a top magazine's wine
editor to provide the information for the Web pages. He brings credibility
to my business. The alliance also separates me from my principal competition,
Virtual Vineyards.  </P>

<P>''I believe that studying entrepreneurship gives
you the ability to control your own destiny. It teaches you to be more aware
of potential business opportunities. You have a framework for analyzing
business ideas.''  </P>
<BR><HR><BR>
 <FONT COLOR="#E6000D"><A NAME="TOP"><FONT SIZE="+3">Top 10 Up-and-Comers</FONT></A></FONT> 

<P>The schools in our survey are the best in the country for entrepreneurs.
They provide you with incredible networking opportunities and the best facilities,
techniques, and ideas for success. </P>

<P>We have designed our survey to reveal the distinctions, resources, and
special expertise of each school. But your choice will sometimes depend
on factors that cannot be measured: Where you live, for example, may determine
the school that is right for you. </P>

<P>The following 10 schools are worthy of investigation for anyone seeking
a top-notch entrepreneurial program. They are the ones to watch for placement
on future lists of the 25 Best. </P>

<UL TYPE="1" START="1">
	<LI><P>Columbia University  </P>

	<LI><P>George Washington University  </P>

	<LI><P>Indiana University at Bloomington  </P>

	<LI><P>University of Iowa </P>

	<LI><P>James Madison University  </P>

	<LI><P>Kennesaw College  </P>

	<LI><P>University of Louisville  </P>

	<LI><P>University of Oregon  </P>

	<LI><P>American Graduate School of International Management-- Thunderbird <BR><BR>
<LI><P>University of Wisconsin -- Madison  </UL>
 
