<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>MLMRev</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>


<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+4">A Hurricane of Success</FONT>
<H3>High-Tech Leverage Stirs Up Powerful Results</H3></CENTER>
	<BR><BR></TD>
</TR>



<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="70%">
	


<P>New information technology is revolutionizing recruiting: Colli Butler
of FreeLife International, sitting in her home office, sends a recorded
voice message to everyone in her downline, asking who wants to participate
in a co-op ad in an MLM trade magazine. Donna Colson gets the message --
at her house several states away. So Donna hits &quot;A&quot; on her telephone
keypad (for &quot;answer&quot;) and leaves a return message. The leads from
the ads come to Colli's voice mail. She distributes them to each contributor
to the ad by typing in his phone number. After a week, each distributor
winds up with the names and phone numbers of, say, 20 people who have expressed
interest in the opportunity. Donna will be talking only to people who want
to talk to her, avoiding both the sting of rejection and a big waste of
time. <BR>
<BR>
Meanwhile, Donna's husband, Stan, has created an Internet Web site for their
business. The page tells their story, collecting leads automatically. The
Colsons send a prospecting kit to anyone who leaves his phone number. <BR>
<BR>
High-leverage technologies enhance the power of what is called &quot;The
Butterfly Effect.&quot; Physicists say that when very large, complex events
happen, such as the weather, a small action in one place -- a micro-event
-- can create a chain of very large consequences somewhere else. In theory,
if a butterfly sitting on a mulberry tree in Peking fluttered its wings,
that force can trigger a long series of reactions that could culminate in
a hurricane in the Caribbean. Like weather, a network-marketing organization
is a complex system, and information technology magnifies the leverage of
our &quot;small actions.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Of course, network marketing itself is a system designed to leverage small
actions, when persistence meets opportunity. When a '60s flower child who
called himself Showshawme was still living &quot;off the land&quot; in poverty
in the jungles of Hawaii, he possessed enormous power -- he just didn't
know it. He had an intimate knowledge of the subculture he would later conquer
through network marketing: the organic food counterculture. When he became
a Cell Tech distributor, he was able to pinpoint and recruit crucial opinion
leaders with wide circles of influence. Today, 97 percent of Cell Tech's
350,000 distributors report to him. <BR>
<BR>
No matter who you are, where you're from, or how you were educated, you
have access to hidden networks unknown and inaccessible to others. <BR>
<BR>
(Adapted from the new book Wave 3 Way by Richard Poe.) <BR><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+3">Business of the Future <BR>
</FONT>
Network marketing has astonishing potential. <BR>
<BR>
Item: Among adults ages 25 to 44, a near-unanimous 96 percent describe themselves
as &quot;very interested&quot; in owning their own business, according to
USA Today. All have reason to pay attention if you happen to know of a way
they could achieve their dreams at a minimal cost, plus sweat equity. <BR>
<BR>
Item: About 50,000 people in the U.S. become independent network-marketing
distributors every week. Worldwide, 21,400 people become distributors each
day. U.S. retail sales in direct selling were almost $18 million in 1995.
Worldwide, the figure was about $100 billion; it's growing more than 10
percent annually. <BR>
<BR>
Item: As a group, publicly held network-marketing companies outperformed
the Dow Jones Industrial Average and the S&amp;P 500 by more than 79 percent.
<BR>
<BR>
Item: One of network marketing's big advantages is that it's a home-based
business. Last year, 42.3 million Americans operated home-based businesses.
Another one opens every 10 seconds. You can put $22,500 each year from your
MLM business into a tax-deferred IRA; you can pay your spouse part-time
(deductibly) for helping with the business, adding another $2,000 per year
into the IRA. And you can sock away $2,000 per year, tax free, for each
child who helps. <BR>
<BR>
Item: Oracles ranging from economist Paul Pilzer to futurist Faith Popcorn
agree that network marketing is the business of the future. Will you be
there? <BR>
<BR>
(Adapted from the new book Business is Booming by Michael S. Clouse.) <BR><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+3">The Perfect Business? </FONT><BR>

Why, when a conventional business fails, do people blame the economy --
but when an MLM business fails, people blame MLM? <BR>
<BR>
People who want to start a business, but don't, offer the same set of reasons
why they don't: lack of money and time, high risk, and not enough knowledge.
Here's an experiment: Over lunch, ask a friend if he's considered starting
a business -- and why he didn't do it. Ask if he'd take the plunge if the
start-up costs were less than $500; if the income potential were higher
than many Fortune-500 CEO salaries; if the time investment to start could
be as little as 5-to-20 hours per week; if there were numerous consultants
available to advise him, absolutely free, indefinitely; and if another company
would take care of R&amp;D, shipping, payroll, taxes, legal, and so on,
for $20 per year. He may not believe such a thing exists, but at least you'll
get his attention. <BR>
<BR>
(Adapted from the new book Inside Network Marketing by Leonard W. Clements.)
	</TD>


	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+3">It's About Time </FONT>(video) <BR>
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#000000">One of the best new prospecting videos out there doesn't
bother to talk about the millions you could potentially make in network
marketing. It's much more powerful than that. It asks you whether you're
making good use of your time. Its title: It's About Time. <BR>
<BR>
More than money, most people want time: to spend with their families, to
go on vacation, or just to not feel hurried through life. It's About Time
explains the life-changing principle of leveraging your time -- the key
to understanding the industry's power. <BR>
<BR>
The video tells the story of two married couples who need just a bit more
money each month. The two husbands, golf buddies, make a pact: They'll each
devote an extra 10 hours per week on strategies to get ahead financially.
<BR>
<BR>
One man takes a job working nights at an electronics store: For each hour
he devotes, he gets an hour's pay. The other signs up in his wife's network-marketing
business. At first, the pay is minimal. But if he signs up, say, five hardworking
people into his organization, for each hour he works on his business, six
hours' work is getting done to build his income. And if they sign up more
people in turn, the time leverage in his favor keeps increasing. <BR>
<BR>
As you might expect, the poor sap working himself bleary-eyed at two jobs
watches amazed as his friend builds his business, wins bonus trips, and
seems to be spending more and more time having fun with his family. And
in the end, the fellow is convinced to overcome his misgivings about this
new way of working and start putting time on his side.
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
 
