<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>10ITHotOps</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER><P><FONT COLOR="#CC000C">INSIDE TRACK</FONT> </center></P>

<center>Hot Opportunities in the College Market</center><BR><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+4">Big Men on Campus</FONT>

<P>Entrepreneurs who've done their homework know that students are a powerful
consumer group. All told, America's 14.5 million college students spend
an estimated $30 billion to $60 billion per year. Cerebellum Corp. </P>

<P>Chip Paucek and James Rena learned an important lesson in college: Students
do better when they have fun. So the two George Washington University grads
teamed up to make soporific subjects like statistics and microeconomics
come alive. </P>

<P>In 1993, the partners launched Cerebellum Corp. of McLean, Va., to produce
humorous yet instructive videos with names like The Creepy Crawly World
of Calculus and The Dissected World of Biology. Each entertaining teaching
tool features professional actors and comedians and supplements a college
course. </P>

<P>The entrepreneurs raised $95,000 to create their first 120-minute video.
At CAMEX (Campus Market Expo), they networked with managers of college bookstores
and secured orders from 150 stores. There was only one problem: The videos
didn't sell. </P>

<P>''We talked to students and discovered we were doing some things wrong,''
says the 25-year-old Paucek. ''The tapes were priced at $29.99, which was
too expensive. And the packaging was all wrong. The covers focused on the
wacky aspect and didn't convey the seriousness of the product.'' The partners
recalled every tape, redesigned the cover, and dropped the price to $19.99.
Sales went through the roof. </P>

<P>Today, Cerebellum has 11 different instructional tapes, which are sold
at 1,100 bookstores. Revenues for 1996 will reach $1.2 million. </P>

<P>Collegiate Student Storage Inc. </P>

<P>Upon graduating from Syracuse University, everyone asked Andrew Koven
the same question: ''What are you going to do with your life?'' But unlike
most kids his age, Koven wasn't worried. He already had a thriving business.
</P>

<P>In 1987, the young New Yorker started Collegiate Student Storage Inc.
''After my freshman year, I realized I had accumulated a lot more stuff
than I started out with,'' says Koven. ''I needed summer storage, but there
was no company that worked with my schedule.'' </P>

<P>Koven and a friend rented a U-haul, put up fliers around campus, and
leased storage space. In between classes, they did everything from loading
boxes to driving the truck. Koven professionalized his storage operation
by aligning himself with an established moving company and expanding to
three more campuses by his senior year. </P>

<P>After graduation, Koven decided to nationalize his operation. He moved
his headquarters to Boston and traveled from campus to campus in search
of motivated students who would promote his concept. Today, his business
serves more than 100 schools and employs 500 students. Revenues will exceed
$1 million this year. </P>

<P>Koven, 27, recently formed a second venture, University Sales and Marketing
Services, to help other businesses crack the college market. ''This is a
time when students develop and solidify their buying preferences,'' he says.
''Companies want to be involved in that.'' One example: He is using his
network of highly trained students to push a Canadian soft drink called
Jones Soda in retail stores across the U.S. </P>

<P>Student Advantage </P>

<P>As a student at an expensive Ivy League university, Raymond Sozzi knew
how tough it was to live on practically nothing. He created the Student
Advantage card to reduce the cost of everything from CDs to train tickets.
</P>

<P>His idea was nothing new, though. Other entrepreneurs had started discounting
businesses, but few took off. Sozzi's goal was to become the first nationwide
savings club for students. </P>

<P>Sozzi signed on big-name companies and also went after mom-and-pops.
''Blockbuster is a huge name,'' he says. ''But it's the little video shop
near campus that's often most relevant to students.'' </P>

<P>Today, Boston-based Student Advantage boasts 500,000 members at more
than 1,000 college and university campuses. Students pay $20 each for a
yearly membership. </P>

<P>Sozzi hires college graduates who sign up local businesses and promote
the cards on campus. His marketing vice president, Todd Eichler, handles
all national accounts, including Kinko's, Princeton Review, and Amtrak.
</P>

<P>Last year, Student Advantage tallied sales of $1 million. Sozzi, a former
consultant with Bain and Co., says revenues will triple by the end of this
year. <!-- This document was created using BeyondPress(TM) 2.0.2 -437838. -->
