<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>mlm:new class</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="4" CELLSPACING="0">

<TR>


	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT SIZE="+4">The New Class</FONT>

<H3>Professionals, Entrepreneurs <BR>and Executives Thrive <BR>in Network Marketing<BR><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">By David Carnoy </FONT>
</H3>
	</TD>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"	WIDTH="40%">
	<IMG SRC="class.gif" VALIGN=BOTTOM ALIGN=left WIDTH="180" HEIGHT="180" BORDER="0">
	</TD>
	<TR><TD></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=BOTTOM COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	<FONT SIZE="-2">Photograph by Klaus Schonwise</FONT>
	</TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD></TD>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1">
	
<BR>
All over the country, high achievers from business
and the professions are leaving their prestigious positions to take up network
marketing. Many of them say that now, for the first time, they are able
to put into practice the business and service ideals they were taught as
preparation for their professions. <BR>
<BR>
A Corporate Star Rises Again <BR>
<BR>
Pete Zdanis was a fast-tracker. Fresh out of Michigan State, he started
working in the sales and marketing division at Mobil Oil Corp. He moved
16 times in 25 years. By 1995, he was earning a six-figure salary and celebrating
his 25th anniversary with Mobil. His boss flew up from the corporate headquarters
and honored Zdanis, who lives near Harrisburg, Pa., with a party and a gold
watch. <BR>
<BR>
Two months later, his boss flew up again. But this time it was to fire him.
Zdanis's position had been eliminated. Though his layoff was a shock, he
wasn't totally unprepared for it. Zdanis had started dabbling in multilevel
marketing after seeing a magazine ad. <BR>
<BR>
''That ad turned out to be a scam,'' he says. ''I lost some money. But the
concept made all the sense in the world to me.'' In October 1994, Zdanis
joined Usana Inc. of Salt Lake City, which sells nutritional and personal
care products. By the spring of 1995, he was making close to $1,000 per
week in network-marketing commissions. <BR>
<BR>
After two years in the business, Zdanis's weekly checks from Usana average
more than $3,000. He's making as much as he did when he left Mobil, and
liking the work a lot better. ''In recent years, concepts like team building
and problem solving have come into corporate America. They talk about them,
they put you through classes -- but when class is over, you go back to the
old cutthroat mentality. <BR>
<BR>
''But in network marketing, team building actually fits in. The more information
you share, the more you motivate people. Ironically, the principles I learned
in corporate America have been 10 times more effective for me in my MLM
business.'' <BR>
<BR>
An Entrepreneur's Discovery <BR>
<BR>
Every Sunday about 3:00 p.m., Ben Kane of Newport Beach, Calif., used to
get nauseated. The thought of having to go to work Monday morning literally
made him sick. One day, he decided he couldn't take it anymore and quit.
<BR>
<BR>
''I walked out on a four-year contract,'' says, Kane, 48, who is divorced
and has two grown children. ''That cost me a ton of money.'' <BR>
<BR>
Kane had started out selling Century 21 franchises in New Jersey, rising
to regional marketing director before moving to Realty World. Then he and
some Century 21 executives started a contractor franchise company called
Dial One Inc., selling control to the same big venture capital firm that
had started Office Depot. Kane quickly grew disenchanted with the new corporate
atmosphere: ''I couldn't take the structure, the bureaucracy, the absolute
waste of money.'' <BR>
<BR>
After Kane resigned in 1995, he cut back on expenses, lived off his savings,
and began to look for a line of work that would let him work with people
of his own choosing. Several friends and former business associates approached
him about network marketing. <BR>
<BR>
''Frankly, I looked down on network marketing,'' he says. I didn't want
to be a vitamin salesman.'' <BR>
<BR>
But then he found a company and a product that appealed to him: World Class
Network Inc., the network of travel agents based in Irvine, Calif. ''Everybody
likes to travel,'' he says. <BR>
<BR>
The process of network marketing came easily to Kane because of his franchising
sales background. ''Network marketing today is like franchising was in the
1970s. You got someone to sign a one-page agreement, and that was it. Today,
the documentation in franchising looks like a small book.'' <BR>
<BR>
After working less than a year for World Class Network, Kane is on track
for a six-figure income this year. ''I work as hard as I ever have,'' he
says. ''But it doesn't seem as hard. And that's what it's all about.'' <BR>
<BR>
What the Doctor Ordered <BR>
<BR>
Jimmy Graham, M.D., of Atlanta had to face the facts: Many of his patients
didn't seem to want to get well. <BR>
<BR>
''Most physicians see a number of people like that,'' Graham says. Two years
ago, Graham, 47, tried the nutritional products his wife was using from
Shaklee U.S. Inc., based in San Francisco and owned by Yamanouchi Pharmaceutical
Company Ltd. of Japan. He was surprised by what a difference they made.
He had more energy and ''just felt better all around.'' Maybe if his ''permanent
invalids'' had that experience, they'd be inspired to take charge of their
health and get genuinely better. <BR>
<BR>
Graham recommended Shaklee products to a few patients to see if they improved.
The results were positive, so he decided to go a step further: He opened
a ''wellness clinic'' as part of his private practice in Atlanta. <BR>
<BR>
''I put people on a program that combines diet, nutritional supplements,
and exercise. It's exciting to be helping people get better.'' <BR>
<BR>
Today, the Grahams are Shaklee Key Coordinators. The average commission
income for someone at their level is $104,000. ''I want to concentrate on
making people well. Ironically, that's something I can do with Shaklee and
could not do with medicine alone.'' <BR>
<BR>
Real Goals <BR>
<BR>
''When they start working for a company, most people have a goal of moving
up to a certain position,'' says Nick Serba, 53, a former New York Life
executive who lives in Atlanta. ''But once they reach their goal, they realize
that isn't what they want anymore.'' <BR>
<BR>
Serba started out as a sales agent for New York Life, worked his way to
a management position, and spent five years as an industry consultant. He
concluded that the higher you rise in the corporate world, the deeper the
wedge you drive between yourself and your family, because you spend so much
time apart. ''I didn't want to let that happen,'' he says. <BR>
<BR>
A friend sold Serba a membership in Pre-Paid Legal Services Inc., a company
based in Ada, Okla., which contracts out attorney services to members for
a monthly fee. He began to tell other friends about it, and he decided to
become a distributor. <BR>
<BR>
Today, Serba and his wife, Gayle, are Silver Executive Bonus Qualifiers
making a combined income of more than $250,000 per year from their Pre-Paid
Legal Services organization. <BR>
<BR>
''It used to be that the type of person getting into the MLM business was
more blue-collar,'' Serba says. ''But with the changes in corporate America,
more professionals are getting involved. And they do very well because they
come into the business with the organizational skills and the discipline
you need to build and run a company.'' <BR>
<BR>
Making Leaders <BR>
<BR>
Paula Cook-Ehrlich was scared. In the space of a month, two of her best
friends had lost their jobs; one was the victim of a merger; the other,
a bankruptcy. <BR>
<BR>
''One day, these people woke up and their lives were totally turned upside
down,'' she says. ''I was terrified the same thing was going to happen to
me.'' <BR>
<BR>
For 26 years, Cook-Ehrlich, 47, had worked in the airlines industry. She
started at Eastern; then, in 1986, moved over to TWA. She managed the worldwide
cruise division and the South America sales division. By 1990, the airlines
industry fell on hard times. Eastern and Pan Am, both based in Miami, folded.
<BR>
<BR>
Cook-Ehrlich had never given a thought to doing network marketing. But one
day she got a call from Richmond Flowers, a contact of her husband's, who'd
been an attorney and started a worldwide commodities firm. He was calling
to talk to her about ''leveraged income.'' Traditionally, he said, people
(like her) were paid an hourly wage or salary for the time they worked.
He explained how in networking marketing, you can work hard for a while,
put a system in place, and then let the leverage of the system generate
residual income for you -- even when you aren't working. <BR>
<BR>
Cook-Ehrlich was very skeptical. Her husband had a Ph.D. in economics, and
they'd both heard their share of negative stories about network marketing.
They flew out to Provo, Utah, to visit the headquarters of Nu Skin International
Inc. They came away impressed by the company and its leaders. At first,
Cook-Ehrlich could work on her new business only an hour each day -- during
lunch. Two and a half years later, she was making almost as much from Nu
Skin as she was at TWA. She decided to pursue network marketing full-time.
<BR>
<BR>
Today, she sleeps in most mornings. After six years in the business, she's
a Blue Diamond executive at Nu Skin. Blue Diamonds typically make $750,000
per year. ''In the corporate world,'' she says, ''you're always trying to
make yourself one of a kind. You want to be indispensable. But in MLM, you
want to duplicate yourself, the faster, the better. This business doesn't
depend on you, it depends on your teaching everyone else.'' <BR>
<BR>
A Lawyer Rests His Case <BR>
<BR>
When Michael Ginsburg opened his law practice in 1990, he was an idealist.
He thought that by practicing law, he was going to help people and improve
society. But what he got instead was a bad case of stress. <BR>
<BR>
''Maybe I was a little naive,'' says Ginsburg, 35, a real estate lawyer
who lives in Visalia, Calif., ''but I quickly found out that law wasn't
as exciting or romantic as L.A. Law made it look.'' Many of the cases he
took on involved family members suing other family members. And Ginsburg
was working 12 to 15 hours per day trying to clear his schedule. <BR>
<BR>
In 1995, Ginsburg's wife, Phyllis, became very sick with pneumonia. Prescription
drugs didn't seem to be doing her any good. ''The doctor was ready to admit
her to the hospital. But a friend suggested she try some nutritional supplements.
Within a week, she was 1,000 percent better.'' <BR>
<BR>
Ginsburg began to look at nutritional MLM companies. He was attracted to
FreeLife International Inc. of Milford, Conn., partly because of its ''unilevel''
compensation plan, which he felt would start him earning more money, sooner,
than others he'd seen. <BR>
<BR>
After only six months of working for FreeLife, he was able to shut down
his law practice and work his network-marketing business full-time. He is
a senior director with more than 1,000 distributors. By the end of this
year, his FreeLife commissions will have surpassed the income he earned
as a lawyer. ''A couple of weeks ago was the first time that I spent totally
undistracted time with my four-year-old daughter,'' says Ginsburg. ''All
she could talk about was how much she enjoyed spending time with me. It's
sad. Professionals shouldn't have to give up so much.''
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
 
