<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>11FranProliles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#095A24" ALINK="#FF0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="1" CELLSPACING="5" WIDTH="550">

<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	FRANCHISE GOLD 100 <BR><BR>
	</TD>
	
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="1">
	
<FONT SIZE="+5">The Future</FONT> 

<H3>The Gold 100 Winners Reveal Their Growth Strategies<BR>
for the 21st Century / By Carol Steinberg
</FONT></H3>
	</TD>
</TR>
 

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550">
	<BR><BR>


<P>After working at KFC for 10 years, Jerome Edmondson
wanted his own restaurant. He waited for a KFC franchise opportunity in
his hometown of Detroit. When none panned out, Edmondson looked elsewhere.
</P>

<P>In March 1995, he was accepted into Denny's minority
Fast Track franchising program, which promised to provide operations and
management training and up to 100 percent financing to buy a restaurant.
After 12 weeks, Edmondson was itching to get started. He offered to resurrect
a dying company unit in Southfield, Mich. He wanted just six months: He'd
turn a profit or close down as scheduled. He got the green light. </P>

<P>At the time, Denny's was planning a major remodeling
of corporate restaurants. Edmondson persuaded the company to refurbish Southfield.
Eleven days and $240,000 later, the restaurant glowed with tan-and-mauve
seating and bright lighting. It added a Baskin-Robbins ice-cream unit. Edmondson
hired high-performance minority managers from KFC and added extra cooks
and hostesses. </P>

<P>In three months, weekly sales climbed from $18,000
to $24,000. In six months, net profit was 17 percent. Earlier this year,
Edmondson, 33, bought the restaurant -- the first of a projected 20. </P>

<P>''I feel good about working with a company that
wants to change and is consistently adding change as part of its structure,''
he says. </P>

<P>The best franchise companies have their ears to
the ground. Winners of the Franchise Gold 100 are continually improving
in order to run over the competition and ensure their longevity. Whether
neophytes or established giants, they're restructuring, identifying new
niches, and moving to meet changing customer needs. Notes Jeffrey Kolton,
president of FRANDATA Corp. of Washington, D.C.: ''The companies that are
doing well are those that got creative and are creative in working with
their franchisees.'' </P>

<P><STRONG>Find Opportunity in Times of Crisis</STRONG> </P>

<P>A major problem forced the 1,503-unit Denny's (#6)
to overhaul its entire business. In the early '90s, Denny's and its parent,
Flagstar Companies Inc. of Spartanburg, S.C., were plagued by discrimination
claims. Some of its restaurants had refused to serve African-Americans.
Flagstar ultimately paid $54 million to settle two class-action suits brought
by customers. New management was hired to straighten out the company. </P>

<P>''As I said the first day I walked in here, we
can either say this is a problem or an opportunity,'' says C. Ronald Petty,
Denny's new CEO and president and a former Burger King executive. </P>

<P>The full-service restaurant chain added minority
board members, senior managers, and vendors. It offered diversity training
to everyone, right down to the dishwashers. Fast Track is one part of an
aggressive minority-franchise recruitment program. </P>

<P>Founded in 1959, Denny's was overloaded with company
units. ''At one time, franchisees were the red-headed stepchildren. That's
all changed,'' says Bruce Mitchell, chairman of Denny's Franchisee Advisory
Board. Franchises, which comprised about 25 percent of its system in 1993,
should hit 50 percent by 1998. </P>

<P>Besides remodeling company units, Denny's has a
new prototype for interstate highway sites, a future growth vehicle. ''It
opens up our brand to a lot more exposure,'' Petty says. The company recognizes
the urgency of efficient customer service. It is installing a $30 million
POS system to relieve bottlenecks and has added consumer hot lines, including
one mandated by the court for discrimination complaints. </P>

<P>''Basically, Denny's up until mid-1993 really didn't
have a marketing strategy . . . a positioning,'' says Petty. ''When I got
here, I said there are only two ways we can go -- value or differentiation.''
Because Denny's has the biggest ad budget and lowest check average in its
category, it chose to be the ''value leader.'' In April 1994, Denny's unveiled
its first value meal, the Grand Slam $1.99 breakfast. Traffic swelled, and
new pricing should help profit margins. The second quarter of 1996 marked
Denny's seventh straight quarterly increase in comparable store sales. </P>

<P><STRONG>Create Powerhouse Franchisees</STRONG> </P>

<P>Multiunit franchisees can make a system grow faster
and stronger. Many companies are hunting for well-capitalized, proven operators
as a means of developing entire markets. </P>

<P>Five years ago, Fazoli's (#24) of Lexington, Ky.,
targeted mom-and-pop restaurant owners to grow its franchise. But the chain
quickly switched to an area-development arrangement. ''You get better consistency
of operations and tighter span of control of franchise representatives,''
says executive vice president Ernie Renaud. The Italian fast-food firm has
opened 145 corporate and 75 franchised units. ''Right now we own a niche,''
he says. ''We go into a market and build as fast as we can, particularly
by doing conversions.'' </P>

<P>Giant multiunit franchisees have helped Applebee's
International Inc. (#82) of Overland Park, Kan., become the nation's largest
casual-dining restaurant chain. The first Applebee's Neighborhood Grill
&amp; Bar opened in 1980, and the concept was later sold to W.R. Grace &amp;
Co. In 1988, Abe Gustin Jr., an Applebee's franchisee, purchased the chain.
</P>

<P>The former franchisee had a new vision for the
corporation. First, he established a franchise business council and wrote
a more franchise-friendly development agreement. Gustin instituted exclusive
territories, enabling franchisees to control regional price promotions and
marketing. ''We wanted to give them enough restaurants to get relatively
wealthy. That was one way to entice them to build additional restaurants,''
the CEO says. </P>

<P>Applebee's also practices ''conscious cannibalization.''
Part of its operating philosophy is to minimize waiting lines and serve
entrees in 15 minutes. To do this, a franchisee often adds another unit
nearby, sacrificing sales at the first restaurant for additional market
capacity. ''We know that convenience has a lot to do with what determines
where you eat these days,'' says president and COO Lloyd Hill. </P>

<P>The chain has exploded in the past three years,
adding 400 of its 700 units. An average restaurant does $2.1 million in
annual sales. Its 40 franchisee groups cover the U.S. -- only parts of Los
Angeles and New York are available. </P>

<P>Franchisee Michael Olander is the type of high
flier who's accelerating Applebee's growth. A Burger King franchisee, he
opened an Applebee's in Cary, N.C., in 1984. Today, his 42 units in four
states ring up $85 million in sales. Olander has reduced his Burger King
holdings to build 50 more Applebee's in the space of three years. He also
plans to open 15 Rio Bravo Cantinas, Applebee's newest Tex-Mex concept.
''Knowing so much about Applebee's,'' Olander says, ''we know they'll do
it right.'' </P>

<P><STRONG>Broaden Your Horizons</STRONG> </P>

<P>More franchisors are offering multiple concepts
under one umbrella. Success with one franchise concept gives them muscle
to sell additional ones. </P>

<P>Minneapolis-based Grow Biz International Inc. is
the pioneer of a new business niche that blends new and used merchandise
in attractive stores. In 1988, it debuted Play It Again Sports (#58), which
sells sporting goods and equipment. The chain now has 615 units. When Grow
Biz saw that consumers liked the idea of recycling and value, it logically
branched into other industries by acquiring compatible chains. Its five
concepts include Computer Renaissance (#43) personal computers and printers,
and Disc-Go-Round (#81) compact discs. </P>

<P>President and CEO Ronald Olson says it's easier
to create new concepts once you have one franchise system down pat. For
example, Grow Biz experimented with five prototypes in three years before
settling on the right look for Play It Again Sports. In contrast, Grow Biz
changed the image and advertising for Disc-Go-Round within four months of
acquiring it back in 1994. </P>

<P>Grow Biz teaches franchisees broad formulas to
acquire goods and fine-tunes them for each concept. Play It Again Sports
relies heavily on garage sales. Disc-Go-Round advertises in college newspapers.
Computer Renaissance phones businesses. </P>

<P>Originally, Olson thought franchisees would acquire
more than one concept and bundle them together. To his surprise, there's
little crossover. ''People who buy any one of the concepts are buying it
not only because it's right for the times, but because they like that industry,''
he says. </P>

<P>Larry Weldon is among the few who own several Grow
Biz concepts. When he was closed out of a territory for Play It Again Sports,
he bought Grow Biz's children's clothing concept, Once Upon A Child, in
1994. Since then, he's opened four Disc-Go-Rounds. ''If you learn about
Once Upon A Child, you're 40 percent there on other concepts,'' he says.
His vision: a strip mall with a Once Upon A Child, Disc-Go-Round, and Computer
Renaissance all sharing a lunchroom. Olson predicts more multi-concept franchisees
will emerge as the chain matures. </P>

<P><STRONG>Build Brand Equity </STRONG></P>

<P>From its start in 1980, San Diego-based Mail Boxes
Etc. (#20) had instituted a strategic plan to expand rapidly in order to
gain critical mass. Today, the 2,650-unit chain dwarfs its competitors tenfold.
Two years ago, it mounted a massive brand-building marketing campaign. </P>

<P>''We were going to take the competitive advantage
that existed because of our size and push our brand-awareness above our
competitors,'' says president and CEO Tony DeSio. ''We hoped to increase
market share.'' </P>

<P>Despite a difficult sell, franchisees agreed to
increase ad royalties from <BR>
2 percent to 3.5 percent of sales to test a brand-awareness campaign. Focus
groups showed customers care most about service, so Mail Boxes developed
this theme: ''It's not what we do. It's how we do it.'' Says DeSio: ''We
want to build trust in the eyes of the consumer that we are the experts.''
TV commercials emphasize that the chain offers more than its name implies.
</P>

<P>In fiscal 1995, the $8.6 million campaign contributed
to a 20 percent rise in same-store sales. The ad budget is $13 million this
year. Says Tom Winters, the chairman of the franchisee's Advertising Advisory
Council, ''The stores really did see the benefit of the advertising we did.''
</P>

<P>So has competitor PostNet (#5) of Henderson, Nev.
''We're feeding off its advertising because the brand 'mail boxes' is fairly
generic,'' says president Steven J. Greenbaum. The 350-unit PostNet began
franchising three years ago. Its ad budget is a mere $102,000. ''We do a
significant amount of outside marketing, introducing our products and services,''
Greenbaum says. </P>

<P><STRONG>Be Nimble, Be Quick </STRONG></P>

<P>Franchises must be able to adapt to ever-changing
marketplace demands. FirstService Franchise Corp. of Toronto owns College
ProPainters Ltd., a franchise concept that employs college students during
summer vacations. But the firm soon recognized a growing demand for professional
painters year-round. In 1993, it spun off Certa ProPainters Ltd. (#97).
</P>

<P>Franchisee David Rankin joined College Pro as a
student. Last October, he gave up teaching to buy two Certa Pro franchises
in Cincinnati. ''It was like moving up to the major leagues,'' he says.
Rankin, 34, projects a 25 percent net profit on $550,000 in sales his first
year. </P>

<P>A typical franchisee manages the business and oversees
a half-dozen painters. ''We really can make the phone ring for them,'' says
Certa Pro president Charles Chase. Sales tactics include direct mail and
imaginative cold-calling, like appearing at an office with a hot pizza.
The average franchisee lands 46 percent of all estimates. </P>

<P>Corporate downsizing has created opportunities
for business-service franchises, including postal centers and employment
agencies. For example, to capture the virtual office worker, Mail Boxes
Etc. gives box holders Internet addresses and receives packages, and it
is testing computers with 24-hour access. PostNet modifies its core operation
to fit users' needs. A center that draws road warriors touts more professional
services, such as desktop publishing, high-speed copying, and computer rentals.
</P>

<P>Most franchisors have expanded beyond Main Street.
Mail Boxes Etc. has kiosks at colleges, convention centers, and soon it
will be in airports. PostNet Express operates in 17 supermarkets in the
Southwest. PostNet also plans more superstores that will combine postal
centers and print shops. </P>

<P>''It's an opportunity for us to service a much
broader segment of the marketplace,'' Greenbaum says. </P>

<P>Susan McLoughlin approached PostNet with the superstore
idea. In August 1995, she and her partner, Jack McGee, unveiled the chain's
first 1,500-square-foot unit in Mill Creek, Wash. Sales swell 15 percent
to 33 percent each month. Says McLoughlin: ''You need to change with the
times, and [Greenbaum] was willing to do that.'' * </P>

<P>SUCCESS contributing writer Carol Steinberg has
been covering franchise businesses for national publications for a dozen
years. </P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE COLSPAN="2" ROWSPAN="1" WIDTH="550"><BR><BR>
